status_message: The fourth movie in the "Jurassic Park" series, "Jurassic World," set an all-time worldwide opening weekend record with $511.8 million June 12-14. The dinosaur film earned $204.6 million in North America, the second largest opening ever after the first "Avengers" movie.
link_name: 'Jurassic World' has largest worldwide opening of all-time

status_message: People in Zimbabwe will receive $5 for amounts up to 175 quadrillion Zimbabwean dollars in their bank account and a cash rate of $1 to 250 trillion Zimbabwe dollars for notes printed before 2009 starting June 15, Central Bank Governor John Mangudya said. The decision is an effort to phase out local currency.
link_name: Zimbabwe offers $1 for 250 trillion Zimbabwean dollars

status_message: Six Yemenis were released from the Guantanamo Bay military prison and flown to Oman for resettlement, the Pentagon said June 13. They were held for more than a decade. Oman gave them "temporary residency," its state news agency reported. The 69 Yemenis still at Guantanamo are more than half its detainees.
link_name: Six detainees released from Guantanamo Bay

status_message: Video released June 13 showed Israeli soldiers beating an unarmed Palestinian man after he was subdued. The man had left his home and approached the soldiers to tell them to stop firing tear gas at protest, Al Jazeera reported. The soldiers had been pelted with rocks during the protest, the Israeli military said.
link_name: Video shows Israeli soldiers beating unarmed Palestinian

status_message: The UK pulled out spies from "hostile countries" due to concerns that Russia and China cracked files leaked by Edward Snowden, the Sunday Times reported June 14. Information in the files could identify UK and US spies. No one had been harmed, a UK government official said. The prime minister's office declined comment to Reuters.
link_name: UK pulls out spies over fears Snowden files cracked, Sunday Times reports

status_message: Rallies occurred ahead of a June 17 vote by lawmakers on electoral reforms including holding direct elections, but with candidates approved by a council filled with Chinese government backers. Thousands of police will be deployed for the vote.
link_name: Hong Kong rallies ahead of election decision

status_message: The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) said on June 12 it would classify all chimpanzees--both wild and captive--as an endangered species. Primate researcher Jane Goodall and several animal rights organizations petitioned the FWS in 2010 to broaden the endangered designation to include chimps in captivity.
link_name: Captive chimps in the US to receive endangered species status

status_message: The Blackhawks' Antoine Vermette scored in the third period to give Chicago a 2-1 win over the Lightning in Game Five on June 13. Chicago could clinch the title at home on June 15, which would be the team's third Stanley Cup since 2010.
link_name: Blackhawks take 3-2 lead in Stanley Cup Finals

status_message: Joyce Mitchell, a seamstress at the Clinton Correctional Facility, will be arraigned June 12, Clinton County Sheriff David Favro told CNN. The facility was the site of a June 6 prison break in which two convicted felons escaped. Mitchell allegedly "provided some form of equipment or tools" as assistance, county prosecutor Andrew Wylie said.
link_name: County Sheriff: NY prison employee to be arraigned in connection to prison break

status_message: A new estimate puts the number of employees affected at between 9 and 14 million. Data targeted in the hack may extend to the sensitive security clearance information used by the military and intelligence agencies, including previous arrests and the identity of close relatives, several anonymous U.S. officials told the AP June 12.
link_name: AP: New estimate puts number of federal employees potentially affected by government data breach at 14 million

status_message: For the first time since 1977, farmers with long-standing rights to California water will face restrictions, the State Water Resources Control Board said June 12. About 300 water right holders in the San Joaquin and Sacramento watersheds and delta will be affected, water that farmers have had rights to since 1903.
link_name: California unveils water restrictions for farmers

status_message: Germany's upper chamber, or Bundesrat, on June 12 passed a resolution calling for the recognition of same-sex marriage, as well as same-sex couples' right to adoption. The resolution, which was sponsored by Social Democrats, Greens and Left party members in nine states, now goes on to the lower chamber for review.
link_name: German upper chamber rules in favor of same-sex marriage

status_message: Tolokonnikova, a member of Russian band Pussy Riot, and Katya Nenasheva, a fellow activist, were detained June 12 after a brief performance in central Moscow in support of female prisoners. The performance, which was cut short by police, involved sewing together strips of fabric in the colors of the Russian flag (white, blue, red).
link_name: Pussy Riot member detained after protest in support of female prisoners

status_message: 1 in 5 women who attended college in the past 4 years were sexually assaulted, a poll from the Washington Post-Kaiser Family Foundation published June 12 said. 1,053 women and men, all undergraduates at 500 four-year colleges since 2011, were surveyed. 25% of the women surveyed said they knew their attacker "fairly well."
link_name: Washington Post poll: 20% of women in college in last 4 years experienced sexual assault

status_message: The New York Times reported on June 12 that despite a ban that prevents the Rohingya people from fleeing Myanmar, the government will not address the plight in the country that is forcing members of the Muslim ethnic group to flee the country. The government refers to the group as Bengalis and refuses to instill basic rights.
link_name: Myanmar refuses to address plight of Rohingya, despite ban from fleeing

status_message: In a 126-302 vote on June 12, the House blocked the Trade Adjustment Assistance bill. TAA provides job training and resources to people who lose their jobs as the result of a trade deal.
link_name: US House blocks Obama trade bill

status_message: Civil rights activist and head of the Spokane NAACP in Washington, Rachel Dolezal has allegedly been pretending to be African-American for nearly a decade. Her parents told the Spokesman-Review on June 12 that Dolezal began changing her appearance after adopting half-black children with her ex-husband.
link_name: Spokane NCAAP president accused of pretending to be African-American for a decade

status_message: Prosecutors dropped charges against Martese Johnson on June 11. The officers involved in the arrest will not be charged. "When I notified him [Johnson], he was truly ecstatic," Johnson's lawyer said.
link_name: Charges dropped against UVA student bloodied by police. Officers not charged.

status_message: South Korea confirmed that 13 people have died from MERS-related illness on June 12. Health officials said that fewer cases are being reported, but two hospitals in the city of Changwon have temporarily shut down.
link_name: South Korea confirms 13th MERS death

status_message: The third season of Netflix's popular original series "Orange is the New Black" was released on June 11, a day ahead of the expected debut on June 12. The show's writers confirmed in May 2014 that it had been renewed for a third season.
link_name: Third season of 'Orange is the New Black' gets early release

status_message: Chad, Nigeria, Cameroon, Benin and Niger leaders meeting in Abuja, Nigeria, for a regional summit June 11 agreed to form a joint military force in the fight against Boko Haram. Nigeria will head the force, which will be headquartered in Chad. Cameroon and Chad will act as deputy commander and chief of staff, respectively.
link_name: Nigeria and four other countries pledge joint military effort against Boko Haram

status_message: Cleveland municipal judge Ronald Adrine ruled June 11 that he found probable cause to pursue murder charges against Timothy Loehmann, as well as negligent homicide charges against Frank Garmback, his partner, in an advisory ruling. The ruling follows a petition by civil rights activists and community leaders that cites an obscure Ohio law.
link_name: Cleveland judge finds sufficient evidence to pursue charges in Tamir Rice shooting

status_message: EU regulators probing U.S. companies for potential antitrust violations said June 11 they were examining Amazon's publishing deals for anti-competitive behavior. According to regulators, clauses in the deals may have prevented European competitors from offering lower-priced e-books. Amazon told the New York Times it will "cooperate fully during this process".
link_name: EU regulators extend antitrust probe to Amazon e-books

status_message: Twitter announced that Dick Costolo would step down as Twitter CEO on July 1. Jack Dorsey would take his place as interim CEO. Costolo will remain on Twitter's board of directors.
link_name: Dick Costolo stepping down as Twitter CEO, Jack Dorsey named interim CEO

status_message: On June 10, Gov. Mary Fallen signed HB 1684 into law to amend Safe School Committee legislation in order to add "duty to develop a rape or sexual assault response program for students and school staff; providing an effective date; and declaring an emergency." Students and staff will both be required to complete the training.
link_name: Oklahoma to require rape and sexual assault prevention programs in schools

status_message: On June 11, Twitter announced they would remove the 140 character limit for direct messages. The change does not impact public tweets.
link_name: Twitter removes 140 character limit for direct messages

status_message: Ornette Coleman passed away on June 11 at the age of 85. An innovator of jazz music, his work in the late 1950s and early '60s set the course for musicians in the genre playing with freedom from preconceived chord sequences. His albums include "The Shape of Jazz to Come," "This Is Our Music," and "Change of the Century."
link_name: Jazz innovator Ornette Coleman dies at 85

status_message: Marseille prosecutor Brice Robin on June 11 said that Andreas Lubitz saw seven doctors in the month of the Germanwings crash and 41 doctors in the last five years. Doctors believed he was not fit to fly, but did not alert authorities "because of medical secrecy requirements," Robin said.
link_name: Germanwings co-pilot saw 7 doctors during month of crash

status_message: Bangkok University became one of the first institutions in Thailand to formalize a transgender dress code. The university said many transgender students were mixing and matching different elements from the dress code and the new outfits will allow them to stay within the dress code and still feel comfortable.
link_name: Bangkok University introduces transgender-friendly dress code

status_message: Guernsey's auction house said on June 9 that the collection of posters, amassed by a U.S. Army officer, will be sold at auction on June 30. Half of the collection is from the U.S., including the famous Uncle Sam "I Want You for U.S. Army" design, and includes others from 15 countries around the world.
link_name: 2,000 rare World War I posters head to auction

status_message: Guatemala's Supreme Court on June 10 said that President Otto Perez Molina should face investigation for his role in a corruption scheme, asking lawmakers to lift the leader's immunity that protects him from being prosecuted. A commission responsible for the investigation will be named.
link_name: Widespread government corruption probe to investigate Guatemalan President Otto Perez Molina

status_message: It begins
link_name: Rupert Murdoch to step down as CEO of 21st Century Fox in 2016

status_message: British actor Sir Christopher Lee died as a result of respiratory problems and heart failure, his wife announced on June 11. He was 93 years old. The couple was married for more than 50 years.
link_name: Actor Christopher Lee dies at 93

status_message: Ex-security chief Zhou Yongkang was sentenced to life in prison for bribery, abuse of power and leaking state secrets, state media said June 11. He is the most senior official convicted of corruption. He was ejected from the Communist Party, where he had been a member of its top leadership, in Dec. 2014.
link_name: Ex-Chinese security chief sentenced to life in prison

status_message: Arbitrary arrests of activists continued in June, a year after Abdel Fattah Al-Sisi was elected president. Rights groups struggle to keep track of all the arrests, with an estimated 66 people disappearing in two months. Many are denied access to a lawyer and family. Dozens were arrested ahead of a general strike planned for June 11.
link_name: Arbitrary arrests continue a year after Sisi elected Egyptian president

status_message: Fake cell phone towers are used for spying in the UK, a June 10 Sky News report found. Sky News used software by German security company GMSK Cryptophone to observe the towers in London. It was the first direct evidence of the technology. UK police have neither confirmed nor denied its use, and its oversight is unknown.
link_name: Fake cell phone towers used for spying in the UK

status_message: Greece's state television ERT had its first broadcast in two years on June 11. The anchors promised the station would be "television for the Greeks... and will not be controlled by any government." The government vowed to rehire the roughly 2,600 staff fired in 2013, paid for by an existing charge on electricity bills.
link_name: Greek state TV returns after austerity shutdown

status_message: The NY Health Dept. on June 10 proposed requiring chain restaurants to add a saltshaker symbol to menus to warn of high-sodium items. The proposal defines high-sodium as more than the recommended daily limit of 2,300 milligrams (1 tsp.) of salt. New York City would be the first U.S. city with the requirement if it passes.
link_name: NY Health Dept. proposes salt warnings on chain restaurant menus

status_message: The Blackhawks won Game 4 on June 10 by a score of 2-1 to tie the best of seven series 2-2. Brandon Saad's third-period goal gave them the win. Saad has given the Blackhawks the lead in the postseason in six of his eight goals, including two game-winning shots.
link_name: Blackhawks tie Lightning 2-2 in Stanley Cup Finals

status_message: Overseas ad sales accounted for 51% of Facebook's total ad revenue in the first quarter, Reuters reported June 10, citing Carolyn Everson, the company's VP of global marketing solutions. Sales grew fastest in the Asia-Pacific region (57%), Everson said. The company had never before reported ad sales as a percentage of total ad revenue.
link_name: Facebook's overseas ad sales surpassed US sales

status_message: Five million children are employed in forced labor, referred to as modern-day slavery, despite a decline in child labor since 2000, the ILO said June 10. The ILO estimates in its annual report that nearly half of almost 170 million child laborers continue to work in hazardous conditions.
link_name: Children make up a quarter of people in modern-day slavery

status_message: The cost of cleaning up the oil spilled on the California coastline has cost $69 million so far, Plains All American Pipeline told the Associated Press on June 10. Almost 76% of the coastline, which spans 97 miles, has been cleared of oil.
link_name: California oil spill cleanup has cost $69 million so far

status_message: In a filing with the FCC, SpaceX asked the government for permission to begin testing a project that would allow even the most remote regions of the world to receive Internet signals. Beamed down from space using 4,000 small satellites, the service "would be like rebuilding the Internet in space.
link_name: SpaceX asks government for permission to provide Internet services from space

status_message: The opening group stage match between the U.S. and Australian women's soccer teams at the Women's World Cup June 8 drew a record 3.3 million domestic viewers, tripling the television audience of the 2011 opener between the U.S. and North Korea and beating a 1999 record of 2.5 million viewers, FOX Sports 1 said.
link_name: US Women's World Cup soccer match draws record 3 million viewers

status_message: Researchers discovered the fossilized dinosaur blood in a 75-million-year-old specimen, according to a study published in Nature Communications on June 9. The scientists did not find any genetic material, however. "No, 'Jurassic Park' has not happened," one of the scientists joked.
link_name: Dinosaur blood discovered by British paleontologists

status_message: "Amelia Earhart's Last Photo Shoot," shot by John Bresnik, was discovered by his son and will be released with an 80-page-book of the same name later this month, according to the AP on June 9. Bresnik shot the footage at the Burbank Airport in March or May of 1937 while his brother, Al, photographed Earhart.
link_name: Never-before-seen 1937 footage of Amelia Earhart found

status_message: Zhanna Nemtsova said she has been forced to flee Russia, fearing for her life after receiving death threats, according to the BBC on June 10. She blamed pro-Putin media for aiding to her fathers death by labeling him and other opposition leaders as "traitors."
link_name: After receiving death threats, daughter of Boris Nemtsov flees Russia

status_message: The NTSB provided a second update on the investigation into the derailment of Amtrak train #188 on June 10. No calls, texts, or data usage occurred at the time of the crash and the conductor did not access the train's WiFi, the report said.
link_name: NTSB: Conductor was not using cell phone or WiFi at time of Amtrak crash

status_message: Pope Francis established a tribunal to hear accusations of child abuse against bishops, the Vatican said June 10. Bishops can also be judged if they do not prevent abuse. Initial investigations will occur with a Vatican department. Abuse survivors' groups have long urged for bishops to be held accountable.
link_name: Pope Francis establishes tribunals to hear accusations of child abuse against bishops

status_message: Spotify now has more than 20 million paying subscribers, the company said June 10. That's up from 12.5 million paying subscribers announced in Nov. 2014, representing an increase of 60%, and 15 million paying subscribers announced in January. The company now has more than 75 million active users overall.
link_name: Spotify tops 20 million paid users, up 60% since late 2014

status_message: Police are investigating accusations of child abuse in the 1970s and 1980s at three UK boarding schools, the BBC reported June 10. Former students said they suffered physical, mental and sexual abuse. Two trials occurred in 2000 for abuse at one of the schools, but one defendant was deemed unfit for trial and another walked free.
link_name: UK police investigating child abuse at boarding schools

status_message: The International Air Transport Association (IATA) proposed standardizing carry-on luggage to 21 by 13.5 by 7.5 inches, it said June 9. The IATA consulted with Boeing and Airbus, airlines and baggage manufacturers. Many airlines allow larger sizes, but several indicated to the IATA they will adopt the proposal.
link_name: Airlines to adopt smaller carry-on luggage size limits

status_message: Cybersecurity firm Kaspersky Lab found a virus widely linked to Israeli spies targeted three European hotels used for Iranian nuclear talks, the Wall Street Journal reported June 10. The Journal reported in March that Israel spied on U.S. officials and shared information with U.S. lawmakers to undermine talks.
link_name: WSJ: Israeli spy virus targeted hotels of Iran nuclear talks

status_message: The bidding process for the 2026 World Cup will be delayed
link_name: Corruption accusations emerge on previous World Cups

status_message: The attorneys general of New York and Connecticut are leading an antitrust investigation into Apple negotiations with music companies. The investigation aims to "ensure that consumers and competition are protected." Universal Music Group confirmed it was cooperating on June 9, a day after Apple announced a paid music subscription service.
link_name: Antitrust investigation focuses on Apple music deals

status_message: A coalition of rebel groups captured a large military base in the southern Deraa province on June 9. The coalition, known as the Southern Front, includes groups directed in Jordan in a covert CIA program and has coordinated with Al-Qaeda's Nusra Front. The base is near an important highway that leads to the capital.
link_name: Syrian army loses key base in south

status_message: Members of the Yazidi community attacked two Arab villages in the Sinjar region in January, killing 21 people, abducting 40 people, and looting and burning homes, a June 10 Amnesty International report said. The raid was an apparent reprisal against for Islamic State attacks. Kurdish fighters were present but did nothing, witnesses said.
link_name: Iraq's Yazidis accused of revenge attacks on villagers

status_message: Multiple attackers targeted the ancient Karnak Temple, wounding four Egyptians. Two assailants were killed and a third was injured, Egypt's Interior Ministry said. At least one attacker breached the temple's security and detonated a suicide bomb, state-run media said. No one claimed responsibility.
link_name: Attackers target ancient Egyptian temple

status_message: Two former Japanese leaders who issued the country's apologies in 1993 and in 1995 for WWII atrocities urged Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to confront Japan's past. Former Liberal Democratic Party president Yohei Kono and ex-prime minister Tomiichi Murayama spoke on the issue June 9 at the Japan National Press Club in Tokyo.
link_name: Former Japanese leaders urge prime minister to face past war atrocities

status_message: South Korea established nationwide health clinics for MERS. People experiencing symptoms have been advised to contact authorities and to not to go to hospitals. At least 47 cases were tied to a medical facility in Seoul. Nine people died from the disease in the country by June 10.
link_name: South Korea sets up nationwide clinics for MERS

status_message: The Cavs won Game 3 on June 9 by a score of 96-91. Lebron James scored 40 points. His 123 points in the first three games is on pace to tie Michael Jordan's 1993 record for points per game in an NBA Finals series at 41.
link_name: Cavs up 2-1 on Warriors with NBA Finals Game 3 win

status_message: 27-year-old right-hander Chris Heston tossed a no-hitter in only his 13th career start, against the New York Mets on June 9. He allowed only three baserunners, all hit batsmen. He struck out 11, including the side in the ninth. He is the first rookie to throw a no-hitter since the Red Sox's Clay Buchholz in 2007.
link_name: Giants rookie has first no-hitter of 2015

status_message: The Los Angeles Police Commission ruled in a closed-door meeting June 9 that one officer involved in Ford's shooting death violated police department policy, while another was justified in using deadly force against Ford. The meeting was preceded by a public meeting attended by protesters, as well as Ford's mother, which lasted three hours.
link_name: One LAPD officer cleared, another found unjustified in shooting of unarmed man

status_message: Six letters by author Harper Lee addressed to several friends and patrons who supported Lee at the time of writing "To Kill a Mockingbird" are expected to fetch between $150,000 and $200,000 at auction June 12. The letters are signed with humorous aliases, like "The Prisoner of Zenda", or Lee's first name, "Nelle".
link_name: Christie's to auction private collector's Harper Lee letters June 12

status_message: The board of supervisors approved the ordinance, which would require beverage companies to place warnings on billboards, bus and taxi ads in the city, saying they increase the risk of diabetes, obesity and other health issues, June 9. The proposal was first made by supervisors Scott Wiener, Malia Cohen and Eric Mar in March.
link_name: San Francisco to unveil health warnings on ads for sugary drinks

status_message: Ingeborg Rapoport, 102 years old, was awarded her doctorate at a ceremony at the University of Hamburg medical center on June 9, telling German news channel NDR she had achieved her goal "to support the great goal of coming to terms with history." She fled to the U.S. in 1938, before returning to Germany in the 1950s with her family.
link_name: World's oldest doctoral student, 102, receives PhD denied her by Nazis

status_message: The provenance of Rembrandt's "Saul and David" was first questioned by an art historian who thought one of the Dutch master's students may have completed the painting, calling its style "superficial and inconsistent". Conservators working to restoring the painting in 2007 now confirm its authenticity.
link_name: Dutch museum confirms authenticity of Rembrandt painting

status_message: Three jurors were dismissed by Judge Carlos Samour Jr. on June 9 after a juror sent the judge a note saying Juror 872 made comments about media coverage of the case in front of two other jurors, 412 and 495, in the juror assembly room. It was the 28th day of trial. Jurors are not allowed to discuss the case with anyone, including each other.
link_name: Three jurors dismissed in Colorado theater shooting trial

status_message: Former U.S. House Speaker Dennis Hastert on June 9 pleaded not guilty to five federal charges of structuring cash withdrawals and lying to federal investigators. A judge told Hastert that he must surrender his passport and stay in the United States. He was released on $4,500 bond.
link_name: Former US House speaker Dennis Hastert pleads not guilty

status_message: An affidavit published by Gawker on June 9 shows that the home of Emilio Herrera was raided by FBI agents in 2014 because "one or more computers used at [Herrera's house] access or attempted to access without authorization multiple celebrities' email and iCloud accounts over the course of several months."
link_name: Feds investigate man allegedly linked to 2014 celebrity photo hack

status_message: All clear given at White House after press briefing room, lawn evacuated due to bomb threat

White House press room being evacuated, this is the second time today a White House office has been evacuated.

Earlier, US Capitol Police cleared Dirksen Senate room 340 with no hazardous material found, suspicious package was cleared.

We'll post updates as they arrive.

Carter announced employment protection changes that will disallow discrimination in the military based on sexual orientation for the first time on June 9. Now, complaints about discrimination based on sexual orientation will be formally investigated by military officials.
link_name: New Pentagon policy extends employment protection to gay and lesbian troops

status_message: Intel announced that it created a $125 million capital investment fund to commit to technology companies with women and minorities as founders or serving on executive boards. Lambert and her team have already spent $16.7 million investing in diverse start-ups, included Brit & Co, headed by a woman.
link_name: Intel creates venture fund to invest in diverse tech companies

status_message: Former FIFA vice president Jack Warner was accused of having diverted $750,000 worth of emergency relief funds intended for Haiti to a bank account under his name, according to the BBC on June 9. Warner is one of 14 recently indicted on racketeering and bribery charges by the U.S. Dept. of Justice.
link_name: $750,000 in Haiti relief funds allegedly stolen by former FIFA VP Jack Warner

status_message: Civil rights activists, clergy, and community leaders announced at a June 9 press conference that they will seek charges against Timothy Loehmann and Frank Garmback, two officers involved in the killing of Tamir Rice. The New York Times said the group provided 6 affidavits seeking charges for aggravated murder and manslaughter.
link_name: Bypassing prosecutors, Cleveland activists file affidavit seeking charges in Tamir Rice shooting death

status_message: Chipotle on June 8 confirmed that it will extend benefits like paid vacation time, sick pay and tuition reimbursement, once only offered to salaried employees, to all of it's workers starting in July. The company hopes to build careers for workers and help recruit high school and college aged employees.
link_name: Chipotle offers all employees tuition reimbursement, sick pay, and paid vacation

status_message: Former Kappa Delta Rho pledge James Vivenzio, 21, sued Penn State and the fraternity on June 8 for "force-feeding bucketfuls of liquor mixed with urine, vomit, hot sauce and other liquid and semi-solid ingredients," among other hazing. The school and fraternity both pledged a "zero tolerance" policy towards hazing.
link_name: Kappa Delta Rho whistleblower sues fraternity, Penn State on hazing allegations

status_message: May was the wettest in 121-year recorded history for the contiguous U.S. Over 4.36 inches of rain fell, 1.45 over the average for May, and 9.33 inches fell for the spring season, according to NOAA's National Centers for Environmental Information on June 9. Spring was the 11th wettest in history.
link_name: NCEI: May was wettest month in US in 121 recorded years

status_message: New Jersey Supreme Court on June 9 ruled in favor of Gov. Chris Christie, overturning a lower court's rejection of pension cuts. He will not be required to put more money in the fund, as the 5-2 ruling said there is no enforceable contract requiring he do so.
link_name: Gov. Chris Christie wins over unions in New Jersey pension gap court case

status_message: Two lobbying groups representing tech giants including Apple, Google, Facebook, IBM and Microsoft published a letter June 9 urging President Barack Obama to protect encryption.
link_name: Tech companies lobby Obama administration to protect encryption

status_message: Albert Woodfox, 68, was ordered to be unconditionally released from state custody on June 9 after 43 years in solitary confinement at the Louisiana State Penitentiary and other prisons. He was convicted twice of murdering a 23-year-old prison guard in 1972, but the convictions were both overruled.
link_name: Albert Woodfox, last of the Angola 3, to be released after 4 decades in solitary confinement

status_message: GE will sell its private equity lending unit, Capital Sponsor Finance, to Canada Pension Plan Investment Board, Canada's largest pension fund, GE said June 9. The deal is worth about $12 billion. It will close in the third quarter of 2015, pending regulatory approval. The unit finances leveraged transactions, growth funding and recapitalization.
link_name: GE selling private equity lending unit to Canadian pension fund

status_message: German prosecutors searched the offices of Deutsche bank on June 9. The search was related to client securities transactions and did not accuse bank employees of wrongdoing, the bank said. Prosecutors declined to provide specifics.
link_name: German prosecutors search offices of Deutsche Bank

status_message: A 68-year-old woman was the seventh person to die from MERS, the South Korean government said June 9. Hong Kong issued its second highest travel alert on the same day, warning citizens to avoid all but essential travel to South Korea.
link_name: MERS-related death toll reaches 7 in South Korea

status_message: An Egyptian court sentenced 11 men to death on June 9 for a deadly soccer stadium incident in Port Said in northern Egypt in 2012. Dozens of defendants were accused of killing fans during riots after a match. A judge had referred the sentencing to the Grand Mufti, the highest Muslim authority in Egypt, in April.
link_name: Egypt sentences 11 to death for 2012 soccer riot

status_message: A study by the U.S. Veterans Affairs Dept. shows female military veterans commit suicide nearly six times more than those who have not served, the LA Times reported on June 8. The study found that females who have never served commit suicide at a rate of 5.2 per 100,000; that rate jumps to 28.7 for female veterans.
link_name: Female military vets nearly 6 times more likely to commit suicide than civilians

status_message: The Lightning won Game 3 in Chicago on June 8 by a score of 3-2 to take a 2-1 lead and regain home ice advantage in the best of seven series.
link_name: Lightning take 2-1 lead in Stanley Cup Finals

status_message: Up to 50,000 HSBC employees will lose their jobs in the bank's restructuring, a June 9 shareholders' meeting showed. The expected sales of HSBC's Brazil and Turkey units would eliminate 25,000 staff and 22,000-25,000 employees will be cut from IT and back office consolidations and branch closures.
link_name: Up to 50,000 HSBC employees will lose jobs in bank restructuring

status_message: The new events -- Big Air snowboarding, mixed doubles in curling (pictured), mass start in speedskating and a team event in skiing -- were ratified by the IOC executive board June 8. Another event, snowboard slalom, was removed to make room for the Big Air event, in which snowboarders fly off a ramp and complete several jumps and flips.
link_name: Olympics adopts "Big Air" snowboarding, curling at 2018 Winter Olympics

status_message: In a 6-3 vote the court reinforced separation-of-powers, saying the president, not congress, has exclusive power to recognize foreign nations. Due to the ongoing conflict between Israelis and Palestinians many countries, including the U.S., do not recognize Jerusalem as being a part of Israel.
link_name: Supreme Court strikes down Jerusalem passport law, affirming presidential powers

status_message:
Apple's annual Worldwide Developers Conference, also known as WWDC, takes place today. They're expected to unveil a music service to compete with Spotify.

Follow this story for live updates:
link_name: Apple expected to unveil streaming music service at WWDC

status_message: A complaint to the National Labor Relations Board, Teamsters Local 385 said Disney is committing an unfair labor practice in disallowing employees to publicly disclose what animated characters they portray. Disney's policy, only two weeks old, prevents actors from revealing what characters they play on social or other medias.
link_name: Disney actors' union challenges confidentiality policy

status_message: After a "thorough and fair review of the facts," the national branch of Kappa Delta Rho announced of June 8 that it will expel 38 of its Penn State fraternity members.
link_name: Kappa Delta Rho expels 38 Penn State fraternity members after secret Facebook brought to light

status_message: On June 8, a South Carolina grand jury returned a murder indictment against former South Carolina police officer Michael Slager in the shooting death of Walter Scott.
link_name: Former South Carolina officer who shot Walter Scott indicted for murder

status_message: The EU said on June 8 that it will continue voicing its concerns and engage Saudi authorities about their "need to recognize and respect freedom of speech for all." Saudi Arabia's supreme court upheld Raif Badawi's sentence, his wife said June 7. The court's decision is final. It can only be overturned by a royal pardon.
link_name: EU calls on Saudi Arabia to halt lashing of blogger

status_message: G7 countries agreed to try to limit global temperatures from rising more than two degrees celsius above pre-industrial levels. The countries will aim to reduce electricity from coal and oil by 40-70% by 2050, following recommendations by recommended by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).
link_name: G7 countries agree to limit climate warming by 2 degrees celsius

status_message: Six people have died in South Korea from MERS-related symptoms and 87 cases have been reported by the Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention as of June 8. At least 29 hospitals have been affected by the outbreak, but confirmed cases are only at 5 hospitals.
link_name: MERS-related death toll reaches 6 in South Korea

status_message: Nepalese authorities recovered the bodies of 53 villagers and trekkers in avalanches, Reuters reported June 8. Search and rescue operations in the area had been suspended due to continued avalanches in May. It was uncertain if the bodies were all lost in April 25 earthquake or subsequent avalanches, the military said.
link_name: Nepalese search teams find dozens of bodies from April avalanche

status_message: South Africa's Supreme Court of Appeal will hear the state's appeal in the case of Oscar Pistorius in November, it said June 8. The athlete is set to be released on parole in August under "correctional supervision."
link_name: Oscar Pistorius to be released on parole in August

status_message: Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto's retained a simple majority in Congress with his Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) and its partners expected to win between 246 and 263 of the 500 seats in the lower house, Mexico's electoral authority INE said. The PRI itself lost seats, an early vote count showed.
link_name: Mexican President Nieto's party keeps ruling coalition

status_message: Former Rikers inmate Kalief Browder, 22, committed suicide June 6. Browder was jailed in 2010 when he was 16 years old on robbery charges that were dropped in 2013. A New Yorker profile in Oct. 2014 detailed his incarceration, including abuse by officers and inmates, two years in solitary confinement, and suicide attempts.
link_name: Former teen detainee in NYC jail commits suicide

status_message: Secret tapes of a FIFA executive committee member claim Morocco won the 2010 World Cup, but FIFA manipulated the results, the Sunday Times reported June 6. Accusations also emerged that Germany got the 2006 World Cup by lifting arms restrictions on Saudi Arabia for its vote, Die Zeit reported June 4.
link_name: Corruption accusations emerge on previous World Cups

status_message: President Erdogan's AKP party was projected to take 258 of the 550 seats in parliament, or 18 less than needed to rule alone. The Republican People's party (CHP) received 25%, the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) got 16.5% and the Peoples' Democratic party (HDP) crossed the 10% threshold for the first time with 13%. Turnout was 86%.
link_name: Turkish President Erdogan's party loses majority in elections

status_message: The survey found a decline in abortions in nearly every state.
link_name: AP: Abortions in US have decreased by 12 percent since 2010, survey

status_message: "These are dangerous men. Please do your duty as a New Yorker and pass on any information you may have." - New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo
link_name: $100,000 reward set as manhunt continues for two convicted killers who escaped NY prison

status_message: Saudi Arabia's supreme court upheld Raif Badawi's sentence, his wife said June 7. The court's decision is final. It can only be overturned by a royal pardon.
link_name: Saudi Arabia upholds 1,000 lashes for blogger

status_message: A few thousand protesters hiked and bused through the Alps to the G7 meeting. They were far outnumbered by police as Germany deployed some 17,000 officers. About 30 protesters were injured a day earlier after a police cordon blocked a crowd, a paramedic said. A court ruling allowed 50 protesters inside the venue's security zone.
link_name: Protesters march against G7 meeting in Germany

status_message: Polls opened for elections for Turkey's parliament on June 7. Although the president is supposed to remain apolitical, Erdogan has actively campaigned for his party during elections. He was criticized for a muted response to a deadly bombing at Kurdish rally June 5.
link_name: Turkey votes for parliament with Erdogan seeking more power

status_message: Chinese rescue workers held a moment of silence June 7 to mark the seventh day since the Eastern Star capsized. The death toll reached 431, the government said, with 11 people missing. The ship operator apologized. The government pledged there would be "no cover-up."
link_name: Hundreds of bodies found in capsized Chinese ship

status_message: The Lightning won a back and forth Game 2 at home June 6, 4-3, to tie the Stanley Cup Finals at a game a piece.
link_name: Lightning tie up Stanley Cup Finals

status_message: American Pharoah, along with jockey Victor Espinoza, made history on June 6 by winning the Belmont Stakes, becoming horse racing's first Triple Crown winner since 1978.
link_name: American Pharoah wins Belmont Stakes, becoming first Triple Crown winner since 1978

status_message: "Indications are, there are 450,000-500,000 migrants in Libya who are waiting at the border."
link_name: European naval vessels save over 2,500 migrants in Mediterranean

status_message: Over 2,700 people have been evacuated from the island of Sumatra in Indonesia. Mt. Sinabung's volcanic activity, including flowing lava, hot ash and smoke, has increased in recent days.
link_name: Nearly 3,000 evacuated as volcano in Indonesia erupts

status_message: Pres. Obama delivered the eulogy for Beau Biden at St. Anthony of Padua Roman Catholic Church in Wilmington, Del. on June 6. First Lady Michelle Obama and their daughter Sasha attended the service. A visibly emotional Obama told the Bidens, "We are here to grieve with you, but more importantly we are here because we love you. Joe, you are my brother."
link_name: Obama gives emotional eulogy at Beau Biden funeral

status_message: Netflix will be available in Italy and Portugal by the end of October, the streaming service announced on June 6. This follows the June 4 announcement that Spain will also receive the service in October. Netflix is currently available in 13 European countries and more than 50 nations worldwide.
link_name: Netflix will be available in Italy, Portugal and Spain by October

status_message: Top-ranked Serena Williams won the French Open, her 20th grand slam title, on June 6. Williams bested defending champion Lucie Safarova, 6-3, 6-7, 6-2, in the final match. Sharapova had reached the French Open finals the previous three straight years, winning in 2012 and 2014.
link_name: Serena Williams wins French Open, her 20th grand slam

status_message: Hundreds of thousands of Argentines protested the death of 14-year-old Chiara Paez in marches across the country, including Buenos Aires, June 4. Paez was beaten to death, allegedly by her 16-year-old boyfriend, and buried alive. She was pregnant at the time.
link_name: Argentines protest teen's death at hands of her boyfriend

status_message: Robel Phillipos was sentenced to 36 months in prison June 5 for removing a backpack containing fireworks from Dzokhar Tsarnaev's room, hampering the ongoing Boston Marathon bombing investigation. Prosecutors had sought a five year sentence. Phillipos has spent the last two years confined to his home.
link_name: Tsarnaev friend, Robel Phillipos, sentenced to 3 years in prison

status_message: Minnesota prosecutors filed criminal charges and a civil petition against the Catholic Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis about the handling of "numerous and repeated reports of troubling conduct by former priest Curtis Wehmeyer (pictured) on June 5. The indictment said the church "failed to protect children."
link_name: St. Paul-Minneapolis archdiocese charged over priest sex abuse

status_message: An independent lab linked Blue Bell ice cream that allegedly gave a Florida man a bout of meningitis to the company's Alabama facility, the first evidence to show that all three Blue Bell facilities produced contaminated ice cream. The company reached a deal with Alabama Dept. of Public Health on June 1.
link_name: Ice cream maker Blue Bell listeria outbreaks linked to all three facilities

status_message: Norway's Parliament on June 5 voted to forego its holdings in companies who rely at least 30% on coal, scheduled to take effect next year. The step is considered symbolic by some, as the decision has "little or no impact on the vast market capitalization of most companies," according to the New York Times.
link_name: Pushing back against climate change, Norway to divest from coal

status_message: Sling TV has reached 250,000 subscribers, according to a report from Recode on June 5, citing industry executives familiar with the matter. If true, at the $20 per month cost point, the company is earning about $5 million a month.
link_name: Recode: Sling TV reaches 250,000 online subscribers

status_message: The Red Cross replied to the ProPublica/NPR report on June 5 and failed to deny that only 6 houses were built during a "pilot program" after the earthquake. On why the number did not grow, Meltzer said, "As the project progressed, we learned a number of lessons that helped us revise our long-term shelter plans. "
link_name: Red Cross on failures in Haiti: "Solutions we decided on ultimately helped more people"

status_message: The U.S. House of Representatives on June 5 voted 247-176 to keep restrictions on Americas seeking to travel to Cuba, blocking rules put forth by the administration in January. The provision was a part of a transportation funding bill and would allow regular scheduled flights to the island.
link_name: US House votes to keep Cuba tourism restrictions in place

status_message: President Poroshenko's parliament address on June 4 came a day after two clashes involving tanks are reported to have occurred west of Donetsk, what the European Union called a "most serious violation" of February's ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine.
link_name: President Petro Poroshenko says Ukraine must prepare for 'full-scale invasion' from Russia

status_message: Greek life infractions, categorized as hazing, alcohol/drugs, sexual misconduct, property damage/mischief, offensive behavior, intimidation, unspecified, and death, were made public by Bloomberg in a timeline released June 4. The compiled data showed that across the U.S., at least 133 infractions have already occurred in 2015.
link_name: Spring semester saw 133 infractions, 4 death investigations at Greek life organizations across US

status_message: Two curators at the United Nations-backed National Museum for Egyptian Civilization are accused of making replicas of antiquities, the museum's general supervisor told NBC News on June 4. The museum, set to open later this year, will now conduct inventory of all antiquities.
link_name: Two Egyptian museum curators accused of switching antiquities for fakes

status_message: On June 5, friend of convicted Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, Azamat Tazhayakov was sentenced to 42 months in prison for impeding Boston Marathon bombing investigation.
link_name: Tsarnaev friend, Azamat Tazhayakov sentenced to 42 months in prison

status_message: 72% of Americans said illegal immigrants living in the country should be allowed to stay if they meet some requirements, including 42% who said they should be allowed to become citizens and 26% who say they should become permanent residents. The research was conducted by Pew Research Center and made public June 4.
link_name: Pew Report: 72% of Americans support a path to legal status for undocumented immigrants

status_message: International Fund for Animal Welfare said a ship carrying 1,700 tons of whale meat left Hafnarfjordur harbor in Iceland on June 4, bound for Japan. The vessel is expected to meet protest at its stops along the way, which include a harbor in Ghana. In 2014, Icelandic whalers caught 137 fin whales and 24 minkes.
link_name: Defying ban, Iceland ships 1,700 tons of whale meat to Japan

status_message: The U.S. added 280,000 jobs in May, the Labor Dept. reported May 8. Economists had expected the country to add 226,000. The overall unemployment rate rose slightly to 5.5% from 5.4% in April.
link_name: US adds 280,000 jobs in May, unemployment rate rises to 5.5%

status_message: Canada and Mexico authorities are seeking $3 billion in sanctions against the U.S. for its meat import labeling rules, which they argue unfairly discriminate against Canadian and Mexican meat imports. The sanctions must be authorized by the World Trade Organization.
link_name: Canada, Mexico seek sanctions against 'discriminatory' US meat labeling rules

status_message: An FDA advisory panel on June 4 issued conditional approval for a drug to treat low libido in women. The approval hinges on the condition that women are fully aware of the risks associated with taking the drug, which include fainting and low blood pressure.
link_name: FDA panel issues conditional approval for drug to treat low female libido

status_message: The EPA released a draft study on June 4 on the effects of hydraulic fracturing in U.S. drinking water and found no widespread contamination. Predictably, the oil industry has applauded the study's results, while environmental groups have come out against it.
link_name: EPA finds fracking causes no widespread harm in drinking water

status_message: The California Senate voted 23-14 on June 4 to approve a bill allowing physicians to prescribe lethal doses of medication to patients with terminal illness. At least two physicians would have to attest to the severity of the illness, and patients would have to make two requests, at least 15 days apart and in the presence of two witnesses, to qualify for receiving the dose.
link_name: California Senate approves assisted suicide bill

status_message: "It's kind of shocking, really, how good they got it. I will have way more hair than when I was 21."
link_name: Texas cancer patient receives first partial skull and scalp transplant

status_message: Chinese hackers allegedly breached the U.S. Office of Personnel Management (OPM) in Dec. 2014, in the second reported attack in under a year, according to the Washington Post June 4. In a statement, the OPM warned 4 million current and former employees their personal data may have been compromised. The FBI confirmed it was investigating the incident.
link_name: Chinese hackers allegedly breached US federal personnel office

status_message: Chinese hackers allegedly breached the U.S. Office of Personnel Management (OPM) in Dec. 2014, in the second reported attack in under a year, according to the Washington Post June 4. In a statement, the OPM warned 4 million current and former employees their personal data may have been compromised.
link_name: Chinese hackers allegedly breached US federal personnel office

status_message: Key measures of a deal to limit Iran from developing nuclear weapons, including cuts to uranium enrichment, may "allow for the supposition that, in the coming period of years, this is a threat in decline", an unnamed Israeli military official was quoted by Reuters as saying in reference to Iran June 4.
link_name: Iranian nuclear threat may decline with deal, Israeli official claims

status_message: An explosion at a gas station in Ghana's capital killed 150 people, President John Dramani Mahama said late June 4. Flooding caused fuel stored at the gas station to reach a nearby house fire which triggered the deadly explosion. The area has been hit with heavy rains over the last two days causing concerns about the country's poor infrastructure.
link_name: Death toll reaches 150 in Ghana's gas station explosion

status_message: Stocks closed lower June 4, a day prior to release of U.S. monthly employment data and amid concerns about Greece's deal with foreign lenders. The Nasdaq closed down 40 points. The Dow also closed down about 171 points, at 17,905.58. The S&P 500 fell 18 points to 2,095.84.
link_name: US stocks down ahead of employment report

status_message: While driving his car in Guatemala City on June 4, Francisco Palomo was shot at least 12 times in the head and chest by gunmen riding on motorcycles. Palomo survived the attack for a short period of time before crashing into a tree. Motives behind the killing remain unclear.
link_name: Guatemalan lawyer who defended former dictator shot dead

status_message: A court filing during the week of June 1 revealed photos of a cache of weapons found in a vehicle and home of Omar Gonzalez. Gonzalez was arrested in Sept. 2014 after he hopped the fence and gained entry into the White House while armed with a knife. Prosecutors are recommending a 21-month prison sentence for Gonzalez. A sentencing date has been set for June 15.
link_name: WH fence jumper facing 21-months, court filing reveals weapons cache

status_message: On June 4, UNC released a 59-page notice of allegations from the NCAA. Among several level one and two violations that "seriously undermine or threaten the integrity of the NCAA collegiate model," the NCAA believes UNC has shown a lack of institutional control of its athletic department, the highest possible offense.
link_name: NCAA alleges 'lack of institutional control' at UNC, highest possible offense

status_message: Barnard College on June 4 announced that transgender women hoping to study at the New York City college will now be eligible to apply. In a statement, the Board of Trustees called the move a "recognition of our changing world and evolving understanding of gender identity."
link_name: Barnard College to accept transgender women

status_message: According to The Daily Mail on July 4, BBC made a bid for $7.1 million to keep "Top Gear" stars James May and Richard Hammond after Jeremy Clarkson's departure from the show. The two would host the show with another guest presenter each episode.
link_name: Daily Mail: BBC bids $7.1 million to keep 'Top Gear' hosts James May and Richard Hammond

status_message: Tumblr on June 4 debuted a feature that allows users to search for GIFs. When creating a new post, users can click on a new button that says 'GIF' and a search engine box will appear. A Tumblr representative told Wired that the feature will "create more interaction with artists through fixed GIF credits."
link_name: Tumblr introduces GIF search engine

status_message: With the help of military advances and arrests, polio cases in Pakistan decreased by 70% in 2015. Only 24 cases have been diagnosed since Jan. compared to 84 over the same period in 2014, WHO said June 4. Authorities have been fighting attacks on health workers by militants who believe polio vaccination programs are part of a scheme to sterilize Muslims.
link_name: Pakistani military efforts reduce polio cases by 70 percent

status_message: The Human Rights Campaign commissioned a review that found an internal work environment "exclusionary," "judgmental," and "sexist" by employees. The report, conducted by The Pipeline Project, was obtained by Buzzfeed through an anonymous source and published on June 3.
link_name: Internal review of Human Rights Campaign finds "White Mens Club"

status_message: A judge granted a new trial to the man convicted of murdering federal intern Chandra Levy. D.C. Superior Court Judge Gerald I. Fisher, the presiding judge in the original case, agreed to the motion on June 4 after prosecutors said they would drop their opposition to a new trial, even though they believe the original verdict was correct.
link_name: New trial granted to man convicted of killing federal intern Chandra Levy in 2001

status_message: Authorities in Italy arrested 44 politicians and business people on June 4 for allegedly fixing profitable public contracts connected to migrant reception centers in Rome. An investigation by Italy's national anti-corruption authority said they had uncovered a widespread network of wrongdoing and have issued search warrants for 21 other suspects.
link_name: 44 arrested in Italy tied to migrant corruption probe

status_message: California on June 3 gave clearance for the "Intolerant Jackass Act" to begin collecting signatures. The measure would require sensitivity training for proponents of the "Sodomite Suppression Act" and would force those pushing the anti gay-killing measure to donate $5,000 to an LGBT group.
link_name: In response to anti-gay ballot measure, California allows "Intolerant Jackass Act" to collect signatures

status_message: A court decided ex-president Hosni Mubarak will face a final retrial for the deaths of protesters during the uprising against his government in 2011. He was sentenced to life in prison, but it was overturned in Nov. 2014. Hundreds of people were killed by law enforcement in the weeks before he was forced from power.
link_name: Ex-Egyptian president Mubarak to face retrial for protester deaths

status_message: Lawmakers from Greece's ruling Syriza party on June 4 rejected reforms demanded by international lenders in exchange for additional loan disbursements. Although the full details of a plan by EU and IMF creditors was not released, some details were leaked including additional austerity measures.
link_name: Greece reject further austerity cuts demanded by foreign lenders

status_message: A fire broke out at a gas station in Ghana's capital of Accra on June 4, killing at least 78 people and sending nearly a dozen people to hospital with injuries, a spokesman for Ghana's national fire brigade said. Many people were seeking shelter at the station from torrential rains, which were believed to be linked to the accident.
link_name: Deadly explosion rocks gas station in Ghana's capital

status_message: Overnight June 3-4, rescuers began cutting through the hull of the Eastern Star in a delicate operation as hope is fading for finding many more survivors. Cranes were also brought to the scene. Nets were placed in the water to catch floating bodies.
link_name: Rescuers cut hull of capsized Chinese cruise ship amid bad weather

status_message: Two members of the Catalina Island Conservatory found a 17-foot oarfish on the morning of June 1. It likely washed up on shore on the island minutes earlier. The oarfish's organs and head were removed and sent to Cal State Fullerton for analysis.
link_name: Another rare oarfish washes up on Southern California island

status_message: An amendment blocking the Justice Dept. from intervening in state medical marijuana programs, passed 242 to 186 June 3. The amendment, brought by California Reps. Dana Rorhrabacher (R) and Sam Farr (D), does not apply to state recreational marijuana programs.
link_name: House votes to ban federal interference with state medical marijuana programs

status_message: The U.S. trade deficit declined $9.7 billion to $40.9 billion in April, despite rising 0.9% year-to-date, the Commerce Department said June 3. A decline in imports to $230.8 billion was cited as a reason for the decline. In March, the trade deficit hit the highest level in almost 6-1/2 years.
link_name: US trade gap falls slightly from 7-year high

status_message: Nix and Hydra, the 2nd and 3rd Plutonian moons, "wobble" unpredictably as they orbit the planet, creating the effect of a "cosmic dance with a chaotic rhythm", a NASA administrator said June 3. Both moons share a gravitational field with Pluto and the ice planet Charon.
link_name: NASA: Pluto moons Nix and Hydra wobble in chaos

status_message: The Wall Street Journal said June 3 that T-Mobile and Dish Networks are in merger talks, citing "people familiar with the matter." The report said that the financials have not yet been decided on but that the companies "are in close agreement what the combined company would look like." Neither company has commented.
link_name: WSJ: Dish and T-Mobile in merger talks

status_message: The Blackhawks scored a pair of goals in the third period in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals June 3 to defeat the Lightning 2-1.
link_name: Blackhawks win first game of Stanley Cup Finals

status_message: The North Carolina House approved a bill extending the waiting period for abortion procedures to 72 hours, as well as requiring doctors to report data regarding second trimester abortions, June 3. The current state waiting period for an abortion is 24 hours. The bill now goes on to Gov. Pat McCrory (R) for review.
link_name: North Carolina lawmakers approve 72-hour waiting period for abortions

status_message: On June 3, a Scottish High Court acquitted Coulson, who faced charges of perjury for testimony he gave during the trial of former Scottish MP Tommy Sheridan and his wife, Gail. Coulson told reporters, "I am obviously delighted by the judge's decision today. It was the right decision...I didn't lie." The case was reassessed in light of the phone hacking scandal.
link_name: Former News of the World editor Andy Coulson acquitted of perjury

status_message: Researchers at the European Organization for Nuclear Energy (CERN) are set to collect the first data that could help optimize the machine's magnets and solve the puzzle of dark matter, the institute reported June 3. The collider resumed smashing particles at a rate of 13 teraelectronvolts (TeV), just under the maximum of 14 TeV, on May 29.
link_name: Large Hadron Collider resumes smashing particles after two-year hiatus

status_message:
Ex-FIFA official admits to bribetaking in testimony 

Chuck Blazer, 70, told a U.S. federal judge in testimony unsealed June 3 that he and other officials accepted bribes from countries like France and South Africa in the run up to the 2010 World Cup. Blazer pleaded guilty to several charges, including racketeering, and agreed to help investigators in Nov. 2013.
link_name: Ex-FIFA official admits to bribetaking in testimony

status_message: The investigation into the death of 12-year-old Tamir Rice has concluded and was handed to the Cuyahoga County Prosecutor Tim McGinty on June 3.
link_name: Cleveland prosecutor receives results of police investigation in shooting death of Tamir Rice

status_message: The Saudi Ministry of Interior released the names of 16 suspects in the bombings of Shia mosques in Dammam and Qudayh June 3, offering a $1.3 million for information leading to their arrest. An additional offer of $1.9 million was extended for tips that could prevent future attacks, Reuters reported.
link_name: Saudi Arabia names suspects in bombing of Shia mosque

status_message: Archeologists and researchers from South Korea traveled to North Korea on June 2 to begin a project between the two nations that aims to exhume the Koryo dynasty's royal palace. It marks the first time people from the two countries will be working in the same place for "40 to 60 days per year" since the division began in 1945.
link_name: North and South Korea join forces to exhume ancient palace

status_message: 29.85 million shares of the San Francisco-based company Fitbit will be offered for $14 to $16 a share, according to a June 2 filing with the Security and Trade Commission. Fitbit is expected to price its IPO on June 17 and would be valued at $3.3 billion at the highest offering.
link_name: Fitbit hopes to raise $478 million in IPO

status_message: The NFL announced June 3 that Yahoo will stream the first free live game over the web. Yahoo will run the Oct. 25 Jacksonville Jaguars, Buffalo Bills game. Re/code said, according to "industry executives familiar with the NFL's negotiations" that Yahoo paid at least $20 million for the exclusive rights.
link_name: Yahoo to stream first NFL game over the web for free

status_message: Pakistan's election commission cancelled the result of local elections in May because women were prevented from voting. A candidate who won said he would challenge the decision. The results of two elections were also canceled for the same reason in 2013, when the country was plagued by violence following polls.
link_name: Pakistan overturns local election after women blocked from voting

status_message: The Red Cross has "spent or committed" $144 million to provide permanent housing and said it has helped provide permanent homes for 130,000 people. According to an investigative report from ProPublica and NPR, it has actually only built 6 in total. Nearly 190,000 homes were destroyed in the earthquake.
link_name: Report: Red Cross failed to administer earthquake response in Haiti

status_message: Gitmo detainee Majid Khan says interrogators hung him naked on a pole for days and did not feed him, doused his mouth, nose and genitals with ice water, kept him in total darkness for nearly a year, held him in a cell with biting insects, and practiced other forms of torture. Khan made a guilty plea deal in exchange for cooperation.
link_name: Gitmo detainee describes years of torture at CIA black site

status_message: Dr. Nabarro said the effort to rid Guinea of Ebola would take longer because the community there is not cooperating with health workers. Nigeria and Senegal were declared Ebola free last year, while Mali was in January. Liberia was declared Ebola free in May.
link_name: UN: Sierra Leone will be Ebola free in a 'matter of weeks'

status_message: Deputy U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken said June 3 that U.S.-led airstrikes had killed more than 10,000 suspected Islamic State fighters. He did not elaborate on how he determined the figure, which could not be verified. A day earlier, an international coalition approved an Iraqi plan to retake territory from the group.
link_name: Thousands of Islamic State suspects killed at start of 'three-year plan,' US says

status_message: Greece will not make a payment of 300 million euros ($335 million) due on June 5 without a deal with its international creditors, Filis said June 3. The payment is the first of 1.6 billion euros ($1.78 million) in June.
link_name: Greece reiterates it will not pay loans without a deal in place

status_message: The boat has come to a halt near shore after drifting downriver for two miles. Chinese state media said June 3 that at least 14 people had been confirmed dead. Over 150 divers are expected to be involved in the rescue operation by the end of June 3.
link_name: Rescue operation continues at capsized ship in China, over 400 still unaccounted for

status_message: President Obama signed the USA Freedom Act into law late on June 2 after the Senate passed the bill without further amendments in a 67-22 vote earlier in the day. The bill moves to limit the National Security Agency's ability to collect call data from telephone companies.
link_name: Senate advances bill to limit surveillance powers

status_message: In the wake of a investigative report that found airport security flaws, TSA acting administrator Melvin Carraway was reassigned to the department's Office of State and Local Law Enforcement. Acting deputy director Mark Hatfield will serve in his position on a temporary basis, the secretary of homeland security said on June 2.
link_name: TSA director reassigned after investigation reveals airport security failures

status_message: Adrian Peterson on June 2 told ESPN and other media outlets that he will return to Vikings practice. The team has not renegotiated his contract, despite the running back's vocalized concern about security for his $45 million deal, as it is not guaranteed.
link_name: Adrian Peterson returns to Vikings practice

status_message: The FBI has been deploying small planes that use surveillance technology while flying above dozens of U.S. cities and states, the AP reported June 2. The planes use fictitious company names as cover and some are equipped with technology that can identify thousands of people through their cellphones. Most of this is done without a judge's consent.
link_name: AP: FBI using small planes for surveillance in US

status_message: The U.S. House of Representatives proposed an appropriations bill June 2 that would block funds for an American embassy or other new diplomatic facility. Funds for a Cuban embassy in the U.S. would also be restricted.
link_name: US House panel introduces bill to block funding for Cuba embassy

status_message: A Delaware court on June 2 granted American Apparel a temporary restraining order against Dov Charney. The former CEO is prevented from "indirectly seeking the removal of any member of the Company's board of directors" and prevented from making disparaging remarks about to company to the press.
link_name: American Apparel takes out restraining order against former CEO Dov Charney

status_message: HSBC is preparing to lay off between 10,000 and 20,000 employees in a cost-cutting effort that will be announced at the bank's annual shareholders' meeting June 9, Sky News reported June 1, citing unnamed people with knowledge of the matter.
link_name: Sky News: HSBC to announce up to 20,000 layoffs to buoy earnings

status_message: "Our job was to write in a pro-government way, to interpret all events in a way that glorifies the government's politics and Putin personally."
link_name: Russian 'troll farm' responsible for fake political comments online sued by former employee

status_message: FIFA president Sepp Blatter will step down. "An extraordinary congress is to be called to elect my successor as soon as possible," Blatter said on June 2. FIFA held a news conference to announce the resignation.
link_name: Authorities tie top lieutenant of FIFA's Sepp Blatter to bribe money

status_message: With a vote of 83 to 14 on June 2, the Senate advanced the USA Freedom Act, a House-passed bill that would limit the National Security Agency's ability to collect call data from telephone companies. Amendments will now be considered and final passage is expected later in the day.
link_name: Senate advances bill to limit surveillance powers

status_message: In testimony prepared for a June 2 Congressional hearing, Kevin Kennedy of Takata said that many of the cars already recalled were repaired with an inflator, known as a "batwing" inflator, now believed to be tied to exploding air bags. There is no estimate on how many vehicles will be re-recalled.
link_name: Takata replacement air bags also recalled

status_message: Fiat Chrysler's U.S. sales grew 4% for the company's best May in over a decade. Jeep sales and Ram utility trucks were the best sellers of the 202,227 vehicles were sold, a larger figure than analysts anticipated. GM is expected to have risen 0.1% and Ford may have declined 3.1%, according to Bloomberg analysts.
link_name: Fiat Chrysler sales rise 4% in May

status_message: Harper Lee's much anticipated follow up to "To Kill A Mockingbird" has already broken the pre-order record for publisher Harper Collins. The book "won't have a huge amount of marketing," as "most people" in the United States have read Lee's "To Kill a Mockingbird." The book will be published on July 14.
link_name: Harper Lee's 'Go Set a Watchman' becomes the most pre-ordered book in publisher Harper Collins history

status_message: German chancellor Angela Merkel on June 1 hosted an emergency summit in Berlin for bailout monitors to settle differences regarding the Greek bailout. France's President Francois Hollande, European Commission president Jean-Claude Juncker, and leaders from the IMF and ECB were also present.
link_name: Goldman Sachs warns Greek default or new elections may be needed to solve debt crisis

status_message: U.S. authorities believe Jerome Valcke, FIFA's secretary general and Sepp Blatter's top lieutenant, "caused" $10 million in wire transfers tied to bribes, according to NY Times sources. Prosecutors say Valcke transferred the money in 2008 from FIFA to accounts controlled by soccer official Jack Warner. The indictment does not say Valcke knew the money was a bribe.
link_name: Authorities tie top lieutenant of FIFA's Sepp Blatter to bribe money

status_message: A judge on June 1 allowed police officers Timothy Loehmann and Frank Garmback at least 60 days to submit materials in the discovery process in the civil rights lawsuit by the Rice family. The officers were ordered to respond to allegations, even if they claim the right against self-incrimination. The 60-day hold does not apply to the city of Cleveland.
link_name: Cleveland judge delays part of trial in police shooting of 12-year-old Tamir Rice

status_message: The 43 homicides in Baltimore in May were the most in a month in 40 years, the Baltimore Sun reported. It was the city's deadliest month ever per-capita because the population is now less than it was in the 1970s. The death toll for the year reached 116. 108 nonfatal shootings occurred in May.
link_name: May was deadliest month in Baltimore in 40 years

status_message: Islamic State (IS) fighters advanced in Aleppo province in the beginning of June, rebel groups said, despite eight months of U.S.-led airstrikes. IS seized villages and was advancing on the main road to the Turkish border, a key entry point for fighters and supplies. Turkey was preparing for an influx of refugees.
link_name: Extremists advance as conflict rages in Syria's Aleppo

status_message: A judge in Quebec ruled June 1 that three tobacco companies must pay more than one million smokers in Quebec $15.5 billion Canadian dollars (US$12.4 billion) in damages in the largest-ever class action lawsuit in Canadian history.
link_name: Quebec court orders tobacco companies to pay US$12.4 billion to smokers

status_message: The French Red Cross faces up to $12.2 million in fines and damage pay after health and safety inspectors found it routinely violated overtime laws, Le Parisien newspaper reported May 31. The inspectors found no fewer than 3,800 violations among 480 employees at its Paris headquarters in 2014.
link_name: French Red Cross fined by inspectors for breaking overtime laws

status_message: A bill extending the waiting period for abortion procedures to 72 hours, as well as requiring doctors to report data regarding second trimester abortions, passed in the North Carolina Senate June 1. The current state waiting period for an abortion is 24 hours.
link_name: North Carolina Senate approves 72-hour waiting period for abortions

status_message: The river cruise ship Eastern Star capsized during a storm according to the Yangtze River navigation authorities. There were 458 people aboard including crew. Seven survivors swam to shore and informed authorities of the disaster, but it is unclear when the rescue effort, which is underway, started.
link_name: River cruise ship with over 450 aboard capsizes in central China

status_message: About 11,000 victims may recover their losses from Bernard Madoff's Ponzi scheme, Madoff Victim Fund's special master Richard Breeden said June 1. The U.S. Department of Justice must approve the claims, a number that could likely double. As of May 15, 54% of the claims received had been reviewed.
link_name: 11,000 more Maddoff victims to receive payout

status_message: In an 8-1 decision, the Supreme Court on June 1 ruled in favor of Anthony Elonis, who was convicted of violating a federal threat statute in the first ruling where the Court has addressed the implications of free speech on social media. Chief Justice John Roberts wrote "negligence is not sufficient to support a conviction."
link_name: In landmark case, Supreme Court rules in favor of man posting threats on Facebook

status_message: KFC, the biggest restaurant operator in China, said on June 1 that it will sue three companies for spreading rumors on social media. KFC asked for 1.5 million yuan ($242,000), plus apologies from each of the companies, who said the restaurant uses genetically modified chickens with six wings and eight legs.
link_name: KFC sues Chinese companies for social media rumors

status_message: An advanced trial of two immunotherapy drugs published May 31 showed skin cancer tumors reduced by as much as a third in 58% of patients for a period of 11.5 months on average. Some of the patients showed no benefit from the treatment, however, and 95.5% suffered side effects including rashes, fatigue, colitis and hypothyroidism.
link_name: Immunotherapy trial shows promise in treating skin cancer

status_message: Modern humans likely migrated from Egypt 50,000-60,000 years ago, scientists said in a study released in the end of May. An examination of genomes of 225 people from Egypt and Ethiopia found Egyptians more closely resembled people living in Europe and Asia. Scientists still question if people migrated via other African routes but left no trace, however.
link_name: Modern humans likely arrived in Europe and Asia from Egypt about 55,000 years ago

status_message: In an 8-1 vote, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled June 1 in favor of a Muslim woman denied a job at an Abercrombie & Fitch Co clothing store in Oklahoma in 2008 because she wore a head scarf for religious reasons.
link_name: Abercrombie discriminates against Muslim woman, Supreme Court rules

status_message: Goldman Sachs said on Monday that new elections and/or a default on Greek debt may be necessary to end the impasse with Greece's creditors. Without a deal in the coming weeks, Greece's government will run out of cash reserves.
link_name: Goldman Sachs warns Greek default or new elections may be needed to solve debt crisis

status_message: Poroshenko appointed Georgian ex-president Mikheil Saakashvili, who has been granted Ukrainian citizenship, as governor of Odessa, the site of deadly clashes a year earlier. Saakashvili, who is known for disputes with Russia's Putin, was summoned in 2014 by Georgian prosecutors for the 2005 death of Georgia's prime minister.
link_name: Ukraine president appoints controversial ex-Georgian president to govern contested region

status_message: Construction spending in the U.S. rose 2.2% in April to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $1 trillion, the highest level since November 2008. Spending had risen 0.5% in March. Residential construction rose 0.6% and non-residential activity jumped 3.1%. Government projects rose 3.3%, the largest increase for state and local projects in three years.
link_name: US construction spending rises in April to highest level since November 2008

status_message: Defending French Open women's champion Maria Sharapova (pictured) lost to Lucie Safarova 7-6, 6-4, in the fourth round on June 1. Sharapova had reached the French Open finals the previous three straight years, winning in 2012 and 2014.
link_name: French Open defending champion Sharapova loses in fourth round

status_message: On June 1, began removing padlocks attached by lovestruck tourists to two bridges above the River Seine. The Pont des Arts and Pont de l'Archeveche have become attractions in recent years, with lovers fastening their locks to the bridges before tossing the keys into the river.
link_name: Paris begins removing famed 'love locks' from bridges

status_message: Police officers killed at least 385 people in the first five months of 2015, the Washington Post reported May 30. The daily death toll of nearly 2.6 was more than double the 1.1 daily average over 10 years, according to FBI records based on voluntary reporting by police agencies.
link_name: US police shot and killed nearly 400 people in 2015

status_message: The cabinet of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on May 31 approved an amendment to laws against rock throwing that removes the need to prove intent of harm. The bill came as Netanyahu said international efforts to boycott Israel intend to "blacken" the country's reputation.
link_name: Israeli cabinet approves punishing rock-throwing with several years imprisonment

status_message: Intel Corp. agreed to buy Altera Corp. for nearly $16.7 billion in cash. Altera stockholders would receive about $54 a share. The company rejected the price in April in an earlier round of talks and is a 56% premium on what Altera was trading at on March 27. Altera's shares closed Friday at $48.85.
