link_name: Intel agrees to buy Altera for $16.7 billion

status_message: China's Ministry of Defense said June 1 that the country will hold live-fire ground and air exercises in Yunnan near the Burmese border. No other details were given other than that the drills will start June 2 and that non-Chinese-military aircraft should avoid the area.
link_name: China will conduct live-fire exercises near Burmese border

status_message: The Solar Impulse 2 was forced to land in Nagoya, Japan, June 1 due to inclement weather on its 120-hour flight path from China to Hawaii. The team's Betrand Piccard said that "we are not daredevils, we are explorers... the weather does not fit."
link_name: Weather forces solar-powered plane to land in Japan

status_message: On May 31, mainland Chinese officials met with both anti-Beijing and pro-Beijing Hong Kong lawmakers as well as HK Chief Executive CY Leung. Following the meetings, anti-Beijing lawmakers said that no compromise was given, which means that they will almost certainly veto Beijing's 2017 election scheme in a mid-June vote.
link_name: Hong Kong pro-democracy lawmakers say they will veto Beijing election plan

status_message: Senate Republicans said May 31 that they were unable to reach an agreement to extend the Patriot Act after opposition from Sen. Rand Paul during a rare Sunday session. The inaction means provisions in the Patriot Act will end at midnight. The Senate then voted to advance the compromise USA Freedom Act, with a final vote expected in the coming days.
link_name: Senate fails to reach deal on extending Patriot Act, advances compromise bill

status_message: Suspected Boko Haram fighters killed at least 29 people during attacks in Maidugur. On May 30, a suicide bomber killed 16 people at a mosque, while 13 lost their lives during rocket-propelled grenade attacks. On May 31, a bomb at a market in the same city wounded four people. Maiduguri is known as the birthplace of Boko Haram.
link_name: Suicide bomb and rocket launcher attacks kill 29 in Nigeria

status_message: The U.S. paid more than 130 suspected Nazi war criminals $20.2 million in benefits, according to a Social Security Administration's inspector general report due to be released the week of June 1.
link_name: US paid suspected Nazis $20 million in Social Security, govt. report says
'San Andreas' rocks weekend box office with $53.2 million

status_message: Bob Schieffer hosted his final episode of "Face the Nation" on May 31 after 24 years as the face of CBS' Sunday news program. He spent 46 years of his 58-year career at the network, covering the Pentagon, Congress, the State Dept., and the White House.
link_name: Bob Schieffer hosts final 'Face the Nation' after 46 years at CBS

status_message: U.S. Defense Sec. Ash Carter said May 31 that the shipping of live anthrax to 11 states and two countries was an "unfortunate incident," pledging to find those responsible and "hold them accountable." Carter said the Pentagon will make sure that "any public health consequences of this are avoided."
link_name: Pentagon chief pledges to hold people accountable for anthrax shipments
CNN: NBC trying to keep Brian Williams but in possible new role

status_message: A 44-year-old South Korean man who arrived in Hong Kong infected with MERS has been placed under quarantine along with 18 fellow passengers, Chinese health authorities said on May 30.
link_name: Hong Kong quarantines 18 following arrival of MERS-infected South Korean man

status_message: Beijing's ban on smoking in restaurants, offices and on public transportation went into effect on June 1. Smoking near hospitals and schools also becomes prohibited and state media reported that shops can no longer sell cigarettes within 100 meters of primary schools.
link_name: Beijing smoking ban takes effect

status_message: U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry, 71, broke his leg in a bike crash near Scionzier, France on May 31. Kerry was helicoptered to Geneva's main medical center, HUG, and is in stable condition. Kerry will return to Boston to receive treatment from a doctor who previously operated on his hip.
link_name: John Kerry breaks leg in bike accident, cuts short overseas trip

status_message: The Blackhawks advanced to their 3rd Stanley Cup Finals this decade with their win over Anaheim Ducks. Tampa Bay beat the New York Rangers in Game 7 on May 29 to advance to their second Stanley Cup final.
link_name: Chicago Blackhawks win the Western Conference Finals, face Tampa Bay for Stanley Cup Final

status_message: Joseph Biden III, known as Beau, died on May 30 at the age of 46, the vice president's office announced. Biden had been battling brain cancer since a small lesion was discovered on his brain in 2013. He was admitted to Walter Reed National Military Medical Center earlier in May.
link_name: Beau Biden, son of vice president, dies at 46

status_message: Sen. Rand Paul said May 30 on his website that he will fight to block authorization of the USA Freedom Act and the renewal of the Patriot Act.
link_name: Rand Paul promises to force expiration of NSA spying programs

status_message: On June 1, Paris will remove padlocks attached by lovestruck tourists to two bridges above the River Seine. Locks on the Pont des Arts and Pont de l'Archeveche have become attractions in recent years, but city officials say they have caused damage and pose a safety risk.
link_name: Paris plans to remove famed 'love locks' from bridges

status_message: Lawmakers in South Korea passed legislation May 29 that would outlaw services using private drivers who don't have a taxi license, making it the first country to do so. The law would effectively ban Uber's inexpensive uberX service nationwide by the end of 2015.
link_name: South Korea passes private taxi ban aimed at uberX

status_message: American citizen Mohamed Soltan was released from an Egyptian prison and is due to arrive in the U.S. on May 30. Soltan, 27, was sentenced to life in prison in April. He was arrested in 2013 during a crackdown on Islamists in Egypt.
link_name: Egypt releases American citizen who was sentenced to life in prison

status_message: The death toll in India passed 2,000 people on May 30, making it the second deadliest heatwave the country has experienced. Most of the deaths have occurred in the southern states of Telangana and Andhra Pradesh.
link_name: India heatwave death toll tops 2,000

status_message: A total of 4,243 migrants were rescued from boats off Libya's Mediterranean coast in last 24 hours, the Italian Coast Guard said on May 30.
link_name: Over 4,200 migrants rescued off Libya's coasts in one day

status_message: Former Maryland Gov. Martin O'Malley (D) announced his candidacy for president on May 30 before hundreds of supporters in Baltimore's Federal Hill Park. O'Malley told the crowd, that the American Dream is "hanging by a thread" and "the presidency is not a crown to be passed back and forth between two families."
link_name: Former Maryland Gov. Martin O'Malley announces presidential bid

status_message: The California Court of Appeal on May 27 rejected Bill Cosby's petition to dismiss a sexual assault lawsuit filed against him. Judy Huth said in a Dec. 2014 suit that she was molested at 15 by Cosby at the Playboy Mansion in 1974. Claiming blackmail, Cosby tried to get the suit dismissed in Dec. but the LA County Superior Court rejected his attempt.
link_name: Court rejects Bill Cosby's appeal to dismiss sexual assault lawsuit

status_message: Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto misrepresented the property value and circumstances under which he acquired a 1,000 square meter piece of land in the town of Valle de Bravo. According to documents acquired by Reuters May 28, the president initially claimed it was a gift from his father, but records show Pena Nieto purchased it himself in 1988.
link_name: Reuters: Mexican president misrepresented property deal to authorities

status_message: The Conservative government under Prime Minister David Cameron on May 28 released a new bill outlining a plan for Scottish devolution, including greater control over fiscal powers. It includes: 10% of UK value-added tax (VAT) revenues raised in Scotland and control over setting income tax rates.
link_name: UK unveils Scotland bill promising greater fiscal powers

status_message: Stocks closed lower May 29 on weaker-than-expected economic data. The Nasdaq closed down 0.55%. The Dow also closed down about 115 points, at 18,046. The S&P 500 and Dow industrials gained about 1% in May.
link_name: US stocks end day and week down, but posts gains overall in May

status_message: Hastert was paying a man to not go public with a claim that Hastert sexually abused him decades ago, according to multiple reports, first published by the Los Angeles Times, citing two federal law enforcement officials.
link_name: Former US House speaker Dennis Hastert indicted on banking-related charges

status_message: Pres. Obama will sign a two-month extension for transportation funding on May 29, the White House announced. A short-term extension bill was passed in the House on May 19 and the Senate on May 23. Funding was due to run out on May 31.
link_name: Pres. Obama to sign short-term transportation bill

status_message: Convicted Silk Road kingpin Ross Ulbricht was on May 29 sentenced to life in prison. Ulbricht, 31 years old, told the New York federal court overseeing his case earlier in the week that he knew it had to "take away" his "middle years," but asked for leniency so he could live his "old age" in peace.
link_name: Silk Road creator Ross Ulbricht sentenced to life in prison

status_message: A federal court on May 29 ruled that Idaho's Idaho's Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act, which bans abortion after 20 weeks, was in violation of the Supreme Court precedent protecting abortions up to the point of viability for a fetus, or 24 weeks.
link_name: Federal court declares Idaho 20-week abortion ban unconstitutional

status_message: New data from the European Central Bank on May 29 showed deposits at Greek banks fell by nearly 6 billion euros in a two month span. The dip in deposits from March (145 billion euros, $153 billion) to April (139.4 billion euros) is the lowest in over a decade. In January, deposits eclipsed 170 billion euros, and deposits rose above 240 billion euros in 2009.
link_name: Bank deposits in Greece hit a 10-year low

status_message: Prince Ali decided to withdraw from the voting before the second round of voting was completed. Neither Sepp Blatter nor Prince Ali bin al-Hussein received 2/3 of the votes in the first round. Blatter received 133 votes, while Ali received 73.
link_name: FIFA presidential election goes to second round after Blatter fails to secure 2/3 of votes

status_message: The FIFA presidential election will go to a second round after neither Sepp Blatter nor Prince Ali bin al-Hussein received a majority of the votes. Blatter received 133 votes, while Ali received 73. A second round of voting will get underway shortly.
link_name: FIFA presidential election goes to second round after Blatter fails to secure 2/3 of votes

status_message: A 2008 sample set shipped to Australia included live anthrax, Reuters reported in May 29. The samples were sent from the same army facility in Utah that shipped live anthrax to nine labs in the U.S. and one in South Korea.
link_name: Reuters: Live anthrax found in defense shipment to Australia

status_message: Police in Guatemala are investigating the death of a teenager caught on video, a scene that shows the girl bloodied and writhing in pain before being doused in gasoline and set ablaze. The teen allegedly participated in the murder of a taxi driver earlier this month, according to CNN on May 29.
link_name: Police investigating murder of Guatemala teen after video of mob lynching goes viral

status_message: Haiti's health ministry says 126 people have died from cholera and 15,000 people have been infected this year. The number of reported cases during the first four months of 2015 was about 400% higher than the figure reported in 2014. 2,400 cases were reported in April.
link_name: Cholera cases in Haiti nearly 400% greater than figure reported in 2014

status_message: The FCC unveiled plans to "reboot" its Lifeline phone program to include subsidies for low-income household broadband Internet access on May 28. Currently, eligible households receive $9.25 per month. With the new proposal, recipients could choose to spend that on broadband, phone services or both. The FCC is expected to vote on the proposal June 18.
link_name: FCC proposes subsidized access to broadband for low-income households

status_message: May 29 marks the last day of a 45-day review period, during which the House and Senate could pass a joint resolution to block a measure to remove Cuba from the State Dept.'s list of state sponsors of terrorism. The White House announced plans to remove Cuba on April 14. Cuba was first added to the list in 1982.
link_name: Cuba slated for release from U.S. state sponsors of terrorism list

status_message: Russian President Vladimir Putin on May 28 signed a decree to censor losses of Russian troops as classified in "special operations" during peacetime. Amnesty International said the decree has "sinister undertones" about Russia's military involvement in Ukraine.
link_name: Russian military hides casualties during peacetime

status_message: Officials on May 28 said that between 2011 and 2015, 15 Chinese nationals aimed to defraud Educational Testing Services and the College Board, which administers college entrance exams like the SATs. The conspirators either took tests for others or paid others to take tests for them, some using fake passports.
link_name: 15 Chinese nationals arrested in college entrance exam scheme

status_message: At a regional migrant crisis summit in Bangkok May 29, Myanmar refused to accept that its treatment of the 1.3 million Rohingyas in its western state of Arakan caused Southeast Asia's crisis. Thailand called on governments to address the "root causes" of the problem.
link_name: UN condemns Myanmar's treatment of Muslim minority

status_message: Australian prime minister Tony Abbott announced May 29 that he will allow government members of parliament a free conscience vote on the opposition leader's same-sex marriage bill. He said it was an important issue that ought to be owned by the parliament and not by any particular party.
link_name: Australian PM allows free vote on marriage equality

status_message: A Shi'ite mosque in Dammam, Saudi Arabia was the target of a car bomb on May 29. The bomb did not reach the al-Anoud mosque but killed four people nearby. This is the second attack on a Shi'ite mosque in Saudi Arabia in the last two weeks.
link_name: Car bomb near Shia mosque in Saudi Arabia's Dammam kills 4

status_message: An ancient skull showing signs of blunt force may shed light on the earliest murder case in human history, the New York Times reported May 27, citing a study by Spanish and American researchers. The skull, which was found in 50 fragments, appeared to have been fractured twice by a single object.
link_name: Ancient human skull points to earliest murder case on record

status_message: Shivashankar, 13, of Kansas, and Venkatachalam, 14, of Missouri, exhausted the spelling list and so both were declared winners. Shivashankar correctly spelled the word "scherenschnitte" and Venkatachalam correctly spelled the word "nunatak."
link_name: Two spelling bee winners, second year in a row

status_message: Social networking app Path announced on May 28 that it was being acquired by South Korean tech company Daum Kakao, which owns the popular messaging service KakoTalk. The majority of Path's users are from Indonesia. The terms of the deal were not disclosed.
link_name: Path sold to South Korean tech company Daum Kakao

status_message: Greenpeace promised to restart campaigns to cut air pollution, protect forests and boost solar power after Delhi's high court ordered the government on May 27 to unblock the agency's bank accounts.
link_name: Delhi court orders Modi government to unblock Greenpeace accounts

status_message: The U.S. Coast Guard closed beaches for 6.5 miles south of Santa Barbara after globs of a tar-like substance washed up May 28. Authorities are testing the oily substance to discover if it is related to the oil spill. The Manhattan Beach coastline outside Los Angeles was closed.
link_name: Californian beaches south of oil spill closed for cleanup

status_message: Hastert, 73, was indicted on federal banking charges and charges of lying to FBI agents May 28 for allegedly concealing a cash withdrawal of $952,000 by withdrawing amounts below the $10,000 reportable limit on banking transactions. The charges carry a penalty of up to 5 years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
link_name: Former US House speaker Dennis Hastert indicted on banking-related charges

status_message: Amazon on May 28 announced it would introduce free same-day shipping for Prime members in 14 major U.S. metropolitan areas, including the Greater Los Angeles Area, Seattle and the Bay Area. Members must place orders of at least $35 before noon and will receive the orders by 9pm the same day.
link_name: Amazon Prime introduces free same-day delivery in 14 cities

status_message: Sundar Pichai, SVP of Android, Chrome and Apps at Google, said at the company's annual I/O developers conference May 28 that 75% of Gmail's 900 million active users access mail on their mobile phones. The number of users has more than doubled from 425 million in 2012.
link_name: Gmail has 900 million active users, 75% on mobile

status_message: JPMorgan is set to lay off over 5,000 employees by 2016, the WSJ reported May 28, citing sources familiar with the matter. The layoffs, which will cut the bank's workforce by 2%, have already affected 1,000 employees. They are part of a plan to reduce expenses by $109.4 million in 2015.
link_name: WSJ: JPMorgan set to lay off 5,000 employees by 2016

status_message: The special report from Vice aired on HBO on February 27 to critical acclaim. The Mayo Clinic will announce on May 29 that the documentary drove about 10,000 people to donate more than $1 million dollars to the Mayo Clinic Cancer Center, a sum matched by Vice Media CEO Shane Smith.
link_name: 'Killing Cancer', Vice's HBO documentary, raises $2 million in donations

status_message: Gov. Chris Christie will call for an end to Common Core standards in the state of New Jersey, according to excerpts of a speech he is expected to give on May 28. He is also expected to assemble a team of educators, legislators and parents to create state-specific education standards for his consideration.
link_name: Gov. Chris Christie expected to pull Common Core standards in New Jersey

status_message: Serial announced two new seasons in a newsletter on May 27. Season two is expected to air in the fall and fans should expect season three in the spring of 2016. Details about the cases are unknown to the public but the producers said they are "no less interesting" than the Adnan Syed story from season one.
link_name: Two new seasons of Serial podcast to begin this fall

status_message: Olympus said it had received a subpoena from federal investigators in March that "seeks information relating to duodenoscopes that Olympus manufactures and sells" in connection to superbug outbreaks, the Los Angeles Times said May 28.
link_name: Justice Dept. to investigate scope maker Olympus over recent superbug outbreaks

status_message: Arkansas Supreme Court said on May 28 that it will not hear new arguments on whether or not same-sex marriage in the state should be legalized, leaving a year-long stay. The ban will be in place until arguments are heard and a ruling is passed down.
link_name: Arkansas Supreme Court won't hear new arguments in same-sex marriage case

status_message: Google Photos boasts unlimited cloud storage for photos under 16 megapixels and 1080p videos. Anything larger will be stored for free, but in a compressed format. Media can be searched for with keywords and tricks that make collages and GIFs are also a feature.
link_name: Google announces unlimited photo storage

status_message: This year, Saudi Arabia executed 90 people as of May 28, equalling the total number of executions that occurred in the Kingdom in 2014, according to Amnesty International. Almost half of the executions this year have been drug-related offenses.
link_name: Saudi Arabia executes 90th person this year, meeting 2014's total

status_message: Trevor Noah will host his first episode of "The Daily Show" on September 28. Jon Stewart's last day as host will be August 6, he said April 20.
link_name: Trevor Noah begins as host of 'The Daily Show' on Sept. 28

status_message: Heightened border security measures have brought the flow of illegal immigrants into the U.S. to its lowest point in at least two decades, especially those coming from Mexico, Pew research published in the Washington Post said May 28. The nation's population of illegal immigrants dropped by about 1 million.
link_name: Pew: Illegal immigration hits 20-year low, drops by 1 million

status_message: Shares rose 7.7% May 28 to $57.35, a four-month high, after CEO Nick Woodman announced the company's plans to develop a drone. Pricing and other specifics about the product will be announced at a later time. The stock was down 16% for the year a day prior.
link_name: GoPro shares rise to four-month high after plans for drone announced

status_message: Sandvine reported May 28 that Netflix accounted for 36.5% of all downstream Internet bandwidth during peak hours during March in North America, up from 34.9% in the second half of 2014 and 31.6% in 2013.
link_name: During peak hours, Netflix bandwidth accounts for 37% of internet traffic

status_message: UEFA said May 28 that it will not boycott the upcoming FIFA presidential election, which is still set to take place tomorrow despite the corruption scandal that has plunged the organization into crisis. UEFA president Michel Platini did confirm, however, that he had asked Blatter to step down.
link_name: European soccer's leading body calls for FIFA presidential election to be postponed

status_message: The Shanghai Composite closed down 6.5% May 28 to 4620.27. Hong Kong's Hang Shen Index was down 2.23% to 27,454.31 while the Shenzhen Composite was down 5.52% to 2,756.93. Part of the downturn, after seven straight days of increases on the Shanghai market, was in reaction to stricter margin trading lending by banks.
link_name: Shanghai composite falls 6.5%, Hong Kong index down 2.23%

status_message: Jawbone filed a lawsuit against Fitbit in California State Court on May 28, claiming systematically plundering of confidential information from Jawbone employees they hired who stole intellectual property from Jawbone prior to leaving the company.
link_name: Fitbit accused of stealing secrets and employees from Jawbone

status_message: Queen Elizabeth II outlined the newly reelected Conservative government's agenda May 27, including a referendum on EU membership. The EU referendum bill will go to parliament May 28. Cameron has banned EU citizens living in the UK from voting in the referendum, which may happen in 2017.
link_name: Queen opens UK parliament with referendum announcement

status_message: U.S. District Court Judge Rudolph Contreras on May 27 ordered a gradual release of Clinton's emails by the State Department every 30 days, starting in June. Contreras has set a timetable so the last of the emails would be released in January 2016, ruling that it was in the public interest.
link_name: Judge sets schedule for release of Clinton emails every 30 days

status_message: A 23-page pitch being sent to advertisers in June claims that 60% of smartphone users, aged 13 to 34, are active on Snapchat. The pitch was reported in a May 26 Bloomberg profile of Snapchat CEO Evan Spiegel.
link_name: Snapchat boasts 2 billion daily video views in advertising push

status_message: Navy Region Hawaii confirmed on Facebook that the dock was damaged and that tourist visits to the memorial had been suspended while damage was assessed.
link_name: Pearl Harbor's USS Arizona Memorial closed after navy ship hits dock

status_message: MySanAntonio listed names of 11 missing people and reported 10 people dead in Texas May 28. With more storms forecast, the toll continues to rise as authorities pull bodies out of swollen rivers, the BBC reported May 27. Gov. Greg Abbott declared a state of disaster in 24 counties May 25.
link_name: Floods leave several people missing and 19 dead in Texas and Oklahoma

status_message: After Adrian Peterson missed the second day of organized team activities on May 27, Minnesota Vikings' head coach Mike Zimmer made it clear that the team has no intentions of trading the running back. Peterson wants out because he is not happy with the way the team treated him after he was indicted on child abuse charges. Peterson is under contract through the 2017 season.
link_name: Vikings' coach: Adrian Peterson will play for us or nobody else

status_message: The Nebraska Legislature voted 30 to 19 on May 27 to override Gov. Pete Ricketts' veto of a bill that repeals the state's death penalty law. The bill passed the legislature a week previously by a 32-15 vote. Ricketts lobbied three senators whose votes were needed to successful block the veto but ultimately only two voted in favor of the governor.
link_name: Nebraska ends death penalty, first time in 40 years by a conservative US state

status_message: Italian officials repatriated 25 artifacts, including rare books, vases and frescoes from the Etruscan era and 1st Century Italy, in a ceremony in Rome May 26. Phillips welcomed the step, saying it meant "returning some important artifacts to their rightful home in Italy."
link_name: Italy repatriates dozens of looted historic artifacts from the United States

status_message: Walmart and Tracy Morgan settled a lawsuit on May 27 brought by the comedic actor who was seriously injured in a June 7, 2014 car accident involving one of the company's trucks on the New Jersey Turnpike. Terms of the settlement have not been disclosed.
link_name: Tracy Morgan and Walmart settle car accident lawsuit

status_message: Russian officials on May 27 weighed in to the ongoing corruption investigation into FIFA, calling it an "illegal extraterritorial use of U.S. law" and questioning the investigation's timing. The 14-count indictment does not include any Russian officials.
link_name: Russian officials: FIFA probe a conspiracy to undermine 2018 World Cup bid

status_message: The Nasdaq closed May 27 up 1.5% from its previous closing high of 5,092.09. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up about 120 points. News that Greece was near a deal to negotiate its debt payments helped raise the market.
link_name: Nasdaq sets record, Dow up 130 points

status_message: The head of European soccer's leading body UEFA on May 27 released a statement calling for the FIFA presidential election to be postponed, and threatened to boycott the FIFA Congress May 29, adding new FIFA presidential elections should "be organized within the next six months."
link_name: European soccer's leading body calls for FIFA presidential election to be postponed

status_message: The EU's European Commission announced a plan on May 27 that asks member nations including; Spain, France and Germany to accept the relocation of 40,000 Syrians and Eritreans migrants from Italy and Greece over the next two years. This is the second plan that includes a quota system the EU has put forward in May.
link_name: EU asks member nations to accept relocation of 40,000 migrants

status_message: ESPN named Chris Connelly interim Editor-In-Chief of Grantland on May 27. Connelly is an ABC News contributor and has also provided reports for ESPN's E:60 and Outside The Lines. Prior to joining ESPN in September 2001, Connelly was a movie correspondent and host at MTV.
link_name: Chris Connelly named interim Editor-In-Chief of Grantland

status_message: The ownership of Martin Luther King Jr.'s traveling Bible and 1964 Nobel Peace Prize will be decided by court-ordered mediation. In a May 27 hearing, both sides told Judge Robert McBurney they had made significant progress toward an agreement. McBurney instructed the parties to complete mediation by Sept. 30.
link_name: Family dispute over Martin Luther King Jr.'s Nobel prize and Bible heads to mediation

status_message: At Re/Code's "Code" conference on May 27, CBS CEO Les Moonves acknowledged CBS has held talks with Apple and that they would "probably" sign a deal to carry the network on Apple's expected streaming service.
link_name: Moonves says CBS will "probably" sign a deal with Apple to stream CBS

status_message: Bob Schieffer of CBS will host his last episode of "Face the Nation" on May 31. He began working for CBS News in 1969 after walking into the bureau chief's office without an appointment and a secretary mistook him for a different 'Bob', longtime NBC reporter Robert Hager, who was scheduled for an interview.
link_name: Bob Schieffer to host last 'Face the Nation' on May 31

status_message: Tony Blair will step down in June after eight years as envoy for the quartet group of Middle East negotiators, made up of the U.S., European Union, United Nations and Russia. The news leaked May 27. Blair was criticized for deteriorating relations with the Palestinian Authority and potential conflicts of interest from conducting business in the region.
link_name: Tony Blair to resign from Middle East envoy post

status_message: Oregon Senate on May 26 unanimously passed a bill to outlaw upskirt photography, proposing the act be considered a misdemeanor in the state. The vote came months after a 61-year-old man was found to have been within the limits of the law after taking a photo up a teenager's skirt in a Target store.
link_name: Oregon lawmakers aim to criminalize upskirt photos

status_message: Penn State on May 26 kicked Kappa Delta Rho off campus for at least three years, finding that some fraternity members engaged in sexual harassment, hazing, and created a "persistent climate of humiliation for several females." Investigators found that members "collectively" knew about the activity.
link_name: Penn State fraternity shut down for 3 years for sexual harassment, hazing

status_message: Greece will begin drafting an accord with creditors on May 27, a source told Bloomberg. The source said disagreements still remain with the creditors, but a deal and a long-term solution on debt is close.
link_name: Bloomberg: Greece to draft deal with creditors on May 27

status_message: Two reactors at the Sendai nuclear power plant in southern Japan are set to resume operations, regulators said on May 27. The plant, owned by Kyushu Electric Power, secured the final permit after Japan's Nuclear Regulation Authority approved the company's new operational safety plans. One reactor will restart in July and the other in September.
link_name: Japan set to restart first nuclear plant since Fukushima disaster

status_message: Negotiations could continue past a June 30 deadline, Iranian nuclear negotiator Abbas Araqchi said on Iranian state TV on May 27. "We want a good deal that covers our demands," he said. France's ambassador to the U.S. said a day earlier that meeting the deadline was "very unlikely" due to unresolved technical issues.
link_name: Nuclear negotiations could pass June deadline, Iran envoy says

status_message: Authorities arrested five Axact executives including chief executive Shoaib Ahmed Shaikh on May 27. They face charges of fraud, forgery, illegal electronic money transfers, money laundering and violating Pakistan's electronic crimes act, law enforcement officials said.
link_name: Police arrest executives of Pakistani company accused of online degree scam

status_message: Saudi airstrikes in the capital of Sanaa killed at least 40 people and injured 100, Yemeni state news said May 27, while airstrikes on the Yemeni-Saudi border killed at least 30 people. Saudi airstrikes also heavily damaged Yemen's largest military port in the Red Sea city of Hodaida, a local official told Reuters.
link_name: Saudi airstrikes kill dozens across Yemen

status_message: The trial opened May 26 for Tom Hayes, a former currency trader for UBS and Citigroup banks. It is the first criminal trial in the Libor-rigging scandal. UK prosecutors called him the "ringmaster" of a conspiracy to fix lending rates between banks.
link_name: UK prosecutors call ex-trader a rates-rigging 'ringmaster'

status_message: At least 3.2 billion people are using the Internet in 2015, according to a UN International Telecommunications Union (ITU) report released May 26. Internet connectivity increased seven-fold to 43% of the global population in 2000-2015.
link_name: Global Internet penetration reaches 3.2 billion, UN says

status_message: Former Petrobras international director Nestor Cervero was sentenced May 26 to five years for money laundering. The federal court also fined him 543,000 reais ($172, 288). His lawyer said he would appeal. He is the second Petrobras director convicted in the ongoing corruption inquiry.
link_name: Second Petrobras director convicted of corruption

status_message: Harvard's Woolly mammoth revival team edited the elephant genome to develop a heavy coat and excess fat and blood with mammoth DNA. Shapiro called it a "booster shot" against extinction, the Telegraph reported May 23. Hybrid DNA inserted into a donor egg could be implanted into a surrogate elephant.
link_name: Scientists explore woolly mammoth DNA to stop elephant extinction

status_message: Six FIFA officials were arrested on corruption charges, including wire fraud, racketeering and money laundering spanning two decades. Bribes totaling more than $100 million were linked to media, marketing and sponsorship rights of tournaments in the U.S. and Latin America, the Swiss Federal Office of Justice said.
link_name: FIFA officials arrested on corruption charges

status_message: On May 26, the Cavaliers reached their first NBA Finals since 2007 during LeBron James' first stint with the team. Cleveland swept the Hawks with a 118-88 Game 4 win at home. James will appear in the NBA Finals for the fifth consecutive year, the first player since the 1960's to do so.
link_name: Cavaliers advance to NBA Finals with sweep of Hawks

status_message: The Ohio legislature on May 26 held its first hearing regarding a concurrent resolution that calls on Major League Baseball to reinstate Pete Rose. The resolution also urges MLB to make Rose eligible for baseball's Hall of Fame. If passed, the resolution would not be legally binding but sponsors hope it will pressure MLB to act.
link_name: Ohio lawmakers begin hearings calling on MLB to reinstate Pete Rose

status_message: Tax returns filed by hundreds of thousands of U.S. taxpayers were accessed by hackers using an online service provided by the Internal Revenue Service (IRS), the AP reported May 26. The service features a screening page that requires a social security number (SSN), date of birth and street address.
link_name: Hackers stole information from 100,000 taxpayers, IRS says

status_message: Hillary Clinton-led U.S. State Dept. approved arms contracts worth $151 billion with 16 countries that donated to the Clinton Foundation, including Algeria, Saudi Arabia and the UAE, an IBTimes investigation revealed May 26. The foundation has come under scrutiny for its donations from foreign governments.
link_name: State Dept. under Clinton approved arms deals with Clinton Foundation donors

status_message: South Sudan is on the brink of economic disaster and potential famine. By July, 4.6 million people in the Sudan will face severe food shortages, the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization announced on May 26. Supply routes for humanitarian aid have been cut off due to fighting between government and rebel forces.
link_name: South Sudan faces severe food shortage, UN says

status_message: Two of three judges in the Fifth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans ruled May 26 to deny a bid to lift a temporary hold on President Obama's immigration action. The ruling concerns lawsuits against the action in 26 states. In the decision, judges clarified the federal government could not demonstrate the "merits of its appeal of the injunction".
link_name: Appeals court denies bid to lift temporary hold on Obama immigration action

status_message: By the end of 2015 inward-facing video cameras will be installed in Amtrak trains that travel through Washington, New York and Boston, the company announced on May 26. Amtrak's Keystone Service trains that run between New York, Philadelphia and Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, will also be equipped. The cameras will be mandatory on all new trains.
link_name: Amtrak set to install inward-facing cameras

status_message: Tourism by U.S. citizen traveling to Cuba has risen 36% this year, the AP reported on May 26. From Jan. 1 to May 9 of this year, 51,458 Americans visited Cuba. A large portion of those traveling arriving by way of third countries like Mexico.
link_name: US tourism to Cuba up 36% since last year

status_message: The Cleveland police department reached an agreement with the Justice Dept. on May 26 that prohibits officers from using force against people who talk back or run away, firing warning shots, and pistol whipping. A independent monitor will oversee the department's progress.
link_name: Cleveland reaches deal with Justice Dept. over police force and misconduct

status_message: The Supreme Court said May 26 that it will hear the case brought by Project on Fair Representation, a Texas-based conservative group, which has appealed the "one person, one vote" rule that has been enforced in all election districts since 1964's Reynolds v. Sims. The group believes districts should reflect the number of eligible voters, not just the total number of people.
link_name: Supreme Court to hear Texas case on drawing voting district lines

status_message: Worldwide smartphone shipments will grow 11.3% in 2015, according to a May 26 IDC forecast. That's down from growth of 27.6% in 2014. IDC attributed the slowdown to slowing growth in China and an overall slowdown in shipments of Android smartphones.
link_name: Smartphone shipments to slow in 2015 as top markets mature

status_message: Nigeria's fuel supply was expected to return to normal within 24 hours of May 25. The government agreed to pay $800 million owed to the Independent Petroleum Marketers Association of Nigeria (IPMA) before President-elect Muhammadu Buhari takes over from Goodluck Jonathan May 29.
link_name: Nigeria fuel supply restored after government pays distributors

status_message: Diana Bedwell, 68, and the body of her husband, Cecil Knutson, 79, were found by off-road drivers, police said May 25. Their car was found stuck in mud. Bedwell said they had been trying to take a shortcut on May 10 when they got lost in the Indian reservation.
link_name: California couple found two weeks after car was trapped, wife survives

status_message: The effectiveness of the government's emergency response to the Oct. 2014 shooting was hampered by the absence of computer technicians and senior executives at the operations center, according to a May 25 Canadian Press report based on documents it obtained under the Access to Information Act.
link_name: Response team was short-handed during Canada's parliament shooting in October 2014

status_message: The closed-door trial for Jason Rezaian began May 26 in Tehran, according to Reuters, which cited the semi-official Tasnim news agency. His family said it has been barred from attending the trial.
link_name: Espionage trial in Iran of Washington Post reporter Jason Rezaian will be closed to the public

status_message: Apple confirmed May 25 that Jony Ive was promoted from senior vice president of design to chief of design, a new position at Apple. Richard Howarth and Alan Dye will take over the day-to-day running of industrial design and user interface design, respectively.
link_name: Jony Ive named Apple's chief of design

status_message: Bangladesh banned Ansarullah Bangla Team (ABT) on May 26 after a recommendation by police based on evidence that ABT had threatened and killed writers. The ban came after international condemnation of the violence against writers in Bangladesh.
link_name: Bangladesh bans militant group accused of attacking bloggers

status_message: The U.S.' Sloane Stephens, 22, defeated fellow American Venus Williams, 34, in the first round of the French Open 7-6, 6-1. Williams also lost in the first round in Paris in 2013.
link_name: Sloane Stephens defeats Venus Williams in first round of French Open

status_message: Taxi drivers in Mexico City held a protest march on May 25 against Uber, a smaller competitor called Cabify and the city government for not stopping an "illegal" service. Hundreds of drivers used their cars to stop traffic on some streets. Uber offered free rides in the city in response.
link_name: Mexico City taxi drivers protest Uber, unlicensed drivers

status_message: The Rocket's James Harden had 45 points in Game 4 of the Western Conference Finals to lead Houston to a 128-115 home win over the Warriors. Golden State, which leads the series three games to one, had a scare when NBA MVP Stephen Curry fell and hit his head, but he was able to return to the game.
link_name: Rockets stave off elimination against Warriors

status_message: A settlement could be announced as early as May 26 between Cleveland and the Justice Department over a number of cases of police misconduct and excessive force, according to the New York Times, who cited people briefed on the case.
link_name: 71 protesters arrested after officer's acquittal in Cleveland

status_message: Dozens of people have been reported injured and at least 13 are dead and 88 injured after tornadoes touched down in the northern Mexico city. Many cars were seen overturned and on top of buildings.
link_name: 10 dead after tornado strikes Mexican city of Ciudad Acuna

status_message: 35 chlorine attacks have occurred in Syria at the hands of the Assad regime since March 16 according to The Guardian, citing Syrian civil defense workers and doctors documenting the incidents. The most recent attack on May 19 injured 1,000 and killed 9.
link_name: Guardian: Assad regime responsible for 35 chlorine attacks in Syria since March 16

status_message: Conservative challenger Andrzej Duda (pictured) defeated centrist incumbent Bronislaw Komorowski for the presidency with 51.55% of the votes, The State Electoral Commission said May 25. Komorowski, who garnered 48.45% of the votes, conceded defeat minutes after poll data was released on May 24.
link_name: Polish president concedes defeat in runoff vote

status_message: Over 500 people have died from heat-related illness in India, state officials said May 25. In Andhra Pradesh, 340 people died over the last week. At least 10 people died of heat in the eastern state of West Bengal.
link_name: Heatwave kills hundreds in India, 'no relief' expected

status_message: Charter Communications is closing in on a deal to buy Time Warner Cable at about $195 a share, with $100 in cash and the rest in its own stock, Bloomberg said on May 25. The deal could be announced on May 26. Bright House Networks, a smaller cable company Charter is attempting to buy, will be included in the deal.
link_name: Bloomberg: Charter Communications near deal to buy Time Warner Cable

status_message: The espionage trial of Jason Rezaian will be closed to the public, including his wife and his mother, a statement from Washington Post Executive Editor Martin Baron said May 25. Attempts by The Post to retain a visa to cover the trial in Tehran were ignored. Rezaian's trial begins May 26.
link_name: Espionage trial in Iran of Washington Post reporter Jason Rezaian will be closed to the public

status_message: A total of 430 heat-related deaths in India were reported by May 25. In Andhra Pradesh, 250 people died May 20-May 24, according to officials cited in the Hindustan Times. At least 10 people died of heat in the eastern state of West Bengal.
link_name: Heatwave kills hundreds in India, 'no relief' expected

status_message: The U.S. and Turkey have a "principle agreement on providing air support" to Syrian rebels, Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said, the Turkish Daily Sabah reported May 24. Cavusoglu did not give details. The U.S. government did not immediately comment.
link_name: Turkey and US to give air cover to Syrian rebels, Turkish minister says

status_message: Authorities will pursue criminal charges against two male team managers, the Sri Lankan sports ministry's spokesman said May 23. He did not name the officials accused. A probe was launched in November and a report was submitted to the ministry on May 21.
link_name: Sri Lankan female cricketers accuse team officials of forcing sex to be on team

status_message: Burundi opposition parties suspended talks with the government May 24 following the killing of Union for Peace and Development party leader Zedi Feruzi in a drive-by shooting on May 23. On May 22 at least three people were killed in a grenade attack on a market in the capital of Bujumbura.
link_name: Burundi talks called off after opposition leader killed

status_message: Guinea families spread Ebola by transporting disguised bodies past inspection points to places where they want to bury loved ones, AP reported May 22. WHO deployed a team May 20 due to a spike in infections. At least 27 new cases were reported.
link_name: Guinea families transporting disguised Ebola corpses

status_message: Historians using radar hope to find the sarcophagus of Henry I, the youngest son of William the Conqueror, in a parking lot or playground, the Guardian reported May 23. They are searching for ruins of Reading Abbey, destroyed during the 16th-century dissolution of monasteries, where Henry was laid to rest in 1135.
link_name: Historians who found Richard III's remains search for Henry I

status_message: The Bank of England was forced to admit May 22 that it is conducting secret research on the financial implications of a British EU exit after an email about the project was accidentally sent to the Guardian newspaper. The bank said the fact that it was carrying out such work "should not come as a surprise."
link_name: Bank of England accidentally reveals secret research on British EU exit

status_message: The Cavs went up 3-0 with a 114-111 overtime win May 24 on the back of LeBron James' triple-double (37 points, 18 rebounds and 17 assists). The Hawks were without Al Horford, who was ejected for an elbow on Cavs' backup guard Matthew Dellavedova, and Kyle Korver, who was injured in Game 2 going for a loose ball with Dellavedova.
link_name: Cavs up 3-0 on triple-double by Lebron James

status_message: Olmert was sentenced to eight months in prison and fined 100,000 shekels (about $25,000). The sentence was in addition to six years in prison in a separate bribery case. Olmert will remain out of prison during a 45-day stay as his lawyer appeals the decision.
link_name: Former Israeli Prime Minister Olmert imprisoned for corruption

status_message: "Tomorrowland" is expected to make a disappointing $40.7 million at the domestic box office over the May 22-25 holiday weekend. The film cost at least $180 million to make.
link_name: 'Tomorrowland' disappoints over slow holiday weekend

status_message: Cleveland Police Chief Calvin Williams said on May 24 that 71 people have been arrested since officer Michael Brelo was found not guilty the day before.
link_name: 71 protesters arrested after officer's acquittal in Cleveland

status_message: Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah, speaking to supporters May 24 from an undisclosed location on a large video screen, pledged that the group's fighters will continue to support Syria's government forces. He said Sunni extremist groups represent an "existential threat."
link_name: Hezbollah leader vows expanded involvement in Syrian civil war

status_message: Following Poland's May 24 vote, exit polls showed conservative challenger Andrzej Duda defeating centrist incumbent Bronislaw Komorowski for the presidency by a 53% to 47% margin. Komorowski conceded defeat minutes after poll data was released. Final results are expected May 25.
link_name: Polish president concedes defeat in runoff vote

status_message: Russia's Vladimir Putin signed a law on May 23 giving prosecutors the power to declare foreign organizations undesirable if they threaten Russia's constitution, security or defense.
link_name: Putin signs law allowing Russia to shutter 'undesirable' foreign organizations

status_message: Juan Pablo Montoya won the 99th Indianapolis 500 on May 24, his second victory after previously taking the checkered flag in 2000. Montoya maintained his lead over Penske teammate Will Power for the final two laps to win the race.
link_name: Juan Pablo Montoya wins Indy 500 for second time
French film 'Dheepan' wins top prize at 2015 Cannes Film Festival

status_message: Greece will be unable to repay $1.76 billion to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) by a June 19 deadline, the country's interior minister said May 24.
link_name: Greece will miss June 19 IMF payment, interior minister says

status_message: Mass graves near suspected human trafficking camps were discovered close to the border of Thailand, Malaysian officials announced on May 24. Local reports said the graves contain hundreds of migrants.
link_name: Mass graves containing suspected human trafficking victims found in Malaysia

status_message: A court in Cairo on May 23 acquitted 17 people charged with breaking the country's protest law after several of them came forward as witnesses to the police killing poet and fellow protester Shaimaa El-Sabbagh. Members of the group who were acquitted said they are disappointed the protest law remains in place.
link_name: Egyptian human rights lawyer rearrested

status_message: John Nash, 86, and his wife Alicia Nash, 82, died after the taxi they were in hit a guardrail on the New Jersey Turnpike at about 4:30pm on May 23, police said May 24.
link_name: 'A Beautiful Mind' mathematician John Nash and wife die in taxi accident

status_message: Iraqi army forces, including Shiite militiamen and allied Sunni tribesmen, launched a counterattack against Islamic State insurgents on May 23. The counter-offensive is the first by Iraqi forces since Ramadi fell on May 17.
link_name: Iraqi fighters launch counterattack against IS near Ramadi
Police charge one, search for more suspects in DC mansion quadruple murder

status_message: By a vote of 62.07% in favor and 37.93% against, Ireland legalized gay marriage. Almost 2 million people took part in the historic vote, the results were announced on May 23.
link_name: Ireland overwhelmingly approves gay marriage by popular vote

status_message: Hundreds of California farmers volunteered to decrease their water use by 25%. State regulators accepted the proposal on May 22. The farmers were prompted to act in order to avoid tougher mandatory cuts. Farmers have until June 1 to opt-in to the program and will have to present plans on how they intend to cut their water use.
link_name: Farmers in California agree to voluntary water cut

status_message: The State Dept. released 296 email documents linked to Benghazi from former Sec. State Hillary Clinton's private email account on May 22. The State Dept. said the emails do not change "the essential facts or our understanding of the [Benghazi] events." At the FBI's request, one email was classified on May 22.
link_name: State Dept. releases Benghazi emails from Clinton's private account
NYT: DOJ finds criminal wrongdoing in GM ignition switch probe
Mozilla revamps smartphone strategy after failing to catch on

status_message: The Senate did not reauthorize the USA Patriot Act and failed to pass the USA Freedom Act, which would reform the NSA's bulk collection of phone data while preserving other provisions of the Patriot Act, after multiple late night votes during a session that ended in the early morning hours of of May 23.
link_name: Senate fails to renew Patriot Act or pass NSA bulk data collection reforms

status_message: Plains Pipeline, the company responsible for the oil spill in California, was issued a corrective action order by federal regulators on May 22. The order says the company must take steps to protect the public, property and the environment from the potential hazards caused by the pipeline failure.
link_name: Crews continue to clean up Santa Barbara oil spill

status_message: Microsoft was in "significant" talks with Salesforce earlier this spring over a possible acquisition before these talks broke down over valuation, CNBC reported May 22. Microsoft was prepared to offer $55 billion for the company but was told it would take $70 billion for the deal to go through.
link_name: CNBC: 'Significant' talks between Microsoft, Salesforce broke down over price

status_message: Michael Sam signed a two-year contract to play for the Canadian Football League's Montreal Alouettes, the team announced on May 22. Sam said he was "excited and proud" to join the Alouettes, who will open the 2015 CFL season June 25 on national television in Canada.
link_name: Michael Sam signs with CFL's Montreal Alouettes

status_message: President Otto Perez Molina fired his intelligence chief, the deputy interior, and the the energy and environment ministers on May 22, the same day he accepted the resignation of Interior Minister Mauricio Lopez Bonilla. He told reporters, "there is an openness to investigate in any place."
link_name: Guatemala president clears cabinet amid corruption scandal

status_message: The fourth round of talks ended May 22 and focused on reopening embassies. The U.S. wants diplomats to have more freedom of movement around Cuba. The U.S. also wants to be assured Cuban citizens will not be prevented from entering the U.S. embassy.
link_name: US wants assurances that Cubans would be able to visit US Embassy

status_message: Eric Lonergan, 21, and Zachary Kramer, 21, were charged with distributing a controlled dangerous substance, known as Molly, on May 22. In February, 11 people fell ill after taking the drug, which was distributed by the men. Three others were arrested in connection to the crimes.
link_name: Two Wesleyan University students charged for selling synthetic "Molly" that led to ODs

status_message: The State Dept. released 296 email documents linked to Benghazi that from former Sec. State Hillary Clinton's private email account on May 22. The State Dept. said the emails do not change "the essential facts or our understanding of the [Benghazi] events." At the FBI's request, one email was classified on May 22.
link_name: State Dept. releases Benghazi emails from Clinton's private account

status_message: Michael C. Ford, who worked in the U.S. Embassy in London since 2009, was arrested and appeared in court on May 21. He is accused of posing as a "talent scout," targeting sorority sisters and stealing photos from their online accounts, which he threatened to post unless they took compromising videos of other women.
link_name: State Department employee arrested for 'sextortion' case involving college-aged women

status_message: Apple's as-yet unannounced streaming TV service may not debut as initially expected early this fall because the company is trying to secure deals that would allow it to include streams of live local broadcast channels, Re/code reported May 22. Apple may not announce the service at WWDC in June if these deals aren't in place.
link_name: Recode: Apple streaming TV service may miss expected early fall debut

status_message: Unlicensed taxis must return to their base between fares, France's top administrative court ruled May 22. The court also ruled that taxi companies are not allowed to use GPS to search for fares. The court's ruling was closely watched by Uber because a Paris appeals court said in March it would rule on the legality of UberPop after the ruling.
link_name: French court upholds restrictions on unlicensed taxis

status_message: Drug Enforcement Agency employees David Polos and Glen Glover, who were also part owners of Twins Plus Go-Go Lounge, were arrested on May 23 after it was discovered that they lied about their ownership and work at the strip club. Polos, 51, had retired from the agency last month. Glover, 45, was placed on administrative leave.
link_name: DEA agents accused of running New Jersey strip club with undocumented workers

status_message: Uber is speaking with banks to raise a $1 billion line of credit, unnamed sources told the WSJ May 21, in what may be a step towards an eventual IPO. Uber is currently valued at $40 billion, making it the second most valuable VC-backed startup behind China's Xiaomi.
link_name: WSJ: Uber seeking $1 billion line of credit

status_message: The Connecticut House of Representatives passed a bill May 21 by a vote of 116-32 to allow Tesla to open three sales rooms in the state. The original version of the bill, which was strongly lobbied against by the state's dealerships association, called for five showrooms, but that was scaled back.
link_name: Bill to allow direct Tesla sales in Connecticut advances

status_message: Thailand marked one year since the 2014 coup on May 22. The International Federation for Human Rights said May 20 that at least 47 people were detained under the strict lese-majeste law in the previous year, which it called "unprecedented."
link_name: Thailand marks one year since military coup, activists briefly detained

status_message: A group of feminists called the Droits Humains collective launched a campaign May 21 calling on the government to cease the official use of "droits de l'Homme" (rights of man) in favor of the gender-neutral "droits humains." Their online petition had gathered more than 1,500 signatures by May 22.
link_name: French feminists push for 'rights of man' term to be dropped for gender-neutral alternative

status_message: Cameron arrived at an EU summit in Riga, Latvia, May 22, aiming to stop EU nationals from chasing jobs and benefits in the UK. In 2014, he said 86,000 EU nationals migrated to the UK looking for work. Cameron wants to limit benefits to EU migrants who have worked 4 years in the UK.
link_name: UK's prime minister set on reducing EU migration

status_message: China's stock markets had one of their best collective weeks since 2008 in the week ending May 22, with the Shanghai Composite closing at a seven-year high of 4,605.42, up 1.7%. The Shenzhen ChiNet exchange, which has increased more than 160% in 2015, had a strong week although May 22 saw losses.
link_name: China's stocks continue to rally with Shanghai composite hitting 7-year high

status_message: United Launch Alliance, the joint venture between Lockheed Martin and Boeing, will go out of business unless it gets more commercial orders, ULA president Tory Bruno said May 21. Bruno said military satellite launches are expected to drop from 10-12 to five a year, Reuters reports.
link_name: Lockheed-Boeing space venture 'cannot survive' on current business

status_message: Japan will raise infrastructure investment in the AIIB-rival ADB by 30%, or $110 billion over 5 years, Abe said May 21. On May 20, the World Bank announced loans for infrastructure worth up to $12 billion to Indonesia. Neither Japan nor the U.S. are members of China's AIIB.
link_name: Japan to increase ADB infrastructure investment by $110 billion

status_message: Florida gun owners who do not have concealed-weapons permits will be allowed to carry their weapons for 48 hours during a state of emergency under a new bill signed by Gov. Rick Scott May 21. The time limit, which wasn't in the 2014 version of the bill, was requested by law enforcement agencies.
link_name: Florida limits natural disaster no-permit gun law

status_message: Irish voters will cast ballots in the referendum May 22. Voters are being asked if the constitution should be amended to included an article that reads "Marriage may be contracted in accordance with law by two persons without distinction as to their sex." The result will be announced on May 23.
link_name: Ireland votes on same-sex marriage

status_message: On May 21, Japan signed over the promised $1.5 billion, which brought the fund up to $5.47 billion, or above the 50% threshold that triggers its operations. The U.S. treasury told Reuters in April that it was working with Congress to fulfill its $3 billion pledge.
link_name: Japan's $1.5 billion contribution allows UN's Green Climate Fund to begin work

status_message: Reynaldo Vargas was sentenced May 21 to a year in federal prison. He admitted to stealing money and property from dealers, and testified against two other officers who were also convicted and sentenced. They were indicted on multiple allegations, including stealing $30,000 from a drug stash house and giving marijuana to a dealer to sell for profit.
link_name: Third San Francisco officer sentenced in corruption scandal

status_message: A lawsuit filed May 21 in the Dallas County district court alleges Twin Peaks restaurant was grossly negligent, inviting rival biker gangs to an event and serving alcohol. Don Carlos Mexican Restaurant, which was caught in the crossfire, is seeking damages worth $1 million.
link_name: $1 million damages sought by Twin Peaks' neighbor, caught in biker gang crossfire

status_message: Four ministers from the minority coalition party Sri Lanka Freedom Party (SLFP) resigned May 21, citing exclusion from decision-making by Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe as a reason. But several media reports say former president Rajapaksa has raised discontent in the coalition formed in March.
link_name: Four ministers quit Sri Lanka's coalition government

status_message: The cleanup accelerated on May 21, with 18 vessels skimming the ocean surface to soak up the crude with booms. The offshore and onshore crews, who are bagging oily sand, are working around the clock, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency said May 21.
link_name: Crews continue to clean up Santa Barbara oil spill

status_message: Aaron Hernandez, who is facing a trial for a 2012 double homicide, pleaded not guilty to charges of witness intimidation on May 21. Aaron Bradley lost his right eye after allegedly being shot by Hernandez in 2013 and and is expected to testify in the double homicide case.
link_name: Aaron Hernandez pleads not guilty to witness intimidation in double homicide case

status_message: All auctions, swap meets and live bird exhibitions, including at the Iowa State Fair, have been canceled through 2015 due to the H5N2 bird flu outbreak, health officials announced on May 21. The highly-pathogenic H5N2 strain has impacted more than 60 Iowa farms and over 25 million birds. Iowa declared a state of emergency on May 1.
link_name: Bird flu causes Iowa to cancel all live bird exhibitions and sales for 2015

status_message: Tribune and the newspaper formerly known as U-T San Diego said May 21 they had closed the acquisition deal. As part of the acquisition, Tribune restored the newspaper's old name to The San Diego Union-Tribune.
link_name: Tribune Co. restores San Diego Union-Tribune's old name

status_message: The names, email addresses and sexual preferences of as many as 3.9 million members of Adult Friend Finder were leaked by hackers, the company said May 21.
link_name: Hackers access 3.9 million records of adult dating website

status_message: HP now expects to incur between $400-$450 million in added expenses related to the split into two publicly traded companies, it said May 21. The split is still on track for November.
link_name: HP expects $400-$450M in added costs as a result of business split

status_message: State Attorney for Baltimore, Marilyn Mosby, said May 21 that all 6 police officers in Freddie Gray case indicted by grand jury.
link_name: All 6 police officers in Freddie Gray case indicted by grand jury

status_message: State Attorney for Baltimore, Marilyn Mosby, said May 21 that all 6 police officers in Freddie Gray case were indicted by grand jury. Mosby said some of the charges against the officers were revised in the grand jury indictment. The case is scheduled to be arraigned on July 2.
link_name: All 6 police officers in Freddie Gray case indicted by grand jury

status_message: Brian Williams will be edited out as host of The Lincoln Awards, honoring people who support veterans and military families. The event's co-founder said Williams asked to be removed because he didn't want to be a distraction. Michelle Obama recorded an introduction instead. The event, recorded in January before Williams' suspension, will air May 22 on PBS.
link_name: Brian Williams edited out as host of The Lincoln Awards, replaced by Michelle Obama

status_message: Mauricio Lopez Bonilla, the head of Guatemala's interior ministry since 2012, resigned on May 21. He has not been linked to the scandal by prosecutors.
link_name: Guatemala's central bank governor arrested on fraud charges

status_message: The surveillance program, called "IRRITANT HORN," was designed to exploit the Internet connection between Android smartphones and app stores runs by Google and Samsung, according to documents published May 21 by the Intercept and CBC News. There is no indication that the NSA or its allies successfully carried out the program.
link_name: NSA targeted Android app stores to install surveillance malware

status_message: At a national meeting in Atlanta on May 21, Boy Scouts President Robert Gates raised the possibility of changing Boy Scout policy to remove the ban against gay leaders in the organization. No formal change has been made.
link_name: President of the Boy Scouts calls to end ban against gay leaders

status_message: Hackers improperly accessed the records of 1.1 million current and former CareFirst BlueShield members, the health insurer said May 20.
link_name: Hackers access 1.1 million records of CareFirst health insurer
MH370 investigators say 'not possible' to know where to search next

status_message: The Senate on May 21 voted 62-38 to end debate on a bill to give President Obama the authority to "fast-track" trade deals, breaking a filibuster on the legislation. The Senate will now vote on amendments to the bill before a final vote on the bill, which is expected to occur May 22.
link_name: 'Fast-track' trade bill clears procedural hurdle in US Senate

status_message: Altice, which is backed by French billionaire Patrick Drahi, has approached Time Warner Cable about a possible takeover, according to multiple reports from publications like Bloomberg and Reuters. While Altice has not confirmed the approach, CEO Dexter Goei did say May 20 that "everything below Comcast is in consolidation mode.
link_name: Reports: European telecom Altice enters race for Time Warner Cable

status_message: Domestic violence charges against former Baltimore Ravens running back Ray Rice have been dismissed after he completed a pre-trial intervention program.
link_name: Ray Rice has domestic violence charges dismissed

status_message:
The Cleveland Cavaliers beat the Atlanta Hawks 97-89 in Game 1 in Atlanta. LeBron James led the Cavs with 31 points, and J.R. Smith came off the bench to score 28 including eight 3 pt shots -- a playoff franchise record for Cleveland.

Regular season MVP Stephen Curry scored 34 points to lead the Warriors to a 110-106 win over the Houston Rockets.
link_name: Cavaliers, Warriors take Game 1 in NBA conference finals

status_message: The number of people seeking unemployment benefits in the week ending May 16 increased by 10,000 to 274,000, the Labor Dept. reported May 21. The 4-week moving average, considered a more reliable measure, fell by 5,500 to 266,250, the lowest level since April 15, 2000.
link_name: US jobless claims rise; four-week average at 15-year low

status_message: Islamic State (IS) fighters took control of the ancient ruins of Palmyra, an UNESCO World Heritage site, on May 20-21, according to the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights. Government troops pulled out of the area. Most residents evacuated, the Syrian government said.
link_name: Islamic State fighters seize ancient city of Palmyra

status_message: Trading stopped May 20 on Hanergy's stock on the Hong Kong stock exchange after the company lost 47% of its value, or $18.6 billion. The solar cell company previously saw its stock price triple in 2015. Hanergy CEO Li Hejun, who owns about 80% of the company, lost $15 billion in the one-hour long plunge.
link_name: China's largest renewable energy company's stock price drops 47%

status_message: A third nuclear plant came a step closer to restarting when the Nuclear Regulatory Authority (NRA) approved its basic safety on May 20. The Shikoku Electric Power Co still needs two more approvals before restarting the Ikata No. 3 reactor. It supplied southwestern Japan before the Fukushima meltdown.
link_name: Japan's nuclear regulator approves third reactor

status_message: A bill aimed at quelling rising union activities is expected to pass through Germany's parliament May 22, the FT reported. Germany's passenger train drivers walked off the job May 20, the third time in 2015, stalling public transport. The German business lobby DIHK criticized the impact on business.
link_name: Germany to tighten collective bargaining laws to stop strikes

status_message: The attorney general's office arrested 16 people, including central bank governor Julio Suarez. It also issued a warrant for the president's former personal secretary, Juan de Dios Rodriguez, on charges including fraud, influence trafficking, and charging illegal commissions, prosecutors said May 20.
link_name: Guatemala's central bank governor arrested on fraud charges

status_message: Federal prosecutors filed a plea deal May 20 in which ConAgra Foods will plead guilty and pay a $11.2 million fine for shipping Peter Pan peanut butter that sickened more than 700 people in a 2006 salmonella outbreak. The company admitted salmonella was found on nine different dates in a Georgia plant. The fine is the largest ever in a food safety investigation.
link_name: Peter Pan maker fined $11.2 million over salmonella poisoning

status_message: Corey Knowlton shot and killed a black rhino in central Namibia May 18. CNN released footage of the hunt May 20. Knowlton's permit is one of five issued a year by Namibia for bulls too old to breed but still dangerous to other males. Knowlton said the hunt brought awareness to the black rhino. It drew fierce criticism from conservationists.
link_name: Texas hunter kills endangered black rhino after winning $350,000 auction

status_message: Transocean said May 20 it had agreed to pay $211.7 million to settle lawsuits with Gulf Coast individuals and businesses who claimed damages after the Deepwater Horizon spill. Transocean said the settlement and a separate settlement with BP announced the same day, resolved "substantially all" of its outstanding spill claims.
link_name: Transocean settles Gulf oil spill claims for $212 million

status_message: Over 2,500 protestors marched to McDonald's headquarters in Illinois on May 20, calling for the company to raise the minimum wage for front-line workers to $15 an hour. The two-day demonstration falls ahead of McDonald's annual shareholder meeting, held May 22.
link_name: 2,500 wage protestors march on McDonald's headquarters

status_message: During their first year of college, 18.6% of women experienced rape or a rape attempt, research published in the June issue of Journal of Adolescent Health said. 483 female students at a major private university in New York were surveyed as they entered school, at the end of the fall and spring semesters, and as they were about to begin their sophomore year.
link_name: Study: About 19% of first-year women at US colleges become victims of rape or attempted rape

status_message: Hulu announced May 20 that all nine Seinfeld seasons will be available on June 24. All 180 episodes are part of the deal. Hulu is estimated to have paid Sony Pictures Television about $180 million for the streaming rights.
link_name: Hulu announces all Seinfeld seasons will be available in June

status_message: Okinawan Gov. Takeshi Onaga said during a May 20 news conference that he will call on U.S. officials to remove the military base during an upcoming trip to Washington, D.C., in the last week of May.
link_name: Okinawa governor to call for removal of US military base

status_message: Citigroup, Barclays, JP Morgan Chase, UBS and Royal Bank of Scotland were ordered on May 20 by the U.S. Justice Department to pay more than $5 billion after pleading guilty to antitrust violations. USB was fined $1.8 billion and Barclays was ordered to pay $1.3 billion in related claims.
link_name: 5 large banks to pay over $5 billion in foreign currency rigging scheme

status_message: The Algerian military said it killed 21 militants suspected of plotting an attack on the capital. An unnamed intelligence official told the AP the army killed "terrorists," which it often uses to describe groups associated with Al-Qaeda or its affiliates.
link_name: Algeria breaks up suspected attack plot outside capital

status_message: On May 19, Plains All American Pipeline said that one of its pipelines on land near Refugio State Beach north of Santa Barbara, CA, ruptured and spilled out an estimated 21,000 gallons of oil before being shut off. The oil ran down a drainage area and into the sea, where it created a 4-mile long slick.
link_name: Ruptured pipeline spills 21,000 gallons of oil on Santa Barbara County beach

status_message: San Bernardino approved a debt-cutting proposal on May 18. Investors who hold pension obligation bonds will be repaid about 1% of what they are owed, and retiree health insurance costs will be eliminate San Bernardino will also outsource its firefighters under the plan.
link_name: Bankrupt city of San Bernardino cuts bonds, replaces firefighters

status_message: Beau Biden was hospitalized at Walter Reed Army Medical Center outside Washington on May 19, the vice president's office said. No details of his medical condition or treatment have been released.
link_name: Joe Biden's son Beau hospitalized at Walter Reed

status_message: Two years after a ban was imposed to save endangered big cats, Zambia will again allow trophy hunting. Zambia's green party president Peter Sinkamba told the Lusaka Times May 18 that the exact number of lions (estimated in 2013 at between 2,500 and 4,700) was unknown as the government did not keep a wildlife census.
link_name: Zambia lifts trophy hunting ban despite poaching concerns

status_message: William McNeilly, 25, turned himself in to police on arrival. He had fled the country after releasing a detailed report on Wikileaks with accusations of safety and security lapses in the Trident nuclear missile program. The Royal Navy said he was being held at a military base in Scotland.
link_name: UK navy whistleblower in military custody after turning himself in

status_message: Japan's GDP grew at 2.4% year-on-year in the first quarter, more than the 1.5% analysts expected. Quarter-on-quarter the economy grew by 0.6%, also higher than the 0.4% expected. The news pushed the Nikkei stock average to a new 15-year high May 20.
link_name: Japan GDP grew at fastest rate in a year in first quarter

status_message: Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei said May 20 that he would not allow inspectors to interview its atomic scientists as part of a deal to limit the country's nuclear program.
link_name: Khamenei won't allow interviews with Iran's nuclear scientists

status_message: Meth amphetamine trade was very profitable for 60% of serious criminals in Australia, according to the ACC's Organized Crime in Australia 2015 report released May 20. International crime syndicates accounted for much of the total illegal drugs trade in Australia worth $6.5 billion, the report says.
link_name: Crystal methamphetamine fuels $6.5 billion illicit drugs trade in Australia

status_message: The Nikkei closed up 0.9% to 20,196.56 May 20 to set a 15-year high after doing so in late April as well. The surge came after Japan posted better than expected GDP growth in the first quarter of 2.4%.
link_name: Nikkei hits 15 year high, closes up almost 1%

status_message: A semi-independent body within WHO was created to alert the world to potential global pandemics, such as Ebola. Germany's chancellor Angela Merkel announced the WHO reform at the World Health Assembly May 18.
link_name: WHO reforms to avert repeat of Ebola epidemic missteps

status_message: The Israeli government said it was suspending a program that forbid Palestinians from riding on buses with Jews in the West Bank on May 20, a day after the program launched. Israeli lawmakers said it would harm "Israel's image around the world" and make building settlements more difficult.
link_name: Israeli backs off segregating buses in the West Bank

status_message: Rezaian's trial will begin May 26, Iranian state media reported May 19. His lawyer confirmed the date. Rezaian is accused of "espionage for the hostile government of the United States of America and propaganda activities against the system," a judiciary spokesman told state media.
link_name: Washington Post reporter in Iran to face espionage trial

status_message:
"I'm going to accept, reluctantly, what he has given to us and not continue this dialogue and rhetoric. We won't appeal." - Robert Kraft. 

Kraft said May 19 his decision to not appeal the Patriots' punishment was for the "collective good of the 32" NFL teams.
link_name: New England Patriots owner won't appeal team's NFL punishment

status_message: Malaysia and Indonesia agreed May 20 to provide temporary shelter to about 7,000 migrants stranded on boats. The offer depended on the international community organizing resettlement or repatriation within a year. Malaysia previously turned away about 800 Rohingyas and Bangladeshis seeking asylum on May 14, the AP reported.
link_name: Philippines will not join region in turning back migrant boats

status_message: Yahoo's shares fell 7.5% in the last 20 minutes of the trading day May 19 after an IRS official said the agency is considering changing its rules regarding spinoffs. The move could impact Yahoo's plans to spin off its stake in Chinese e-commerce giant Alibaba in a way that would avoid billions in taxes.
link_name: Yahoo shares plunge on report that IRS spinoff rules could change

status_message: The House passed a two-month extension for transportation funding on May 19. The short-term extension now heads to the Senate where a vote is expected May 21. Lawmakers are trying to pass an extension before funding runs out at the end of the month.
link_name: House passes short-term transportation bill

status_message: The number of children internally displaced by conflict in South Sudan has grown to 802,000, according to a UNICEF report released in early May. UNICEF reported May 18 on a recent increase in violence against children, with dozens killed, at least 12 raped and others abducted over a two-week period.
link_name: 802,000 children internally displaced by South Sudan conflict
