status_message: Etsy shares fell 12% in after-hours trade following the company's first ever earnings report that showed an unexpected loss in the quarter. Etsy reported a net loss of $36.6 million, or 84 cents a share, compared with a year-earlier loss of $500,000, or one cent a share. Analysts expected EPS to break even.
link_name: Etsy shares dive on unexpected loss

status_message: L'Oreal will produce skin in an effort to automate skin production in the next five years at its California facilities and Organovo's labs, Bloomberg said on May 18. The company has exclusive rights to the 3D printed skin for nonprescription skin care products.
link_name: L'Oreal to 3D print human skin to test products

status_message: A car bomb in the parking lot of Afghanistan's Ministry of Justice exploded May 19, killing at least five people. It was the third attack on the justice system this month. Taliban spokesman Zabihullah Mujahid claimed responsibility saying his group will continue to kill "slave" judges.
link_name: Car bomb outside Afghan Justice Ministry kills five

status_message: The Los Angeles City Council voted May 19 to increase its minimum wage to $15 an hour by 2020. The increase passed in a 14-1 vote. More than 40% of the city's workforce earns less than $15 per hour.
link_name: Los Angeles City Council votes to increase minimum wage to $15 per hour

status_message: Adam Schiff, ranking Democrat on the House intelligence committee, confirmed to reporters May 19 that US intelligence agencies are investigating if Kayla Mueller was being held by IS commander Abu Sayyaf, who was killed by US special forces during a raid in Syria on May 15.
link_name: US investigating if aid worker was held by recently killed IS leader

status_message: Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-KY) said May 19 the Senate will vote on bill overhauling the NSA's bulk collection of phone metadata, saying "I certainly think we ought to allow a vote on the House-passed bill." McConnell, who is trying to renew the Patriot Act, said letting the Patriot Act expire would be irresponsible.
link_name: McConnell to allow vote on bill overhauling NSA's bulk collection of phone metadata

status_message: 6 people were charged with economic espionage on behalf of the Chinese government, the U.S. Department of Justice said on May 19. The men were accused of stealing trade secrets from Avago Technologies and Skyworks Solutions in a "long-running effort" to secure an economic advantage.
link_name: 6 Chinese nationals accused of stealing US trade secrets

status_message: Housing starts rose 20.2% to a 1.14 million annualized rate, the biggest rise since November 2007, up from a 944,000 in March, according to the Commerce Department. New construction beat Bloomberg's analysts expectations of 1.02 million.
link_name: New residential construction rises in April to highest level in more than 7 years

status_message: Walmart reported fiscal-first quarter revenue of $114 billion, down 0.1% from a year ago and missing analyst expectations of $115.6 billion. Income was $3.34 billion, $1.03 per share, down from $3.59 billion and $1.11 a share a year ago and missing analysts expectations of $1.05 per share. Walmart cited workers receiving higher wages and a strong dollar for the drop in earnings.
link_name: Walmart reports weak sales, missed profit

status_message: Apple more than a year ago "put on ice" plans to create a dedicated, stand-alone television, the Wall Street Journal reported May 18. Despite planned features like a built-in camera for voice calling and a high-res screen, Apple executives decided against entering the "highly competitive" TV business.
link_name: WSJ: Apple's plans to develop stand-alone TV 'put on ice'

status_message: A May 19 HRW statement blamed to Israeli Supreme Court decisions in May for providing "legal cover for forced evictions." The decisions pertain to the villages of Umm Al-Hiran in Israel's Negev desert and Susya in the occupied West Bank, which will be destroyed to make way for Jewish settlements.
link_name: Israel's Supreme Court gives "legal cover for forced evictions," HRW says

status_message: The New York Stock Exchange debuted its Bitcoin index on May 19, with the symbol $NYXBT. The index will track the value of a single bitcoin across a number of select Bitcoin exchanges. This is the first exchange-calculated and disseminated bitcoin index ever. It will initially use Coinbase Exchange data.
link_name: NYSE debuts Bitcoin index

status_message: A May 19 International Federation for Human Rights report based on interviews found "involvement of police, National Security Intelligence officers and the military in sexual violence, including rape, sexual assault, rape with objects, electrocution of genitalia, sex-based defamation and blackmail."
link_name: Sexual violence by Egyptian regime 'surges' under military rule, rights group says

status_message:
"This is the first time the CPI [Consumer Price Index] has fallen over the year since official records began in 1996 and the first time since 1960 based on comparable historic estimates," the UK Office for National Statistics (ONS) said.
The UK CPI fell 0.1% year-on-year in April, the ONS said May 19. The figure met the government's target, the ONS said. Cheaper travel fares contributed to the fall due to the time of Easter.
link_name: UK inflation turns negative for first time in decades

status_message: The Thai cabinet agreed May 19 that a referendum on the constitution should occur, pushing back elections to at least Aug. 2016. The National Reform Council, which is reviewing the draft constitution, asked for the vote. The draft would give amnesty to 2014 coup leaders and allow unelected individuals to become prime minister.
link_name: Thai government to hold constitutional referendum, pushing back elections

status_message: The Philippines government on May 18 refuted a report saying it would join Malaysia, Indonesia and Thailand in pushing back boats. Although the Philippines is far from the crisis zone, the International Organization for Migration said the offer of refuge was a "hopeful sign."
link_name: Philippines will not join region in turning back migrant boats

status_message: China's National Development and Reform Commission approved six new rail projects at a cost of $40.3 billion, Reuters reported May 18. Five projects were approved earlier in 2015, the commission said. In addition to intracity high-speed lines, the NDRC also approved a subway system for the western city of Chengdu.
link_name: Chinese government approves $40 billion rail and subway projects

status_message: Waco police arrested and charged 170 suspected members of five biker gangs, Waco police said May 18. Each suspect was required to pay a bond of a million dollars for release from McLennan County Jail.
link_name: Nearly 200 arrested after Texas shootout among rival motorcycle gangs

status_message: Highly educated, stay-at-home moms receive bonuses worth $10,000 or more, Martin wrote in the NY Times May 16. Her memoir about the marriage economics of "Manhattan Geishas" and segregation of the sexes among the rich and powerful, will be released June 2.
link_name: New York Upper East Side women earn good wife bonuses

status_message: Saudi's Ministry of Civil Service on May 18 began advertising eight executioner positions on its website. No special qualifications are required, it said. The jobs are classed as "religious functionaries" and will have a low pay grade, Reuters reported. Saudi Arabia faces a dearth of swordsmen authorized to carry out beheadings.
link_name: Saudi Arabia puts out recruitment ads for eight executioners

status_message: A thousand Stuttgart police stood between about 4,000 protestors who held a counter protest to a small PEGIDA rally on May 17. The "For diversity, against racism" protest tried to block the anti-immigrant group's demonstration, police said.
link_name: Thousands of Germans rally against PEGIDA in Stuttgart

status_message: Xiaomi opened online stores for the U.S., UK, France and Germany May 18 and 19. The stores are only offering a handful of items, including its $15 Mi Band fitness tracking device, which has been popular in China.
link_name: Xiaomi begins selling accessories in US, Europe

status_message: Around one in seven people across the globe still live without electricity, according to a World Bank report released May 18. Nearly 3 billion still cook using polluting fuels such as kerosene, wood, charcoal and dung.
link_name: One in seven people live without electricity, World Bank says

status_message: Arizona's GOP-led legislature May 18 reduced the total amount of time welfare recipients can receive benefits to 12 months, the shortest window in the nation according to the AP. At least 1,600 families, including 2,700 children, will be cut on July 1, 2016. The AP said the cuts will shave $4 million off the budget, but the timeframe was unclear.
link_name: Arizona lawmakers cut welfare program to most restrictive in nation

status_message: A landslide in Colombia's northwest mountains May 18 killed at least 52 and injured dozens, officials said.
link_name: More than 50 dead in Colombia landslide

status_message: Manhattan District Attorney Cyrus Vance Jr. told MSNBC on May 18 of his plans to re-try the case which ended in a mistrial after all but one of the 12 jurors voted to convict defendant Pedro Hernandez. An official announcement will come June 10 in court
link_name: Manhattan District Attorney plans retrial of Etan Patz case

status_message: By the end of Missouri's legislative session May 15, more than 60 Ferguson-related measures had been introduced but only two passed, according to the AP.
link_name: Missouri legislature passes few Ferguson-inspired bills

status_message: The U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency and U.S. prosecutors are building a case against several high-ranking officials for running "a global hub for cocaine trafficking and money laundering," according to a May 18 Wall Street Journal report citing unnamed sources.
link_name: WSJ: US investigating Venezuela officials for running a cocaine trafficking hub

status_message: 49 people were shot in Chicago over the weekend of May 16, leaving at least one person dead. Shooting incidences are up 22% in 2015, the Chicago Tribune reports, with 627 shootings between Jan. and May 10.
link_name: Chicago shootings up 22% in 2015

status_message: Former ABC anchor Carole Simpson referred to Stephanopoulos in a comment to CNN May 18, saying that his error reflected a lack of judgment. Stephanopoulos' inability to "separate himself from his political background to become a journalist" means "he really isn't a journalist," the former colleague said in the televised interview.
link_name: Former ABC News anchor: Stephanopoulos "not a journalist", mixed reporting with politics

status_message: David Hodge of Miami University in Ohio will receive his full annual salary of $419,000, even after he steps down mid-year in 2016. According to the Dayton Daily News on May 14, costly sabbaticals or tenure positions are becoming the norm for leaders who step down.
link_name: Miami University president will get $419K after leaving

status_message: Four passengers who were aboard Amtrak train #188 filed suit against Amtrak in federal court on May 18. According to the suit, victims suffered injuries including torn ligaments, internal and head injuries, abrasions, and fractured ribs. The plaintiffs said the crash could have been avoided and named train engineer Brian Bostian in the suit.
link_name: Amtrak says full service will be restored on Monday

status_message: Thailand police arrested suspected human trafficking kingpin Patchuban Angchotipan, Reuters reported May 18. Angchotipan, also known as "Kor Tong," was charged with human trafficking, holding people for ransom and smuggling illegal migrant workers into Thailand. Angchotipan, a former government official in Satun province, has denied the charges.
link_name: Reuters: Thailand arrests suspected human trafficking kingpin

status_message: The Dow Jones Industrial Average reached an intraday high, closing at 18,298 points May 18. The S&P 500 was up 6 points to 2,129 -- a record close for the index for the third straight day. Investors reacted positively to calmer European bond markets.
link_name: Dow, S&P close at record highs

status_message: Carl Icahn published yet another open letter addressed to Apple CEO Tim Cook May 18 in which he once again asked the company to buy back more shares of its own stock. Icahn claimed Apple is truly worth $240 per share, which would value the company at $1.5 trillion. Apple opened trading May 18 at $128.77.
link_name: Carl Icahn: Apple undervalued by investors, should be a $1.5 trillion company

status_message: Vice President Chacon on May 17 announced an executive order that pledges to punish public workers for discrimination against others based on their sexual orientation or gender identity. Individual institutions will determine how punishment will be enforced and the rule only effects institutions under the executive branch.
link_name: Costa Rica will punish public workers for LGBT discrimination

status_message: The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled May 18 Google should not have removed the video from YouTube. The court found doing so violated the First Amendment. The decision overturns a previous decision from a three-judge panel of the court that required Google to remove the film over copyright concerns.
link_name: Appeals court rules 'Innocence of Muslims' film should have stayed on YouTube

status_message: Sanders, who is running for the 2016 Democratic nomination for president, will unveil a bill May 19 offer U.S. students a tuition-free college education at public institutions
link_name: Sanders to introduce bill to offer tuition-free college education

status_message: U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry called out North Korea for its continued pursuit of a nuclear weapon and human rights violations, including recent reports of public executions, during a news conference in South Korea on May 18.
link_name: US says it is discussing tougher sanctions on North Korea with China

status_message: The Supreme Court ruled unanimously May 18 in favor of employees, throwing out lower court rulings that barred employees from suing. The lawsuit now goes back to the lower court to decide to what extent Edison is required to monitor the investments.
link_name: Supreme Court sides with Edison employees in 401(k) dispute

status_message: Performing to a sold-out crowd of 2,056 people on May 15, the Minnesota Orchestra became the first major U.S. orchestra to perform in Cuba in over 15 years.
link_name: Minnesota Orchestra becomes first major US group to perform in Cuba since relations thaw

status_message: About 50 weapons were recovered from the scene and 192 people have been arrested in connection to the incident. According to Waco police, the brawl seems to have started in a restroom and moved to the parking lot, where police were already in position awaiting trouble from the gangs.
link_name: Nearly 200 arrested after Texas shootout among rival motorcycle gangs

status_message: Former tennis Grand Slam champion Bob Hewitt was sentenced to six years in prison on May 18 after being found guilty on two rape charges and one charge of sexual assault of a minor. Hewitt raped both Theresa "Twiggy" Tolken and Suellen Sheehan in the 1980s and sexually assaulted an unnamed woman in the 1990s.
link_name: Former tennis champion Bob Hewitt sentenced to 6 years in prison for rape

status_message: Ukraine officials say they captured two Russian special forces soldiers who were wounded during fighting in eastern Ukraine on May 17. Russia denies sending troops to the area. On May 18 Ukraine's Interior Ministry posted video of one of the soldiers admitting he was on a Russian spy mission. Authorities said the two will be prosecuted for "terrorist" acts.
link_name: Russian special forces captured in Ukraine

status_message: Thousands of Israeli nationalists marched through Jerusalem's Muslim Quarter to mark Israel capturing the city in 1967. Videos showed them shouting slogans against Arabs and Muslims. Leaflets called the government to "bring down the mosques on the Temple Mount." Israeli police arrested a handful of Palestinians in counter protests.
link_name: Israeli nationalists hold marches through Jerusalem's Muslim Quarter

status_message: Russia's Roscosmos space agency said May 18 that the night before it was able to start the engines of its Progress cargo craft which is attached to the ISS. Roscosmos had been unable to start the engines May 15. With the orbit correction, three Expedition 43 crew members will be able to return to Earth in June.
link_name: Russia corrects Space Station orbit, after supply craft spiraled out of control

status_message: The BBC submitted Freedom of Information requests to 152 councils in February asking for data from the 2013-14 and 2014-15 financial years. Councils said they received 4,748 reports of sexual abuse against the disabled, with 63% against people with learning disabilities and 37% against the physically disabled, the BBC reported May 18.
link_name: Thousands of disabled people sexually abused in England

status_message: A Human Rights Watch report released May 18 found some 150 members of the U.S. military said in interviews that they faced retaliation after reporting assault. They said they experienced threats, harassment, loss of job opportunities and promotions, disciplinary actions and criminal charges.
link_name: US military sexual abuse survivors say they suffered retaliation

status_message: Pre-referendum polls suggest that Ireland will vote 'yes' at the referendum, though support appears to have fallen as the date approaches. A number of public figures, including the health minister, have come out during the campaign. Ireland only decriminalized homosexuality in 1993.
link_name: Ireland could become world's first country to approve same-sex marriage by popular vote

status_message: President Barack Obama will ban federal programs from providing some military equipment to local police. Obama will announce the move at an event in Camden, NJ on May 18. The decision blocks police from acquiring armored vehicles, firearms of .50-caliber or higher, grenade launchers, bayonets and camouflage uniforms. The administration wants to retrieve existing equipment.
link_name: President Obama restricts military equipment to local police

status_message: Ecuador's President Rafael Correa announced that the mass planting in one day on May 16 had broken a Guinness record, AFP reported May 17. They also planted 50 more species than the previous record, a Guinness adjudicator said.
link_name: Volunteers in Ecuador plant 647,250 trees to break reforestation record

status_message: Malaysia called on Myanmar on May 17 to take responsibility for the exodus. Myanmar refuses to participate in May 20 foreign minister meetings with Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia if the term "Rohingya" is used. The country does not accept allegations that it is "the source of the problem," a presidential spokesman said May 16.
link_name: Pressure mounts on Myanmar as southeast Asia's refugee crisis continues

status_message: China North Railway will delist itself May 20, Chinese state media said May 18, in preparation for a stock swap and merger with China South Railway. The combined company will be called CRRC. It will be listed in Shanghai.
link_name: China two largest railway companies moving forward with merger

status_message: The UN envoy to Yemen requested that a five-day humanitarian pause, which expired May 17, be extended five more days. However, Saudi airstrikes expanded in Yemen's southern city of Aden. At least 20 people were also killed and 70 wounded on May 17 in Yemen's southern province of Taiz, according to a medical official.
link_name: UN calls for extension of humanitarian pause in Yemen

status_message: The final episode of "Mad Men" aired on AMC on May 17. The series won a number of awards during its run including 15 Emmy Awards (out of 105 nominations), including four straight Emmys for best drama from 2008-2011. The show also won three straight Golden Globes from 2008-2010 for best drama.
link_name: 'Mad Men' airs series finale

status_message: The Marines said that one Marine died after an Osprey crashed during a training exercise at Bellows Air Force Base, Hawaii, around 11:40am May 17. The 21 other Marines onboard were brought to hospitals for "assessment and treatment." An investigation is ongoing.
link_name: One Marine killed, 21 injured after Osprey makes "hard landing"

status_message: Late on May 16 Potter, 43, and climbing partner Hunt, 29, jumped from Taft Point, which rises 3,000 feet above Yosemite Valley, attempting a BASE jump and wingsuit dive. Neither of the men's parachutes deployed and their bodies were found by a rescue helicopter the next day and recovered.
link_name: Climbing great Dean Potter dies in wingsuit accident at Yosemite

status_message: Amtrak will restore service along the Northeast Corridor beginning May 18. Travel between Philadelphia and New York had been suspended since the derailment on May 12.
link_name: Amtrak says full service will be restored on Monday

status_message: "Pitch Perfect 2" opened in first place with $70.3 million at the North American weekend box office. The first film made $65 million domestically during its entire theatrical run. The R-rated "Mad Max: Fury Road" debuted in second with $44.4 million, and "Avengers: Age of Ultron" made another $38.8 million.
link_name: 'Pitch Perfect 2' tops weekend box office with $70.3 million

status_message: The two earthquakes that hit Nepal within one month of each other are now the deadliest in the country's history. Government officials said on May 17 that the death toll has risen to 8,583 as rescuers continue to work. Approximately 8,519 were killed in a 1934 earthquake in Nepal.
link_name: Nepal earthquakes deadliest ever for country

status_message: Pope Francis canonized a total of four nuns on May 17, including two from 19th century Palestine, Sisters Mariam Bawardy and Marie Alphonsine Ghattas. Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas joined some 2,000 pilgrims from the region for the event. The pope said he hoped the move would encourage Christians in the Middle East facing extremism.
link_name: Pope Francis canonizes 2 Palestinian nuns from 19th century

status_message: Islamic State militants have taken over the last remaining government held districts in the Iraqi city Ramadi. On May 17, IS took control of the provincial operations command center in the city as the Iraqi army withdrew. Prime Minister Haider al-Abadi ordered forces to not abandon their posts after some security personnel pulled out of the region.
link_name: Islamic State seizes control of Iraqi city Ramadi

status_message: Over 20,000 protesters, carrying Macedonian and Albanian flags, gathered in front of Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski's office in Macedonia's capital Skopje on May 17. Opposition leaders said the protests would not end until Gruevski steps down.
link_name: Tens of thousands protest in Macedonia, call for government to step down

status_message: A May 15 UN Human Rights Council report makes 348 recommendations to improve how the U.S. handles human rights. It covers a range of topics including torture abroad, as well as police brutality, excessive use of force, racial profiling and immigrant detentions. The report is part of a review of human rights for all UN member states.
link_name: UN makes hundreds of recommendations for US human rights violations

status_message: On May 17, President Pierre Nkurunziza made his first appearance in the capital since a failed coup attempt on May 13. Some 100 people took to the streets a day earlier to protest. The protests are over President Nkurunziza violating the constitution by attempting to run for another five-year term. Reuters reported 18 people were taken into custody for involvement in the failed coup.
link_name: President Nkurunziza returns to capital following failed coup in Burundi

status_message: The U.N. envoy to Yemen requested that the current humanitarian pause, which expires 2000 GMT (4 p.m. ET) on May 17, be extended five more days. At least 20 people were killed and 70 wounded May 17 in Yemen's southern province of Taiz, according to a senior medical official. Several of Yemen's political parties, tribes, and members of parliament were expected to engage in dialogue at a conference in Riyadh on May 17.
link_name: UN calls for extension of humanitarian pause in Yemen

status_message: The UK government rewrote the Computer Misuse Act (CMA) in 2015 to grant immunity to GCHQ employees and law enforcement for hacking computers, Privacy International said May 15. The CMA covers domestic investigations. It is believed that individual warrants are not issued in the cases, the Guardian reported.
link_name: UK gives immunity to spies, police for hacking computers

status_message: Turkish fighter jets destroyed a Syrian helicopter in Turkey's airspace, the Turkish government said May 16. Syrian state press said it was a surveillance drone, not a helicopter.
link_name: Turkey shoots down Syrian aircraft

status_message: "The Mindy Project" will return for a fourth season, Hulu announced on May 15. The streaming service ordered 26 new episodes of the show.
link_name: Hulu picks up 'The Mindy Project'

status_message: The Syrian Observatory for Human Rights reported May 16 that IS jihadists had moved into part of the ancient city of Palmyra amid ongoing fighting with Syrian government forces.
link_name: Monitor says IS seizes part of Syria's ancient city of Palmyra

status_message: A Russian Proton-M rocket lifted off on May 16 at 11:47am, but crashed about eight minutes later in the Chita region of Siberia. The rocket, carrying a Mexican telecommunications satellite, appeared to have an "anomaly" with its third stage.
link_name: Russian rocket carrying Mexican satellite crashes in Siberia

status_message: The FAO Schwarz toy store in New York will close on July 15, the store's owner Toys R Us announced on May 15. The company cited high rent as a reason for the closure and is looking for a less costly Manhattan location.
link_name: FAO Schwarz toy store in New York City to close in July

status_message: A strong aftershock measuring 5.7 on the Richter scale shook Nepal and the northern Indian states of Bihar and Uttar Pradesh May 16, U.S. Geological Survey said. There were no reports of damage, but an aftershock of this strength days after a major earthquake is rare. The epicenter was located 74km east of Kathmandu at a shallow 10km depth.
link_name: Strong aftershock felt in Nepal, Northern India

status_message: A rapidly spreading meningococcal meningitis outbreak in Niger has infected an estimated 5,855 people and claimed 406 lives, the World Health Organization (WHO) reported May 15. Suspected cases have tripled since April 29. The outbreak, focused mainly in urban areas, is caused by a strain rarely seen in Africa.
link_name: Meningitis outbreak in Niger growing rapidly

status_message: Google will add a "buy button" to mobile search results within the next few weeks, the Wall Street Journal reported May 15. The button will only appear on sponsored search results. When clicked shoppers will be taken to a product page where they can complete their order. Macy's is already in talks with Google about participating in the program.
link_name: WSJ: Google to add 'buy button' to mobile search results

status_message: In a reversal from a month earlier, Showtime and Lynch confirmed that Lynch is back onboard the production, which will now "total more than the originally announced nine hours" of airtime for the revival.
link_name: David Lynch now says he will direct new "Twin Peaks"

status_message: The drought is due to lack of snowpack, not rain. "Snowpack is down to just 16% of normal‚Ä¶This is an unprecedented low," Inslee said. 66 of 98 of the snow sites the Conservation Service measured in Washington are currently snow free. Washington state Department of Natural Resources warned the drought could fuel the intensity and frequency of wildfires.
link_name: Statewide drought emergency declared in Washington State

status_message: Security analyst Chris Roberts, who had previously been kicked off a flight for tweeting about flight vulnerabilities, is accused of taking control of a plane briefly by hacking into the in-flight system. In a document obtained by Wired, FBI Special Agent Mark Hurley claims Roberts "caused one of the airplane engines to climb resulting in a lateral or sideways movement of the plane..."
link_name: Feds claim banned security researcher commandeered plane

status_message: On May 16, Morsi was sentenced to death for his role in a 2011 prison break. He was among 106 other Muslim Brotherhood members on trial for the incident. Morsi was arrested Jan 28, 2011 with 24 Muslim Brotherhood leaders and placed in Wadi al-Natrun prison in Cairo, but escaped two days later. Riots followed at other prisons around Cairo and thousands of inmates escaped. Turkey's Erdogan said Morsi's death sentence was a return to 'ancient Egypt.'
link_name: Ex-Egyptian president Morsi sentenced to death over 2011 prison break

status_message: According to CNN, U.S. Special Operations forces conducted a raid overnight on May 15/16 in eastern Syria to capture Abu Sayyaf, a senior ISIS commander. Sayyaf was in charge of ISIS' oil and gas operations. Sayyaf was killed during the raid, his wife, an Iraqi named Umm Sayyaf, was captured and taken to Iraq for interrogation.
link_name: CNN: U.S. troops kill top IS commander

status_message: Romney conceded defeat by TKO to Holyfield after two rounds of the fight which was held in Salt Lake City May 15. At one point Holyfield fell to the mat, pretending that Romney had knocked him down.
link_name: Mitt Romney loses charity boxing match to Evander Holyfield
Former Texas Gov. Rick Perry to announce 2016 run for president on June 4

status_message: Since Jan. 2014, Hillary and Bill Clinton made $30 million from paid speeches and book royalties, according to financial disclosure forms filed May 15.
link_name: Clintons earned $25 million in speaking fees in 16 months

status_message: U.S. crude futures fell to $59.69 May 15 on a weaker dollar and a decline in U.S. oil rig activity, including a decrease in the number of oil rigs by eight. Prices of the West Texas Intermediate (WTI) crude oil benchmark have risen for nine straight weeks, the longest streak since 1983.
link_name: US crude futures rise for ninth straight week, setting 30-year record

status_message: Two manicurists working for NYC nail salons on May 14 filed a proposed class action lawsuit alleging four Upper East Side nail salons underpaid them and violated federal overtime laws.
link_name: NY nail salon workers seek overtime, back pay in proposed class action lawsuit
Islamic State seizes control of gov't compound in Iraq's largest province
Poland moving forward on payments to terrorism suspects allegedly tortured by CIA

status_message: The jury decided May 15 to sentence Dzhokhar Tsarnaev to death for the Boston Marathon bombing. Jury deliberations began May 13 and lasted 14 hours in the penalty phase. Tsarnaev was found guilty April 8 on 30 counts, 17 of which carried a potential death sentence.
link_name: Jury reaches decision in penalty phase of Boston Marathon bombings trial
Oculus recommends $350 graphics card for optimal Rift performance
Aaron Hernandez appeals murder conviction, claims jury used 'guesswork'
House approves $612 billion military funding bill
Reports: Netflix in talks to enter China
Bill Cosby breaks silence about sexual assault allegations
Lyft raises additional $150 million in extended round of funding

status_message: The Mexican government is compensating families of 15 people killed by soldiers in 2014, it said May 14. A commission for victims of cartel violence is dividing 50 million pesos ($3.31 million) between 13 families. An investigation found 12-15 suspects were killed after surrendering. Three soldiers were charged with murder.
link_name: Mexico to pay families of victims killed by soldiers

status_message: A federal judge in Manhattan on May 14 blocked a class action lawsuit by Detroit homeowners accusing Morgan Stanley of pushing pushing risky loans, Reuters reported. The judge ruled the claims were too varied for class action. The decision came days after Detroit extended a deadline for city homeowners to pay back property taxes.
link_name: Judge blocks class action lawsuit by Detroit homeowners against Morgan Stanley

status_message: Indian Prime Minister Modi visited Xian May 14, where he toured the terracotta warriors site and met with Chinese President Xi Jinping. He then went to Beijing May 15 where he met with Chinese Premier Li Keqiang. The two countries signed 24 agreements worth more than $10 billion.
link_name: Indian and Chinese leaders sign billions of dollars in deals

status_message: Rapoport defended her thesis on diphtheria May 13 to the University of Hamburg's medical faculty dean and two professors at her Berlin home, the Wall Street Journal reported. With the help of relatives and friends, she studied advances in the field since World War Two in preparation. The medical faculty dean said she was "brilliant."
link_name: 102-year-old defends Nazi-era thesis to become oldest ever doctorate recipient

status_message: On May 14, Mozambique seized 340 elephant tusks weighing about 2,557 pounds and 65 rhino horns weighing 273.4 pounds that amounted to a total of 1.3 metric tons of poached tusks and horns. The haul was the result of 65 rhino deaths and 170 elephant deaths, police told Reuters.
link_name: Mozambique arrests Chinese national with 1.3 tons of poached tusks and rhino horn

status_message: Typhoon Dolphin was expected directly hit Guam and Rota Island late May 15, bringing up to 12 inches of rain, according to the National Weather Service. Guam was preparing for coastal flooding of up to three feet because the heavy rains were likely to coincide with a high tide.
link_name: Guam braces for Typhoon Dolphin's impact

status_message: Nepal's army reported May 15 it found the wreckage of a U.S. helicopter that went missing May 12 with six marines and two Nepalese soldiers on board. It was unknown if there were survivors, a military official told the AFP. A rescue team found three bodies, Nepal's defense secretary said.
link_name: Nepalese army finds wreckage of missing U.S. helicopter

status_message: President Pierre Nkurunziza returned from a summit in Tanzania May 14 after loyalist police and the military took control of the streets, the airport and TV and radio stations in the capital Bujumbura, AFP reported May 15. The coup leader, Major General Godefroid Niyombare, had disappeared.
link_name: Burundi president returns after coup fails

status_message: Fishermen brought more than 700 Rohingyas and Bangladeshis ashore on the Indonesian island of Sumatra, Reuters reported. They were sheltering in a port warehouse temporarily, according to an official from the Aceh province town of Langsa.
link_name: Hundreds of migrants rescued off of Sumatra

status_message: The gills of the opah, or moonfish, are different to other fish. They use a "counter-current heat exchange system" allowing the opah to keep its body warm in cold water by heating and recirculating its blood like a mammal or a bird said a study published in Science May 15.
link_name: Scientists say fish warms its blood through gills

status_message: B.B. King died on May 15 at the age of 89. He had been battling illness and was forced to cancel the 8 remaining shows on his most recent tour at the end of 2014.
link_name: Blues legend B.B. King has died at age 89

status_message: The Bronx district attorney's office said May 14 the engineer who who fell asleep at the controls of a New York City commuter train in 2013 will not face criminal charges for the accident that killed four and injured more than 70. William Rockefeller, a 15-year veteran, fell asleep due to an undiagnosed sleep disorder.
link_name: No charges for engineer who caused deadly 2013 NYC derailment

status_message: Kevin Halpern, the founder of a company called Celluride Wireless, filed a lawsuit May 13 against Uber, its founders Travis Kalanick and Garrett Camp, and several early investors. He claims they engaged in unfair business practices and in 2006 stole trade secrets to fund and build Uber using his ideas.
link_name: Uber sued for $1 billion over ownership claim

status_message: On May 15 in Sydney, Australian authorities charged a 66-year-old Hong Kong man after customs officers found 331 pounds (150kg) of crystal methamphetamine in a freight shipment that arrived by sea in April. The consignment was handed over to the Australian Federal Police for testing before the man was arrested.
link_name: Hong Kong man charged with importing 331 pounds of crystal methamphetamine
Connecticut police identify two more victims of New Britain serial killer
3 Baltic nations request NATO ground troops in response to Russian activity
Obama attempts to assure Saudi Arabia, other Gulf allies over Iran nuclear talks

status_message: A new control system that could have prevented the accident "had not been turned on," though it was installed in the section of the track where the train entered a curve with a speed limit of 50 mph, according to Reps. Charlie Dent (R-PA) and Andy Harris (R-MD) on May 14.
link_name: Eighth body found in Amtrak derailment wreckage
Calif. governor proposes $115.3 billion budget

status_message: Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika on May 14 replaced nearly a dozen ministers in a major cabinet reshuffle.
link_name: Algeria announces major cabinet reshuffle amid weakening economy
NFL players union appeals Tom Brady's 4-game 'Deflategate' suspension
Candy Crush Saga maker King falls 11% despite Q1 expectations beat
US Congress passes bill to require review of nuclear deal with Iran
Greece abandons legal fight with British Museum over Elgin Marbles
Dropbox acquires audio content startup Umano

status_message: Shares in beauty products seller Avon rose nearly 20% on May 14 fueled by a takeover bid by UK firm, PTG Capital Partners that turned out to be phony. Avon later revealed it had never received the bid, sending its shares down by 14%. Several outlets had raised concerns about the provenance of the company, which is not registered with the UK financial authority.
link_name: Avon shares soar 20% over phony takeover bid

status_message: An audio message, purported to be by Abu Bakr Al-Baghdadi, the Islamic State leader, is the first in several months since Al-Baghdadi's injury in a U.S. air strike. The message was released May 14 by Site Intelligence Group. The Arabic-language message, in which Baghdadi condemns the Saudi royal family, has not been independently verified.
link_name: SITE Intelligence Group: Islamic State releases alleged audio message by leader Abu Bakr Al-Baghdadi

status_message: The People's Harm Reduction Alliance, a non-profit group which runs needle exchanges, is running an illegal program in Seattle that provides meth users with free pipes. The program which has been running since March aims to curb infectious diseases by stopping drug users resorting to using needles if they cannot find a pipe.
link_name: Needle exchange group trials free meth pipes in Seattle
Dow up 189 points, S&P500 closes at record high
Stephanopoulos apologizes for not disclosing Clinton Foundation donations to viewers

status_message: Rep. Loretta Sanchez (D-CA) said at an event May 14 that she will also seek Boxer's open seat. Sanchez, who is an underdog in the race, becomes the first major opponent to Calif. Attorney Gen. Kamala Harris. Sanchez is a moderate Democrat who serves on the House Armed Services and Homeland Security committees.
link_name: California Congresswoman Loretta Sanchez announces 2016 run for Senate
Chinese police order residents of restive Xinjiang to turn in passports
Los Angeles dogs lead the US in attacking postal workers in 2014
Calif. Senate approves bill to abolish personal belief exemption, require vaccinations

status_message: A bill abolishing the personal exemption for vaccines in California schools was passed by the state Senate on May 14. It will now move to the Assembly, and then must gain approval from Gov. Jerry Brown before becoming law. Only Mississippi and West Virginia have such strict requirements.
link_name: Calif. Senate approves bill to abolish personal belief exemption, require vaccinations

status_message: Secret Service agents detained a man outside of the White House after he attempted to fly a remote-controlled aerial device over the White House fence on May 14. President Barack Obama was not in the White House at the time of the incident.
link_name: Man detained after attempting to fly drone over White House fence
AP: Feds develop labels for GMO-free foods
Telecoms ask appeals court to halt net neutrality
Explosives found in Ireland ahead of visit from Prince Charles
Eighth body found in Amtrak derailment wreckage

status_message: With a couple of tweets late May 13, actor Harry Shearer indicated he was leaving "The Simpsons" due to a contract dispute related to a desire to engage in other work. Producer Al Jean confirmed to CNN that Shearer would not be with the show. The characters would not be killed off, he said, but would use others for voice overs.
link_name: Harry Shearer to leave 'The Simpsons'

status_message: In the first 3 months of the year, immigration to the U.S. by Cubans surged 118% since 2014. 9,371 Cubans have arrived to the U.S., mostly by way of Miami or the Mexico border. The rise has been attributed to fear that the government will rescind the Cuban Refugee Adjustment Act amid diplomatic negotiations.
link_name: Diplomatic negotiations lead to 118% rise in immigration by Cubans to U.S. since 2014

status_message: Sharp will cut about 10% of its total workforce, it announced May 14. The company said it lost $1.86 billion in the last financial year and that 3,500 employees would go in Japan. It will sell the building of its headquarters in the city of Osaka.
link_name: Sharp announces cuts to its workforce after $1.86 billion loss

status_message: China Vanke and Wanda Group, the largest residential and retail real estate developers in the country, respectively, announced a partnership May 14.The two companies will work together to explore land deals and possibly build joint projects. Wanda is chaired by Wang Jianlin, Asia's richest man.
link_name: China's two largest real estate developers start partnership

status_message: Human Rights Watch (HRW) on May 13 called on the International Committee of Military Medicine to urge the Indonesian armed forces to end virginity tests on female applicants, which HRW called gender-based violence. The committee meets in Indonesia May 17-22.
link_name: Indonesian military conducts 'virginity tests' on female applicants

status_message: Armed Syrian opposition groups will not participate in UN-sponsored consultations in Geneva, Reuters reported May 13. A letter from 30 groups accused UN Syria envoy Staffan de Mistura of "standing on the side of one party without the other." The exiled National Coalition said days earlier it also would not join talks.
link_name: Syrian armed groups, opposition abroad reject UN peace talks

status_message: Farid Ismail, a former member of parliament and member of the Muslim Brotherhood died from liver failure in prison on May 13, a statement from the Brotherhood's banned political party said. He was suffering from liver cirrhosis and Hepatitis C. Supporters blamed his death on a lack of proper medical attention.
link_name: Muslim Brotherhood politician dies in Egyptian prison

status_message: Gunmen stormed a guesthouse in the Shar-e-Naw neighborhood during a party on the evening of May 13 in Kabul, leaving at least five people dead including a U.S. citizen and two Indian nationals. Six people were injured and 54 hostages were rescued, police said. The Taliban claimed responsibility in a statement.
link_name: Gunmen attack Kabul guesthouse party
Five of those killed in Amtrak derailment identified, including Naval Academy student
Christie's New York auctions smash billion-dollar milestone
South Carolina approves police body camera bill named for Walter Scott
GoPro founder pays $229m to keep an old promise
GOP senator unveils contingency plan in case Supreme Court guts Obamacare tax credits
NTSB: New safety system would have prevented deadly Amtrak accident

status_message: Shake Shack posted Q1 2015 revenue of $37.8 million, up 56% from $24.2 million a year prior. The company posted a net loss of $12.7 million, or $1.06 per share in the quarter ending April 1. Shake Shack stock was up 7.39% in after-hours trading following the earnings report.
link_name: Shake Shack revenue up 56% in Q1

status_message: Walmart this summer will launch a service for its online shoppers that delivers items in three days or less, the company said May 13. The service will cost $50 per year, half of what Amazon Prime costs (though Prime also includes access to a streaming video library, among other perks).
link_name: Walmart plans $50 per year three-day shipping service
Nurse who rejected Guantanamo force-feeding set to return to work
Jury begins deliberations on penalty phase in Boston Marathon bombings trial

status_message: The U.S. House of Representatives passed the USA Freedom Act in a 338 to 88 vote May 13. The bill now heads to the Senate, where it faces an uncertain future due to opposition from Sen. Maj. Leader Mitch McConnell (R-KY).
link_name: House passes bill to end NSA's bulk collection of phone metadata

status_message: Sen. Bill Cassidy (R-LA) unveiled a plan on May 13 to allow people to keep insurance until Aug. 2017 if the Supreme Court rules that federally purchased insurance does not qualify for tax credits. It would allow low-income residents to access insurance through special savings accounts linked to age, not their income.
link_name: GOP senator unveils contingency plan in case Supreme Court guts Obamacare tax credits
House passes bill to ban abortions after 20 weeks

status_message: Preliminary data from the National Transportation and Safety Board on May 13 found that the train was traveling at speeds of over 100 mph at the time of the crash. The group will continue to conduct calibrations. NTSB released video of the scene on May 13.
link_name: Philadelphia Amtrak death toll rises to 7, train found to be speeding

status_message: Spotify accounted for 10% of U.S. record label revenue in 2014, the company's director of economics said at a May 12 music industry conference. The executive, Will Page, added that Spotify alone accounted for half of the worldwide streaming music market, currently valued at $1.5 billion.
link_name: Spotify claims they account for 10% of US record label revenue

status_message: The train was traveling in excess of 100mph as it entered a sharp curve with a speed limit of 50mph, the WSJ reported May 13 citing people with knowledge of the investigation.
link_name: Philadelphia Amtrak death toll rises to 7, train found to be speeding

status_message: International inspectors found traces of the banned toxins sarin and ricin in three military locations in Syria, the NY Times reported May 12. Inspectors said the small amounts are not necessarily proof of an ongoing chemical weapons program. Diplomats said the use of chlorine bombs may be more concerning. Inspectors will investigate further on May 16.
link_name: Inspectors find banned toxic chemicals at military locations in Syria

status_message: Prince Charles' "black spider memos" were published on the Cabinet Office on May 13. The correspondence with government departments that were made available included a letter to former health secretary John Reid and a letter to then-prime minister Tony Blair. The Guardian issued analysis of the correspondence.
link_name: Secret Prince Charles letters to government made available

status_message: The American Petroleum Institute said May 12 it filed a federal lawsuit against some of the new regulations. API wants to push back the deadline to retrofit older cars, undo new braking system requirements, and ease some operation restrictions.
link_name: Oil industry files lawsuit to stop new safety rules for oil tank cars

status_message:
A123 Systems claimed in February that Apple had "improperly raided" it in search of engineers who could work on a battery project. Apple disputed the claims.

Apple has been reported to be working on an electric car project.
link_name: Apple reaches settlement with electric car battery company for "improperly" poaching its engineers

status_message: At least 92% of married women between ages 15 and 49 in Egypt have undergone female genital mutilation, Egypt's Minister of Health Adel Adawy reported on May 10. Only 31% of FGM operations are performed by a doctor and the majority occur when women are still girls, between ages 9 and 12.
link_name: Study finds 92% of Egypt's married women have experienced female genital mutilation

status_message: The Vatican released a statement May 13 naming the State of Palestine as party to talks with the Holy See. Although the Vatican and Pope Francis have referred to the State of Palestine in the past, it appeared to be the first time in an official document related to a treaty.
link_name: Vatican names State of Palestine in treaty document

status_message: The images displayed on traffic lights at dozens of pedestrian crossings were changed in early May to show couples, including gay and lesbian ones, instead of the normal solitary figure. They will stay up until June.
link_name: To promote tolerance and road safety, Vienna installs crossing lights showing same-sex couples

status_message: ICC prosecutor Fatou Bensouda said in an interview with the AP published May 13 that she had yet to receive information from Palestinians and Israelis. The inquiry into the Gaza war is still in preliminary stages and is not a formal investigation.
link_name: ICC prosecutor urges cooperation in Gaza probe

status_message: As the outbreak ends, vaccine trials in Africa may not be completed, a World Health Organization (WHO) research and development summit in Geneva heard May 11-12. Data collected so far does not prove the effectiveness of vaccines and there is international disquiet about nonstandard, random testing.
link_name: Continuation of Ebola vaccine trials in Africa in doubt

status_message: An airstrike by the U.S.-led coalition killed IS deputy leader Abu Alaa Al-Afri, Iraqi military spokesman spokesman Tahsin Ibrahim said May 13. Al-Afri was believed to be the head of the organization since Abu Bakr Al-Baghdadi was severely injured in an airstrike earlier in the year.
link_name: Airstrike killed Islamic State number two, Iraqi military says

status_message: Yukiya Amano, the head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, disputed in an interview with the AP published May 12 that the nuclear deal restricted access to Iranian military sites. Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei has said military sites are off-limits.
link_name: UN nuclear head says Iran deal includes access to military sites

status_message: Nguyen Chi Tuyen, also known as Anh Chi, told VOA May 12 that he blamed authorities after a group of men beat him with a metal pipe in Hanoi on May 11. He was active in demonstrations earlier in the year against government plans to cut down thousands of trees in the capital.
link_name: Vietnamese activist beaten unconscious in Hanoi street

status_message: Australian Treasurer Joe Hockey released the government's budget May 12 with a deficit of 35.1 billion Australian dollars ($28.1B). A program worth 5.5 billion Australian dollars ($4.4B) allows small businesses to claim equipment investments up to 20,000 Australian dollars ($16,000).
link_name: Australian budget includes small business package, tax reforms

status_message: Pakistan's the News reported May 12 that Brigadier Usman Khalid defected to give the U.S. information about bin Laden's whereabouts. Pakistani generals told AFP that a defector, presumably Khalifa, didn't know bin Laden's location.
link_name: Journalists corroborate parts of controversial report on bin Laden assassination

status_message: A shipment of blankets, sleeping mats and kitchen utensils by the UN refugee agency arrived in Yemen on May 12. Iran sent a ship with aid, as well as warships to prevent it being intercepted. The U.S. is tracking the Iranian ships and urged Iran to use a UN distribution hub in Djibouti, a U.S. government spokesman said.
link_name: Humanitarian aid arriving in Yemen during ceasefire

status_message: A fire razed a factory for making plastic slippers, killing at least three people, authorities said. Workers' relatives reported 62 people missing, Valenzuela Mayor Rex Gatchalian said. Seven survivors were reported after the blaze was put under control, which took five hours.
link_name: Deadly fire hits Philippines factory, dozens missing

status_message: On May 13 a South Korean reserve soldier identified as Choi, 23, shot and killed another reserve solider and injured three others before committing suicide in Seoul, South Korea's defense ministry said. No other details have been given.
link_name: South Korean soldier kills solider, then himself at training camp

status_message: In Europe, the UK best safeguards legal rights of lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) people. Within the UK, Scottish law best protects equal rights, according to the 2015 Rainbow Europe Index compiled by the European Region of the International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association (ILGA-Europe).
link_name: Scotland tops 2015 EU Rainbow Index for LGBT equality

status_message: Thousands of people slept out in the open overnight May 12 for fear of further earthquakes, the AP reported May 13. Nepalese officials encouraged people to evacuate damaged buildings.
link_name: Thousands sleep on the streets in Nepal after earthquakes

status_message: HRW released a report May 13 that claims torture is still widely used by police in China to extract confessions. The report was based on dozens of interviews with detainees and their families, as well as lawyers and officials.
link_name: Chinese police torturing suspects despite ban, Human Rights Watch says

status_message: Gunmen on motorcycles killed at least 47 people when they opened fire on a bus in Karachi carrying women, children and men mainly from the Ismaili Shiite community, according to eyewitness accounts. At least two dozen people were injured.
link_name: Gunmen kill dozens of people on a Karachi bus

status_message: Ali Herz, 50, Ali's brother Bassem, 29, Ali's son Adam, 22, and Bassem's wife, Sarah Zeaiter, 24, face charges of conspiracy to export arms to Lebanon without a license, an unsealed court document revealed May 12. All four are being held without bail and face a maximum sentence of 5 years in prison if convicted.
link_name: US charges four with trying to export arms without a license to Lebanon

status_message: Late on May 12, Facebook confirmed earlier reports that it will now allow certain news organizations to publish original articles on Facebook. Facebook says that "Instant Articles" will first be available only on Facebook's iPhone app.
link_name: Facebook officially launches "Instant Articles"
Three men plead guilty to providing material support to Somali extremists
Jimmy Carter feeling 'fine' after falling ill
Rand Paul's son pleads guilty to driving under the influence
Ultra HD Blu-ray Disc format finalized, consumer products due this year
FDA recommends lifting ban on blood donations from gay men
US budget surplus reaches seven-year high in April
Prosecutor will not press charges in police shooting of Wisconsin teen
Pew: Number of Americans unaffiliated with a religion grows
Report finds many migrants die unrecorded at sea

status_message: Bleep, an encrypted voice and text chat app for Android, iOS, Mac OS X, and Windows, was released by BitTorrent, Inc. on May 12. In addition to encrypting user's voice and text messages, Bleep can also optionally erase messages after they've been viewed. The app is free, though the company says it's considering adding premium features.
link_name: BitTorrent's encrypted chat app Bleep follows ephemeral messaging trend

status_message: 80% of the 60% of Network Rail employees who turned out to vote on May 12, voted in favor of a strike. The workers, represented by the Rail, Maritime and Transport Union (RMT), rejected a pay offer from Network Rail of 500 GBP plus pay rises in line with inflation.
link_name: British rail workers vote to strike over pay
Harriet Tubman named as candidate to replace Andrew Jackson on $20 bill
Senate Democrats block fast-tracking Obama's trade deal
Family of possible 5th Boston Marathon bombing victim files for benefits
Feds warn transportation funding is running out

status_message: Sprint agreed on May 12 to pay $68 million to settle charges that it engaging in "cramming," or charging its customers for unwanted items. At least $50 million will go toward refunding customers for the unwanted items, while $6 million will be paid to the U.S. Treasury as a fine. States participating in the settlement will get $12 million.
link_name: Sprint to pay $68 million to settle 'cramming' investigation

status_message: UVA Dean Nicole Eramo filed a defamation suit against Rolling Stone and journalist Sabrina Rubin Erdely seeking $7.85 million in damages on May 12. Eramo said she was cast as the "chief villain" in the article, which she said "depicted the UVA as an institution that is indifferent to rape on campus."
link_name: University of Virginia dean sues Rolling Stone for defamation over discredited rape story

status_message: 32-year-old Derrick Dewayne Charles, set to die in Texas on the evening May 12, entered a last-minute plea for a delay of punishment. Charles pled guilty to killing his 15-year-old girlfriend, her mother and her grandfather in 2003. He would be the seventh person killed by the state this year.
link_name: Houston man, scheduled to die May 12, makes last-minute plea for execution halt

status_message: Maryland Governor Larry Hogan was expected to sign a law later in the day May 12 that would allow for the direct sale of Tesla cars to consumers. The law goes into effect in October. Gov. Hogan said he wanted to make sure that Maryland had a positive "business climate."
link_name: Maryland to allow direct Tesla sales

status_message: Vit Jedlicka, a Czech politician and "president" of Liberland, was detained May 9 by Croatian police, the self-proclaimed republic announced on its website May 10. The group's Facebook page said May 11 that Jedlicka was released the next day after a "very friendly meeting" with police and a judge.
link_name: Leader of self-proclaimed 'Liberland' detained by Croatian police

status_message: The Barack Obama Foundation announced May 12 that the library will be built on Chicago's South Side near the University of Chicago, which submitted a bid. Both Obama and the First Lady at one time worked at the university and their Chicago home is near it.
link_name: Obama Foundation to announce location of future presidential library tomorrow

status_message: Amos Yee was found guilty on two charges May 12. A third charge related to statements specifically about former leader Lee Kuan Yew was withdrawn. The prosecution called for Yee to undergo counseling and probation. His lawyer argued for a fine and pointed out he has spent 18 days in detention.
link_name: Singapore teen blogger convicted on two charges

status_message: A witness at a congressional hearing in Brazil on May 11 accused President Dilma Rousseff and former president Lula da Silva of knowing about corruption in Petrobras, the Wall Street Journal reported May 11. The witness, Alberto Youssef, was imprisoned for three years in April for money laundering as part of a deal to testify.
link_name: Witness accuses Brazilian leaders of knowing about Petrobras corruption

status_message: A masked gang armed with machetes on May 12 killed blogger Ananta Bijoy Das, the third blogger killed since February. Das also wrote for a website that was once moderated by Avijit Roy, who was killed in the capital of Dhaka, the BBC reported.
link_name: Third blogger killed in Bangladesh since February

status_message: Human rights lawyer and activist Mahinour El-Masry was arrested during a court session. She is appealing a 2014 sentence of 2 years in prison on accusations of rioting in 2013. She was also imprisoned in 2014 for breaking a law banning protests. She received an international human rights award after she was released in Sept. 2014.
link_name: Egyptian human rights lawyer rearrested

status_message: Up to 8,000 Rohingyas and Bangladeshis may be stranded off the Thai coast, the International Organization for Migration (IOM) said May 11. Human smugglers were not landing due to a crackdown in Thailand, it said. The UN refugee agency and IOM called for a regional response May 12. Indonesia has been turning away boats.
link_name: Rohingya and Bangladeshi migrants smuggled to Indonesia and Malaysia

status_message: China and Russia began naval exercises in the Mediterranean May 11. Three Chinese ships, including two 054A/Jiangkai II class missile frigates, and six Russian ships are involved in the drills. Chinese President Xi Jinping attended Russia's Victory Day celebrations in Moscow two days earlier.
link_name: China and Russia begin joint naval exercises in Mediterranean

status_message: Colombia ordered special forces to crackdown on FARC's unapproved mining business to end its $9 million a month revenue stream, defense minister Juan Carlos Pinzon said May 11. Despite peace talks in Cuba, the army blew up machinery in 63 tungsten, gold and coltan mines and arrested 59 people.
link_name: Colombian forces raid FARC's lucrative mines

status_message: A strong earthquake with a preliminary magnitude of 7.4 hit Nepal near the Chinese border not far from Mount Everest around midday May 12. People came out onto the street and some buildings that survived the April quake had collapsed, witnesses in Nepal said.
link_name: Another strong earthquake hits Nepal, causes more damage
Detroit starts issuing water shut-off warnings to 25,000 residents
Macedonia charges 30 with terrorism after clashes in breakaway region
German postal workers threaten strikes as train drivers end week-long work stoppage

status_message: Investigators looking into the case of a serial killer targeting women in Hartford County, CT, are "confident" a single person is responsible for the deaths of seven women, the chief state's attorney, Kevin Kane, said May 11.
link_name: Connecticut police identify suspected serial killer in New Britain case

status_message: Aaron Hernandez was indicted on May 11 in Massachusetts on witness intimidation charges for allegedly shooting his former friend, Alexander Bradley, in the face in 2013. Bradley survived and is an alleged witness to the 2012 double murder that Hernandez is charged with committing. Bradley is expected to testify in the upcoming trial.
link_name: Aaron Hernandez indicted for witness intimidation
Google: Self-driving cars involved in 11 'minor' accidents so far
Senators threaten to filibuster reauthorization of Patriot Act

status_message: South Africa saw an 18% increase in the number of rhinos killed by poachers in the first four months of 2015 compared to the same period in 2014, the country's environment minister said May 10.
link_name: South Africa sees 18% rise in rhino poaching in 2015
Soccer legend Pele leaves hospital after prostate surgery
NY Gov. Cuomo orders emergency measures to protect nail salon workers
H5N8 bird flu strain found in Indiana

status_message: Skelos agreed to step down from his position in the New York Senate May 12, while still maintaining he is innocent of the charges filed against him. Skelos will be replaced by state Senator John Flanagan of Suffolk County, NY.
link_name: NY Senate leader Dean Skelos resigns amid ongoing corruption probe
Police officers killed on duty nearly doubled in 2014, FBI reports
Wrigley Field debuts new bleachers
Christie's hopes to break world record with sale of Picasso's 'Women of Algiers'

status_message: GM said May 11 that compensation manager Ken Feinberg has found at least 100 death claims eligible for compensation for accidents linked to the faulty ignition switches as of May 8, up from 80 in early April. Feinberg also found 184 injured people are eligible for payments. The company has 626 cases still under review.
link_name: 100 deaths linked to faulty GM ignition switches eligible for compensation

status_message: The NFL announced on May 11 that Patriots quarterback Tom Brady would be suspended four games, and the Patriots fined $1 million and stripped of a first-round draft pick in 2016 and a fourth-round pick in 2017 over their involvement in deflating footballs during the AFC Championship Game in January.
link_name: Tom Brady suspended four games over 'deflategate'

status_message: U.S. companies now hold $1.1 trillion in overseas cash, according to a May 10 report from Moody's. That's up from $950 billion a year ago. All told, U.S. companies now hold $1.73 trillion in cash, with five tech companies (Apple, Cisco, Google, Microsoft, and Oracle) according for $430 billion.
link_name: US companies hold $1.1 trillion in cash overseas
Nasdaq to trial bitcoin technology for private company trades
Calif. lawmakers denounce initiative that calls for the execution of gay people

status_message: Scientists writing in the journal Nature Climate Change on May 11 used more precise measurements than previous studies to determine that the rate of sea level rise since 1999 has been underestimated, while estimates for the 1990s were slightly overstated.
link_name: Sea level rise since 1990 may have accelerated faster than previously thought

status_message: The Obama administration on May 11 granted conditional approval to allow Shell to drill for oil in the Arctic Ocean, pending approval of drilling permits, the New York Times reported. In a statement, Shell called the decision an "important milestone" for the company's offshore exploration plans.
link_name: White House grants conditional approval for Shell's Arctic drilling

status_message: An account of the bin Laden assassination written by author Seymour Hersh was published by the London Review of Books May 10. Hersh claimed the White House lied about the events of bin Laden's death, citing an anonymous "retired senior intelligence official who was knowledgeable about the initial intelligence about bin Laden's presence in Abottabad."
link_name: White House dismisses controversial new report on bin Laden assassination

status_message: Japan's ruling coalition signed amendments on May 11 that significantly expand Japanese military operations abroad. The bill is expected to pass on majority lines in parliament. The amendments allow Japan to increase its missiles systems, deploy its military to conflicts and conduct other operations like minesweeping.
link_name: Japan's ruling bloc approves expanded military power
Dawn probe takes best pictures yet of Ceres' mysterious bright spots
New York Times makes 'NYT Now' mobile app free
FCC rejects telecom petition to delay net neutrality implementation
Defense rests in Boston Marathon bombing sentencing phase
Latest 'Game of Thrones' episode breaks piracy record

status_message: The Barack Obama Foundation said May 11 that the location of the future library will be announced May 12 at an event in Chicago. The event will be attended by Chicago Mayor Rahm Emanuel.
link_name: Obama Foundation to announce location of future presidential library tomorrow

status_message: EU foreign policy chief Federica Mogherini will ask the UN Security Council May 11 to allow military action against human smugglers in Libyan waters. Libya opposes the move. The UK drafted the UN resolution, which would put a military operation of about 10 EU countries under Italian command, the Guardian reported.
link_name: EU seeks UN military mandate against traffickers in Libya

status_message: The UN is counseling hundreds of pregnant girls rescued by the Nigerian military and being ridiculed at home as "Boko Haram wives." Girls who escaped hours after their abduction from a Chibok school in Feb. 2014 left home after similar experiences even though they were not raped, AFP reported May 11.
link_name: Rescued girls stigmatized after being raped by Boko Haram

status_message: Sweden's supreme court rejected Assange's appeal May 11, saying there was no need to revoke the warrant for his detention since prosecutors decided in March to question him in London about allegations of sexual assault. One of the five appeal judges dissented, the Australian ABC reported.
link_name: Swedish court rejects Assange's appeal against arrest warrant

status_message: Smartphone shipments in China fell 4.3% year-over-year and 8% quarter-over-quarter in Q1 2015 to 98.8 million units, IDC said May 11. It was the first year-on-year decline in six years. Apple had the largest market share in the quarter with 14.7%, followed by Xiaomi with 13.7%.
link_name: China smartphone shipments decline for first time in 6 years

status_message: Three boats for human smuggling unloaded 1,018 Rohingya and Bangladeshi migrants on a resort island, police said. The group of 555 Bangladeshis and 463 Rohingya were detained. A Bangladeshi man told police they had not eaten for three days.  Close to 600 Rohingya and Bangladeshi migrants were rescued off Aceh, Indonesia May 10. It is believed they left from Thailand, where refugees are often held in trafficking camps, and were told they were going to Malaysia. Another boat carrying about 400 people was spotted early May 11.
link_name: Rohingya and Bangladeshi migrants smuggled to Indonesia and Malaysia

status_message: Japan's ruling coalition signed amendments on May 11 that significantly expand Japanese military operations abroad. The bill is expected to pass on majority lines in parliament. The amendments allow Japan to increase its missiles systems, deploy its military to conflicts and conduct other operations like minesweeping.
link_name: Japan's ruling bloc approves expanded military power

status_message: Saadi Gaddafi appeared in court on May 10. He is on trial for killing a soccer coach and for unlawful imprisonment. The trial was adjourned until July to give his lawyers more time on the case. He faces other charges, but this case is the most serious as it carries the death penalty.
link_name: Gaddafi son Saadi appears in court for murder charge

status_message: Saudi Arabia announced May 10 that King Salman would not meet U.S. President Barack Obama in Washington or attend a Gulf Arab summit at Camp David. The next men two in line for the throne, Interior Minister and Crown Prince Mohammed bin Nayef, and the defense minister, Deputy Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, will travel to the U.S.
link_name: Saudi King Salman skips US summit

status_message: Officer Benjamin Deen, 34, stopped a vehicle for speeding on May 9, officials said. Officer Liquori Tate, 25, a rookie, arrived after Deen radioed for backup, Hattiesburg Mayor Johnny L. DuPree said. Deen, Tate and a K-9 officer were killed. A memorial service was planned for May 11.
link_name: Four people arrested for deaths of two Mississippi police officers

status_message: Former President Jimmy Carter cut short a trip to Guyana on May 10 due to unspecified health concerns. Carter was in the South American country as part of an election observation mission, the 100th such operation for the Carter Center.
link_name: Former President Jimmy Carter, 90, cuts trip abroad short after falling ill

status_message: "Avengers: Age of Ultron" earned $77.2 million in North America during its second weekend for a domestic 10-day total of $312.9 million. Globally, "Age of Ultron" has made $875.3 million, with the film still to debut in China and Japan.
link_name: 'Avengers' 10-day global total reaches $875.3 million

status_message: By May 10, the death toll had topped 8,000 people. Avalanches and poor weather conditions on May 8-9 forced officials to halt recovery efforts in the northern village of Langtang, authorities said.
link_name: Recovery efforts suspended in Nepal due to avalanches as death toll tops 8,000

status_message: The monthly global average concentration of carbon dioxide surpassed 400 parts per million (ppm) in March 2015, according to NOAA data released in May. It was the first time the monthly concentration passed 400 since measurements began, the NOAA said.
link_name: Global carbon dioxide concentrations hit record high

status_message: The U.S. National Weather Service issued tornado warnings on May 9 for six states: Arkansas, Colorado, Kansas, Nebraska, Oklahoma and Texas. One person was killed May 9 after a tornado touched down in Cisco, Texas, about 100 miles west of Fort Worth. Several states were hit with severe weather.
link_name: Tornado warnings issued in six US states

status_message: Yemen's Houthis on May 10 accepted a five-day ceasefire proposal from Saudi Arabia to start on May 12. The truce would allow humanitarian agencies to operate. Houthis said they would respond to ceasefire violations including by "Al-Qaeda and those who stand with it and support it and fund it."
link_name: Yemen's Houthis accept truce proposal from Saudi Arabia

status_message: The storm strengthened to a super typhoon and made landfall May 10. Officials warned of landslides and flash flooding. Coastal residents were told to evacuate to safer land. The storm reached maximum sustained winds of 115 mph and a diameter of 93 miles, the Philippine government said.
link_name: Super Typhoon bears down on Philippines

status_message: San Francisco Mayor Ed Lee on May 8 signed an ordinance to ban smokeless tobacco from all athletic venues in the city, including AT&T Park, home of the San Francisco Giants. The ordinance, which will take effect Jan. 1, 2016, specifically refers to baseball and is the first of its kind in the U.S.
link_name: SF mayor bans smokeless tobacco at city fields, including Giants' AT&T Park

status_message: Research published May 7 in the journal Science said that Mercury's magnetic field is 3.8 billion years old and may have once been as strong as Earth's. Data gathered by MESSENGER in 2014-2015 when the probe flew very close to Mercury's surface, at times as low as 9 miles above the planet, was used for the study.
link_name: Mercury's magnetic field is ancient and may have once equaled Earth's
Los Angeles becomes first US city to set earthquake standards for cellphone towers

status_message: Jameis Winston filed a counterclaim on May 8 against former FSU student Erica Kinsman, who filed a lawsuit in April claiming Winston raped her in 2012. He is seeking at least $75,000, plus punitive damages.
link_name: Jameis Winston files counterclaim against rape accuser

status_message: Native American members of the Yellowstone Ecosystem Subcommittee say they oppose delisting grizzly bears over concerns of planned sports hunting. The subcommittee, which oversees Yellowstone grizzly bears, is composed of officials representing the federal government, states and tribes.
link_name: Tribes oppose sport hunting of Yellowstone grizzly bears
Suspected pirate silver found off Madagascar
210 Zappos employees take buyout after management style change

status_message: According to the California Office of Statewide Health Planning and Development, emergency rooms across the state saw 1,300 heroin poisoning cases involving young adults between the ages of 20 and 29 in 2014, compared to 200 in 2005.
link_name: Calif. emergency rooms see spike in heroin poisoning cases among young adults

status_message: Hosni Mubarak and his sons Gamal and Alaa were sentenced on May 9 to three years in prison without the possibility of parole and fined following a retrial on corruption charges. It wasn't immediately clear whether the three will get credit for time served and go free.
link_name: Hosni Mubarak and sons sentenced to 3 years in prison

status_message: Total pay-per-view buys for the fight may reach as high as 5.625 million, according to Yahoo Sports boxing reporter Kevin Iole. That would be more than double the previous record of 2.48 million set in 2007.
link_name: Yahoo Sports: Mayweather-Pacquiao PPV buys could top 5.6 million

status_message: Spotify posted a loss of $197 million in 2014, according to documents filed in Luxembourg that were made public May 8. That compares to a loss of $68 million in 2013.
link_name: Spotify reports $197 million loss for 2014

status_message: After going 42 days without a new case, Liberia was declared Ebola-free by the World Health Organization (WHO) on May 9.
link_name: Liberia declared Ebola-free by WHO

status_message: A draft provincial building regulation made public in May in Zhejiang Province would officially restrict Christian churches from having crosses above their roofs.
link_name: Chinese province continues crackdown on Christian church crosses
Reports: Uber seeking $50 billion valuation with new funding round

status_message: Starbucks announced on May 8 that it is moving the sourcing and manufacturing of its bottled water brand Ethos Water out of California. The coffee chain said it will begin to move production to its Pennsylvania supplier right away due to "serious drought conditions." The company also said it's looking for a new source and supplier to serve its West Coast distribution.
link_name: Starbucks moves bottled water production out of California
Guatemala vice president resigns amid corruption scandal

status_message: The Postal Service reported on May 8 a net loss of $1.5 billion during the first three months of 2015, down from $1.9 billion it lost in the same quarter last year. USPS saw a 2.1% decline in the volume of first-class mail sent and 1.1% drop in standard mail. In all, it sent 420 million fewer pieces of mail year-over-year.
link_name: US Postal Service reports $1.5 billion loss in first 3 months of 2015

status_message: The California Supreme Court on May 7 overturned a lower court decision in favor of drugmaker Bayer, ruling there was a potential antitrust problem posed by its decision to pay a smaller firm to delay the release of a generic alternative to Bayer's Cipro antibiotic. Bayer had offered the company, Barr, $398.1 million to delay the release of the drug.
link_name: California court reopens pay-to-delay case against drugmaker Bayer
Mayor of Tehran outfits 1,500 billboards around Iranian capital with art
Italy's Renzi: Missed opportunity for US trade deal would be 'own goal' for Europe
Eurozone employment rate rises for first time since 2008
Court sides with FAA in case over allowing gadgets on planes

status_message: Kyle Dube, now 22, was sentenced to 60 years in prison for orchestrating a 2013 kidnapping plot that ended in a Maine teen's death. Citing the defendant's lack of remorse, the judge ruled Dube will serve a concurrent 30 years for kidnapping. His attorneys are appealing the conviction.
