link_name: Man sentenced to 60 years for botched kidnapping plot that led to victim's death
Pilot error cited for deadly 2014 hot air balloon accident in Virginia
Tennessee governor signs new abortion clinic regulations into law

status_message: A jury ruled in favor of HBO on May 8 in a lawsuit brought by Mitre Sports International, a sporting goods company, that was featured in a 2008 episode of "Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel." Mitre claimed HBO had fabricated scenes depicting child labor abuses in India during the segment titled "Children of Industry."
link_name: Jury clears HBO in defamation suit
Two dozen sei whales beached on Chile's shores
Obama visits 50th state as president, arriving in South Dakota
Former Energy Dept. employee charged with attempting to steal nuclear secrets for China
Effects of subtropical storm Ana likely to be minor, officials say
'Biosimilar' rival to Amgen chemotherapy drug can't be sold in US, court rules
China, Russia sign cyber 'nonaggression pact'
GoPro executive steps in at SurveyMonkey following death of CEO David Goldberg
Appeals court overturns convictions of 3 peace activists for nuclear site break-in

status_message: Jurors notified the trial judge May 8 that they could not reach a unanimous verdict. Justice Maxwell Wiley later called a mistrial after the defense claimed that prolonging deliberations would amount to coercion to reach a verdict. This was the third time they told the judge they were unable to reach a unanimous verdict. They had been deliberating since April 15.
link_name: Judge declares mistrial in Etan Patz murder case after jury fails to reach verdict
Nintendo expects first mobile game this year
WSJ: GE offers retention bonuses to key employees amid financial services selloff
Illinois high court strikes down state's $111 billion pension deficit fix
Court backs TV programmers in key AT&T-DirecTV merger lawsuit
'More adult' Muppets show to return to TV
Ukraine's president says nearly 7,000 civilians killed
Mexican police officer arrested in missing students case

status_message: A Las Vegas court ruled against three children of B.B. King who sought control of their father's affairs. The May 7 decision cited two investigations that found no evidence of wrongdoing by King's business manager regarding the singer's finances and medical care. The court also said the petition can not be considered until all of King's family members receive legal notice.
link_name: Family members of B.B. King denied guardianship

status_message: Israel approved 900 Jewish settler homes in East Jerusalem after Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu formed a government, Israeli NGO Peace Now said May 7. Netanyahu gave key posts to the pro-settlement Jewish Home party including the Justice, Agriculture and Education ministries and other positions that influence settlement policy.
link_name: Israel approved 900 settler homes shortly after forming government

status_message: The tennis center and the basketball center are under construction, but work on the equestrian and BMX centers did not start, Reuters reported May 8. The rush to complete the projects within 500 days will raise expenses. The cost of 25% of construction had yet to be determined.
link_name: Construction delays plague Rio Olympics with 500 days to go

status_message: Greece removed pensions and wages from the negotiating table with its creditors on May 7. It faces a 750-million-euro payment ($850.4 million) to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) May 12. A Greek government spokesman said Eurozone creditors should not expect the government to break its election promises.
link_name: Greek government balks creditor demands to cut pensions and wages

status_message: Johnson will take his seat in the House of Commons while continuing mayoral duties until his term expires in 2016. He won his seat May 8 with 50% of the vote, which was nearly double the next candidate. He previously represented the seat of Henley for seven years before becoming mayor in 2008.
link_name: London Mayor Boris Johnson wins House of Commons seat

status_message: A court initially granted Khan bail on May 7 on the condition that he surrender his passport and post a bond of Rs 30,000 ($468). Police dispersed Khan supporters protesting his conviction from outside the high court on May 8, when it decided he would remain out of jail through his next hearing in June.
link_name: Indian court grants bail to Bollywood star Salman Khan until it hears his appeal

status_message: Satellite images from the last four years show Vietnam conducting land reclamation in the South China Sea, the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) told Reuters May 7. Some of the installations appear to have military uses. China's artificial island work "dwarfs Vietnam's," CSIS said.
link_name: Vietnam building artificial islands in South China Sea

status_message: Chinese state media May 8 quoted experts saying that China may end its one-child policy completely within the next three to five years. While not an actual policy change, such a story in state media would almost certainly have gotten government approval before publication.
link_name: Chinese state media: All couples likely to be allowed two children by 2020

status_message: Standard Chartered says it is examining the project's environmental credentials, the Guardian reported May 7. The London-based bank is "in active discussions" with the government and "ready to meet green campaigners," as it considers backing the coal mine that would use the Abbot Point terminal, it said.
link_name: London bank plans to look at environmental impact of coal port on Great Barrier Reef

status_message: A recent study shows Enceladus' ocean is likely similar to 'soda lakes' on Earth, which have high concentrations of sodium carbonate. The ocean's pH level is around 11 or 12, or about that of a household cleaner solution. It is likely the result of a process called serpentinization, which creates molecular hydrogen (H2).
link_name: Saturn moon likely has a hidden 'soda ocean'

status_message: China's April exports fell 6.4% year-on-year, far lower than the 2.4% drop expected by analysts. China's General Administration of Customs also said May 8 that imports fell 16.2% in April, leading to a $34.13 billion trade surplus.
link_name: Chinese exports fell further than expected in April

status_message: In a TV special to air May 9 after a match replay, Mayweather tells Showtime that he changed his mind about a rematch and says he could detect no sign of injury during the fight. Mayweather says Pacquiao was strong and fast, Showtime Sports tweeted May 7.
link_name: Mayweather: No rematch, Pacquiao's "a sore loser"

status_message: Lumber Liquidators said May 7 it was suspending sales of its Chinese laminate flooring pending an internal review into the "processes and practices of its suppliers." Former FBI director Louis Freeh's consulting firm will lead the review, the company said in a statement.
link_name: Lumber Liquidators suspends Chinese laminate sales amid formaldehyde concerns

status_message: A new bill proposed by California Democrats to ostensibly improve transparency in investigations of police officer-involved injuries would restrict investigations of incidents to local prosecutors, who are elected. The bill passed 23-12 in the California Senate on May 7.
link_name: California bill would ban grand jury investigations into police shootings

status_message: A U.S. government program to train and equip vetted Syrian rebels is underway in Jordan, nearly 10 months after President Obama requested $500 million for the operation, the AP reported May 7. More than 3,750 rebels have volunteered and other training sites are planned for Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Turkey.
link_name: US government program begins training Syrian rebels

status_message: Tribune Co. announced it would be acquiring the San Diego Union-Tribune for $85 million in cash and stock, adding another major Southern Californian newspaper to its roster after the LA Times, which it acquired in 2000.
link_name: Tribune Co. buys San Diego's U-T newspaper for $85 million

status_message: The Nevada Dept. of Transportation announced a license to allow Daimler, the maker of an 18-wheel self-driving truck, to test the truck on its public roads. The state plans to offer its existing federal land and straightaways between its two largest cities, Las Vegas and Reno, for testing.
link_name: Nevada to allow testing of self-driving truck on public roads

status_message: American Airlines flew its first commercial passenger flight with its new Boeing 787 "Dreamliner" May 6. Many of the passengers on the Dallas/Ft. Worth-Chicago O'Hare trip had booked reservations solely for the experience of flying on the new Dreamliner. American is the second U.S. airline after United to use the plane.
link_name: American Airlines becomes second US airline to use Boeing 787 Dreamliner

status_message: Museum Director Lonnie Bunch said May 7 the construction is on schedule for the museum to open in 2016. So far the museum has raised $476 million in public and private funds.
link_name: African-American museum in DC on track to open in 2016

status_message: Soccer icon Pele had prostate surgery and is recovering in a stable condition, according to Sao Paulo's Albert Einstein Hospital on May 7.
link_name: Soccer legend Pele hospitalized for prostate surgery

status_message: French prosecutors on May 7 opened a criminal investigation into allegations of sexual abuse by French peacekeepers deployed as part of a UN mission in Central African Republic. Prosecutors also accuse the United Nations of impeding an investigation into the issue.
link_name: France launches probe into allegations of sexual assault by French troops in CAR

status_message: The Spanish Football Federation and the players' union have called for a strike beginning May 16 in response to a new law that changes the way money generated from the sale of soccer TV rights are distributed.
link_name: Remainder of Spanish soccer season in doubt following strike threat

status_message: Germany's BND will reduce its cooperation with the NSA, a meeting of government ministers decided late May 6. BND will now require "clear justification" from the NSA for searches of its data. Chancellor Angela Merkel has maintained that intelligence sharing with the U.S. helps German security, but her government has been under increasing pressure to curb activities with the NSA.
link_name: German government restricts cooperation with NSA

status_message: A second layer of steel spikes will be added to the White House fence, according to recently approved plans by the Secret Service to improve security at the White House. The plans were approved at a meeting of the National Capitol Planning Commission on May 7.
link_name: White House fence to get second layer of steel spikes

status_message: A U.S. airstrike over Yemen killed Nasser bin Ali al-Ansi in the city of Mukalla in late April, SITE Intelligence Group said May 7.
link_name: Report: US drone strike kills senior Al-Qaeda official Nasser bin Ali al-Ansi

status_message: The U.S. Senate voted 98 to 1 on May 7 to approve a bill giving Congress an opportunity to review, and possibly reject, a nuclear deal with Iran. The bill gives Congress 30 days to review the deal. To reject the deal, Congress would have to pass a veto-proof bill.
link_name: US Senate passes bill to review nuclear deal with Iran
Yelp jumps 18% following reports company is exploring a sale

status_message: An audit of "Government Travel Charge Transactions" by the Department of Defense Office of Inspector General found that civilians and military officials used employee credit cards on escorts and gambling in Las Vegas and Atlantic City, Politico reported on May 6. The spending occurred between July 1, 2013, to June 30, 2014.
link_name: Report: Pentagon audit reveals employees spent $1 million on gambling, escorts

status_message: Former Guantanamo Bay prisoner Omar Ahmed Khadr made bail and was released on May 7 after 12 years and 9 months. He was free to leave a Canada jail while he appeals his convictions in the U.S. for war crimes.
link_name: Omar Khadr, once youngest Gitmo detainee, released from Canada jail

status_message: Stephen Colbert said May 7 he would fund all existing grant requests from public school teachers in South Carolina posted on DonorsChoose.org. The move will fund nearly 1,000 projects for more than 800 teachers to the tune of $800,000. The fund requests seek to obtain everything from dodge balls to iPads.
link_name: Stephen Colbert gives $800,000 donations to South Carolina public school teachers

status_message: 25-year-old Sanjay Williams of Montego Bay, Jamaica, was found guilty of conspiracy, wire fraud and money laundering on May 6 in North Dakota for his role as a "lead broker" in a scheme that preyed on vulnerable citizens.
link_name: Man faces up to 40 years for role in Jamaican lottery scam

status_message: A survey, published April 24 by the firm GlobalWebIndex, first gained widespread attention following a May 7 report in the Guardian. The survey claimed that 30% of Tinder's users are already married, and that 12% of users are otherwise already in a relationship. Only 54% of Tinder's users are single, according to GlobalWebIndex.
link_name: Tinder disputes survey suggesting nearly one-third of users are married

status_message: Polls opened at 7am local time on May 7 and will close at 10pm. Voters in 650 constituencies will elect an MP to represent them in parliament. The final Guardian/ICM poll had Labour with 36% of national support and the Conservatives with 35%.
link_name: British voters go to the polls to elect parliament

status_message: Skin whitening creams are banned in the Ivory Coast, the country's health ministry said in a statement in late April. Products banned include those that contain mercury and its derivatives, corticosteroids, vitamin A or more than 2% hydroquinone, which inhibits melanin production.
link_name: Skin whitening creams banned in Ivory Coast due to health effects

status_message: Amos Yee's two-day trial began May 7. He pleaded not guilty to two charges: making remarks intended to wound the feelings of Christians and transmitting an obscene image. He could be jailed for up to three years on the first charge. Yee, 16, is being tried as an adult. Some Singaporeans have criticized the case.
link_name: Trial begins for Singapore teen blogger

status_message: India signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with Iran on May 6 to jointly develop Iran's Port of Chabahar. The MOU opens up strategic land and sea trade routes to Afghanistan, bypassing Pakistan. The U.S. ambassador in India cautioned against "rushing in" to investments ahead of resolving Iran's nuclear program.
link_name: India signs port agreement with Iran

status_message: Iran released a Maersk ship and its crew, the state-run IRNA reported May 7. The confiscation was due to a lawsuit claiming Maersk had unpaid debts in Iran, according to IRNA, which said "there was absolutely no political or security intentions...behind [the] Maersk confiscation." The cargo will be released when the lawsuit is settled.
link_name: Iran released Marshall Islands-flagged, Maersk cargo ship, state media says

status_message: Scientists reported finding two new lemur species in the unexplored darkness of the Aven, Mitoho, and Malaza Manga freshwater caves of Tsimanampetsotsa National Park. The discovery was documented in the Journal of Human Evolution. The lemurs were found at depths of up to 137.8 feet.
link_name: Large fossil find in Madagascar caves uncovers two new extinct lemur species

status_message: An audit by the Treasury's watchdog found that of the 1,580 employees who willfully violated tax laws between 2003 and 2013, 960 or 61% kept their job. At most, they were given suspensions, reprimands or counseling. By law the IRS is required to fire workers who break tax laws, but the penalty can be waived by the commissioner.
link_name: Most IRS workers who violated tax laws kept their jobs, audit finds

status_message: Right-wing violence incidents tripled to 1,029 crimes (2013-2014), interior minister Thomas de Maiziere said May 6.
link_name: Racist violence rises in Germany, Europe's top migrant destination

status_message: Nearly two dozen endangered cockatoos, which are native to Indonesia, were found stuffed into plastic bottles and water containers by harbor police on May 6. Seven birds had died. The others were cut from the water bottles by customs officials.
link_name: Indonesia seizes dozens of endangered cockatoos smuggled in plastic bottles

status_message: On May 6, Oklahoma Gov. Mary Fallin (R) signed into law a bill that will extend the waiting period before a woman can have an abortion from 24 to 72 hours. The law, which Fallin says will give women time to weigh risks, becomes effective November 1.
link_name: Oklahoma governor signs bill implementing 72-hour wait time for abortions into law

status_message: Federal prosecutors filled charges against a former MillerCoors vice president and seven others May 6 for allegedly embezzling $7 million from the beer company.
link_name: Former MillerCoors executive and 7 others charged with embezzling $7 million

status_message: The UK service industry reported 28 months of growth in April, offering a pre-election boost to Conservatives. Financial data firm Markit's Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) for the service sector rose to 59.5 from a March figure of 58.9, it said May 6. Anything above 50 indicates the market is expanding.
link_name: UK service sector PMI hits eight-month high

status_message: Ehab Al Shihabi, CEO of Al Jazeera America, has been replaced by Al Anstey effective immediately, the cable news network announced on May 6.
link_name: Al Jazeera America ousts CEO Ehab Al Shihabi
Bill introduced to set Congressional term limits

status_message: A Russian resupply capsule that catapulted out of control while entering orbit is expected to reach Earth's atmosphere and burn up much earlier than previously thought, U.S. Air Force data shows. It is now expected to reach the atmosphere around 5am ET May 8.
link_name: Failed Russian capsule expected to burn up in atmosphere May 8

status_message: U.S. senators in a May 6 letter called on the Dept. of Justice to investigate Corinthian Colleges executives, citing a comment by a Dept. of Education under secretary who told the LA Times that resources to pursue investigations are "limited." The letter said that if the DOJ's tools are inadequate, then "Congress may need to act."
link_name: Senators seek DOJ investigation of Corinthian Colleges executives
Cablevision admits interest in partnering with Time Warner Cable

status_message: Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced the formation of a new Israeli government composed of a slim majority of 61 seats, including right-wing and religious factions, before a May 6 deadline.
link_name: Netanyahu forms coalition government ahead of May 6 deadline
Reports: US antitrust officials examining Apple's Beats Music deals

status_message: A newly discovered microbe being dubbed a genomic "starter-kit" for complex bacteria, known as eukaryotes, was introduced in a study published May 6 in Nature Magazine.
link_name: Deep-ocean microbe offers clues to origin of life

status_message: Tesla Motors on May 6 released its Q1 2015 financial results. The company lost 36 cents per share on $1.1 billion in revenue. Analysts were expecting a loss of 50 cents per share on $1.04 billion in revenue.
link_name: Tesla Motors easily beats expectations in latest quarter

status_message: The FAA said May 6 it is launching a program, dubbed Pathfinder, to study further loosening rules for commercial drone use.
link_name: FAA looks to further expand allowing commercial drones

status_message: Zynga said May 6 that it will lay off 18% of its employees worldwide in an effort to cut costs. The company announced the layoffs as part of its Q1 2015 financial results. The layoffs should result in about 364 lost jobs.
link_name: Zynga to lay off 18% of employees

status_message: AT&T will from now on only throttle LTE smartphones on unlimited data plans "at times and in areas that are experiencing network congestion." The previous policy did not limit throttling to congested areas.
link_name: AT&T tweaks LTE throttling policy, will now only apply during congestion

status_message: NFL-appointed attorney Ted Wells released results of an investigation May 6 into whether the New England Patriots deflated footballs in the January AFC Championship Game against the Indianapolis Colts. Although QB Tom Brady was "at least generally aware of the inappropriate activities," the report had no evidence connecting management or head coach Bill Belichick to the scandal.
link_name: NFL report on 'deflategate' scandal says Tom Brady was "at least generally aware"

status_message: A lifetime study of 3,000 golden retrievers by Colorado-based Morris Animal Foundation seeks to discover why the breed's lifespan has declined in recent years.
link_name: Researchers investigate why cancer plagues golden retrievers

status_message: The IRS will create a new team to investigate cyber fraud following a rise in cases earlier this year. The head of IRS criminal investigations, Richard Weber, says the agency suspects individuals abroad may be responsible for some of the criminal activity.
link_name: New IRS cyber team to investigate fraud

status_message: Baltimore Mayor Stephanie Rawlings-Blake has asked the U.S. Dept. of Justice to open a federal civil rights investigation of the Baltimore Police Department. During a May 6 news conference the mayor said, "I believe that we need the assistance of the DOJ and the civil rights investigation ... to shore up a foundation of trust."
link_name: Baltimore mayor seeks DOJ investigation of city's police dept.

status_message: At least 2,232 people have died as a result of India's swine flu epidemic as of April 26, the government said May 6. Since the start of the outbreak, 35,687 people have been affected.
link_name: Over 2,000 dead from H1N1 swine flu outbreak in India

status_message: Airbus delivered A350 XWB to airlines by 3D printing more than 1,000 parts, the BBC reported May 6. The process uses 90% less electricity and it takes less material to make lighter and stronger parts, Airbus' Peter Sander previously said.
link_name: Airbus delivered planes with more than 1,000 3D-printed parts

status_message: The EU is investigating accusations by trade unions that McDonald's used a Luxembourg-based subsidiary to avoid more than 1 billion euros ($1.12B) in taxes in 2009-2013. EU Competition Commissioner Margrethe Vestager said May 5 that she was assessing if there is a case. McDonald's declined to comment.
link_name: EU investigating accusations that McDonald's avoided taxes

status_message: U.S. national Robert Hays was convicted of indecent assault with aggravating circumstances against two girls and sentenced to two years in prison. Action Pour Les Enfants (APLE), a child protection NGO, told Circa the girls were aged 3 and 8 when Hays assaulted them.
link_name: US man convicted of 'indecent assault' of two young girls in Cambodia

status_message: By 2030, obesity will affect up to 89% of Irish, Uzbek, Belgian and Bulgarian men, according to World Health Organization (WHO) data presented to the European Congress on Obesity May 6. Obesity in Greece, Spain, Sweden, Austria and Czech Republic is forecast to rise.
link_name: Obesity in Europe could be widespread by 2030, WHO study finds

status_message: Ranch workers found the balloon hundreds of miles from a city or town. A NASA team was on its way to retrieve the balloon, which took off from New Zealand in late March. NASA terminated the balloon 32 days into its flight, in the last week of April.
link_name: NASA's Super Pressure Balloon crashes in Australian outback

status_message: The U.S. Treasury Dept. on May 5 approved licenses for ferries between the U.S. and Cuba. Companies would be providing ferry services for the first time since the 1960's. Cuba would need to also approve ferries before they could begin operation.
link_name: JetBlue to start weekly Friday flights to Cuba in July

status_message: A judge ruled Salman Khan was drunk driving when he ran over five homeless people, including a man who died, and drove off in Mumbai in 2002. Khan denied being the driver and being drunk. The court rejected evidence from Khan's driver that a tire burst while he was driving Khan's car.
link_name: Bollywood's Salman Khan convicted on six counts in hit and run case

status_message: The U.S. on May 5 offered a total of $20 million in rewards for information on four suspected IS leaders, including Harzi, who is the "chief of [IS'] suicide bombers" and Adnani, a group spokesperson.
link_name: US offers $20 million in rewards for suspected Islamic State leaders
Clinton backs path to citizenship for undocumented immigrants
Blue whales lack the ability to avoid cargo ships, study finds
De La Soul Kickstarter campaign raises $600,874
Los Angeles sues Wells Fargo, alleges 'unlawful and fraudulent conduct'
JetBlue to start weekly Friday flights to Cuba in July
New weekly Ebola infections drop to less than 20 for the first time since mid-2014
Ancestry.com unit shared private DNA information with law enforcement officials
RFA: Chinese officials demand Muslim shops sell alcohol and cigarettes
FCC seeking information on development of LTE-Unlicensed
News Corp misses earnings expectations amid 12% decline in ad sales
Uber ceases operations in Kansas in response to new regulations
Indiana governor, facing HIV outbreak, signs bill allowing needle exchange programs
GE announces deal with Qualcomm, Apple to target lighting business
Google commits $150 million to improve diversity in tech
Stocks tumble on weak trade data, euro nerves
French lawmakers advance controversial bill to expand gov't surveillance
Manny Pacquiao accused of fraud for hiding injury from spectators
The Intercept: NSA developed automatic speech-to-text capabilities
Obama nominates Dunford as next Joint Chiefs chairman
SAP CEO: We have 'zero interest' in Salesforce.com
Jury in Etan Patz case deadlocked once again
Trial shows new blood tests can detect 86% of ovarian cancers
Netflix asks FCC to reject proposed AT&T-DirecTV merger

status_message: The state government of Victoria announced an inquiry into allegations of abuse of foreign workers. The inquiry follows an ABC Four Corners documentary aired on May 4 about slave-like conditions for people on working holiday visas at farms supplying supermarket chains.
link_name: Australia investigates exploitation of foreign workers

status_message: Nkurunziza's bid for a third term is legal, Burundi's constitutional court ruled May 5. Although the constitution states a president can only be elected for two terms, Nkurunziza's supporters argue he can run again because parliament appointed him for his first term.
link_name: Burundi court approves president's re-election bid amid protests

status_message: Indonesia will no longer send migrant workers to 21 countries, Minister of Manpower Muhammad Hanif Dhakir said May 4, state news agency Antara reported. The decision aims to protect them from rights violations and other issues. The execution of two Indonesian domestic workers in Saudi Arabia in April caused the decision, he said.
link_name: Indonesia announces ban on domestic workers going to 21 countries

status_message: Australia's interest rates hit a new low of 2% on May 5 when the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) cut the cash rate by 25 basis points. The RBA board hoped to encourage consumer confidence, RBA Governor Glenn Stevens said.
link_name: Australian interest rates drop to historic 2% low

status_message: The Libyan Coast Guard intercepted about 500 migrants on five boats heading for Europe May 3-4, and placed them in detention centers. An official in charge of processing migrants for the Tripoli-based government told AFP May 4 that about 7,000 migrants are detained in the country.
link_name: Libyan coast guard intercepts boats carrying hundreds of migrants

status_message: Shanghai became the first city and province on May 5 to ban spouses of high ranking officials, including judicial officials, from operating business, either as an owner or otherwise, state media reported May 4. The children of officials and their spouses are also banned from operating businesses in Shanghai.
link_name: Shanghai bans families of officials from owning businesses

status_message: A May 4 parliamentary vote resulted in 334 votes in favor to 61 against electoral reforms. The change gives a party with at least 40% of votes in a national election 340 of 630 seats in parliament. If the 40% threshold is not reached, two parties with the most votes have a runoff. It takes effect in 2016.
link_name: Italian parliament passes PM Renzi's electoral reform

status_message: CNN met with Joo Won-moon May 5 in Pyongyang, the first contact Joo had with anyone outside of North Korea since his detention. Joo told his family not to worry about him, that he does not know what, if any, charges he will face.
link_name: North Korea holding South Korean NYU student

status_message: H5N2 was confirmed at a farm with 1.1 million chickens, the Minnesota Board of Animal Health said. It is the largest farm in the state stricken with bird flu so far, and the 80th overall. The unnamed farm is the first to have the disease in Nicollet County.
link_name: Bird flu hits large Minnesota farm

status_message: Volunteers and police exhumed 26 bodies at a mass grave. Three survivors, including two children, were found. All were believed to be victims of human trafficking. They likely came from Myanmar and Bangladesh, but identifying the bodies will take time, police said. At least one human trafficking camp is near the site.
link_name: Four suspects detained for mass grave in Thailand

status_message: South Korea and Vietnam signed a trade agreement in Hanoi, according to the Yonhap News Agency May 5. The deal needs ratification by each country's legislature. The agreement will decrease tariffs over 15 years, surpassing agreements between South Korea and the group of Southeast Asia ASEAN nations.
link_name: South Korea and Vietnam sign trade agreement

status_message: Pimco reported May 4 investors had pulled $5.6 billion from its flagship Total Return Fund in April. It was the 24th consecutive month of net outflows, bringing its assets to $110.4 billion. Pimco now sits below The Vanguard Total Bond Market Index Fund, which had $117.3 billion as of April 30.
link_name: Pimco Total Return no longer world's biggest bond fund

status_message: Jean-Marie Le Pen was suspended from the National Front pending his dismissal from an honorary position, the party said May 4.
link_name: France National Front suspends founder Jean-Marie Le Pen

status_message: More than 200 scientists joined a call to limit fluorine compounds known as poly- and perfluoroalkyl substances (PFASs). Their statement, known as the Madrid Statement, appeared May 1 in Environmental Health Perspectives journal.
link_name: 200 scientists call to limit fluorochemicals to save environment
Pope Francis issues call to declassify Vatican 'Dirty War' files
Google creates Pinterest-like 'Collections' for Google+
Obama launches foundation aimed at helping boys and young men of color
Reports: SurveyMonkey CEO Dave Goldberg, husband of Sheryl Sandberg, died in exercise accident
Supreme Court to review energy efficiency rule
Pinterest invites developers to create apps
Air Force leadership largely white and male, data shows
New York City commits $70 million for universal broadband
New Annie Leibovitz 'Star Wars' photos revealed
Still under federal watch, Harvard College appoints first Title IX investigator
Obamacare program yields $384 million in savings in first two years
Earthquake relief piles up, as death toll surpasses 7,200 in Nepal
FT: Ford abandons heart attack-detecting car seat
Supreme Court keeps in place NJ's ban on 'gay conversion therapy'

status_message: Human Rights Watch released images and other evidence on May 3 of U.S.-supplied cluster bombs dropped by Saudi Arabia on Yemen near villages. Cluster bombs have submunitions that spread over a large area. A 2008 treaty banned cluster bombs, but the U.S., Saudi Arabia and Yemen didn't sign it.
link_name: Saudi Arabia dropped US-supplied cluster bombs on Yemen

status_message: Representatives of the Afghan Taliban and the Afghan government held informal talks for a second day. The sides discussed a possible ceasefire, but could not agree on the presence of U.S. troops, Reuters reported. The Afghan government has not made an official statement on the meetings.
link_name: Afghanistan and Taliban attempting to restart peace talks

status_message: South Korea on May 4 demanded North Korea free four South Korean citizens. The latest detention was of Joo Won-moon, 21, a U.S. permanent resident and New York University student. He is accused of crossing into North Korea illegally in April. U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer (D-NY) called for Joo's release.
link_name: North Korea holding South Korean NYU student

status_message: Puerto Rico's Governor Alejandro Garcia Padilla will allow marijuana use for pain relief for epilepsy, multiple sclerosis and AIDS, according to his May 3 statement. An opposition spokesperson said the move left controlled substances laws "in limbo." In 2013, the parliament debated the issue but did not vote on it.
link_name: Puerto Rico governor legalizes medical marijuana

status_message: Kuomintang (KMT) Party chairman Eric Chu met with Chinese President Xi Jinping May 4, the highest level meeting between the KMT and mainland China's ruling party in at least 7 years. Chu is considered a potential candidate for Taiwan's presidential elections in Jan. 2016.
link_name: China and Taiwan leaders hold highest-level meeting in years

status_message: Authorities have yet to determine if blindness and other problems including headaches, hearing loss, heart pain, extreme fatigue and muscle and joint pain, result from the virus, treatment, or heavy disinfection, Nanyonga said. The symptoms have been known for several months.
link_name: Authorities yet to determine cause of blindness for Ebola survivors

status_message: Former John Hopkins Hospital chief of pediatric neurosurgery Ben Carson said May 3 that he is running for the Republican nomination for president. Carson has never held public office and has only been a prominent figure in GOP politics in the past few years after criticizing President Obama.
link_name: Physician Ben Carson running for GOP presidential nomination

status_message: An HSBC/Markit survey May 4 showed China's Manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) was 48.9 in April, the lowest PMI since April 2014. A rate below 50 indicates the economy is contracting. China's official PMI for April released May 1 was 50.1, the same as in March. (Correction: The May 1 data was previously reported as HSBC/Markit data.)
link_name: China's manufacturing index falls to yearlong low, HSBC/Markit says

status_message: Toward the end of an event called the "Muhammad Art Exhibit" the two men began shooting outside the community center where the heavily guarded event was taking place. A security guard was injured before police returned fire and killed the suspects. The guard was later released from the hospital.
link_name: Two men killed in Texas after they fired shots outside Prophet Mohammad "art" event

status_message: Thousands of Israeli Ethiopians held mostly peaceful protests in Tel Aviv against police brutality and racism on May 3. Demonstrators blocked roads and a major highway in the city. Clashes with police later in the day left at least 20 officers hurt and "multiple protesters" arrested, Israeli police said.
link_name: Israeli Ethiopians protest racism, some clashes reported

status_message: Germany's GDL train drivers' union called for a seven-day strike on May 3, set to begin with freight trains the afternoon of May 4 and passenger trains on the morning of May 5.
link_name: German train drivers' union calls for week-long strike

status_message: Disney announced on May 3 that products from the upcoming film will hit stores at midnight on Sept. 4 for an event dubbed "Force Friday."
link_name: Plans for upcoming 'Star Wars' movie merchandise released

status_message: Bryon and Darla Dickson, the parents of slain State Police trooper Cpl. Bryon Dickson II, spoke at a Pennsylvania church on May 3 and expressed forgiveness for their son's alleged killer, Eric Frein.
link_name: Parents of slain PA state trooper forgive son's alleged murderer

status_message: Paramount Pictures is sending every high school in the U.S., both public and private, free DVD copies of the award-winning film "Selma." The movie studio is also making companion study guides available for free to teachers to help further illuminate the historical events depicted in the film.
link_name: Every high school in US to receive free copy of 'Selma' DVD

status_message: German Chancellor Angela Merkel joined survivors and liberators to mark the 70th anniversary of the camp's liberation on May 3. "We will remember, for the sake of the victims, for our sake and for the sake of future generations," Merkel said.
link_name: Liberation of Dachau Concentration Camp marked by Merkel, survivors, US vets

status_message: "Avengers: Age of Ultron" grossed $187.7 million in its North American opening weekend, second only to "The Avengers" (2012), and beating "Iron Man 3" (2013), which is third overall.
link_name: 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' scores second-best opening weekend ever

status_message: Italian authorities said May 3 that 3,690 migrants had been rescued at sea on board several overcrowded boats during the previous 24 hours, one of the highest totals ever recorded.
link_name: Italy reports 3,690 migrants rescued in single day

status_message: According to a May 3 Reuters report, Germany has launched an investigation into allegations that its foreign intelligence agency, BND, violated laws when it helped the NSA spy on European companies.
link_name: Report: German spy agency under investigation for helping NSA

status_message: A U.S.-led airstrike killed at least 52 civilians from six different families, including seven children, the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said. The civilian death toll was expected to rise with 13 people missing. U.S. Central Command said it could not confirm the deaths.
link_name: US-led airstrike kills at least 52 civilians in Syria, monitor says

status_message: Volunteers and police exhumed 26 bodies at a mass grave by May 2. Three survivors, including two children, were found. All were believed to be victims of human trafficking. They likely came from Myanmar and Bangladesh, but identifying the bodies will take time, police said. At least one human trafficking camp is near the site.
link_name: Mass grave in Thailand held suspected trafficking victims

status_message: A New York jury on May 1 found ex-Goldman Sachs programmer Sergey Aleynikov guilty of stealing "secret scientific material" from his former employer.
link_name: Former Goldman programmer found guilty of stealing code
Federal judge blocks pilots from going on strike

status_message: Activists with the Syrian Civil Defense group told the AP on May 2 that the Syrian government launched chlorine attacks on civilians that left 40 people injured and one child dead.
link_name: Suspected chemical attacks leave 40 injured in Syria

status_message: A French patrol ship rescued 217 migrants off the coast of Libya on May 2. According to maritime police, the migrants were all men on three small boats. Two of the men are suspected people smugglers.
link_name: French patrol ship rescues 217 migrants off Libyan coast
SurveyMonkey CEO Dave Goldberg, husband of Sheryl Sandberg, dies suddenly

status_message: The final seven coffins carrying human remains arrived in the Netherlands aboard a Dutch air force plane on May 2. Investigators finished their search for remains and personal belongings on April 30. Officials are hopeful DNA testing will lead to the identification of the final two of the 298 victims.
link_name: Final MH17 victim remains arrive in the Netherlands
Muscular Dystrophy Association ends Labor Day telethon

status_message: A study says future astronauts exposed to radiation from cosmic rays during a trip to Mars could suffer physical architectural changes to their brains that might cause damage to the nervous system and memory loss.
link_name: Astronauts risk brain damage during mission to Mars, study says

status_message: Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew Goldstein on May 1 announced a system to use some of the $8.9 billion paid by BNP Paribas to compensate people harmed by Cuba, Iran and Sudan between 2004 to 2012 when the bank admitted wrongdoing. Others harmed outside of that timeframe can also make claims until July 30.
link_name: United States v. BNP Paribas S.A.

status_message: The number of sexual assaults among U.S. service members has dropped 27% over the last two years, according to a new Pentagon study released on May 1.
link_name: US military study shows drop in sexual assaults

status_message: Wikileaks on May 1 once again began accepting online document submissions for the first time since Oct. 2010.
link_name: Wikileaks accepting submissions again after four-year hiatus

status_message: Kate Middleton, the Duchess of Cambridge, gave birth to a daughter on May 2, the Palace reported, weighing a 8lbs 3oz.
link_name: Duchess of Cambridge gives birth to baby girl
After short hospital stay, B.B. King tells fans he's in hospice care
Bird flu prompts Iowa governor to declare state of emergency

status_message: A California Superior Court judge ordered Google April 30 to turn over the IP addresses for all email sent and received by Florida Gov. Rick Scott's private Gmail account, as well as the the accounts of two staffers, the Tampa Bay Times reported. The order covers all correspondence since Jan. 2011.
link_name: Judge orders Google to turn over Florida governor's Gmail data
Kurt Cobain documentary director says new 'solo' album coming soon
Cartel violence leaves 7 dead in Jalisco, Mexico
California cites SeaWorld for employee safety violations
Garage collapse at famed Watergate building leaves at least 1 hurt
UK's GCHQ ordered to destroy some illegally obtained documents
Lawmakers want FTC to investigate adulterated herbal supplements
US health officials caution Ebola survivors about unprotected sex
AT&T, telecom groups seek to halt net neutrality implementation
Feds unveil final safety rules for oil tank cars
Roll Call: US Capitol Police left guns in bathrooms, one discovered by visiting child
US, Qatar begin talks about fate of militants exchanged for Bergdahl
Bird flu found at five more farms in Iowa
CNBC: Spotify raises $350 million, reaches $8 billion valuation

status_message: David Wildstein plead guilty May 1 to unspecified charges related to the lane closings. Federal indictments are expected against Bill Baroni, former deputy executive director of the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, and Bridget Anne Kelly, Christie's former deputy chief of staff.
link_name: Former Christie ally pleads guilty in NJ lane-closure controversy

status_message: Labor Day union demonstrations are planned in Turkey, despite a ban on Istanbul's Taksim Square and a warning against protest from the country's prime minister. 10,000 police have been mobilized and barricades are already in place. On April 30, 90 people were injured in related protests, the Istanbul governor's office said.
link_name: Turkey prepares for Labor Day protests

status_message: Freddie Gray's death will be prosecuted as a homicide, Baltimore State Attorney Marilyn Mosby said on May 1. Mosby said that Gray's neck injury occurred because he was cuffed and shackled in the back of the police van without a seatbelt, which is against Baltimore County police orders. The van driver never called for medical help, despite having checked in Gray's condition. Other officers also failed to call for medical help.
link_name: Baltimore police turn over Freddie Gray investigation to state attorney's office

status_message: The Obama administration will provide $20 million in grants to help police departments buy body cameras, the Dept. of Justice said May 1. It is the first tranche of the $75 million in funding requested by President Obama to assist local police departments. Police departments will be part of a pilot program monitored by the Bureau of Justice Statistics.
link_name: Obama administration to provide $20 million in grants for police body cameras

status_message: China said April 30 that it will hold joint naval exercises with Russia in the Mediterranean Sea in the middle of May. Nine ships in all will take part in the drills, which will include live-fire exercises.
link_name: China and Russia to hold more joint naval exercises

status_message: Amos Yee was detained for a third time April 30 after breaching bail conditions by posting online. He refused to make the posts "private." While on his way to court, Yee was slapped across the face by a man who fled the scene. A 49-year-old was arrested in connection with the assault, police said May 1.
link_name: Singapore teen blogger detained for third time

status_message: Royal Dutch Shell's profits for the first quarter plunged 56% from a year earlier to $3.2 billion, it reported April 30. The results beat analysts' expectations of about $2.5 billion in profit. Shell said while earnings from exploration and production were hit by low crude prices, profits from refining businesses improved.
link_name: ExxonMobil Q1 earnings beat expectations but drop overall

status_message: MESSENGER crashed into the surface of Mercury April 30 as planned. The crash occurred on the opposite side of Mercury from Earth, and was not recorded visibly. The impact of the craft, which hit the planet at over 8,700 mph, was expected to create a 50-foot-wide crater to be studied later.
link_name: NASA probe ends 10-year mission by crashing into Mercury

status_message: Temporary zones reserved for birds during seasonal migration or permanent reserves in special habitats would protect wildlife and human lives, scientists recommended in a May 1 article published in the journal Science. The most conflict occurs in the first 328 feet from the ground.
link_name: Airspace reserves needed for wildlife in skies crowded by human activity, scientists say

status_message: Net profits fell 5% in the first quarter to $144.7M, the company reported April 29. The fall was due to "a continued difficult economic and consumer environment in Mexico and Brazil," CEO John Santa Maria Otazua said in his official message included in the report.
link_name: Coca-Cola first quarter net profits fall 5%

status_message: On April 30 Grooveshark shutdown its service as "part of a settlement agreement" with record labels. Grooveshark has handed over basically the entire company, including the website and intellectual property, as part of the settlement, it said.
link_name: Music service Grooveshark shuts down

status_message: Police and officials raided Uber's offices in the southern metropolis of Guangzhou on April 30. Uber was accused of illegally running a car service office equipment was seized, according to Chinese media. Uber is "working closely with local authorities in cooperation," the company told Tech In Asia.
link_name: Uber office in China raided by police

status_message: A $900,000 program using CCTV and alarms to fight domestic violence is a first in Australia. Community groups will run it. The cameras will stream live to a call center to notify police. So far in 2015, 34 women died in Australia due to domestic violence, or about two women a week, up from one a week in 2014.
link_name: Australian state funds cameras and alarms for domestic violence program

status_message: Peace TV was issued an order to shut down immediately April 30, news site Prachatai reported, citing an opposition Red Shirts figure. The government's broadcasting commission announced April 27 that it was revoking the station's license because it aired "content that leads to conflicts."
link_name: Thai junta shuts down TV station aligned with ousted government

status_message: RBS reported a first-quarter net loss of $688 million on April 30, far worse than the expected $269.4 million loss. RBS, the UK's largest government-controlled bank, set aside $515 million to cover a settlement with U.S. authorities over foreign exchange rate manipulation.
link_name: Royal Bank of Scotland's first quarter loss of $688 million was more than expected

status_message: BP has conducted seismic investigations and is in the process of applying for permission for exploration drilling in 2016. It was seeking permission from the National Offshore Petroleum Safety and Environmental Management Authority (NOPSEMA) as of May 1 and was conducting community consultations.
link_name: BP plans to drill for oil in Great Australian Bight marine park

status_message: Gilead Sciences said April 30 combined sales of Sovaldi and Harvoni were $4.55 billion in Q1 2015, nearly doubling the company's quarterly profit year-over-year. Harvoni, which combines Sovaldi with another drug and which sells for a higher price, had sales of $3.58 billion. Sovaldi sales fell year-over-year to $972 million from $2.27 billion.
link_name: Sales of hepatitis C drugs doubles Gilead Sciences' first-quarter profit

status_message: The U.S., Japan and Australia failed to meet an April 30 deadline to pay their promised contributions to the Green Climate Fund. Britain, Germany, Sweden, France, Norway and the Netherlands fulfilled their commitments.
link_name: Green Climate Fund waits on promised billions from US, Japan and Australia

status_message: The Energy Dept. said April 30 it will fund $73 million in infrastructure projects in New Mexico as part of a settlement with the state over nuclear waste violations. New Mexico agreed to drop $54 million in fines stemming from a 2014 radiation leak and mistakes made by Energy Dept. contractors.
link_name: Energy Dept. to pay New Mexico $73 million over radiation leak
India will keep marital rape legal, government says
Disgraced former Rep. Aaron Schock might be missing
LinkedIn falls 25% following Q1 2015 results
Tablet shipments decline for second straight quarter
California lawmakers advance bill to implement automatic voter registration
ExxonMobil Q1 earnings beat expectations but drop overall
FCC asks courts to consolidate net neutrality lawsuits
Former FBI agent accused of lying during trial against mobster Whitey Bulger
Chilean volcano erupts again
HBO, Showtime sue alleged pirates ahead of Mayweather-Pacquiao
State Dept. turns over 4,000 pages of new documents to Benghazi investigation panel
Nokia blames price cuts for Q1 profit drop

status_message: The investigation into Freddie Gray's death has been passed along to the state attorney's office, Baltimore's police commissioner said April 30. 30 detectives have been assigned to the case. The police will not disclose the details of their investigation. If the state's attorney chooses to prosecute any of the officers involved, a grand jury will hear the case.
link_name: Baltimore police turn over Freddie Gray investigation to state attorney's office

status_message: The series, still not dated for release, will profile a standoffish inventor named Guy and Sam-I-Am as they adventure on a cross-country trip together. According to Netflix, the characters will eventually eat green eggs and ham.
link_name: Netflix to adapt Dr. Seuss' 'Green Eggs and Ham'

status_message: According to emails obtained by the NY Times, between 2003 and 2006, the American Psychological Association (APA), a professional organization of U.S. psychologists, coordinated with the Defense Dept., the CIA and the Bush administration to craft ethical guidelines for torture. The APA denies its involvement.
link_name: NYT: American Psychological Association enabled torture at US detention facilities

status_message: Aden appeared "disastrous," a local activist said. Many residents have fled. At least 375 civilians were killed and 2,500 injured, mostly civilians, in the city since Saudi airstrikes began in March, a health official said. Houthis and their allies made recent advances, raising questions about the effectiveness of airstrikes.
link_name: Conflict tears through southern Yemeni city of Aden

status_message: Vice joined A+E to produce a venture cable channel that would take the place of A+E's H2. Along with A+E's parent companies, Disney and Hearst, Vice has submitted required regulatory filings with the FTC. In 2014, A+E invested $250 million for a 10% stake in Vice. This deal will likely lead to a larger investment.
link_name: Vice to take over A+E's H2 programming

status_message: The U.S. military is continuing operations in Afghanistan months after the official end of combat in Dec. 2014, the NY Times reported April 29. The missions include airstrikes, mostly by drones, and ground offensives. It conducted at least 128 airstrikes in the first three months of 2015.
link_name: NYT: US military continuing war in Afghanistan after official end to combat

status_message: Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dung said at a speech in Ho Chi Minh City (formerly Saigon) April 30 that the U.S. "committed countless barbarous crimes [and] caused immeasurable losses and pain to our people and country," during the Vietnam War. Vietnamese refer to the conflict as the American War in Vietnam.
link_name: Vietnam PM decries 'barbarous crimes' of US during 40th anniversary of war's end

status_message: Ten men accused of the attack on Malala received life sentences April 30 by a court in the Swat Valley northwest Pakistan, reports said. The men were arrested in Sept. 2014. They are part of the Pakistani Taliban and all from the Swat Valley, officials say. The specific charges they faced was unclear.
link_name: Ten men given life sentences for shooting of Malala Yousafzai

status_message: A replica of the iron gate was installed as April 29 memorial ceremonies marked the 70th anniversary of Dachau's liberation by U.S. troops. The thieves are yet to be found and an investigation has made little headway, police say.
link_name: Replacement 'work will set you free' gate installed at Dachau concentration camp

status_message: South Korean lawmakers on April 29 accused Kim of executing at least 15 officials in 2015, including two vice ministers, following a briefing from South Korea's spy agency. The executions were often the result disagreements with Kim, the lawmakers said. They were mostly carried out by firing squad.
link_name: South Korea accuses North's leader of executing 15 officials in 2015

status_message: A Muslim schoolgirl, 15, was sent home twice in late April for wearing a long, black skirt to school, which the principal said violated laws banning religious symbols. The decision sparked an outcry, with tens of thousands of tweets sent under the hashtag "I wear my skirt how I want to" (#JePorteMaJupeCommeJeVeux) since April 28.
link_name: French Muslim student sent home for wearing long skirt sparks debate

status_message: A crisis in affordable housing traps youth, pensioners, single and low-income households in "ongoing poverty, isolation and disadvantage" in Australia, an April 30 report says. The report found a dire shortage of affordable housing, despite the value of the housing market skyrocketing in 2012-2015.
link_name: Australia has an affordable housing crisis, report says
Dept. of Justice seeking criminal charges against Lumber Liquidators

status_message: Sen. Bernie Sanders (I-VT) officially announces 2016 presidential run, becoming first Democratic challenger to Hillary Clinton.
link_name: AP: Bernie Sanders joins 2016 race for president
FCC says it doesn't control cellphone 'stingray' tracking devices
iPad glitch blamed for dozens of delayed American Airlines flights
Report: Faulty component to blame for slow Apple Watch rollout
Congressional Republicans reach budget deal

status_message: The FBI brokered a $250,000 ransom payment to Warren Weinstein's kidnappers in 2012, the WSJ reported April 29, citing officials familiar with the case. Although the FBI neither approved nor authorized the payment, which violates U.S. hostage policy, it helped Weinstein's family verify the identity of a middleman.
link_name: Report: FBI brokered ransom payment for U.S. drone strike victim

status_message: U.S. Supreme Court Justices ruled April 29 to reject a challenge to a Florida law that bans judicial candidates from directly soliciting campaign contributions. In their 5-4 decision, Justices ruled the state "may assure its people that judges will apply the law without fear or favor - and without having personally asked anyone for money."
link_name: Supreme Court rules to allow restrictions on judicial campaign contributions

status_message: The Supreme Court on April 29 heard arguments in a case involving the legality of a lethal injection drug used in the botched 2014 execution of an Oklahoma inmate. If lethal injections are found unconstitutional, the state of Oklahoma could use the electric chair, nitrogen or the firing squad to execute convicts.
link_name: Supreme Court hears arguments in Oklahoma lethal injection case

status_message: The Cyberspace Administration of China said April 28 that Internet companies violating its rules could be fined or closed. The rules include publishing unapproved news reports and content deemed pornographic. The agency may also meet companies to discuss violations, something it has done with Chinese web portals Sina and Netease.
link_name: China threatens Internet companies with fines and closure

status_message: The UN Security Council extended its MINURSO military mission in the contested territory by a year. The force has been in the area since a 1991 ceasefire was negotiated between Morocco and the Polisario Front, which controls part of the territory. Most of the phosphate-rich territory is under Morrocan control.
link_name: UN renewal of military force in Western Sahara falls short of African Union requests

status_message: King Salman, 79, consolidated his line of succession April 29 by installing his nephew Mohammed bin Nayef as crown prince to replace Muqrin bin Abdulaziz as next in line for the throne. Interior Minister Nayef's son, Mohammed bin Salman, became deputy crown prince in place of his father, who took the position soon after Salman became king.
link_name: Saudi king shuffles line of succession, cabinet

status_message: India deregistered 8,975 NGOs and required them to account for foreign funds received and how they were spent, April 28 reports said. The order by the Home Ministry, dated April 6, accused them of failing to file mandatory annual returns since 2009-10. It put the U.S.-based Ford Foundation on a security watch list.
link_name: India cancels registration of 8,975 non-governmental organizations

status_message:
Nepalese increasingly frustrated over perceived slow earthquake response
http://circanews.com/news/nepal-april-2015-earthquake

Sri Lanka's parliament adopted the 19th constitutional amendment April 28 to dilute the president's power to control parliament. It reduces the terms of parliament and the president to five years instead of six, and limits a president to two terms in office. The bill passed by 212 votes to 13.
link_name: Sri Lanka limits power, terms of president

status_message: Hulu has bought the rights to air reruns of the hit television show Seinfeld, according to unnamed sources cited by Variety and The Wall St. Journal April 28. The deal is estimated at between $700,000 and $1 million an episode, making it the biggest acquisition in Hulu's history. Netflix dropped a potential bid for the show in 2014.
link_name: Hulu strikes deal for 'Seinfeld' reruns, reports say
Number of unaccompanied children crossing Mexican border continues to shrink
Feds partly blame transit authority for 2014 derailed Chicago train
Russian resupply capsule spinning out of control on trip to space station
Hundreds of girls rescued from Boko Haram camps, Nigerian army says
UN peacekeeping convoy comes under fire in Mali
Report: Video game startup Ouya seeking buyer
Courtney Love sued by memoir co-author
Critical phase of Panama Canal expansion project to begin
Indonesia executes 8 convicted 'Bali Nine' drug smugglers
Victims give first witness testimony against Colorado shooter James Holmes
UK GDP growth slowed to 0.3% in Q1
Report: Uber to end UberPop service in Germany

status_message: Twitter's Q1 2015 financial results appeared to have leaked about an hour before they were to be officially released on April 28. The leaked earnings indicated earnings of 7 cents per share (versus expectations of 4 cents per share) and revenue of $436 million (versus expectations of $456 million). Twitter's shares were halted following the apparent leak.
link_name: Twitter shares down 5% after possible earnings leak

status_message: President Obama said April 28 that there have been "too many instances" of police interacting with black men in ways that "raise troubling questions." He also said there is "no excuse" for the violence and looting in Baltimore, adding "that is not a protest, it is a handful of people taking advantage of the situation."
link_name: Protestors and police clash in Baltimore following Freddie Gray funeral
Japanese retail sales plunge 9.7% in March
Bumble Bee charged after employee burned to death in tuna oven
Skyfall, Airplane! expiring from Netflix in May
NFL announces it is ending tax-exempt status

status_message:
Iran seizes Marshall Islands-flagged cargo ship in Strait of Hormuz 

The vessel in question, built in 2014 and 255 meters (836 feet) in length, was headed to the United Arab Emirates, according to the ship tracking website Marine Traffic. The Pentagon says no U.S. citizens are aboard the ship and a U.S. naval destroyer has been sent to the region to "monitor" the situation.
link_name: Iran seizes Marshall Islands-flagged cargo ship in Strait of Hormuz

status_message: Ford reported April 28 quarterly profit of 23 cents per share, versus analyst expectations of 26 cents per share, on revenues of $33.9 billion. The company cited a higher tax rate as a reason for the shortfall. Its 6.7% operating profit margin in North America was due to weaker sales of the F-150 pickup truck.
link_name: Ford sticks to annual forecast, despite disappointing earnings

status_message: Firefighters continued to battle fires throughout the city on the evening of April 27 into the morning of April 28. A total of 500 National Guard troops had been deployed by early April 28, with many surrounding Baltimore's Western District. Police Commissioner Anthony Batts blamed high school students for riots.
link_name: Protestors and police clash in Baltimore following Freddie Gray funeral

status_message: Conservation group Oceana and an environmental law clinic petitioned the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission April 27 to investigate Shell's proposed Arctic operations. They claim Shell failed to disclose in regulatory filings that its "response capabilities" to a major oil spill will likely not work in the Arctic, the AP reported.
link_name: SEC petitioned to investigate Shell Arctic drilling plans

status_message: China Railway Construction Co. has signed a $3.5 billion deal for an intercity rail project in Nigeria, the company said in a regulatory filing April 28. The company will also be working on a $1.93 billion deal to build a residential project in Zimbabwe, the state-run media outlet Xinhua said.
link_name: Chinese rail company awarded $3.5 billion rail project in Nigeria

status_message: Preliminary tests indicated the presence of H5N2 at five poultry more farms in Iowa, all of which have been quarantined, state officials said April 27. If confirmed, the state will have at least eight affected farms, with nearly 10 million birds in total, mostly egg-laying hens.
link_name: Bird flu outbreak in poultry spreads to more Iowa farms

status_message: The only witness to Mahmud's murder is her injured mother, who is being treated in a hospital. By April 27, police were unable to trace the gunmen from bullet casings at the scene. Mahmud's friends told police she had received death threats over her many years of activism and defending human rights.
link_name: Pakistani police searching for killers of human rights activist

status_message: The Colombian health ministry recommended April 27 that aerial spraying of the herbicide glyphosate be immediately stopped, the AP reported. The move followed a March decision by an arm of the World Health Organization to reclassify glyphosate as a carcinogen.
link_name: Colombian health ministry calls for halt to coca crop spraying with controversial herbicide

status_message: An April 27 UN report found Israeli attacks killed 44 Palestinians and injured 227 more who were seeking shelter during Israel's 2014 Gaza offensive. It found no weapons near 7 UN shelters attacked, including 3 girls' schools, and that Israel knew the locations. It also found Palestinian armed groups hid weapons at 3 empty UN sites.
link_name: UN blames Israel for attacks on Gaza shelters that killed 44 Palestinian civilians in 2014

status_message: An estimated 8 million people living in 39 districts were affected as of April 27, the UN said. More than 2 million people live in "11 severely affected districts," and at least 1.4 million people require food assistance. Prime Minister Sushil Koirala told Reuters April 28 that the death toll could reach 10,000.
link_name: UN: 8 million people affected by Nepal earthquake

status_message: Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras replaced outspoken, anti-austerity Finance Minister Yanis Varoufakis with Deputy Foreign Minister Euclid Tsakalotos April 27 as the lead negotiator with Greece's creditors. Varoufakis continues to supervise negotiations but Tsakalotos will deal with creditors.
link_name: Greece removes finance minister from lead role in credit negotiations

status_message: Hundreds of people were found dead as thousands of displaced people were attempting to return to Damasak, Nigeria. The bodies, which were found in houses, streets and a river, were given mass burials. Troops from Chad and Niger retook the town from Boko Haram in March. Officials think the massacre happened in January.
link_name: Hundreds of bodies found in Nigerian town from suspected Boko Haram massacre

status_message: On April 28, a South Korean appeals court increased the sentence of Sewol captain Lee Joon-seok to life in prison for murder. Lee had originally been sentenced in Nov. 2014 to 36 years in prison for negligence and abandoning passengers. Prosecutors had once again asked for the death penalty, which is rare in South Korea.
link_name: South Korean appeals court imposes life sentence on ferry captain

status_message: Baltimore Mayor Stephanie Rawlings-Blake said on April 27 that a one-week curfew lasting from 10pm to 5am each night would begin on April 28. She said the violence was being perpetrated by "thugs... trying to tear down what so many have fought for." Rawlings-Blake also said the Maryland National Guard would be deployed in the city.
link_name: Protestors and police clash in Baltimore following Freddie Gray funeral
SpaceX launches first communications satellite for Turkmenistan
Construction begins on US's first offshore wind farm
Judge won't delay sex reassignment surgery for trans prisoner in CA
Suspect says he'll plead guilty to shootings at Jewish sites in Kansas
Google to create $163 million 'innovation fund' for European news publishers
Josh Hamilton returns to Rangers after Angels trade outfielder
Observers find significant problems with Kazakhstan presidential election
US and Japan set new military guidelines
Trial begins for Colorado theater shooter James Holmes

status_message: Following the funeral of Gray, some demonstrators threw objects at police on April 27. According to a report by the AP, "several" police officers were injured. Police, who threw tear gas at demonstrators, issued a statement saying there was a "credible threat" that gangs were partnering to "take-out" police officers.
link_name: Protestors and police clash in Baltimore following Freddie Gray funeral

status_message: Uber on April 27 began lobbying New Jersey legislators about a proposed law it claims would "literally guarantee" the company's exit from the state. The proposed law, which passed a lower house committee in March, would force Uber to pay the same licensing fees that taxi companies pay. If passed, the law would take away drivers' "livelihoods," Uber claimed.
link_name: Uber warns proposed New Jersey law would force it out of the state
Facebook adds video calling to Messenger
Truckers at Southern California ports go on strike
US lowers recommended fluoridation levels in drinking water
China to investigate petrochemical CEO Wang Tianpu for corruption
Supreme Court throws out pro-Obamacare contraception ruling, sends case back to lower court
Death toll in Nepal passes 4,000 following devastating earthquake

status_message: ESPN on April 27 sued Verizon in New York state Supreme Court, claiming the company had violated its contractual agreement by offering ESPN as part of a sports bundle with its new "Custom TV" package. ESPN said it merely wanted Verizon to "abide" by their contract.
link_name: ESPN sues Verizon over 'Custom TV' package

status_message: Fugitive Dai Xuemin was detained April 25 when he tried to enter China using phony passport and name, state media said April 27. He is the first of the 100 "most wanted" fugitives to be captured. Dai is accused of embezzling $1.77 million.
link_name: China captures one of its "most wanted" officials for corruption

status_message: Fitch on April 27 downgraded Japan's credit from A+ to A with a stable outlook. The A rating is five levels below the agency's highest rating of AAA.
link_name: Fitch drops Japan's credit rating

status_message: President Bashir won reelection April 27 after taking 94.5% of the vote on 46.4% turnout of registered voters, election organizers said.
link_name: Sudanese President Bashir wins reelection with 94.5% of vote

status_message: President Park accepted Lee Wan-koo's resignation on April 27. There has been no word on a possible replacement, which the president nominates.
link_name: South Korean prime minister's resignation accepted amid corruption investigation

status_message: Mustafa Akinci won a presidential election runoff in northern Cyprus (officially the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus), electoral authorities said April 27. Akinci, 67, is a former mayor of the Turkish half of Nicosia, the capital. He defeated incumbent president Dervis Eroglu with 60.3% of the vote.
link_name: Northern Cyprus election brings promise of peace

status_message: Torrential rains caused houses to collapse, closed the airport, flooded roads and cut power. Up to 44 people died, mostly women and children, reports said. Hospitals declared an emergency as people carried the injured in because the roads were impassable. More rain was forecast.
link_name: Violent storms kill up to 44 people in northwest Pakistan

status_message: Sirisena introduced a constitutional amendment into parliament April 27 to reverse the expanded executive powers former president Mahinda Rajapaksa gave himself. Sirisena, an ex-health minister, ran against Rajapaksa and won in January with 51.3% of the vote, compared to Rajapaksa's 47.6%.
link_name: Sri Lanka's president acts on election promise to rollback executive powers

status_message: Chipotle removed all GMO sources from its foods, the company said April 26. The move was the first for a large restaurant chain in the U.S. The change takes effect April 27. Chipotle in June 2013 was the first chain to outline which of its foods contained GMOs.
link_name: Chipotle stops serving food with GMOs

status_message: Five protesters were shot dead during two days of street clashes, Reuters reported April 27. The agency quoted "prominent activist" Pierre Claver Mbonimpa saying that three people were shot in riots and two were killed by the ruling party's youth wing on April 26.
link_name: Burundi president's bid for third term sparks deadly protests

status_message: The 10-country Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) released a statement ahead of a summit in Kuala Lumpur April 27 saying China's artificial islands are threatening regional stability, AFP reported. Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary Albert del Rosario said a day earlier that China could have "de facto control" of the South China Sea.
link_name: ASEAN leaders warn China's artificial islands "may undermine peace"

status_message: By April 27, at least 3,617 people were confirmed dead in Nepal, over a thousand more than the day before, with an additional 6,500 injured. At least 61 deaths were also reported in India, Tibet, Bangladesh and along the Nepal-Chinese border.
link_name: Two days after quake, death toll in Nepal at over 3,600 as search and rescue continues

status_message: Furious 7" became the first movie since 2012 to remain in the No. 1 position for four consecutive weeks, taking the April 24-26 weekend with another $18.3 million for a total domestic haul of $320.5 million.
link_name: 'Furious 7' wins North American box office for fourth straight weekend

status_message: Corinthian Colleges will close all of its remaining schools effective April 27. The embattled for-profit made the announcement to close 28 of its remaining campuses on April 26. Corinthian said it would work with other educational institutions to help approximately 16,000 students across the U.S. that will be displaced by the closures.
link_name: Corinthian Colleges shutters all remaining schools

status_message: Israel's military said April 26 that it had conducted an airstrike on a group of militants attempting to plant a bomb on a fence in the Golan Heights near the Syrian border. Israeli aircraft "targeted the squad, preventing the attack," which the military says was intended to target Israeli troops.
link_name: Israel says airstrike on border with Syria targeted militants

status_message: Russian authorities jailed three women after a YouTube video surfaced showing five women twerking in front of a WWII memorial in Novorossiysk, Russia. All five women were found guilty April 25 of hooliganism.
link_name: Three women in Russia jailed for twerking near WWII memorial

status_message: The Clinton Foundation's acting chief admitted in a statement posted April 26 that "government grants were mistakenly combined with other donations."
link_name: Clinton Foundation admits to making mistakes on donor disclosures

status_message: Exit polls showed 74-year-old Nursultan Nazarbayev, who has led Kazakhstan since its independence in 1991, was reelected April 26 to a fifth five-year term as the country's president with 97.5% of the vote. The two other candidates in the election received 1.87% and 0.63%.
link_name: Kazakhstan election won by incumbent Nazarbayev, exit polls show

status_message: The Ohio Bureau of Criminal Investigation and Cuyahoga County Sheriff's Office on April 26 visited the scene where Tamir Rice was killed, using special camera equipment to create a 360-degree 3D mock-up of the shooting. A police car was parked in the same spot as during the incident, and officers took measurements of the area.
link_name: Police return to scene of Tamir Rice shooting to create 3D scan of scene

status_message: Abercrombie & Fitch will phase out the company's "Look Policy," introduced by former CEO Michael Jeffries, which enforced strict rules on employee appearance. Rules included no eyeliner or French tip manicures for women, and no mustaches on men. The company will also drop shirtless male models from its advertising and in-store operations.
link_name: Abercrombie ditches shirtless male models

status_message: By April 26, at least 2,430 people were confirmed dead in Nepal. At least 61 deaths were also reported in India, Tibet, Bangladesh and along the Nepal-Chinese border.
link_name: Nepal earthquake leaves more than 2,500 dead
UK Labour Party rules out coalition with Scottish nationalists

status_message: In the first three weeks of April, around 1,000 people were reported to poison control centers after taking spice, according to the American Assoc. of Poison Control Centers.
link_name: Health alerts issued after synthetic pot sends hundreds to emergency rooms

status_message: Ash from the Chile's Calbuco eruption spread to Brazil on April 25, causing cancellations of flights to Chile, Argentina and Uraguay. Delta, American Airlines, Air Canada, Air France and Qantas Airways have suspended flights in and out of Santiago, Buenos Aires and Montevideo airports.
link_name: Flights cancelled as ash from Chile volcano spreads to Brazil

status_message: The Office of the Director of National Intelligence released a 2009 report on April 25 that analyzed the President's Surveillance Program, code-named Stellarwind, that President George W. Bush put in place after the terrorist attacks on Sept. 11, 2001. The release was part of a Freedom of Information Act lawsuit by the New York Times.
link_name: Obama administration releases 2009 report on NSA surveillance program
Palestinians shot dead after separate attacks on Israeli police officers

status_message: Two Australians, Andrew Chan and Myuran Sukumaran, were notified by Indonesian authorities on April 25 that their executions "will be scheduled imminently," Australian Foreign Minister Julie Bishop said. Mary Jane Veloso of the Philippines, who worked as a "mule" in the operation, was also informed of her pending execution.
link_name: Indonesia issues execution notices for 3 'Bali Nine' drug smugglers

status_message: Volkswagen announced on April 25 that Chairman Ferdinand Piech had resigned. The resignation comes after a power struggle with CEO Martin Winterkorn.
link_name: Volkswagen Chairman Ferdinand Piech unexpectedly resigns
Switzerland at the top of 'world's happiest' list

status_message: Baltimore police admitted April 24 that Freddie Gray was not seat-belted when he was placed in a police van during his arrest, a violation of department policy. Police also said that Gray should have received medical attention at the scene of the arrest.
link_name: Baltimore police concede proper 'medical attention' not given to Freddie Gray

status_message: Alibaba and state-owned China Telecom announced a partnership April 24 to sell mobile phones to people in smaller cities and rural areas in China. The phones come with four months of free 2G wireless Internet access. The partnership is designed to help "spread commerce" to these areas, the companies said.
link_name: Alibaba partners with China Telecom to sell phones in rural areas

status_message: The New York Times, citing anonymous sources, reported April 24 that the NBC News internal investigation into Brian Williams has turned up "a half-dozen instances in which he is thought to have fabricated, misrepresented or embellished his accounts.
link_name: Report: NBC News investigation into Brian Williams uncovers more embellishment
Chinese court hands Apple favorable Siri patent ruling
