status_message: Nepal rocked by 7.5 magnitude earthquake, damage reported
link_name: Nepal rocked by 7.5 magnitude earthquake, damage reported

status_message: Hawaii has become the fourth state in the U.S. to ban e-cigarettes where conventional cigarettes are banned, after Gov. David Ige signed a bill April 24.
link_name: Hawaii governor signs bill banning e-cigarettes in places where cigarettes are banned

status_message: A report says the Ivanpah Solar Electric Generating station in San Bernardino County, California, has killed 3,504 birds during its first year online. According to the report, some 83 different species have been found.
link_name: Report: Massive California solar farm has killed 3,500 birds

status_message: Researchers at the University of Utah published a study in the journal Science that details a newly-discovered magma reservoir under the Yellowstone supervolcano. The magma reservoir of partly molten rock is big enough to fill the Grand Canyon more than 11 times. The discovery does not increase the likelihood of an eruption.
link_name: Researchers find massive magma reservoir under Yellowstone supervolcano

status_message: On April 24 Ford issued a recall for approximately 390,000 vehicles. The company will replace, for free, faulty door latches that "may unlatch while driving." Models in the North America recall include; Ford Fiesta (2012 - 2014), Ford Fusion (2013 - 2014) and Lincoln MKZ (2013 - 2014). U.S. safety regulators opened an investigation in 2014 after receiving 61 complaints.
link_name: Ford recalls 390,000 cars due to faulty door latches

status_message: On April 24 a Canadian court granted former Guantanamo detainee Omar Ahmed Khadr bail. A hearing is scheduled for May 5 when a judge is expected to set conditions for Khadr's official release. The Canadian government said it would appeal the bail decision.
link_name: Canada grants Omar Khadr bail, once youngest Gitmo detainee

status_message: Officials gave an all clear about 4 hours after evacuations began. The National Park Service said April 24 that all visitors and personnel on Liberty Island were safe. The Service said in a statement that someone placed a 911 call around 11am saying they were going to "blow up" the Statue of Liberty.
link_name: Statue of Liberty evacuated over suspicious package

status_message: Tickets for the Mayweather-Pacquiao boxing match sold out shortly after they went on sale April 23. Only about 500 tickets went on sale to the public, the rest being allocated to the fighters' camps and to the MGM Grand for sale to its guests. The cheapest tickets, which sold for $1,500, are now going for more than $5,000 on the secondary market.
link_name: Cheapest tickets for Mayweather-Pacquiao top $5,000 on secondary market

status_message: Male student accused of rape at Columbia University sues school for gender bias
link_name: Male student accused of rape at Columbia University sues school for gender bias

status_message: Statue of Liberty evacuated over suspicious package
link_name: Statue of Liberty evacuated over suspicious package

status_message: General Motors on April 24 released details about CEO Mary Barra's compensation package. The automaker paid Barra some $16.2 million in 2014--about 78% more than her predecessor Dan Akerson made in 2013. Akerson's compensation was capped by the Treasury Dept. while it still owned GM shares.
link_name: GM CEO Mary Barra's compensation reached $16.2M in 2014

status_message: Comcast on April 24 officially dropped plans for its proposed merger with Time Warner Cable. The company had run into stiff regulatory resistance from the FCC and Dept. of Justice. Both Bloomberg and the New York Times reported on April 23 that Comcast had called off the merger.
link_name: Report: Comcast drops plans to acquire Time Warner Cable

status_message: The European Council committed to at least triple funding for Italy's Triton sea borders operation after an emergency summit April 23. It said this would bolster search and rescue possibilities. Officials also pledged to destroy traffickers' boats as part of a 17-point plan on migrants.
link_name: Europe to triple funding on sea operations after crisis meeting on migrants

status_message: U.S. Army Major Xiong Yan was denied entry to Hong Kong at the airport April 24, according to the NY Times. Xiong, who fled China after 1989 protests, said he was trying to visit his ailing mother in China. It is unclear if he would have been allowed entry to the mainland. He went to Hong Kong in 2009.
link_name: Ex-Tiananmen Square activist, a US army major, barred entry to Hong Kong

status_message: High-ranking lawmaker Regina Ip denied on April 24 on Facebook that her April 17 article for the popular newspaper Ming Pao was racist. "I have received complaints from expatriate women‚Ä¶ that Filipino domestic helpers seduce their husbands," she wrote.
link_name: Hong Kong lawmaker denies racism against domestic workers

status_message: Minnesota Governor Mark Dayton on April 23 declared a state of emergency over an H5N2 bird flu outbreak responsible for the deaths of 2.5 million turkeys from 46 Minnesota farms. The National Guard will provide support, but Dayton has not ordered troops deployments.
link_name: Minnesota declares state of emergency over bird flu in poultry
Airports ask Congress to nearly double facility fees for passengers
Starbucks sees best non-holiday quarter
US crude futures hit 2015 high
New USGS hazard maps to include risk of manmade earthquakes
In-store phone-tracking company settles FTC complaint
Guatemala seeks to renew UN-led corruption investigation
Kleiner Perkins asks for nearly $1 million for defense costs in gender discrimination case
Ice cream maker Jeni's recalling all products over possible listeria

status_message: Petraeus pled guilty to sharing classified information on April 23. His charges include one count of unauthorized removal and retention of classified material, which carries 1-year maximum prison sentence. As a part of a plea deal, Petraeus received 2 years of probation and a $100,000 fine, with waived right to appeal conviction.
link_name: Retired Gen. Petraeus receives 2 years probation in plea deal for sharing classified material

status_message: Bloomberg reported April 23 that Comcast has dropped its plans to acquire Time Warner Cable amid regulatory resistance.
link_name: Report: Comcast drops plans to acquire Time Warner Cable

status_message: The proposed bill, dubbed the SAFE Act, would also ban the export of horses to slaughterhouses in Canada and Mexico. According to lawmakers who introduced the bill, some 150,000 American horses were exported in 2014 for slaughter.
link_name: US lawmakers introduce bill to ban slaughterhouses for horse meat
HTC, Valve make VR helmet available for developers
Jerry Sandusky given permission to file appeal
Senate approves Loretta Lynch to be next US attorney general
Highlights brings curated tweets to Android devices
Robert Durst's Louisiana gun charges dropped
Netflix now accounts for 6% of total TV viewing, analyst says

status_message: South Korea's GDP rose 0.8% quarter-on-quarter and 2.4% year-on-year in the first quarter of 2015, preliminary government data showed April 23. The figures were largely driven by 7.5% quarter-on-quarter growth in construction, a 14-year quarterly growth high.
link_name: South Korean economy slightly recovers in first quarter

status_message: The White House revealed April 23 that a January military operation on the Afghan-Pakistan border region killed two Al-Qaeda hostages: Dr. Warren Weinstein, an American held by Al-Qaeda since 2011 and Giovanni Lo Porto, an Italian national who had been an al-Qaeda hostage since 2012. Ahmed Farouq, an American who was an A-Qaeda leader, was killed in the same operation. Adam Gadahn, an American who became an Al-Qaeda member, was killed in a different operation.
link_name: US admits accidentally killing two al-Qaeda hostages in counterterrorism strike

status_message: Basil Rajapaksa, the brother of former premier Mahinda Rajapaksa, was arrested by Sri Lankan police. He has been charged with siphoning state funds connected with a public housing project, his lawyer said. Basil, a Sri Lankan-U.S. dual citizen, served as economic development minister in his brother's cabinet.
link_name: Former Sri Lankan president's brother detained in corruption probe

status_message: Attorneys for Michael Brown's family said April 22 that they will file a wrongful death suit against the city of Ferguson. It is unclear if Darren Wilson or any other party will be named in the suit. The family previously said in March that they intended to sue.
link_name: Michael Brown's family to sue Ferguson

status_message: The Australian government has failed the elderly, less educated people, unemployed households, certain neighborhoods, indigenous Australians and people with chronic health problems, CEDA says in a report published April 21.
link_name: Australian policies are worsening poverty, think tank says

status_message: A draft proposal on migrants presented at an April 23 EU summit will resettle 5,000 people as refugees across Europe, with others repatriated, reports said. The proposal also includes military operations to destroy traffickers' boats. About 219,000 migrants crossed the Mediterranean in 2014, and more than 3,000 died, the UN said.
link_name: EU proposal calls for 5,000 refugees resettled amid migrant crisis

status_message: The Jiangsu Provincial Bureau of Commodity Prices fined Mercedes-Benz $56 million on April 23. Mercedes "met with its dealers to control prices or directly notified them about quoted prices... between January 2013 and July 2014," according to state media. The report said Mercedes agreed to pay the fine.
link_name: Mercedes-Benz fined $56 million over anti-trust violations in China

status_message: China's Central Commission for Discipline Inspection April 22 published a list of 100 fugitives wanted for economic crimes that it has also shared with Interpol. The anti-corruption commission posted the pictures and other details of the fugitives on its website.
link_name: China issues "most wanted" list of corrupt officials

status_message: Chinese geneticists at Sun Yat-sen University modified the DNA of human embryos for the first time, an April study in Protein & Cell said. The embryos used from local fertility clinics were "non-viable" with an extra set of chromosomes and would not have resulted in live births.
link_name: Chinese scientists spliced human embryo genes, a controversial first

status_message: Mary Doyle Keefe, 92, died in Connecticut, her family said April 22. In 1943, Keefe was 19, and was not a riveter, when she modeled for neighbor Norman Rockwell as "Rosie the Riveter." Although it wasn't the first depiction of "Rosie," the painting was on the cover of the Saturday Evening Post and used to sell war bonds.
link_name: Rockwell's 'Rosie the Riveter' model dies at 92

status_message: China told U.S. nuclear officials in February that North Korea has up to 20 nuclear bombs and "enough weapons-grade uranium to double its arsenal by next year" the Wall Street Journal April 22. The report quoted former Los Alamos National Laboratory chief Siegfried Hecker, who said he attended the Feb. meeting.
link_name: China says North Korea may have up to 20 nuclear warheads
Puerto Rico officials warn of imminent government shutdown
IRS phone service dropped 8 million calls
300,000 sign petition against El Salvador's strict abortion laws
House passes bill to help thwart cyberattacks
Brazil's Petrobras loses $8.8 billion in Q4 in wake of corruption scandal
Qualcomm cuts revenue forecast by $1 billion following loss of 'large' customer
Southern Chile in state of red alert following Calbuco volcano eruption

status_message: An 11-judge panel in the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Apr. 22 reversed Bonds' conviction for obstruction of justice. A three-judge panel in the 9th Circuit had previously upheld the conviction. The government could request that all 29 judges in the circuit reconsider the case, but such a meeting has not been convened since smaller panels came into use in 1980.
link_name: Barry Bonds' obstruction conviction thrown out

status_message: AT&T said April 22 that it may save as much as $2.5 billion in "cost synergies" if its proposed merger with DirecTV is approved by regulators. AT&T previously put this amount at $1.6 billion. These "cost synergies" are likely to include reduced programming expenses and job cuts.
link_name: If approved, AT&T expects to save $2.5 billion with DirecTV merger
EBay beats Q1 expectations, PayPal split on target for Q3
Tickets for Mayweather-Pacquiao expected to go on sale today

status_message: Chipotle sales missed Wall St. estimates on April 21, causing shares to fall 8.3% to $635.25 on the same day. At stores open for longer than one year, sales rose 10.4% from the previous quarter. Overall sales reached $1.09 billion, a 20.9% increase and profits rose 47.6% to $122.6 million, both less than analysts expected.
link_name: Lack of carnitas threaten to undercut Chipotle growth

status_message:
Facebook beat earnings estimates but missed on sales, posted earnings of 42 per share on $3.54 in revenue. Wall Street analysts expected earnings of 40 cents per share on $3.56 billion in revenue.

Daily active users climbed 17% in March 2015 from March 2014 to 936M.
link_name: Facebook beats earnings, misses sales expectations in Q1 2015

status_message: In an April 22 email sent to analysts and investors, Tesla Motors said that it will announce a home battery and a "very large" utility-scale battery at a high-profile event next week. The email was obtained by Bloomberg, which then quoted Tesla as saying it will explain why past battery technology is "not compelling."
link_name: Tesla to announce home and large utility battery at April 30 event

status_message: The European Commission (EC) filed antitrust charges against Russian energy giant Gazprom on April 22, claiming the world's largest producer of gas has gauged prices and is abusing its power. The charges amount to a challenge of Russian President Vladimir Putin's geopolitical and economic strategy. One-third of the European Union's natural gas is supplied by Russia.
link_name: EU files antitrust charges against Russian energy giant Gazprom

status_message: A study Berkeley in April found the U.S. government and states spend $152.8 billion annually on public assistance programs for working families, or 56% of spending. The study examined major programs including Medicaid, food stamps and tax credits.
link_name: Most US public assistance goes to working families, study says

status_message: A 66-hour freight train strike began April 21. Passenger train drivers walked out in the early hours of April 22 and will return to work the night of April 23. Rail operator Deutsche Bahn said one-third of long distance trains would be running April 22-23, with up to 85% of regional trains cancelled.
link_name: German train drivers strike for higher pay, fewer working hours

status_message: An April study in Astrophysical Journal Letters discusses a possible "binary" system of two supermassive black holes. The researchers say the black holes are "emitting gravitational waves, which were predicted by Einstein's theory of general relativity."
link_name: Scientists see evidence of a "binary" system of black holes

status_message: The fast food giant is seeing declining traffic. Its latest financial results show a steep drop in earnings and revenue from a year ago.
link_name: McDonald's first quarter sales disappoint amid sluggish traffic

status_message: Djungan Clan elders expressed relief for the safety of their mountain cultural sites, which date back 35,000 years, after Mantle withdrew its drilling application. The Djungan signed a 2012 land use agreement with Mantle, but ended it on grounds that the company did not inform them of the impact of fracking, the Guardian reported.
link_name: Mining company drops plans to drill on Australian indigenous site

status_message: Solar Impulse 2 landed in eastern China after a more than 17-hour flight from Chongqing. It was grounded for three weeks until the weather was good enough for its sixth flight, the second of two Chinese stops. It will next fly across the Pacific Ocean to Hawaii, a trip that will take an estimated 120 hours.
link_name: Solar-powered flight completes Chinese leg of round-the-world journey

status_message: In an April 21 interview with Reuters, Xu provided a rare opposing opinion by a Chinese executive to the government's plans of "localization" of the technology used in China.
link_name: Huawei CEO criticizes China's push to localize technology

status_message: Court allows Japanese nuclear reactor restart
link_name: Court allows Japanese nuclear reactor restart

status_message: On April 22, the Kagoshima district court rejected an injunction from residents opposing the restart of Kyushu Electric Power's Sendai nuclear station. Operators said preparations were underway to have the plant operating by June.
link_name: Court allows Japanese nuclear reactor restart

status_message: Three people died in floods when 12 inches of rain fell in 24 hours through 9am on April 22. A woman and two men died after their homes were washed away in Dungog, north of Newcastle. Residents in Sydney's northern beaches were on alert with Manly Dam spilling over.
link_name: Three Aussies dead, two missing in wild storms

status_message: An anonymous buyer bought a 100.2-carat, emerald-cut diamond for $22 million during a Sotheby's auction in New York City on April 21. The "perfect" diamond was expected fetch between $19 million and $25 million. The stone was mined by De Beers in South Africa in the last decade.
link_name: 'Perfect' 100.2-carat diamond fetches $22 million

status_message: The Hong Kong government released its blueprint on April 22 for 2017 elections for chief executive. Protesters gathered outside the Legislative Council. The plan came after reviewing comments from a wide range of Hong Kong society. It is almost identical to Beijing's plan in Aug. 2014 that set off pro-democracy protests.
link_name: Hong Kong releases unchanged election plan

status_message: The San Diego Chargers and Oakland Raiders told The LA Times Feb 19 they're proposing a shared, privately financed $1.7 billion stadium in Carson. The teams said the proposal is a contingency plan if publicly subsidized stadium deals in their respective cities don't occur in 2015.
link_name: Los Angeles council approves NFL stadium proposal

status_message: Yum posted first quarter results April 21. Sales at existing branches in China fell 12% year-on-year in January and February. Quarterly sales were down 9% to $1.26 billion. However, the company's stock rose 4.5% to $84.52 after Creed said China sales saw "continued progress."
link_name: Yum Brands struggling in China, but CEO sees "progress"
GOP senator unveils contingency plan in case Supreme Court guts Obamacare tax credits
Obama won't use 'genocide' to describe 1915 Armenian deaths, White House says
Fox, NBC join ESPN in criticizing Verizon's 'Custom TV' bundles
New study further debunks link between MMR vaccine and autism
Supreme Court rules prolonging traffic stops for drug-sniffing dogs unconstitutional
Sentencing phase underway in Boston Marathon bomber trial
Facebook 'balances' News Feed to show more from friends, less from brands

status_message: In a letter submitted to Congress on April 21, President Obama put forth an agreement with China that, if approved, would last 30 years and allow the two nations to transfer nuclear material, reactors, components, and technology.
link_name: Obama puts forth 30-year nuclear power proposal with China
US companies partner with French health agency to expand breast cancer gene database

status_message: The Saudi-led coalition fighting against Shia Houthi rebels in Yemen will end its bombing campaign in Yemen by the end of April 21, General Asseri said the same day on Saudi-owned Arabiya TV. The coalition will now focus on aid and a political solution in Yemen and security in Saudi Arabia.
link_name: Saudi-led coalition to cease bombing campaign in Yemen
UK futures trader charged for role in 2010 'flash crash'
Poland in talks with US over major missile purchase
Aereo pays broadcasters $950,000 to settle copyright claims
Generic drugmaker Teva offers to buy rival Mylan for $40.1 billion
HP to sell Snapfish photo service as part of company split
At least 10 dead after Somalia car bombing aimed at government officials
Twitter to lock abusive accounts in harassment crackdown
Google boosts search rankings of mobile-friendly websites

status_message: A third of all African-American men aged 25 to 54 years (1.5 million men) in the U.S. were missing from daily life because they died young or were in jail, an April 20 NYT analysis of the 2010 census showed.
link_name: About 1.5 million African-Americans killed or imprisoned, past census data shows

status_message: A report released by HCEfh in mid-April found all 600 women polled outside Paris said they experienced some form of sexual harassment on public transport. Harassment was defined as "the imposition of any kind of words or behavior that are intended to create a situation that is intimidating, humiliating, degrading of offensive."
link_name: France public transport survey finds rampant sexual harassment

status_message: uberAUTO allows bookings for the green-and-yellow rickshaws found in the Indian capital. The company is also allowing Indian users to pay in cash according to the metered fare, instead of its regular e-payment model. The city has some 100,000 auto-rickshaws on its roads.
link_name: Uber adds rickshaws and cash payments in India

status_message: A mob attacked Zia's car April 20 during a Dhaka mayoral election rally. Zia has tried to force Bangladesh back to the polls since Jan. 2014, when she lost the election. Her party contested fewer than half of the seats. It says the election was rigged with no foreign observers.
link_name: Mob attacks car of Bangladesh's former prime minister in rally

status_message: Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe sent a "masakaki" tree as an offering to the Yasukuni shrine on April 21. There has not been any official reaction by other nations. A day earlier Abe said he would not apologize for Japan's role in WWII when he speaks later in 2015 on the 70th anniversary of the end of the war.
link_name: Japan's Abe sends gift to controversial WWII shrine

status_message: China's National People's Congress Standing Committee began deliberations April 20 on a potential ban on tobacco advertising, according to state media. It would allow China to adhere to a World Health Organization treaty it signed in 2003, according to the report.
link_name: Chinese draft law bans tobacco advertising

status_message: A magnetic levitation train, or maglev train, set a world record on April 21 near Mt. Fuji with a top speed of 374.7mph. The seven-car train traveled 11 seconds at a sustained speed of more than 373mph. Normal trains cannot reach such speeds because the friction of wheels on tracks.
link_name: Japan's maglev train breaks world speed record of more than 373 mph

status_message: Fake and substandard drugs are a "global pandemic," according to a collection of articles published in the American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene April 20. The articles contend the drugs kill hundreds of thousands of people a year and threaten to undermine decades of work to combat HIV/AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis.
link_name: Report: Fake and low-quality drugs are a 'global pandemic'

status_message: The UN called for "unhindered access" to the Yarmouk refugee camp in an April 20 statement. The UN has made an emergency appeal of $30 million to provide humanitarian aid to residents of the camp, which was set up in 1957 for Palestinians. The UN wants to set up distribution points for aid.
link_name: UN calls for humanitarian access to Palestinian refugee camp in Syria

status_message: At least 90,000 people have fled Ramadi, Anbar province since April 8, the UN said April 19, adding to the 2.7 million Iraqis displaced since Jan. 2014. Aid agencies expect hundreds of thousands more displaced when the Iraqi military steps up operations in Anbar. Some 500,000 fled Anbar in early 2014 amid government airstrikes.
link_name: Tens of thousands flee conflict in western Iraq

status_message: Netflix confirmed April 20 that it ordered a 13-episode reboot of the sitcom "Full House," entitled "Fuller House." It will star Candace Cameron-Bure playing the role of D.J. "Full House" ended its original run in 1995. "Fuller House" is expected to be released in 2016.
link_name: Netflix confirms reboot of "Full House"
Vermont formally adopts regulations for GMO labeling law
Thailand seizes smuggled African elephant tusks worth $6 million
Colombian government, FARC trade accusations after deadly clash
AC/DC's Phil Rudd pleads guilty to threatening to kill, drug charges
FDA head says agency moving forward on e-cigarette regulations
Prosecutor dismisses allegations against Argentine president
Feds propose loosening protections for most humpback whales
Utah mother who murdered 6 babies gets up to life in prison

status_message: The U.S. deployed the USS Theodore Roosevelt to Yemeni waters on April 20 to join the effort of intercepting possible Iranian vessels from providing aid to Houthis rebels. The move follows a UN arms embargo adopted a week before. Navy officials told the AP there are currently about 9 U.S. vessels in the region.
link_name: US warship heads toward Yemeni waters

status_message: Quarterback Tim Tebow officially signed with the Philadelphia Eagles April 20, on a one year deal. Tebow, 27 hasn't been on an NFL roster since the 2013 preseason when he was with the New England Patriots. The 2007 Heisman winner has an 8-6 record as a starting quarterback including a playoff victory against the Pittsburgh Steelers in 2011.
link_name: Tim Tebow signs with Philadelphia Eagles

status_message: The 2015 Pulitzer Prize Awards were announced in April 20. The Post and Courier of Charleston, S.C. won the gold medal for public service, the most prestigious prize for journalism, for its "Till Death Do Us Part" series on the high number of deaths related to domestic violence in the state. It is the first small paper to win the award in 5 years.
link_name: Pulitzer Prize winners include coverage of domestic violence in SC, Secret Service misconduct
New York man sentenced to 25 years for attempting to join Al-Qaeda
Study: Acetaminophen may blunt emotions
Blind users sue Uber over inability to bring guide dogs
Chicago prosecutor pledges to dismiss future minor marijuana cases
Kraft will stop using artificial colors and preservatives in mac and cheese
China pledges $28 billion to Pakistan for infrastructure projects
Greece requires public sector entities to transfer cash balances to central bank
GE looking to sell lending operation, in talks with Wells Fargo, others
FTC to host workshop on effects of sharing economy
Supreme Court sends North Carolina voting changes case back to state court
Caroline Rotich, Lelisa Desisa win women's and men's titles at Boston Marathon

status_message: Bloomberg reported April 20, based on two unnamed sources, that Elon Musk in March 2013 was working on a deal to sell Tesla Motors to Google for around $6 billion. Google CEO Larry Page reportedly agreed to the deal, but it was broken off after sales of the Model S quickly improved the company's financial position.
link_name: Report: Elon Musk looked to sell Tesla Motors to Google in 2013

status_message: WHO said in a statement in April that the organization's Ebola response was "slow and insufficient." "We were not aggressive in alerting the world," and poor communication caused confusion, it said.
link_name: WHO admits it was too slow in Ebola response

status_message: The junta-appointed National Reform Council began discussions April 20 on a draft constitution ahead of elections planned for 2016. The draft would give amnesty to leaders of the 2014 coup, allow unelected individuals to become prime minister and enact an electoral system favoring coalition governments.
link_name: Junta-appointed Thai council begins discussions on constitution

status_message: The U.S., China and European Union (EU) questioned Australia's commitment during a UN meeting, Fairfax reported April 20. The EU asked if Australia could aim for a 15-25% cut, instead of 5%. Brazil and China doubted the reduction target when current emissions are about 31% higher than 1990, according to Dec. 2014 research.
link_name: Australia's climate change commitment challenged in the UN

status_message: South Korea will increase its 2016-2020 military budget by $8.03 billion, the Korean Herald reported April 20. Some of the increased funding will go to its "Kill Chain" system that includes drones and Taurus missiles, while other funds will go to its air defense system.
link_name: South Korea to increase military budget by several billions

status_message: Forty percent of the 116 environmental activists killed in 2014 were defending indigenous land rights in South America against hydropower projects, mining, agribusiness and logging interests, an April 20 Global Witness report says. It found 29 killed in Brazil, 25 in Colombia and at least four in Peru.
link_name: Killings of environmentalists increased in 2014, report says

status_message: China's central bank on April 19 cut the reserve requirement ratio for Chinese banks by a percentage point to 18.5% effective April 20. The rate, which was cut the most since 2008, allows $194 billion in additional funds for loans.
link_name: China's central bank stimulus opens up $194 billion

status_message: Yuniel Lopez, 26, of the Independent and Democratic Cuba Party and Hildebrando Chaviano, 65, an independent, both conceded defeat in elections for municipal assembly seats on April 19. They had been voted into the final round of elections by a show of hands in their district.
link_name: Opposition candidates in Cuba lose municipal races

status_message: An unidentified person was detained late on April 19, said the Secret Service. Charges have not yet been filed.
link_name: Secret Service detains person attempting to climb White House fence

status_message: "Furious 7" made another $29.1 million at the North American box office during the April 17-19 weekend, remaining in the No. 1 spot for the third straight week. It has made a total of $292.4 million in domestic sales, along with $858.3 million globally, for a worldwide box office take of $1.15 billion.
link_name: 'Furious 7' stays atop box office, passes $1 billion worldwide

status_message: Finnish Prime Minister Alexander Stubb was ousted after the opposition Centre party took 49 of 200 seats in parliament. IT millionaire Juha Sipila, who favors austerity measures, will become the country's next leader.
link_name: Finland election won by opposition Centre party

status_message: Hawaii Gov. David Ige said April 17 that the company behind the Thirty Meter Telescope had decided to postpone construction for a second time. Ige said future announcements about when construction schedule will come from the company.
link_name: Construction on Hawaii's Thirty Meter Telescope postponed again

status_message: NOAA, along with the U.S. Navy and private contractors, have located the wreckage of the USS Independence, which NOAA scientists described April 16 as "amazingly intact" after over 60 years underwater. The ship fought in World War II and was part of the atomic bomb tests at Bikini Atoll. The Navy scuttled it near California's Farallon Islands in 1951.
link_name: Wreckage of USS Independence WWII ship found intact

status_message: Robert Gentile, 79, was arrested on April 17 on unrelated gun charges while the FBI was conducting a sting operation in connection with the 1990 Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum art heist in Boston, Mass. The FBI says Gentile was attempting to negotiate the sale of the paintings, worth $500 million, to an undercover FBI agent.
link_name: FBI arrests man with connections to $500 million 1990 art heist in Boston

status_message: Mets pitcher Alex Torres, the only MLB player to wear a protective cap in a game, debuted a new version of the headgear on April 18.
link_name: Mets pitcher debuts new version of protective cap

status_message: According to the AP, court hearings are expected to begin on April 22 to decide whether John Hinckley Jr., who has spent over 30 years in a mental hospital for attempting to assassinate President Ronald Reagan in 1981, should be freed permanently.
link_name: Court set to decide if Reagan shooter should be released permanently

status_message: French customs officials said April 18 that a seizure earlier in the week netted 2.25 tons of cocaine, valued at some $105 million, the largest ever bust for French authorities. One Venezuelan and two Spanish citizens were arrested. The smugglers were caught in a sailboat falsely flying the U.S. flag off the French Caribbean island of Martinique.
link_name: French authorities nab record 2.25 tons of cocaine in Caribbean

status_message: The FBI and Justice Dept. acknowledged that almost all forensic hair testimony given by analysts in the FBI Laboratory's microscopic hair comparison unit against defendants was flawed during the 20-year period before 2000, according to a Washington Post report April 18.
link_name: Report: FBI admits to overstating forensic hair matches for 20 years
Survivors remember 20th anniversary of Oklahoma City bombing

status_message: A former spy under Saddam Hussein, Samir Al-Khlifawi, aka Haji Bakr, drew up the blueprints for the Islamic State by 2012, an April 18 Der Spiegel report showed. A total of 31 handwritten pages from Bakr's home in Syria were smuggled to Turkey in April-Nov. 2014. Syrian rebels killed Bakr in Jan. 2014.
link_name: Saddam Hussein spy made blueprints for Islamic State, smuggled papers show

status_message: Jack White's Third Man Records on April 18 released a vinyl copy of Elvis' songs "My Happiness" and "That's Where Your Heartaches Begin" on a 10-inch, 78rpm facsimile.
link_name: Jack White releases limited vinyl copy of Elvis' early songs

status_message: IMF members on April 18 said they were committed to a "more robust, balanced and job-rich global economy" after warning that economic growth in emerging economies may be hindered by weakening commodity prices and exports. IMF and World Bank members are meeting in Washington, DC, for the three-day conference April 17-19.
link_name: IMF aims for 'more robust' global economy

status_message: Some 1 million people have made reservations to see the Shroud of Turin so far, according to the city's mayor. The last time the shroud was on display, some 2.5 million people visited.
link_name: Shroud of Turin goes back on display for the first time in 5 years

status_message: Two animal rights protesters were arrested in San Bernardino, Calif., after activists allegedly brawled with clowns and other workers from a Ramos Bros. Circus show on April 18.
link_name: Clowns brawl with animal rights protesters at Calif. circus

status_message: Authorities in Mexico said the arrest of Gulf Cartel chief Jose Tiburcio Hernandez Fuentes on April 17 has led to violence and road blockades of burning vehicles in Reynosa, Mexico, near the border with Texas.
link_name: Arrest of cartel chief leads to gunfights in Mexico

status_message: The UN said April 18 that an attack the previous day on a peacekeeping convoy in northern Mali had left two drivers shot dead. A third person was also wounded. The latest attack came after an Al-Qaeda-linked suicide bomber hit a UN barracks in the region on April 15, killing two and wounding nine peacekeepers from Niger.
link_name: UN peacekeeping convoy attacked in Mali, 2 drivers dead

status_message: Prague opened a new section of its metro extending closer to the airport than before. However, passengers still must travel 8 kilometers (5 miles) from the metro station to the airport. The best public transit option is a bus line, but passengers must scale 32 steep steps to reach the bus terminal.
link_name: Missing escalator causes problems for Prague airport visitors

status_message: BMW has been forced to recall 91,800 MINI Coopers due to a faulty mat sensor located on the passenger side floor. The sensor is supposed to detect occupancy of the front passenger side seat in order for an airbag to activate during an accident. The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) announced the recall on April 18.
link_name: BMW set to recall 91,800 MINI Coopers due to airbag deployment glitch

status_message: South African President Jacob Zuma canceled a state visit to Indonesia on April 18 "in order to attend to matters at home relating to the attacks on foreign nationals," his office said.
link_name: South Africa's president cancels foreign trip over anti-immigrant unrest

status_message: Kendall Schler, 26, was disqualified as the winner of the 2015 Go! St. Louis Marathon held on April 12 in Missouri. Officials say Schler also faked her third-place finish in 2014. On April 15, Schler was disqualified from both the 2015 and 2014 marathons.
link_name: St. Louis marathon winner disqualified, never ran race
MakerBot lays off 20% of its staff, closes retail stores

status_message: WhatsApp now has 800 million monthly active users, CEO Jan Koum said April 17. That's up from 700 million announced in January and 600 million announced in Aug. 2014. WhatsApp users send 30 billion messages per day.
link_name: WhatsApp hits 800 million active users

status_message: A suicide bomber detonated a bomb at then entrance of a bank in Jalalabad on April 18. At least 33 people died, mostly civilians, and over 100 other people were injured.
link_name: Suicide bombing outside Afghan bank kills at least 33
Oklahoma governor signs bill to allow the use of nitrogen gas for executions
Navy drone completes first test of unmanned aircraft aerial refueling
Indiana reports more than 120 HIV cases in county outbreak
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar undergoes successful heart surgery
5 people, 4 companies indicted for illegally shipping technology to Iran
Prosecutors drop investigation against former News of the World editor Andy Coulson
Education Dept. fines Corinthian Colleges $30 million
CEO of Jay Z music service Tidal steps down
Women twice as likely to be hired as equally qualified men in STEM fields
Nissan expands recall for faulty airbags
Stock markets take a dive, Dow down 280
Fort Hood shooting victims granted benefits after Purple Hearts awarded
Ohio settles lawsuit over early voting changes
Muslim migrants throw Christians overboard while en route from Libya to Italy

status_message: Verizon told Reuters April 16 that FIOS customers each month will be able to switch the bundle of channels that are part of their subscription. This "Custom TV" package includes broadband, 36 basic channels, and two additional channels bundles, such as kids channels and sports channels. The package costs $65 per month.
link_name: Verizon to let customers swap channel bundles each month
FCC opens government-controlled wireless spectrum for mobile broadband

status_message: Bloomberg reported April 17 that U.S. antitrust regulators are currently leaning against approving the proposed merger between Comcast and Time Warner Cable.
link_name: Bloomberg report: US leaning against approving Comcast-TWC merger
20 current and former tax chiefs arrested in Guatemala corruption probe

status_message: Mario Kreutzberger, who goes by the stage name Don Francisco said in a statement, "I would like to say from the bottom of my heart and in capital letters, THANK YOU VERY MUCH." Univision has not said why the show is going off air, or what it plans to do with the time-slot.
link_name: Spanish-language show 'Sabado Gigante' ends after more than five decades
Report: Apple Pay slated to launch in Canada this fall
UN asks US and other Western countries to take in Syrian refugees
Disneyland measles outbreak over, health officials declare
Car bomb detonates near US consulate in Iraqi Kurdistan's capital Erbil

status_message: Virtu is the first large high-frequency trading firm to go public, according to the Wall Street Journal. Virtu priced its shares at $19 each at its IPO on April 15, raising more than $300 million. It debuted on the Nasdaq April 16, surging to $23.67 before closing at $22.18, up 17%. That valued the firm at $3.2 billion.
link_name: High-speed trader Virtu surges in market debut

status_message: South Africans have also held marches in support of immigrants. Disaster relief agency Gift of the Givers, however, said April 17 that about 8,500 people had fled to refugee centers or police stations in the previous week due to violence.
link_name: Immigration takes center stage in South Africa amid economic woes

status_message: The Shanghai Composite Index closed 2.2% up on April 17 at 4,287.30. It reached a high of 4317.22, its highest price since March 2008, according to CNBC. Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index also was near the seven-year-high it hit April 13. Japan's Nikkei fell 1.2% April 13 after reaching a 15-year high of 20,006 on April 11.
link_name: Shanghai index reaches seven-year high in trading

status_message: Qantas ranked 75th out of 80 airlines for being on time at London Heathrow Airport in February, according to a leaked internal memo first reported by the Australian Financial Review on April 16. Many of the airline's flagship A380 super-jumbos were arriving late.
link_name: Qantas Airways on notice at Heathrow for tardiness

status_message: Imagery taken March 23 and released April 15 by IHS Jane's shows China is quickly building a concrete runway on an artificial island at Fiery Cross Reef in the Spratly Islands. The 1,500-foot runway is long enough for fighter jets and other military aircraft to use, experts say.
link_name: China building airstrip on artificial island in South China Sea

status_message: Sweden's Foreign Minister Margo Wallstrom told the New Yorker in an article published April 15 that she would continue her "feminist" foreign policy because research showed global security was directly related to women's security. The more violent a state was to women, the likely it would act violently to the outside world.
link_name: Swedish minister discusses pursuit of feminist foreign policy

status_message: A coalition of women's groups and U.S. Representative Katherine Clark (D-Mass.) held a Congressional briefing on Capitol Hill April 16 to educate lawmakers about the impact of not taking cyberstalking and online threats seriously. Game developer Zoe Quinn described how she was harassed and her privacy was invaded, and efforts to fight cyberstalking.
link_name: Congressional hearing addresses online harassment
Jameis Winston sued for alleged rape in 2012
Judges skeptical of GOP's lawsuit against EPA coal plant rules
NBA to test players for human growth hormone
Michael Phelps returns to swimming after 6-month suspension
Instagram overhauls guidelines to fight harassment, pornography
Madoff trustee seeks to disburse $1.25 billion
Gyrocopter pilot who landed on Capitol West Lawn charged with felony
Etsy surges more than 87% in first day of trading
Internal memo: Apple Watch unlikely to be available for in-store purchase through May
Walmart wins court battle against church regarding gun sales
Lawmakers reach deal to fast-track Obama trade deals
CDC: Teen use of e-cigarettes tripled from 2013 to 2014
GM shielded from ignition switch claims made after its bankruptcy, judge rules
Activists launch hunger strike over delay of vote for attorney general nominee
Adrian Peterson to be reinstated by NFL
Former Australian model killed fighting for Islamic State

status_message:
Star Wars: The Force Awakens releases new teaser trailer 



http://circanews.com/news/star-wars-episode-vii-developments
link_name: Star Wars: The Force Awakens Official Teaser #2

status_message: In a televised call-in show shown April 16 across several national channels, including Rossiya-1, Putin took 70 questions from Russian citizens and officials. Asked by former finance minister Alexei Kudrin to comment on the state of the Russian economy, the president said his policies targeted the link between welfare and social stability.
link_name: Vladimir Putin takes questions on economy, social reforms in live broadcast
Washburn University fraternity suspended for sexually lewd group texts
Target agrees to $19 million data breach settlement with MasterCard

status_message: At the end of a hearing on April 16, a judge ruled that there was sufficient evidence for Knight to stand trial for murder. The hearing was focused on testimony from Cle "Bone" Sloan, who survived a hit from Knight's pickup truck in January.
link_name: Judge rules Suge Knight will stand trial for murder
Health officials: Disneyland measles outbreak may be over
Slack reaches $2.8 billion valuation after raising $160 million

status_message: WikiLeaks on April 16 published the "Sony Archives," a complete, searchable data of the emails that were leaked as a result of the Sony Pictures hack. WikiLeaks says the archive offers "rare insight" in a multinational corporation.
link_name: WikiLeaks publishes complete database of leaked Sony Pictures emails
Netflix soars 15% after better-than-expected subscriber gains

status_message: Indonesia summoned Saudi Arabia's ambassador on April 15 to protest the April 14 beheading of Siti Zainab, a domestic worker convicted of killing her employer in 1999. Indonesia said it was informed about the execution after it happened. Rights groups said Zainab acted in self-defense and may have been mentally ill.
link_name: Indonesia protests Saudi Arabia's execution of domestic worker

status_message: A ban on the sale of alcoholic beverages in small shops and mini-markets in Indonesia came into force April 16. The tourism industry has strongly opposed it. More than 70,000 shops are affected, AFP reported.
link_name: Indonesia bans alcohol sales at small shops

status_message: Mayawati Kumari, Bahujan Samaj Party (BSP) leader and the former chief minister of Uttar Pradesh, India's agricultural and most populous state, announced April 15 a statewide campaign on April 27 against land reform. She says it disadvantages poor farmers and farm workers, and lacks compensation to farmers wiped out by unseasonal storms in March.
link_name: Indian Prime Minister Modi's land reform draws ire of farmers, opposition party

status_message: Small, water-polluting factories that do not meet standards will be closed down by the end of 2016, China's State Council said April 16. Industries include oil refining, pesticides, arsenic refining, and paper, printing and leather industrial plants.
link_name: China to close down small, water-polluting factories that don't meet standards

status_message: In a memorial speech April 16, South Korean President Geun-hye Park for the first time promised to raise the sunken ferry, after persistent calls by the families of the victims to do so. Earlier in the day, the country's National Assembly overwhelmingly passed a resolution to salvage the ship.
link_name: South Korea marks one year since ferry disaster

status_message: Malaysia, Australia and China agreed April 16 to double the search area to around 46,000 square miles for MH370 if the plane is not found in the current search area. "That would cover almost all of the highest probability areas identified by the expert analysis," Australian Deputy PM Warren Truss said.
link_name: MH370 search area to double if plane not found in current area

status_message: Japan held $1.2244 trillion in U.S. debt by the end of February, surpassing China's $1.2237 trillion, April 15 U.S. Treasury Dept. data showed. A Wall Street Journal analysis, however, said China actually increased its total U.S. holdings and the calculations did not include transactions in foreign countries on behalf of China.
link_name: Japan overtakes China as top foreign holder of US debt, Treasury data shows

status_message: Brazilian Worker's Party ex-treasurer Joao Vaccari was arrested April 15 in connection with the Petrobras scandal. He was indicted mid-March on charges including money laundering and accepting kickbacks. Although the Worker's Party said he was innocent, he resigned after his arrest.
link_name: Brazilian party treasurer arrested over Petrobras corruption scandal
Chinese real estate development investment falls to six-year low
Texas executes man for killing SWAT team officer
South Korea marks one year since ferry disaster
Sardine population crisis closes West Coast fisheries starting July 1
LA school district wants multimillion-dollar refund from Apple for problem software
Kansas governor to approve new restrictions for welfare recipients
Toyota to open $1 billion plant in Mexico
Federal judge keeps marijuana on dangerous drugs list
Iran limits jailed Washington Post reporter's access to lawyer
Congressional watchdog warns wireless connectivity may put flights at risk of cyberattacks
Report: Etsy to raise $267 million in IPO
FDA tells Kind bars to remove 'healthy' from labels

status_message: A man has been taken into custody after landing a gyrocopter on the west lawn of the US Capitol.
link_name: Gyrocopter lands on Capitol West lawn

status_message: AT&T is now the first major broadband provider to file a lawsuit of its own against the FCC challenging the new net neutrality regulations. The lawsuit was filed April 14, shortly after two trade groups, the National Cable & Telecommunications Association and CTIA (formerly the Cellular Telephone Industries Association) filed their own lawsuits.
link_name: Two more trade groups sue FCC over net neutrality

status_message: The New York Times said April 15 that it will make NYT Now free beginning on May 11. The app, which previously cost $8 per month, presents a series of "hand-selected" news stories from the Times and from its partners. Capital New York first reported earlier in April that NYT Now would soon become free.
link_name: New York Times to make 'NYT Now' app free

status_message: Kaspersky developed the tool in conjunction with Dutch authorities. The tool decrypts files encrypted with CoinVault, a piece of malware that first surfaced in 2014 that encrypts files on Windows PCs. Previously, the only way to decrypt these files was to pay a bitcoin ransom to the malware's creators.
link_name: Kaspersky releases tool to unlock PCs crippled by ransomware

status_message: The FBI and NYPD announced April 15 that they will give up to a $115,000 reward to anyone who can provide useful information to help identify or capture suspects involved with the March 6, 2008 Times Square bombing of a U.S. Armed Forces Recruiting Station. Surveillance footage shows an unidentified suspect planting the bomb and riding away on a bike.
link_name: FBI, NYPD offer $115,000 reward for information on 2008 Times Square bombing

status_message: An April 15 TI report examined and ranked 19 European countries and three EU institutions on how they safeguard against undue influence in public decision-making. It measured transparency, integrity, and quality of access. The results were "sobering," it said.
link_name: Europe 'a playground' for special interests due to lax lobbying rules, report says

status_message: Vanuatu has received only 23% of $5 million aid requested for urgent health and nutrition needs, the World Health Organization said April 15. The funds are needed for safe water, food, and to fix the struggling health system for a population where 12,500 children are aged under 5 years.
link_name: Vanuatu struggles without adequate aid to provide food and water after cyclone

status_message: Japanese fighter jets were scrambled 943 times in the 12 months ending March 31, the Japanese military said April 15. The number was one shy of the 1984 record during the Cold War, and 133 more than the previous year, a 16% increase. Records began in 1958. Most scrambles were in response to Russian and Chinese aircraft.
link_name: Japanese fighter jet scrambles reach Cold War high

status_message: Israeli troops and police detained at least 29 people in an overnight raid April 14/15. Many of the detained were suspected members of Hamas and have previously spent time in Israeli prisons, the Shin Bet intelligence service said. Israel has conducted overnight raids frequently in 2015, sometimes detaining minors.
link_name: Israel detains dozens of Palestinians in West Bank raids
Aaron Hernandez found guilty of first degree murder

status_message: Tsai was named the DPP's 2016 presidential candidate April 15. She is considered one of the favorites to win the presidency in 2016. Her party routed the ruling KMT party of President Ma Ying-jeou in local elections in Nov. 2014.
link_name: Taiwan opposition party names leader as 2016 presidential candidate

status_message: Japanese fighter jets had been scrambled 943 times in the year ending March 31, the Japanese military said April 15. The number was one shy of the 1984 record during the Cold War, and 133 more than the previous year, a 16% increase. Records began in 1958. Most scrambles were in response to Russian and Chinese aircraft.
link_name: Japanese fighter jet scrambles reach Cold War high

status_message: A video posted to YouTube April 11 shows Apple's virtual assistant Siri offering "homophobic" answers to questions about gay clubs and gay marriage. "I will pretend I haven't heard it," Siri replies when asked how to register a gay marriage in the UK. Apple has said the responses were the result of a bug which has been fixed, the BBC reported April 15.
link_name: Apple fixes bug to Russian Siri after accusations of homophobia

status_message: European regulators officially filed antitrust charges against Google on April 15, accusing the company of giving itself an "unfair advantage" by emphasizing its own shopping services over competitors' services in search results. Google quickly denied any wrongdoing.
link_name: Report: EU to file formal antitrust charges against Google

status_message: Melinda Magsino, a former correspondent for the Philippine Daily Inquirer, was shot and killed at close range by a gunman on April 13. A second suspect drove the killer away on a motorcycle. Magsino, 40, died at the scene, police said. Vice President Jejomar Binay said the killing was a "tragedy" for democracy. The National Bureau of Investigation opened a case on April 14.
link_name: Filipino police investigating murder of former journalist

status_message: Researchers have extracted the oldest Neanderthal DNA from a skeleton in a limestone cave near Altamura in southern Italy, LiveScience reported April 10. "Altamura Man's" DNA is between 150,000-170,000 years old. They hope to solve unanswered questions about Neanderthal anatomy, lifestyles and habitats.
link_name: Researchers examining 150,000-170,000-year-old Neanderthal DNA

status_message: Israeli troops and police detained at least 29 people in an overnight raid April 14-15. Many of the detained were suspected members of Hamas and have previously spent time in Israeli prisons, the Shin Bet intelligence service said. Israel has conducted overnight raids frequently in 2015, sometimes detaining minors.
link_name: Israel detains dozens of Palestinians in West Bank raids

status_message: The Chinese government published a white paper April 15 that calls the Dalai Lama's Tibetan government in exile "the remnants of the feudal serf owners" of Tibet. It calls on the Dalai Lama to "face up to reality" that Tibet will never be independent.
link_name: China says Dalai Lama should "face up to reality" and abandon Tibet independence

status_message: The UN is planning to restart peace talks in May, a UN spokesman told Reuters on April 14. The talks will be based on a June 2012 document on a political transition for Syria that does not determine the fate of President Bashar Al-Assad. The UN wants to include Iran in the talks, although Iran previously opposed the document.
link_name: UN hopes to restart Syria peace talks

status_message: NineBot CEO Gao Lufeng said at a press conference April 15 that NineBot bought 100% of Segway for an undisclosed sum. A Segway executive confirmed the news in a video statement, according to Michael Kan of the IDG News Service.
link_name: Chinese robotics company buys Segway

status_message: An annual performance report by Wichita State University ranked Virgin America, Hawaiian Airlines and Delta as the top three U.S. airlines in 2014. Only three of the 12 airlines evaluated improved in the ranking. The three lowest-ranked companies were SkyWest, ExpressJet and Envoy.
link_name: Report: 8 of 12 US airlines' performance dropped in 2014

status_message: Nokia will purchase Alcatel-Lucent for 15.6 billion euros ($16.59 billion), Nokia said April 15. Both boards approved the deal. Nokia shareholders will own 66.5% of the merged company and 33.5% will go to Alcatel-Lucent shareholders. The new company would have around 114,000 employees.
link_name: Nokia to buy network equipment maker Alcatel-Lucent for $16.59 billion

status_message: On April 15, China said first quarter GDP growth was 7%, which was in-line with estimates, but is still the lowest quarterly growth since Q1 2009. Quarter-to-quarter GDP growth was 1.3%.
link_name: China GDP growth falls to 7% in first quarter
Lawmaker wants lifetime ban on politicians becoming lobbyists
Unidentified remains of USS Oklahoma crew to be exhumed

status_message: The 12 jurors and 12 alternates in the James Holmes trial were seated on April 14, with opening statements are set to begin April 27.
link_name: Jury seated in Colorado shooter James Holmes' death penalty trial
NASA probe sends back first color images of Pluto
Feds investigate Nestle's expired permit to bottle water in California
Obama war authorization against Islamic State stalls in the House
Ohio lawmakers advance bill saying Connecticut was not 'first in flight'

status_message: Dimitris Avramopoulos, commissioner for migration for the European Union, said April 14 that over 7,000 migrants have been pulled from the Mediterranean Sea since April 10.
link_name: EU: Over 7,000 people recused from Mediterranean since April 10
Report: EU to file formal antitrust charges against Google

status_message: Apple said April 14 that it had acquired LinX, an Israeli camera technology company. The Wall Street Journal reported, citing unnamed sources, that the deal was worth around $20 million. Founded in 2011, LinX developed camera technology can be used to gauge depth.
link_name: Apple buys Israeli camera tech company for $20M
Lawmakers unveil bill to increase funding for weapons modernization by $1 billion
Kim Jong-un's wife makes first public appearance in months

status_message: Intel on April 14 released its financial results for Q1 2015. The company posted earnings of 41 cents per share on $12.8 billion in revenue. That's in line with Wall Street estimates of 41 cents per share but below estimates of $12.9 billion in revenue. The company blamed flat PC growth for the revenue miss. $INTC
link_name: Intel blames flat PC business for Q1 revenue miss
Study: 29 million US health records improperly accessed from 2010-2013
Obama to remove Cuba from 'State Sponsors of Terrorism' list
Russian bombers intercepted near British airspace
Critics praise improved graphics of PC version of 'Grand Theft Auto V'
22 Colombian army generals investigated in 'false positives' scandal
Two more trade groups sue FCC over net neutrality
Atlanta teachers sentenced in statewide cheating scandal
Nokia confirms talks with network equipment maker Alcatel-Lucent

status_message: The primary suspect in the shooting, Kenneth Stancil, 20, was arrested early April 14 in Daytona Beach, FL following a manhunt, police said. He was approached by officers for violating a city ordinance against sleeping on the beach. He is being held without bail.
link_name: Police arrest ex-student for North Carolina community college shooting

status_message: About 200 Taliban fighters attacked government checkpoints in Badakhshan April 10, the Ministry of Defense told Reuters April 13. At least 18 Afghan police and soldiers were killed, 10 were wounded, and at least 10 more went missing, a spokesman for the Badakhshan governor said.
link_name: Attack in northeast Afghanistan starts Taliban's annual spring offensive

status_message: Five opposition figures and three activist monks arrested in recent months on charges widely considered political were released April 13. Some had been denied bail numerous times. They were set free days after the ruling CPP and opposition CNRP finalized long-negotiated election reforms.
link_name: Cambodian activists released from imprisonment

status_message: The $1.5 billion Emissions Reduction Fund (ERF) launched April 14 with bids mostly from farmers and landfill operators. Projects could include carbon reduction programs such as reforestation of cleared farmland, landfill gas recovery and management of methane from livestock.
link_name: Australia's $1.5 billion fund pays polluters to cut emissions

status_message: China will increase video surveillance, create a "national population information database linked to citizens' ID and credit records," and step up police patrols "in crowded places," especially public transport stations, the central government said April 13, according to state media.
link_name: China to increase widespread video surveillance and measures to track citizens

status_message: A proposed bill would ban the sale, production, distribution and consumption of beverages containing more than 1% alcohol, according to a report from the English-language Jakarta Post April 14. Offenders could face imprisonment of between three months and two years.
link_name: Indonesia lawmakers propose alcohol ban

status_message: Singapore's Transport Ministry submitted a draft law to parliament April 13 to require taxi hailing apps to register with the country's Land Transport Authority before they operate. Among the regulations proposed in the law is a requirement that all drivers be licensed taxi drivers.
link_name: Singapore lawmakers take up proposed regulations for taxi hailing apps

status_message: China's customs office said April 13 that coal imports fell 41.5% in January-March year-over-year, according to Chinese state media. Jiang said China's coal companies had more than $2 billion in financial losses in the first quarter.
link_name: Chinese coal imports drop due to overcapacity and economic slowdown

status_message: Fukushima operator TEPCO on April 13 released the first video from inside of one of the plant's destroyed nuclear reactors since the disaster. A robot took the video from the No. 1 reactor on April 10. Plant technicians lost contact with the robot after a few hours and had to abandon it, the Wall Street Journal reported.
link_name: Robot sends video from inside Fukushima reactor

status_message: HarperCollins said April 13 that it has come to an unspecified multiyear deal with Amazon. Amazon has not yet commented on the deal.
link_name: Amazon and HarperCollins sign publishing deal

status_message: The Beijing government on April 13 set up a WeChat account for people to upload pictures of smokers who violate the indoor ban that starts in June. The city also is asking residents to vote on a hand signal that would tell people to stop smoking.
link_name: Beijing asks citizens to use WeChat to catch smokers
US regulators propose new rules for offshore drilling operations
Alan Turing's secret notebook sells for more than $1 million at auction
IBM's Watson to support health data generated by iOS devices
Executives sentenced to 3 months in jail in egg contamination case
Officer who 'mistakenly' used gun instead of Taser charged with second-degree manslaughter
Illinois county wants former Rep. Aaron Schock to pay for special election
House Democrats introduce anti-LBGT discrimination resolution
'Better Call Saul' highest-rated new cable show of the season
Daredevil Nik Wallenda will walk on 400-foot spinning Orlando Eye

status_message: Nicholas Slatten received a life sentence on April 13 for his first-degree murder conviction. The other three former guards, Dustin Heard, Evan Liberty and Paul Slough, were each sentenced to 30 years. All four men are in their 30s.
link_name: Former Blackwater security guards sentenced for crimes in Iraq

status_message: The U.S. budget deficit increased to $52.9 billion in March, up 19% from March 2014 when it was $36.9 billion, the Treasury Dept. reported April 13.
link_name: US budget deficit running ahead of 2014 pace
Russia lifts ban on delivering S-300 missiles to Iran
Major broadband group files lawsuit against FCC over net neutrality
Trial begins for managers of Turkish mine where 301 died in 2014 disaster

status_message: Capt. Katie Higgins became the first woman to fly with the Blue Angels aviation team, piloting a C-130 known as "Fat Albert" on April 11. Higgins joined the Blue Angels in 2014 and will fly with the team for eight months out of the year.
link_name: First female Blue Angels pilot in 69-year history takes flight
Rate of uninsured Americans drops to 11.9% in first quarter of 2015

status_message: Falling commodity prices meant the government's revenue estimates in Dec. 2014 were short $4.7 billion, the Australian Financial Review reported April 13.
link_name: Iron ore price slump drives $4.7 billion hole in Australian budget

status_message: Jean-Marie Le Pen will not run as a National Front candidate in upcoming regional elections in the southeastern Paca region, he said in an interview with French daily Le Figaro published April 13. He recommended his granddaughter Marion Marechal-Le Pen as the best replacement candidate.
link_name: French far-right party founder Le Pen will not run for office

status_message: Helen Zille, 62, announced April 12 that she was standing down as the leader of South Africa's main opposition party, the Democratic Alliance (DA). Zille is the premier of Western Cape province and a former mayor of Cape Town. Local government elections will occur in 2016 and are expected to be tightly contested.
link_name: South African opposition leader to step down

status_message: Researchers compared adults with a healthy body mass index (BMI) to people who were underweight and to those who were obese. Severely obese people (BMI greater than 40 kg/m2) were 29% less likely to develop dementia than people of normal weight, they reported in research published April 9.
link_name: Researchers find surprising link between obesity and reduced risk of dementia

status_message: Grass, 87, was a novelist, poet and playwright whose works included the novels "The Tin Drum," "The Fisherman and His Wife," and "The Rat." Grass was drafted into the Nazi Germany army in 1944 at the age of 16. He opposed Germany's reunification and was a recent critic of Israel's policies again Iran.
link_name: Writer Gunter Grass, German Nobel laureate, dies

status_message: The corruption trial of Jiang Jiemin, former chairman of China National Petroleum Company, began April 13, Chinese state media said. He is one of the highest ranking officials to reach trial since a corruption crackdown began in 2012-2013. He is accused of accepting bribes, having undeclared assets and abusing power.
link_name: Corruption trial of former oil company chairman begins in China

status_message: Taiwan's bid to become a founding member of the AIIB was rejected, China said April 13. China did not cite a reason. China and Taiwan, however, did not rule out the possibility of Taiwan joining the bank at a later point. It was the first formal announcement that a country was rejected.
link_name: China rejects Taiwan's application to join Asian investment bank

status_message: Anti-Rousseff protesters took to the streets April 12 in dozens of cities. At least 100,000 marched in Sao Paulo. About 75% of Brazilians surveyed in a poll released a day earlier said they supported the protests.
link_name: Brazilian protesters call for impeachment of President Rousseff

status_message: China said April 13 that it changed visa allowances for Shenzhen residents to visit Hong Kong from unlimited multiple-entry to once per week. Although the central government cited overwhelming numbers of tourists as the reason for the limit, many so-called "parallel traders" come from Shenzhen.
link_name: Amid protests in Hong Kong, China limits entry from citizens in nearby Shenzhen

status_message: "Furious 7" opened in China April 12, setting a new single-day box office record there with $68.6 million. It made at least $800.5 million worldwide, which is a franchise record. "Furious 6" totaled $789 million worldwide in 2013. "Furious 7" made $60.6 million in North America during its second weekend to total to $252.2 million there.
link_name: 'Furious 7' passes $800 million in worldwide box office in two weeks

status_message: Analyst Trilby Lundberg reported April 12 that gas prices dropped $0.05 in the past three weeks to an average $2.45 a gallon. The survey, based on data from 2,500 gas stations nationwide, found the highest prices in San Francisco ($3.13 a gallon) and the lowest prices in Charleston, SC ($2.10 a gallon).
link_name: US gas prices fell 5 cents in past 3 weeks

status_message: HBO has confirmed that the first four episodes of "Game of Thrones" season five were leaked online April 11. The new season is set to premiere on April 12. According to piracy-tracking firm Excipio, the episodes have been downloaded at least 1 million times worldwide.
link_name: New episodes from season 5 of 'Game of Thrones' leak online

status_message: Authorities in Mexico arrested Cesar Gastelum Serrano, the Sinaloa Cartel's lead cocaine trafficker on April 11 in Cancun. The U.S. Treasury describes Gastelum Serrano as "one of the most prolific cocaine suppliers for Mexico's Sinaloa Cartel" and says he oversees a network that can move "tons of cocaine per week" across international borders.
link_name: Mexico arrests Sinaloa cartel's lead cocaine trafficker
Four MLB pitchers begin 2015 season suspended for positive drug tests

status_message: Iran's Fars news agency reported April 12 that Jason Rezaian is facing "security" charges stemming from accusations of "espionage" and "acting against national security." The report said Rezaian will stand trial in the Revolutionary Court for selling economic and industrial information to the U.S. amid crippling sanctions.
link_name: Iranian news agency says Washington Post reporter accused of 'espionage'
Former Blackwater security guards, guilty of Iraq crimes, to be sentenced

status_message: Bob Schieffer, moderator of CBS News' Face the Nation, announced on the April 12 edition of the Sunday morning news program that CBS News political director John Dickerson will take over as the show's host. Schieffer, 78, announced on April 8 that he will retire in the summer of 2015.
link_name: CBS names new host of 'Face the Nation'
Two attacks in Sinai hit Egyptian military and police
Kenya calls on UN to close and relocate world's largest refugee camp

status_message: The pope's remarks came during an Armenian-Rite Mass at the Vatican, April 12, attended by the Armenian president and other dignitaries to mark the 100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide.
link_name: Pope calls Ottoman killing of Armenians 'genocide,' angers Turkey

status_message: Unidentified gunmen killed two local security guards, and injured others in an attack on the South Korean Embassy in Tripoli on April 12.
link_name: South Korean embassy in Libya targeted in attack

status_message: U.S. President Barack Obama said April 11 that Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff will visit the White House on June 30, nearly two years after she canceled a planned visit following revelations that her personal communications had been intercepted.
link_name: Brazilian President Rousseff plans US trip 2 years after canceling over NSA spat

status_message: Cooper Union trustees voted in favor of not renewing school president Jamshed Bharucha's contract if the move would help to end the New York attorney general's investigation and pending litigation against the school over its financial situation.
link_name: Cooper Union willing to let president's deal expire if NY attorney general drops probe

status_message: Russian media regulator Roskomnadzor issued an update to its "personal data laws" that makes it illegal to publish Internet memes which depict a public figure contrary to their personality. These images "harm the honor, dignity and business of public figures," Roskomnadzor said.
link_name: Russia bans unflattering Internet memes of public figures

status_message: Yeshi Khando carried out a self-immolation protest in Eastern Tibet, advocacy groups reported April 10. The nun set herself on fire near a police station while shouting, "Tibet needs freedom." Police used extinguishers to put out the flames. Khando is believed to have died. She was the second Tibetan woman to set herself on fire this year.
link_name: Tibetan nun set herself on fire to protest Chinese rule

Obama, Castro meet in first sit-down between US, Cuban leaders in more than half century.

http://circanews.com/news/us-cuba-relations

status_message: Police reported gunshots were fired near the west front of the U.S. Capitol building on April 11. Authorities have confirmed that the shooting was an apparent suicide. Capitol Police are also investigating a suspicious package that was found near the building. All surrounding streets have been closed.
link_name: Gunshots fired near Capitol an apparent suicide, building in lockdown

status_message: U.S. President Obama and Cuban President Raul Castro met on April 11 at the Summit of the Americas in Panama and held the first in-person talks between presidents of the two countries in more than 50 years.
link_name: Summit of the Americas marks turning point in US-Cuba relations

status_message: Mohamad Kamaruzzaman, a senior Islamist party leader who was convicted of war crimes during Bangladesh's 1971 independence war against Pakistan, was executed the evening of April 11 in the capital of Dhaka.
link_name: Bangladesh executes Islamist party leader convicted of war crimes

status_message: Georgia has decided to allow transgender inmates to take hormone therapy. The announcement came on April 10, less than a week after the Justice Dept. came out in support of a lawsuit filed by a transgender inmate. According to Georgia officials the new policy went into effect on April 7.
link_name: Georgia will allow transgender prisoners hormone therapy

status_message: The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office on April 10 invalidated several key claims of a patent that was used to sue several well-known podcasters. The invalidation means that the so-called "podcasting patent" can no longer be used to sue podcasters.
link_name: Patent Office invalidates key claims of 'podcast patent'

status_message: Microsoft told the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit this week that the U.S. government is "rewriting" a 1986 law to suit its current argument against the company. Congress did not write the Electronic Communications Privacy Act "to expand the geographic reach of search warrants," Microsoft claimed.
link_name: Microsoft accuses US of 'rewriting' laws in email turnover case

status_message: A study published in Nature in April says that astronomers have for the first time detected complex organic molecules in another star system some 455 light years away from Earth.
link_name: Scientists find complex organic molecules in another star system for first time

status_message: A court upheld the death sentences against Mohamed Badie and the 13 others April 11. Their cases can still be appealed. The court also sentenced 23 other Muslim Brotherhood members to 25 years in prison, which is considered a life sentence in Egypt.
link_name: Egypt court upholds deaths sentences for Muslim Brotherhood leader, 13 others

Inspection of ice cream factory found no violations after listeria outbreak

The Obamas paid $93,362 in federal taxes for 2014
FCC investigating Verizon 'supercookies' for privacy violations

Cable companies complain to FCC about rising programming costs
Boeing's space capsule tested for water landing
Portion of boat from Japan tsunami washes up on Oregon coast

status_message: On April 10, Jordan Spieth, 21, set a 36-hole scoring record at the Masters. His 14-under 130 total broke Raymond Floyd's 1976 record of 131.
link_name: Jordan Spieth sets 36-hole scoring record at the Masters
Dow back above 18,000
Ubuntu smartphone now available on EU-only online store
San Bernardino sheriff's deputies caught beating a suspect on camera
Man charged with plotting to blow up car bomb at Kansas military base on behalf of Islamic State
Penalty phase of Boston Marathon bomber to begin April 21

status_message: Illinois Governor Bruce Rauner said April 10 that two people had died as a result of tornadoes the previous day. Authorities said 11 other people were injured and that at least 17 structures were destroyed.
