status_message: The Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) asked the Federal Trade Commission April 9 to ensure that Vox Populi, which handles the newly created ".sucks" domain, isn't breaking any laws. Several companies have complained to ICANN about having to register ".sucks" domains to protect their brands.
link_name: FTC asked to review legality of '.sucks' domain

status_message: The Syrian Observatory for Human Rights, a group monitoring the conflict in Syria, said April 10 that the Islamic State militant group launched an attack near Aleppo on April 9. According to a rebel commander cited by Reuters, IS has been calling-in reinforcement in the area and launching attacks against insurgents.
link_name: Report: Islamic State launches attack near Aleppo

status_message: Reuters reported April 9 that Prime Minister Narendra Modi will launch a scheme in May to encourage temples to deposit gold with banks and receive interest payments in return. Ancient temples in the country have collected billions of dollars worth of gold over centuries, securing their stashes in vaults.
link_name: Indian PM Modi wants Hindu temples' gold stashes to fix trade imbalance

status_message: U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry held talks with Cuban Foreign Minister Bruno Rodriguez on April 9 in Panama. It was the highest-level meeting between the two countries in more than half a century. The pair talked for more than two hours and had a "very constructive" discussion, a State Dept. official told Reuters.
link_name: US and Cuba hold highest-level meeting in more than 50 years

status_message: Jean-Marie Le Pen, 86, the party's honorary chairman, sparked outrage with comments that Nazi gas chambers were "a detail" of history in an interview April 2. In another interview days later, he defended French wartime leader and Nazi collaborator Philippe Petain. Marine Le Pen said April 8 she was calling a party meeting in response to her father's comments and would block him from running in December regional elections.
link_name: French far-right leader Marine Le Pen splits with her father, the party's founder

status_message: Despite efforts by locals and the coast guard to return them to the water, the tide pushed more than 130 melon-headed whales back onto the sand, AFP reported. They were washed up along a six-mile stretch of the beach.
link_name: More than 130 melon-headed whales beached in Japan

status_message: CERN said April 10 that the LHC had produced a beam of 6.5 terelectronvolts (TeV) the previous night. The eventual plan is to reach 13 TeV.
link_name: Large Hadron Collider team ramping up beam energy

status_message: South Korean police on April 9 intercepted activists trying to send balloons with leaflets as well as DVDs and USBs with "The Interview," preventing them from launching more. Well-known activist Park Sang-hak said he could try to send the balloons on another day.
link_name: South Korean police stop activists from sending more balloons into North Korea

status_message: The Malaysian parliament approved controversial amendments to the Sedition Act April 10. The law imposes a minimum three-year jail term and allows the government to block online media deemed to be seditious. Criticism of the government and judiciary, however, will no longer be treated as sedition.
link_name: Malaysian parliament approves amendments to controversial sedition act

status_message: On April 10, Australian customs seized 110 kilograms (242.5 pounds) of ivory, valued at $385,000, from a ship on a stopover from southeast Africa en route to Malaysia. The tusks were believed to come from poached elephants in Malawi.
link_name: $385,000 ivory shipment from Africa seized by Australian authorities

status_message: China is considering extending a rail line in Tibet to the Nepalese border by 2020, Wang Mengshu of the Chinese Academy of Engineering said April 8. The route could include "some very long tunnels" through Mt. Everest, according to Wang.
link_name: China considering train tunnel through Mt. Everest

status_message: A record seven University of Kentucky players declared for the NBA draft on April 9: Willie Cauley-Stein, twin brothers Andrew and Aaron Harrison, Dakari Johnson, Devin Booker, Trey Lyles and Karl-Anthony Towns. The previous record for players from a single team declaring was six in 2012, also from Kentucky.
link_name: Record seven Kentucky players opt for NBA draft

status_message: Apple began accepting pre-orders for the Apple Watch at midnight PST on April 10.
link_name: Apple Watch available for pre-order

status_message: Greece made a 460-million-euro ($US497 million) repayment to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on April 9. Greece also made two payments in March, but the payments are draining cash reserves. Euro zone finance ministers meet on April 24 to consider Greek reform proposals to unlock more funds to avoid bankruptcy.
link_name: Greece makes IMF repayment and announces sales of public assets

status_message: The Penn State Board of Trustees voted 18-6 April 9 to settle Sandusky-related litigation for an undisclosed amount of money. One trustee called it an "extraordinary expenditure." The university still faces more litigation related to the abuse.
link_name: Penn State trustee calls latest abuse victim settlement "feeding at the trough"

status_message: A security guard at the U.S. Census Bureau headquarters was shot late April 9 and later died from his wounds, according to police officials. Police said the unnamed suspect was captured after a shootout in Northeast DC.

status_message: John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts announced April 9 that Eddie Murphy, 54, will be honored at its 18th-annual nationally televised gala, set to air October 19. The organization will now contact other actors and comics that "love him" about performing in the show.
link_name: Eddie Murphy to receive 2015 Mark Twain Prize for humor

Wisconsin man charged for trying to join Islamic State
Amazon files first-ever lawsuit over fake product reviews

status_message: Durst pleaded not guilty on April 9 to illegal possession of a firearm by a felon, and illegal possession of a firearm in the presence of a controlled substance. Durst would face between five and 20 years in prison if convicted on both counts. A judge denied bail.
link_name: Robert Durst pleads not guilty to gun charges

status_message: The number of people seeking unemployment benefits in the U.S. rose 14,000 to a seasonally adjusted 281,000, the Labor Department said April 9. The four-week average, a less volatile measure, dropped by 3,000 to 282,250 -- the lowest level for the average since June 2000.
link_name: New claims for jobless benefits at 15-year low

status_message: LinkedIn said April 9 that it had agreed to acquire Lynda dot com in a deal that's 52% cash and 48% stock. The deal is expected to close in the second quarter of 2015. Most Lynda dot com employees will move to LinkedIn after the deal closes.
link_name: LinkedIn acquires educational website Lynda.com for $1.5 billion
LinkedIn acquires educational website Lynda.com

status_message: Judges at the UN International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia (ICTY) dismissed most of Tolimir's 26 grounds for appeal on April 8.
link_name: War crimes tribunal upholds life sentence for Bosnian Serb general for genocide

status_message: The U.S. State Dept. approved a $57 million sale of Lockheed Martin Hellfire II missiles to Egypt as well as associated equipment, parts and training, the U.S. military's Defense Security Cooperation Agency said April 8. The agency notified Congress, which needs to approve the possible sale.
link_name: US State Department approves Hellfire missiles sale to Egypt

status_message: The UN said April 8 that it needs $111 million more in 2015 for humanitarian programs in North Korea. It said there is "grave concern" over food security. The funds will pay for projects in food and agriculture, health and nutrition, and water and sanitation.
link_name: UN asks for funds to address North Korean food and agriculture issues

status_message: The journal Nature reported April 8 that successful trial of two new vaccines on monkeys at the University of Texas opens the way for human trials. Vaccinated monkeys did not become ill when injected with the new Makona strain of Ebola. Researchers improved the vaccine currently being tested in Liberia.
link_name: Ebola vaccine successful in trials on monkeys

status_message: The Australian government released an energy policy white paper on April 8. It predicts Australia's export earnings from energy resources will grow from $55 billion in 2012-13 to $87.6 billion in the next 5 years. The forecast is based on expectations that global energy demand will increase in the coming decades.
link_name: Australian energy policy sticks to fossil fuel investments

status_message: North Korea April 8 said that Mexico has illegally detained a freighter stuck on a reef in July 2014. However, a member of the UN's commission monitoring North Korean sanctions said "evidence is overwhelming" that the ship is owned by a sanctioned North Korean shipping company.
link_name: North Korea demands Mexico return detained ship

China requiring Tibetan temples to fly national flag
Emails show former Oregon first lady acted as if 'deputy governor'
Despite education advances, US women more likely to live in poverty than men
Greed, corruption blamed for Russian trawler accident that killed 56

Twitter removes Discover tab, puts greater emphasis on trending topics
Zynga founder Mark Pincus reclaims CEO post

link_name: Dzhokhar Tsarnaev found guilty of Boston Marathon bombing, faces death penalty

Durst would face between five and 20 years in prison if convicted on both counts. A judge denied bail.
link_name: Robert Durst indicted by Louisiana grand jury on gun charges

status_message: Both HBO and Showtime, which have the exclusive rights to Pacquiao and Mayweather fights, have confirmed that the pay-per-view fight will cost $89.95 in SD. Individual cable providers can set their own price for the HD version, though it's expected to cost $99.95 in most cases.
link_name: Mayweather-Pacquiao pay-per-view price starts at $89.95

status_message: A NATO soldier was killed and two U.S. troops were injured after an Afghan soldier opened fire, police and NATO said. The Afghan soldier, who was killed in the ensuing firefight, started shooting soon after a U.S. Embassy official departed the provincial governor's compound. The NATO troops were from the U.S., police said.
link_name: Afghan soldier kills American soldier in insider attack

status_message: Air France canceled hundreds of short- and medium-haul flights due to an air traffic controllers strike, but said in a statement April 7 that it "expects to operate almost all its long-haul flights." easyJet cancelled 118 flights, the Independent reported April 8. Ryanair said it canceled more than 250 flights on April 8.
link_name: Hundreds of flights canceled due to French air traffic controllers' strike

status_message: Mario Steven Ambarita ran to a Boeing 737-800 and climbed into the wheel well as it was preparing for take off. He staggered out of the space after it landed at Jakarta's Soekarno-Hatta airport an hour later. He required medical treatment.
link_name: Indonesian stowaway survives flight hiding in landing gear

status_message: Taiwan's Water Resources Agency will ration water to Taoyuan, New Taipei City and Hsinchu county, which surround the capital of Taipei. The reservoir that feeds the areas is at less than 25% capacity after the lowest rainfall since 1947.
link_name: Taiwan rationing water to at least 800,000 households

status_message: The Federal Court of Australia in an April 7 ruling ordered six ISPs to hand over the names and addresses of customers connected to 4,726 IP addresses. The ISPs had opposed a request by Dallas Buyers Club LLC and Voltage Pictures LLC for details of people accused of sharing the film online.
link_name: ISPs in Australia and Singapore ordered to hand over details of film downloaders

status_message: Australian Prime Minister Tony Abbott announced on April 8 that the government formed a special task force on crystal meth. The task force head, former Victoria state police commissioner Ken Lay, will coordinate local, state and federal agencies to fight the use, sale, manufacture and importation of it.
link_name: Australia forms task force to tackle crystal meth epidemic

status_message: At least 549 people have been killed in Yemen, including 74 children, since the start of airstrikes, the UN said April 7. About 100,000 people have fled their homes. Medical supply deliveries have been delayed. Food, water and electricity shortages are occurring nationwide.
link_name: US steps up Saudi arms shipments as Yemen on the verge of humanitarian collapse

status_message: Japan's Nikkei share average closed at a 15-year high April 8 at at 19,723.42. The market rallied amid speculation of increased stimulus packages in Japan and China and that the U.S. Federal Reserve may not raise rates immediately. Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng Index was up 602.06 points, or 2.38%, by midday April 8 to trade at its highest point since May 2008.
link_name: Japanese and Hong Kong stock indexes hit multi-year highs

status_message: Fifteen state police officers were killed and five injured when they were ambushed by members of the "New Generation" cartel, Mexican prosecutors said. The attack was one of the deadliest on police in nearly five years. At least six other officers were killed in the state in the last month.
link_name: Fifteen Mexican police officers killed in suspected cartel ambush

status_message: Xiaomi is running a multi-country "Mi Fanfest" sale April 8. Xiaomi VP Hugo Barra said the company had sold more than a million phones in less than 3.5 hours.
link_name: Xiaomi sells more than a million phones in a few hours during sale

status_message: The U.S. has "expedited weapons deliveries" and "increased intelligence" to Saudi Arabia, U.S. Deputy Sec. of State Antony Blinken said April 7. The weapons include existing orders and "some new requirements" said the Pentagon. Blinken also warned of the consequences of "unintended civilian casualties."
link_name: US steps up Saudi arms shipments as Yemen on the verge of humanitarian collapse

status_message: Ferguson's City Council gained two black members, Wesley Bell and Ella Jones, in the April 7 election. Bell was elected to the ward that covers the area where Michael Brown was killed. Before the election, the mayor and 5 of 6 members were white. Despite heavy rain, 29% of voters went to the polls. Typical turnout is 12%.
link_name: Ferguson sees high voter turnout in election of 2 new black city council members

status_message: Jean Germain, 67, was found dead near his home on April 7; his lawyer said he left a suicide note. Germain served as mayor of Tours for nearly two decades, ending in 2014. He was facing trial over a scandal in which he, along with an aide, stood accused of mishandling public funds.
link_name: French senator found dead ahead of corruption trial

status_message: The UConn women's team defeated Notre Dame in the final on April 7. They led at the half and pulled away as the game came wound down to win 63-53.
link_name: UConn wins third straight NCAA women's basketball championship

status_message: With more than 70% of the vote counted late April 7, the Chicago Tribune reported Mayor Rahm Emanuel held 55.8% of the unofficial vote to Jesus "Chuy" Garcia's 44.2%. Garcia called Emanuel to concede, according to the former challenger's campaign manager.
link_name: Rahm Emanuel reelected as Chicago mayor

link_name: Vivendi confirms talks with Orange over Dailymotion

Trace amounts of radioactive isotopes cesium-134 and cesium-137 were found on the shoreline of the small town of Ucluelet in British Columbia, Canada, scientists from the Massachusetts-based Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution said. The amounts detected are well below levels of concern for humans and marine life.

status_message: FedEx and TNT Express announced in Amsterdam April 7 that FedEx made a $4.8 billion offer for TNT, or a 33% premium on TNT's April 2 share price.
link_name: FedEx offers to buy Dutch shipping company TNT Express for $4.8 billion

status_message: Former Nauru mental health and social workers accused the Australian government of tolerating sexual and physical abuse of women and children on Nauru, an open letter published on April 7 said. Immigration Minister Peter Dutton's office did not immediately comment on it, Reuters reported.
link_name: Australian government accused of tolerating abuse of asylum seekers in Nauru

status_message: Rutgers informed the leaders of its 86 fraternities and sororities of the ban, campus officials said April 6. It does not apply to end-of-year formals and events where a licensed third-party vendor serves alcohol.
link_name: Rutgers University suspends fraternity and sorority parties

status_message: Chinese state media on April 7 quoted a report in a military newspaper saying a brigade of the country's armed forces, the PLA, instructed spouses of officers on avoiding leaking secrets on WeChat. The report also said the PLA issued rules in February on online behavior, including banning "online chatting."
link_name: China warns military spouses against leaking secrets on WeChat

status_message: The NBA and the International Basketball Federation will hold a camp for male and female players April 23-26 in Havana. The event will mark the first visit by a U.S. pro sports league since the thaw in relations. Retired NBA players Steve Nash and Dikembe Mutombo will join former WNBA star Ticha Penicheiro at the camp.
link_name: NBA to hold development camp in Cuba

status_message: The Canadian government approved 243.5 million Canadian dollars ($195.12) over 10 years for the TMT on April 6, following long delays. The observatory's 184-foot movable steel dome will be built in Canada. The other major backers of the $1.5 billion project are the Univ. of California, CalTech, China, and India.
link_name: Canadian government approves funds for Hawaii's Thirty Meter Telescope

status_message: Disney will release all six "Star Wars" movies in digital HD with bonus materials for download on April 10. Pre-orders for the movies started April 6. Individual movies cost $19.99 and the complete set costs $99.99. The movies are available for pre-order on iTunes, Xbox, Amazon, Google Play and other services.
link_name: All "Star Wars" movies to be released in digital HD

status_message: Starbucks said April 6 it will pay for up to 4 years of undergraduate online tuition at ASU, up from 2 years. The company predicts 25,000 employees will receive degrees through the program by 2025, and that it is spending an additional $250 million on the extended coverage.
link_name: Starbucks extends online college tuition payments to 4 years

status_message: Duke won the 2015 NCAA men's basketball championship over Wisconsin 68-63 April 6 in a back-and-forth game in Indianapolis. The win is Duke's fifth national championship, with all coming under head coach Mike Krzyzewski.
link_name: Duke wins NCAA men's basketball championship
Minnesota turkey farms continue to battle deadly bird flu
Arkansas' Gertrude Weaver, world's oldest person for 6 days, dies at 116
Cuban trade minister says US steps to ease embargo are 'insufficient'

status_message: Iraqi forensic specialists, on April 6, began to inspect 12 mass graves found in the now liberated city of Tikrit. The excavation could uncover up to 1,700 bodies of Shiite soldiers who were killed by Islamic State (IS) militants after they swept through Iraq in June 2014.
link_name: Mass graves in Iraq may total 1,700 victims
Appeals court asks US government to explain mobile phone 'kill switch' program
New York hometown of Lucille Ball wants questionable statue replaced
Judge finds Chapel Hill shooter eligible for death penalty in triple murder case
Report: servicemen question women's abilities in special ops roles
New rules for British pensioners take effect
Judge gives NY woman permission to serve husband divorce papers via Facebook

status_message: All testimony in the trial concluded on April 6. The defense rested after calling three witnesses to the stand, including a pharmacologist who testified that PCP can cause "violent or aggressive behavior." Two of Hernandez's accomplices, Ernest Wallace and Carlos Ortiz, have been linked to PCP use during the weekend of the murder.
link_name: Closing arguments to begin in Aaron Hernandez case
Basketball Hall of Fame announces 11 inductees including Dikembe Mutombo
India to monitor air pollution in ten cities
Jury hears closing arguments in Boston Marathon trial

status_message: Kyushu University, a Japanese medical school, opened a new history museum on its campus April 4 and one exhibit acknowledges a dark incident from its past: the cruel and gruesome medical experiments it conducted on U.S. prisoners of war during World War II. The school has avoided publicly discussing the incident until now.
link_name: Museum in Japan displays evidence of live experiments used on American POWs

status_message: The Thailand-based Assistance Association for Political Prisoners (AAPP) said April 4 that it holds records of 172 political prisoners that remain behind bars. A further 296 political activists were awaiting trial, it said.
link_name: Myanmar NGO says 172 political prisoners remain behind bars

status_message: An April 4 El Pais article cites extracts from a Spanish military report that accuses Israel of intentionally firing on the UN. Shells at first landed 500 meters from a UN post before the Israeli military "corrected the trajectory" toward it, the report said. The article also cites a UN report that Israel warned UN troops not to venture out before shelling started.
link_name: Israel targeted UN troops in Lebanon, report says

status_message: An April 4 Washington Post report with interviews of former Iraqi army intelligence officer Hassan Dulaimi, analysts and an ex-IS fighter says members of Saddam Hussein's Baath regime are leading IS behind the scenes. It cites the de-Baathification law passed by Paul Bremer, who ruled Iraq  in 2003-2004 during the U.S. occupation, as the initial spark that eventually lead them to IS.
link_name: Saddam Hussein's ousted officers leading Islamic State's shadow networks

status_message: Most of the 24,000 people evacuated on April 4 from the Aurora province returned home on April 5 when the typhoon was downgraded to a tropical storm. Two men drowned at a beach resort and another in a river on April 3-4 but authorities have not determined if the deaths were related to the storm.
link_name: People return home after tropical storm passes over Philippines

status_message: "Little Foot," a 3.67-million-year-old skeleton in South Africa and not "Lucy" from Ethiopia (3.2 million years old) is now considered the earliest known human ancestor. Research published April 1 describes a method that measures a hominid skeleton's exposure to cosmic rays, which dated Little Foot.
link_name: South Africa's "Little Foot" predates Ethiopia's "Lucy"

status_message: A study published in April in Nature by Collins and two others describes their invention of the "ankle exo," a one-pound lower-leg exoskeleton that is completely mechanical.
link_name: Motor-less exoskeleton ankle brace developed

status_message: Indonesia's State Administrative Court said on April 6 that it had no jurisdiction to rule on a clemency decision by the country's president. It dismissed what is believed to be the final possible appeal for Chan and Sukumaran.
link_name: 'Bali 9' final execution appeal denied in Indonesia

status_message: Lynch April 5 said on Twitter that he will not participate in the nine-episode revival of "Twin Peaks" planned for 2016. He said he had been negotiating the financials with Showtime for 16 months, but "not enough money was offered to do the script the way I felt it needed to be done."
link_name: David Lynch says he will not direct new "Twin Peaks"

status_message: The Supreme Court on April 6 upheld the death penalty of Mohamad Kamaruzzaman, assistant secretary general of the Jamaat-e-Islami party. It was Kamaruzzamen's final appeal. He was found guilty of war crimes in May 2014.
link_name: Bangladesh Islamist party leader war crimes death sentence upheld

status_message: Xue, 50, was released from prison in Beijing and had immediately flown to the U.S., where he is now, U.S.-based human rights group Dui Hua said April 3. The U.S. Embassy in Beijing has not yet confirmed his release.
link_name: US man released after 8 years in Chinese prison for buying commercial database

status_message: Greece will make its next IMF payment of 460 million euros ($505 million) as scheduled on April 9, Greek Finance Minister Yanis Varoufakis confirmed during meetings in Washington DC, according to International Monetary Fund (IMF) chief Christine Lagarde on April 5.
link_name: IMF chief says Greece will meet deadline on next payment

status_message: Paul sent out a tweet with a video April 5 that essentially confirmed he will officially announce his presidential run on April 7.
link_name: Rand Paul to announce 2016 US presidential run April 7

status_message: Rolling Stone on April 5 released the findings of an independent review conducted by the Columbia Graduate School of Journalism that was launched in Dec. 2014 after controversy erupted over the article. The magazine officially retracted the article after the report was released.
link_name: Rolling Stone retracts University of Virginia rape article

status_message: "Furious 7" roared to the top of the box office in its April 3-5 opening weekend, netting $143.6 million. That bests the previous high for an April debut, set by "Captain America: The Winter Soldier" with $95 million in 2014. "Furious 7" also made $240.4 million internationally in its opening weekend.
link_name: 'Furious 7' dominates weekend box office with $143.6 million
French investigators release probable cause of 2014 Air Algerie crash
Red Cross says it's been given permission to deliver aid in Yemen
New research shows Anne Frank died earlier than previously thought

status_message: Palestinian Authority President Mahmoud Abbas said April 5 that Israel had released a portion of tax revenues, but ordered the funds returned over deductions made to pay Israeli utilities companies. The Israeli government didn't immediately comment.
link_name: Abbas rejects tax revenues transferred by Israel over deductions

status_message: Four Ukrainian soldiers were killed April 4 when their vehicle was hit by pro-Russian rebel shells, Ukraine's interior ministry said. The forces were crossing a bridge in the government-held town of Schastye when they were hit.
link_name: Four Ukrainian soldiers killed near Luhansk

status_message: Delivering his "Urbi et Orbi" ("to the city and the world") address on April 5, Pope Francis called for peace in Iraq and Syria, as well as the Holy Land, Ukraine, Libya, Yemen, Nigeria, Sudan and the DR Congo.
link_name: Pope Francis calls for peace in Iraq, Syria in Easter message

status_message: The Icelandic ship Landhelgisgaeslan arrived at the Sicilian port of Pozzallo after rescuing 318 migrants, Italian media reported April 4.
link_name: EU patrol rescues 318 migrants off Sicily

status_message: Islamic State militants and fighters from Al-Qaeda's Syrian arm, the Nusra Front, seized control of 90% of the Yarmouk refugee camp near Damascus on April 3. According to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights, nearly 18,000 Syrian and Palestinian refugees live in the camp.
link_name: Islamic State has taken control of 90% of refugee camp near Damascus

status_message: Following a Freedom of Information request, officials in Ferguson released racially charged emails that were circulated by three city employees between 2008-2011. All three lost their jobs when the Dept. of Justice released its report in March.
link_name: Racist emails from former Ferguson officials released

status_message: A group of monks in northern Iraq saved a library of historic Christian manuscripts dating back half a millennium. They were located in the Mar Matti monastery, which was on the path of advancing Islamic State forces.
link_name: Historic Christian manuscripts saved from Islamic State militants

status_message: Arizona Gov. Doug Ducey in late March signed into law a bill that requires doctors to inform patients who take an abortion pill that there is a hormone treatment to reverse the effects of the abortion pill. The new law makes Arizona the first state in the nation with such a requirement.
link_name: Arizona to require doctors to inform patients of abortion-reversal option

status_message: With his visit to Utah on April 2-3, President Obama has traveled to 49 U.S. states since taking office. South Dakota remains the only state not visited during his presidency. Obama could become the fourth president to visit all 50 states. Richard Nixon, George H.W. Bush and Bill Clinton also accomplished the feat.
link_name: Obama visits 49th state as president, only South Dakota remains

status_message: Cuban media reported April 4 that Fidel Castro made a public appearance on March 30, greeting a delegation of Venezuelans while seated in his vehicle. It wasn't clear why five days passed before reports emerged about the encounter, which was Castro's first outing in public since Jan. 2014.
link_name: Fidel Castro makes first public appearance in over a year

status_message: Sotheby's announced on April 3 that it will auction off six paintings by French impressionist painter Claude Monet on May 5 in New York. The works could fetch between $78 million and $110 million.
link_name: Sotheby's to auction 6 Monet paintings, expected to fetch up to $110M

status_message: Beijing police said April 4 that more than 30 taxi drivers from the northwest province of Heilongjiang took pesticide and laid down in the middle of one of Beijing's busiest commercial walking streets. They were taken to the hospital but it is unclear what their conditions are.
link_name: 30 Chinese taxi drivers drink poison on Beijing commercial street
Prosecutors move to reject Ross Ulbricht's request for new Silk Road trial

status_message: West Virginia Governor Earl Ray Tomblin on April 3 signed a law that will prohibit Tesla Motors from directly selling cars in the state. While the state is not a major market in itself, as Automotive New points out, it borders a number of states and is close to Washington, D.C.
link_name: West Virginia bans direct Tesla sales to consumers
Mourning and outrage in Kenya after university attack
'Revenge porn' site operator sentenced to 18 years in prison
Future Microsoft browsers will turn off 'Do Not Track' by default
Philadelphia mother arrested for trying to join Islamic State
Report: NFL to name first full-time female official

status_message: Fiat Chrysler's sales grew 1.7% in March, its 60th consecutive month of year-on-year sales growth. Ford's sales slipped 3.4% and GM's sales fell 2.4%. Ford is still struggling to ramp production on its newest F-150 model truck, one of its most popular vehicles.
link_name: Fiat Chrysler sales up for 60 consecutive months
Tigers Woods to play in the Masters
Report: Clinton campaign secures Brooklyn Heights headquarters

status_message: Suspected Al-Qaeda fighters stormed a military base in the port city of Mukalla, killing five soldiers and raiding its munition stores. Soldiers fled the base after the attack. Local residents and officials said Al-Qaeda fighters also raided banks, government buildings, and a local broadcasting station.
link_name: Suspected Al-Qaeda fighters take army base in east Yemen
Google releases tool to run Android apps in Chrome browser
Hundreds of Guatemalans sue Johns Hopkins for STD infections

status_message: A report by the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency, released April 3, found that law enforcement lacked "weapons discipline" during the manhunt of Boston bombing suspects Tamerlan and Dzhokhar Tsarnaev.
link_name: Report finds police lacked weapons discipline in Boston bombing manhunt
Alabama man freed from death row after 30 years
Indonesian officials rescue over 300 fishermen in Thai slavery probe

status_message: LGBT group Deti 404 will face trial April 6 on accusations of violating the propaganda law, HRW said April 3. The UN Human Rights Committee called on Russia a day earlier to repeal laws that discriminate against LGBT people.
link_name: Russian LGBT group to face trial over 'propaganda' law

status_message: In a report released April 2, Oxfam accused the IFC of failing to perform due diligence and manage risks in many of its investments in financial intermediaries. The report says "shocking abuses" have taken place as a result of projects financed by third-party lenders through IFC investments.
link_name: World Bank accused by Oxfam of rights abuses for its investments

status_message: Thai Prime Minister Prayuth Chan-o-cha issued a warning to critical media outlets on April 3, AFP reported. He has faced fresh criticism after replacing martial law on April 1 with powers that continue to give him absolute authority.
link_name: Thai prime minister threatens to shut down critical media

status_message: The U.S. added 125,000 jobs in March, the Labor Dept. reported April 3. Economists had expected the country to add 245,000. The overall unemployment rate remained unchanged at 5.5%.
link_name: US adds 126,000 jobs in March, lowest since December 2013

status_message: U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Anne Richard told reporters April 2 that the U.S. has admitted 648 Syrian refugees in four years. She expects 1,000-2,000 to be accepted by September and then more in 2016. The U.S. is focused on "very vulnerable cases," she said.
link_name: US has accepted hundreds of Syrian refugees in four years

status_message: The UK spied on the Argentine leadership and military between 2008 and 2011, according to a report published April 2 in The Intercept, which cited documents provided by National Security Agency whistleblower Edward Snowden.
link_name: UK spied on Argentina over Falkland Islands: report

status_message: Malaysian cartoonist Zulkiflee Anwar Ulhaque, or Zunar, was charged April 3 with nine counts of sedition. He had posted bail, but was re-arrested soon after for a photo posted to his fan club's Facebook page, his lawyer said.
link_name: Malaysian cartoonist charged with sedition for tweets

status_message: The second black box, which is used to record technical flight data, further confirmed that Lubitz intentionally crashed the plane, French investigators said April 3.
link_name: Second black box confirms Germanwings copilot intentionally crashed plane, prosecutors say

status_message: A court issued a non-bailable warrant for Musharraf's arrest if he failed to appear on April 27 on charges for the murder of cleric Abdul Rasheed Ghazi and his mother. They were among 91 civilians killed in the 2007 Lal Masjid crackdown, an 8-day siege on a mosque accused of supporting the Taliban.
link_name: Warrant issued for Pakistan's Musharraf to appear in murder trial

status_message: A Karachi court issued a non-bailable warrant for Musharraf's arrest if he failed to appear on April 27 on charges for the murder of cleric Abdul Rasheed Ghazi and his mother. They were among 91 civilians killed in the 2007 Lal Masjid crackdown, an 8-day siege on a pro-Taliban mosque.
link_name: Warrant issued for Pakistan's Musharraf to appear in murder trial

status_message: The "Houston Express" German container ship spotted a man sitting on the hull of an overturned sailboat, and pulled him to safety. A Coast Guard helicopter picked up the man and transported him to Sentara Norfolk General Hospital in Virginia.
link_name: South Carolina man rescued after being missing at sea for 66 days

status_message: The U.S. Marshals Service said April 2 it is offering $5,000 for information leading to the arrest of Paul Ceglia. Ceglia is facing fraud charges for allegedly faking documents that showed he owned part of Facebook. Marshals say he disappeared with his family from their Corning, New York home on March 6.
link_name: US Marshals searching for Paul Ceglia, man accused of fraud in Facebook ownership lawsuit
Study: Ocean ecosystems took 1,000 years to recover from past climate change
Netflix renews 'House of Cards' for fourth season
Sprint settles $131 million shareholder lawsuit

status_message: UK political leaders face off in televised debate
link_name: UK political leaders face off in televised debate
Former Toronto mayor Rob Ford to have cancerous tumor removed
Defying national policy, NY Boy Scouts hire gay Eagle Scout as camp leader
Airbnb expands lodging to 1,000 homes in Cuba
Snapchat locks out third-party apps to enhance user safety

status_message:
Arkansas lawmakers gave final approval to a revised version of the religious freedom bill on April 2 that is meant to address concerns of possible discrimination of LGBT people. Gov. Asa Hutchinson promptly signed the bill after it was approved by state lawmakers.

Lawmakers in Indiana also gave final approval to amend the contentious religious freedom bill, sending the bill to Gov. Mike Pence's desk for a signature. The new language clarifies businesses cannot discriminate on the basis of sexual orientation.

Closing with pathologist testimony, prosecution rests in Aaron Hernandez trial
Sen. Menendez pleads not guilty to corruption charges
Uber appoints chief security officer following data breach

status_message: EU, Iran to read joint statement on progress of nuclear talks around 1pm EST

A group of Egyptians listed as witnesses of the death of activist Shaimaa El-Sabagh will face a trial starting April 4 for protesting illegally. They include members of El-Sabagh's opposition party and a prominent lawyer who said she was passing by when El-Sabagh was shot. Dozens of lawyers signed up for their defense by April 1.
link_name: Egyptian witnesses to protester death to face trial for protesting

status_message: Israel's attorney general on April 1 approved deporting Eritrean and Sudanese asylum seekers to Rwanda and Uganda. A report published a month earlier by rights groups criticized sending asylum seekers there because they "have no legal status or rights and therefore cannot survive in these states."
link_name: Israel approves deporting African asylum seekers

status_message: State-backed newspaper the Global New Light of Myanmar reported April 2 that Myanmar hit a trade deficit of more than $4.9 billion for the 2014 fiscal year that ended March 31. Total trade volume was more than $27.7 billion. Reuters reported that the 2013 deficit was $2.6 billion, citing a senior Commerce Ministry official.
link_name: Myanmar trade deficit jumps as economy expands

status_message: Suspected Al-Qaeda fighters stormed a central prison, freeing at up to 300 people, local police and officials said. Khaled Batarfi, a prominent Al-Qaeda figure, is believed to be among the prisoners freed. The prison break occurred several days after Saudi Arabia launched airstrikes in Yemen.
link_name: Prison break in Yemen by suspected Al-Qaeda fighters frees as many as 300 people

status_message: Billboard reported April 2 that the highest bid for the secret album so far was $5 million. Details of the eventual sale will be announced on a microsite after the auction closes, Forbes reported in January.
link_name: Wu-Tang album that can't be sold for 88 years gets $5 million bid

status_message: The South Korean government said March 31-April 1 that it will compensate families of the students who died with $380,000 and families of the teachers who died with $700,000. Other families of deceased victims will receive up to $550,000 each, and survivors of the disaster will also get compensation.
link_name: South Korea sets compensation for ferry sinking victims

status_message: The 337-foot-long Dalniy Vostok sank 205 miles west of Krutogorovsky. Emergency officials said the vessel didn't send a distress signal. 63 people have been rescued and 54 are confirmed dead. The remaining missing crew members were likely inside the ship as it sank. 78 of the crew were Russian, with others from Latvia, Ukraine, Myanmar and Vanuatu.
link_name: At least 54 dead after Russian trawler with 132 crew sinks in Sea of Okhotsk
German cabinet passes anti-fracking draft law
4 killed, 300 evacuated after oil platform fire in the Gulf of Mexico
KBR to pay fine for violating whistleblower protection rule
Justice Dept. won't charge former IRS official Lois Lerner with contempt
British law student sentenced to 42 months for bomb manual
New Jersey Sen. Menendez indicted on corruption charges
HBO to be added to Sling TV service

status_message: On March 31, the federal judge presiding over the FTC's lawsuit against AT&T ruled against AT&T's request to dismiss the lawsuit. The request for dismissal was first filed in January, with AT&T claiming that the FTC did not have the legal authority to regulate how it manages its network.
link_name: Judge rejects AT&T's request to dismiss FTC data throttling lawsuit

status_message: Libya's General National Congress (GNC), the country's rival parliament based in Tripoli, removed Omar Al-Hassi as prime minister on March 31. The decision followed an investigation that found he exaggerated government revenues, a GNC spokesman said.
link_name: Libya's Tripoli-based parliament fires prime minister

status_message: Islamic State fighters took over a "large part" of the camp after clashes with rival Islamic battalions and a Palestinian group also opposed to President Bashar Al-Assad's regime, a UK-based observatory said. The regime was shelling the camp and a southern neighborhood from which the group likely entered.
link_name: Islamic State seizes decimated Palestinian refugee camp in Damascus

status_message: Philippine President Benigno Aquino instructed government disaster agencies to stock up on relief supplies and be on alert for the Easter weekend. Thousands of people embark on religious pilgrimages or holiday tours in the mostly Catholic nation.
link_name: Philippines prepares for Typhoon Maysak to hit on Easter

status_message: A federal judge approved a plan March 31 to have 1,740 RadioShack stores co-branded with Sprint. Standard General supports the move. The $160 million plan should allow around 7,500 RadioShack employees to keep their jobs. Sprint products will take up about a third of the floor space at the locations.
link_name: US court approves plan to brand RadioShack stores with Sprint

status_message: Thousands of workers at a Taiwanese-owned footwear factory that manufactures international brands including Nike and Adidas continued to strike for a sixth straight day on April 1. The strike at the Pou Yuen factory has been one of largest and longest ever in Vietnam, the BBC reported.
link_name: Thousands strike at Vietnamese footwear factory in rare anti-government protest

status_message: Palestine formally joined the ICC on April 1. The court could investigate issues including the civilian toll of conflicts and Jewish settlements on occupied Palestinian land. A Human Rights Watch lawyer praised the move, saying any investigation "is not in the hands of the Palestinians or the Israelis."
link_name: Palestine officially joins the International Criminal Court

status_message: Hormone and chemical exposure affect fish offspring for generations, a March 30 study in Scientific Reports found. Up to 68% of the hormones in commonly used birth control pills are released from women's bodies into waterways, the study said. Male bass in the U.S. have developed ovaries, effectively switching sexes.
link_name: Flushed birth control and plastics disrupt fish fertility

status_message: Representatives of 16 major ethnic rebel groups signed a draft ceasefire agreement with the government on March 31 after two years of talks. President Thein Sein has prioritized efforts to end hostilities with the groups that have taken up arms since independence. Kokang rebels did not participate.
link_name: Myanmar government signs draft peace deal with ethnic rebel groups

status_message: Ludhiana police arrested another four undocumented migrants from Bangladesh on March 31. The Times of India reports their names as: Salim, Habibul, Aslam Sohad and Jinnat, all aged in their late 20s.
link_name: Indian authorities arrest four suspects for rape of nun

status_message: The chemicals used to replace BPA may be just as disruptive to the body's hormone system as BPA, according to an analysis of 32 studies conducted over the last 15 years. Bisphenol S and F, known as BPS and BPF, are "structural analogs" to BPA and interact with the body in a similar way, according to researchers.
link_name: Replacements for BPA in plastics cause similar disruptions to hormones

status_message: China's State Council said the country will spend the three years reviewing laws and regulations to determine which are obsolete, according to Chinese state media April 1. It is unclear if the purge will include laws and regulations at all levels of government.
link_name: China to abolish out-of-date laws

status_message: The Oversight and Government Reform committee subpoenaed two Secret Service agents March 31 in connection to the incident where two agents hit a security barrier. It's unknown if the subpoena is for the two agents who were involved.
link_name: Secret Service agents subpoenaed by House committee

status_message: "The truth of the matter is we have absolutely no system in place to respond. None‚Ä¶ It tugs at my heart. This is a massive kill-off, and we have absolutely no federal mechanism to respond," Rep. Denny Heck (D-WA). Heck introduced a bill called the Marine Disease Emergency Act of 2015 that would appropriate $12 million for federal agencies to research and respond to the disease. The bill would also create a marine disease emergency fund that would accept public donations.
link_name: With millions of sea stars mysteriously dying, lawmakers seek intervention

status_message: Farmland prices in Iowa are down 11% in the last year according to the Iowa Realtors Land Institute March 31. The price of corn has dropped roughly 50% since 2012, pulling down land values with it. Iowa is the top U.S. corn and soybean state and its land values are seen as an agriculture economic bellwether by banks and policymakers.
link_name: Falling grain prices drive down Iowa farmland prices 11%
Obama renews military aid for Egypt
Redesigned Samsung Galaxy S6 earns positive reviews
Verizon now lets customers opt out of mobile tracking 'supercookies'

status_message: Sen. Elizabeth Warren (D-MA) said during an appearance on NBC's Today show on March 31, "I am not running and I'm not going to run." The comments come as liberal groups continue to push an effort to compel Warren to run in 2016. The group "Run Warren Run" will be hosting an even in New York City on April 20.
link_name: Warren says she's 'not going to run' for president

status_message: The father of the gunman who killed four teens and himself in Oct. 2014, was arrested March 31 for unlawful possession of firearms. The handgun used in the shooting was one of five purchased between Jan. 2013 and July 2014 when the shooter's father was under a permanent order that prevented him from possessing firearms.
link_name: Father of Washington state high school shooter arrested on gun charges
Report: Cablevision to bid on NY Daily News
Title and release date announced for latest 'Dragon Tattoo' sequel

status_message: The defense team said they had no additional witnesses to call to the stand on March 31. Four people testified in total, including a fingerprint expert who said items from the investigation including a jar of nails, two rolls of tape and a pressure cooker lid bore the fingerprints of Tamerlan Tsarnaev, but not his younger brother.
link_name: Defense rests in Boston Marathon trial, closing statements due April 6
Iran nuclear talks to continue past deadline
Shootout leaves 2 Istanbul hostage takers dead, captive wounded
Congressman wants to interview Clinton by May 1 regarding Benghazi emails
80% of bodies found in Mexico's mass graves since 2006 still unidentified
Germanwings co-pilot disclosed mental health issues in 2009, Lufthansa says

status_message: Lufthansa on March 31 said that Lubitz told the airline about the depressive episodes in 2009. European airlines do not have regulations for regular mental health checks, industry executives told the FT.
link_name: Germanwings copilot 'concealed' illness from airline, authorities say
Amazon debuts Dash button for one-touch ordering
White House pledges up to 28% cut in emissions for UN treaty

status_message: Former president Goodluck Jonathan called his rival, Muhammadu Buhari, late March 31 to congratulate him on winning the country's general election, the BBC reported. The tally of votes remained close on the final day of the election.
link_name: Nigerian opposition declare victory in close election

status_message: HP said March 31 that it has sued former Autonomy executives Mike Lynch (the former CEO) and Sushovan Hussain (the former CFO) for $5.1 billion in damages accusing them of fraud. HP's lawsuit, filed in London, was quickly countered by a $148 million lawsuit that accused the company of conducting a "smear campaign" against the executives.
link_name: HP seeks $5.1 billion in damages from ex-Autonomy management

status_message: The UN said March 31 that at least 93 civilians were killed and 364 injured in five cities since March 27. It also noted a growing number of displaced people. Yemenis fleeing violence were seen arriving in Somalia. The Red Cross on the same day called for the safety of medical workers and supplies.
link_name: UN, Red Cross express concern about civilian impact in Yemen

status_message: A spokesperson for Buhari's All Progressives Congress (APC) declared victory in Nigeria's election the evening of March 31, saying the country was "witnessing history." It is the first time an incumbent has been unseated in the country's elections. Goodluck Jonathan, the leader of the People's Democratic Party (PDP), is likely to contest the results, however.
link_name: Nigerian opposition declare victory in close election

status_message: An attacker assaulted a nun and shot a priest shot four times, leaving him for dead. The individuals targeted a convent in the mountains north of the Haitian capital, making off with electronics and $300 in cash.
link_name: Catholic nuns targeted in crime spree in Haiti

status_message: Iraqi troops and militias took over key parts of Tikrit including all government buildings, an Iraqi Interior Ministry spokesman said. The troops were forced to deal with explosive devices planted around the city, a network of bunkers and tunnels, and snipers. The operation began in early March.
link_name: Iraqi troops and militias take over key areas of Tikrit

status_message: IBM announced the initiative on March 31, devoting $3 billion over the next four years to create a new Internet of Things unit within the company. This new unit will help IBM's corporate customers integrate data generated by devices like smartphones, tablets, and cars to "inform decision-making."
link_name: IBM to invest $3 billion into the 'Internet of Things'

status_message: NBC said March 30 it plans to produce a live staging of "The Wiz" on Thursday, Dec. 3. The show will be a co-production with Cirque du Soleil, and executives plan to roll it out in the 2016-17 season. The musical, produced on Broadway in 1974, was adapted into a 1978 Sidney Lumet-directed film starring Diana Ross and Michael Jackson (poster pictured above).
link_name: NBC plans live staging of 'The Wiz'

status_message: The annual Syria donors conference opened with pledges of $507 million by the U.S., $500 million by Kuwait, $100 million by the UAE and $60 million by Saudi Arabia. The UN has appealed for $8.4 billion for aid to Syrians inside and outside of their country in 2015. The UN secured $2.4 billion of a $6.5-billion appeal in 2014.
link_name: Syria donor conference opens with more than $1 billion in pledges

status_message: The Senate completely revised the proposed sex work law on March 30, removing a provision that would see clients heavily fined, France24 reported. Prostitutes will continue to face fines of up to $4000 and two months in jail for selling sex under the revised law, which will require National Assembly approval.
link_name: French Senate overturns bill that sought to decriminalize sex workers, fine clients

status_message: Three editors, the publisher and the chief executive of the Malaysian Insider news site were detained by March 31 on suspicion of sedition, their lawyers and police said. The site reported the monarchy rejected a proposal to allow an interpretation of Islamic law in a northeastern state. The monarchy denied discussing the proposal.
link_name: Malaysian editors and publisher arrested on suspicion of sedition

status_message: Thai PM and coup leader Prayuth Chan-o-cha said March 31 that he had asked the King for permission to lift martial law, which has been in place since the May 2014 coup. He plans on replacing it with an article in the interim constitution that will still give sweeping powers to the military.
link_name: Thai prime minister moves to replace martial law with sweeping military powers

status_message: March 30 research published in the medical journal Lancet confirms that a new strain of Enterovirus D68 called B-1 was implicated in respiratory and paralysis cases reported in 2014. The strain resembles other enteroviruses including polio, researcher Dr. Charles Chiu told NBC.
link_name: Research shows Enterovirus mutation caused child paralysis

status_message: Peace TV and 24TV were suspended for seven days, the Thai broadcasting authority said March 30. It judged programs could "create confusion, instigate conflicts or divisions within society," the Bangkok Post reported. The channels are aligned with the Red Shirts movement that support the ousted prime minister.
link_name: Thai government takes opposition-affiliated TV stations off air

status_message: Campaigning officially began when Cameron visited the queen to announce the dissolution of parliament. Candidates addressed contentious issues including immigration, the economy and the UK's status in the EU.
link_name: UK elections campaigning begins

status_message: After Oxycontin-maker Purdue Pharma missed a court deadline in March, a judge cleared the way for Kentucky to win a lawsuit it filed against the company in 2007. Kentucky expects a billion-dollar verdict in its favor. Purdue disputes the deadline and asked the state Supreme Court to intervene on March 26.
link_name: Missed deadline in OxyContin abuse lawsuit could mean billion-dollar verdict for Kentucky
Indiana lawmakers to 'clarify' language of religious freedom law
Pharmacist groups discourage members from supplying execution drugs
Baltimore jail illegally keeping juveniles in solitary, Justice Dept. says
Jay Z debuts high-end music streaming service Tidal
DOJ sues Southeastern Oklahoma State for discrimination against transgender professor
Rubio to announce 2016 plans on April 13
Obama admin pushes for $478 billion transportation bill
Supreme Court sends Virginia redistricting case back to federal judicial panel
Library of Congress to preserve Radiohead's 'OK Computer'
Robin Williams' widow and children agree to settle estate dispute
Atlanta Falcons to lose NFL draft pick for fake crowd noise in stadium
Spotify app now available for PS3, PS4
Madison Square Garden announces split into two separate companies
Tiger Woods out of world's top 100 golfers for first time since 1996

status_message: The leading line of inquiry for the joint investigation is that MH17 was shot down by a Russian BUK missile system. The Netherlands team released a video March 30 showing a Russian flatbed truck carrying a BUK, along with audio of an intercepted phone call between Russian separatists discussing the missiles. The team has appealed for witnesses to come forward.
link_name: Dutch MH17 investigators seek witnesses to Russian missiles
GM to compensate at least 77 death claims linked to faulty ignition switch
Tesla Motors to announce 'major new product line'

status_message: Rep. Tammy Duckworth (D-IL) announced on March 30 that she will run for U.S. Senate in 2016. Duckworth is looking to unseat Illinois Republican Sen. Mark Kirk. Duckworth, 47, is an Iraq War veteran and was elected to the House in 2012.
link_name: Congresswoman Tammy Duckworth running for Senate
Two federal agents accused of stealing money from the Silk Road

status_message: The National Institutes of Health (NIH) said March 30 that the condition of the healthcare worker infected with Ebola has improved and the worker is now in fair condition. The worker's condition had previously worsened from "serious" to "critical" in mid-March.
link_name: US healthcare worker infected with Ebola now in fair condition

status_message: Apple on March 30 expanded its in-store trade-in program to include select Android and BlackBerry devices. The program lets customers trade in devices for credit toward a new iPhone. Reports of the expanded program first surfaced earlier this month.
link_name: Apple launches Android trade-in program for iPhones
Former JetBlue pilot sues company for $14.9 million after flight diverted
One dead after trying to storm NSA facility in Fort Meade

status_message: The U.S. Supreme Court declined to take up the appeals on March 30 without providing comment. The decision upholds lower court rulings that sided with administrators who established the ban.
link_name: Supreme Court declines to hear case on school banning US flag shirts

status_message: An Australia immigration department employee sent the passport numbers, visa details and other personal information of world leaders to the organizers of the Asian Cup soccer tournament, the Guardian reported March 30. The leaders included U.S. President Barack Obama and Russian President Vladimir Putin.
link_name: Australia accidentally revealed world leaders' personal details at G20 meetings

status_message: Amos Yee, 17, was arrested on March 29 after uploading a video to YouTube celebrating Lee's death and mocking Christianity. In the video, Yee dared Singapore PM Lee Hsien Loong to sue him. At least 20 police reports have been filed against Yee since March 27, the Straits Times reported. The video has been removed and reposted.
link_name: Singapore teen blogger arrested after posting video celebrating ex-leader's death

status_message: Ex-president Nicolas Sarkozy's right-wing UMP party and its allies dominated the second round of local elections on March 29. Based on exit polls, Le Monde reported they won at least 67 departments out of 101 in total, with 28 departments throwing out left-wing parties in favor of the right.
link_name: French conservatives winning local elections, exit polls show

status_message: A crisis in rural India is being fueled by low prices farmers receive, anti-inflation policies, no compensation for income lost to natural disasters, and falling subsidies, Reuters reported March 29. The government says suicides are not linked to storms that damaged about 24.7 million acres of crops.
link_name: India faces rural crisis as Modi shifts focus from subsidies to investment

status_message: GitHub said March 29 that it had been under a DDoS attack for days, but that "we are continuing to adapt and mitigate it." The attack seemed to be focused on two projects: one used by GreatFire, and the other a mirror site for blocked New York Times content for Chinese readers, the Wall Street Journal reported.
link_name: GitHub comes under DDoS attack, Chinese anti-censorship projects targeted

status_message: A court found Olmert guilty of fraud under aggravating circumstances and breach of trust. Olmert accepted bribes from U.S. businessman Morris Talansky in cash-stuffed envelopes containing hundreds of thousands of dollars without reporting it. The charges carry combined maximum sentences of 8 years in prison.
link_name: Former Israeli Prime Minister Olmert guilty in corruption retrial

status_message: Denmark and Australia applied to be founding members of the AIIB, China's Ministry of Finance said March 29. The ministry "welcomed" their decision, the state-run Xinxua news agency reported. The deadline to join the founding of the bank is March 31.
link_name: Australia and Denmark apply to join Asian development bank

status_message: "There's something very dangerous happening in states across the country‚Ä¶ These [religious freedom] bills rationalize injustice by pretending to defend something many of us hold dear‚Ä¶ This isn't a political issue. It isn't a religious issue. This is about how we treat each other as human beings." - Apple CEO Tim Cook
link_name: Apple's Tim Cook speaks out against religious freedom bills allowing discrimination against gays

status_message: Police said on March 29 that two bodies had been recovered from the rubble at the scene of the building collapse, three days after the explosion at the site. Authorities said the remains had not yet been identified.
link_name: Two bodies recovered from scene of NYC building collapse

status_message: Best Buy announced plans on March 28 to consolidate its Future Shop stores and websites in Canada under the Best Buy brand.
link_name: Best Buy closes Canada's Future Shop outlets

status_message: The highly pathogenic H5N2 strain of avian influenza has infected a third turkey farm in Minnesota, the U.S. Department of Agriculture confirmed on March 28. The latest case was discovered in a commercial flock of 39,000 birds in Stearns County.
link_name: Bird flu outbreak hits Minnesota poultry farms
Nashville DA stops practice of adding sterilization to plea deals

status_message: In response to an increase in new Ebola cases, Guinea's President Alpha Conde on March 28 declared a 45-day "health emergency" that calls for restrictions on movement, shuttering hospitals and clinics where new cases of the virus have been treated and new burial rules.
link_name: Five regions in Guinea under Ebola 'health emergency'

status_message: Thousands lined up in Singapore to pay their respects during the state funeral for Lee on March 29. About 450,000 people, or more than 12% of Singapore's citizens, visited parliament to file past his body by the time a public wake ended March 28, officials said.
link_name: Singapore holds state funeral for 'founding father' Lee Kuan Yew

status_message: A U.S. Dept. of Energy report revealed that a Feb. 2014 radiation leak at the New Mexico's Waste Isolation Pilot Plant was likely due to a reaction from "chemically incompatible" waste, including cat litter, which caused a barrel containing radioactive materials to rupture.
link_name: Cat litter to blame for radiation leak at New Mexico nuclear waste facility
Freddie Mercury biopic starring Sacha Baron Cohen is back on

status_message: Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif said March 28 he is confident negotiators will be able to overcome hurdles and reach a deal. Zarif's comments, ahead of the self-imposed March 31 deadline, came after separate meetings with his French and German counterparts.
link_name: Iranian foreign minister confident a nuclear deal will be reached as deadline nears

status_message: Nigerian elections officials said March 28 that voting in some parts of the country had been extended through March 29 due to technical issues with new biometric scanners used for registration.
link_name: Nigeria election extended in some areas due to technical problems
Barbados PM wants to replace Queen of England as island's head of state

status_message: With the Yangtze finless porpoise facing extinction, the Chinese government announced steps to save the species. The plan includes moving some of the critically endangered porpoises out of the polluted Yangtze River and into secure conservation areas with hopes of repopulating the species.
link_name: China sets plan to save critically endangered Yangtze finless porpoise

status_message: Pebble's second Kickstarter campaign ended at 10pm ET on March 27 having raised a total of $20.3 million, which is a new Kickstarter record. A total of 78,471 backers contributed to the campaign.
link_name: Second Pebble Kickstarter concludes, raises $20.3 million

status_message: Amazon will remove non-compete clauses for hourly warehouse workers in the U.S., the company confirmed March 27.
link_name: Amazon to remove non-compete clauses for warehouse workers
Russian deputy PM says Russia will join Asian development bank

status_message: A Somali UN diplomat and at least 13 other people were killed and dozens injured by the attackers who detonated a car bomb at the hotel entrance before shooting their way inside. Somali special forces eventually killed all six attackers.
link_name: Mogadishu hotel siege ends, at least 20 dead including attackers

status_message: Texas prison officials said March 25 they had acquired enough pentobarbital to carry out out the four executions scheduled for April. Earlier estimates had the state running out in March. The new supply came from an undisclosed compounding pharmacy.
link_name: Texas finds more lethal injection drugs after almost running out
Israel releasing 3 months' worth of Palestinian tax revenue
Arkansas governor says he will sign 'religious freedom' bill that allows discrimination of gay...
Republican lawmaker wants voluntary GMO food labeling
Foot surgery ends season for NBA star Kevin Durant

Google to face UK lawsuit over Safari privacy violations

status_message: On March 26, Premera Blue Cross was sued in federal court in Washington state for not adequately protecting its customers' private data.
link_name: Premera Blue Cross hit with class action lawsuit following hack
Hackers breach Slack database containing user data
China and Philippines reignite dispute over sea territory
Tim Cook to donate entire $785 million fortune to charity
Swiss bankers sentenced to 5 years' probation in US tax evasion case

status_message: Reid announced March 27 he would not seek re-election in 2016. He said he contemplated the decision for months and that it was not related to a recent accident while exercising, or the loss of his Senate majority in Nov. 2014 midterm elections.
link_name: Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid will not seek re-election

status_message: The government released a statement on March 26 signed by both frontrunners calling on supporters to "refrain from violence." The pair were renewing a similar pledge made in January before the Feb. 14 elections were postponed due to registration problems and security concerns related to Boko Haram.
link_name: Nigerian presidential candidates ask supporters to respect results, avoid violence

status_message: Protests continued in Kabul on March 26 against the killing of Farkhunda, a 27-year-old female religious scholar, a week earlier. A cleric at the protest called on the government to hang the perpetrators "as a lesson for future generations." Further demonstrations are planned.
link_name: Afghans continue protests of killing of female religious scholar

status_message: Arab foreign ministers agreed to a draft resolution to form a unified military force. It could include about 40,000 troops, warships and planes, Egyptian officials told the AP. It would likely be headquartered in Egypt or Saudi Arabia. They will meet again in a month to further discuss the issue.
link_name: Arab League plans to form joint military force

status_message: UN Middle East envoy Robert Serry said March 26: "Illegal settlement activity simply cannot be reconciled with the objective of a negotiated two-state solution and may kill the very possibility of reaching peace on the paradigm of two states for two peoples."
link_name: UN envoy warns Israeli settlements may have killed two-state idea

status_message: At least 20 student activists have had their homes visited by plainclothes police and military officers, Reuters reported March 26, with students saying the visits had occurred in the previous week. A junta spokesman said the visits were part of a policy to discourage protests.
link_name: Thai junta visits homes of student activists, delivers warnings

status_message: North Korea said late March 26 that it had arrested two South Korean nationals sometime in 2014 on spying charges. The men, identified as Choe Chun Gil and Kim Kuk Gi were shown in pictures released by the North at a press conference in Pyongyang.
link_name: North Korea arrests two South Koreans accused of spying

status_message: A number of airlines worldwide said they were immediately changing their rules to require at least two pilots in the cockpit at all times. All U.S. airlines already have the rule in place.
link_name: Officials: Copilot intentionally crashed Germanwings jet

status_message: South Korea on March 26 announced that has agreed to become a founding member of the AIIB. It was unclear what safeguards China has committed to the bank.
link_name: South Korea says it will join Asian development bank

status_message: In a show of bipartisanship, the Republican-controlled Senate voted 61-39 on March 26 to back President Obama's proposal to allow workers to earn up to seven days of paid sick leave. It is unclear if the measure will survive the budget process and become law.
link_name: Senate backs Obama proposal for paid sick leave
Wildlife agency to allow Texan hunter to return with trophy carcass of endangered rhino
Audit: ATF spent $600,000 on drones it never flew

status_message: The 27 so-called "black spider memos" were sent between September 2004 and April 2005 to ministers in seven UK government departments. Despite a freedom of information tribunal agreeing they should be released, the UK's former attorney general Dominic Grieve blocked their publication arguing they could undermine Charles' "position of political neutrality."
link_name: UK supreme court clears release of secret Prince Charles letters to government
'Mega-dam' linked to death of indigenous Guatemalans

status_message: Princeton University researchers warned that antibiotic use in livestock could climb by 67% worldwide between 2010 and 2030, which may give rise to drug-resistant superbugs in humans. The study says growing consumption in emerging economies, particularly Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa, has fueled the increase.
link_name: Study: Use of antibiotics in livestock boosts risk of drug-resistant of superbugs
Indiana declares emergency over HIV outbreak

status_message: Pepsi overtook Diet Coke as the second-most popular carbonated soft drink in the U.S. in 2014, according to a March 26 report from the trade publication Beverage Digest. Diet Coke had been second to Coca-Cola since 2010.
link_name: Diet Coke falls behind Pepsi as second-most popular soft drink

link_name: Iraqi troops make final push to retake Tikrit
Schlumberger to pay $233 million to Justice Dept. for sanctions violations
House overwhelmingly approves $214 billion bipartisan 'doc fix' Medicare deal

status_message: Uber's offices in the Dutch capital of Amsterdam were raided March 26 by transportation regulators. A Dutch court in Dec. 2014 ruled that UberPop, the company's service that relies on private drivers using their own cars, was illegal. Regulators said they were looking for documents showing the size of UberPop.
link_name: Dutch regulators raid Uber's Amsterdam offices

status_message: WikiLeaks on March 25 released a draft TPP chapter dated Jan. 20. It says no country can treat foreign and local investors differently with policies such as export and supply controls, technology transfer and nationalizations. It would allow foreign firms to sue if they believe a policy harmed their interests.
link_name: Leaked details of Pacific trade deal confirm foreign investors could sue governments

status_message: A French prosecutor said March 26 that the copilot took sole control of the plane while the pilot was locked out of the cockpit. The prosecutor said it was the copilot's "intention to destroy" the plane.
link_name: Officials: Copilot intentionally crashed Germanwings jet

status_message: About 866,000 people sought asylum in 2014, nearly reaching the "all-time high" of almost 900,000 in 1992, a UNHCR report released March 26 said. EU nations received the bulk with 570,800 applications, an increase of 44% from 2013. A fifth of asylum-seekers were Syrians. Iraqis and Afghans were the next largest groups.
link_name: Asylum applications nearly reach 'all-time high' in 2014, UN says

status_message: UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will ask military officials from more than 100 countries to support global peacekeeping efforts during an unprecedented meeting on March 27, the AP reported. His pitch will come following a U.S. call for European nations to step up their contributions.
link_name: UN to ask member states to boost support for troop deployments

status_message: The more than 1,500 Palestinian civilians killed and the estimated 50,000 internally displaced persons in 2014 were the most since war in 1967, the UN said March 26. The death toll was primarily due to the war in Gaza, but also "from policies and practices related to the Israeli occupation."
link_name: UN: Palestinians killed or displaced in 2014 were the most since 1967

status_message: The pronoun "hen" is used to refer to someone without revealing their gender. It was first used in the 1960s but only became widely used in recent years after the transgender community claimed it around 2000. It will join "han" (he) and "hon" (she) in the latest version of the academy's dictionary.
link_name: Official Swedish dictionary to add gender-neutral pronoun

status_message: IOC officials began a 5-day tour of Beijing March 24. On March 25 they toured a suburb of the city where Alpine skiing would be held. Zhang Jiandong, vice-chair of Beijing's bid committee he has "confidence" the city can reduce its notorious pollution before the Games.
link_name: Beijing addresses pollution, Internet access during Olympics bid inspection

status_message: A Chinese foreign ministry spokesperson on March 25 rejected calls from the UN, EU, U.S. and UK to release the women. Two of the women have been transferred to the medical clinics of their detention centers. One of the women claimed she was denied treatment for more than a week in detention, her former lawyer said.
link_name: China rejects calls to release female activists detained for sexual harassment campaign

status_message: Police arrested a suspect on March 26 in Mumbai by tracing his phone's communications tower location. The suspect, Mohammad Selim, was flown back to Kolkata, the capital of West Bengal state, for interrogation. Police hope Selim will lead them to the other men involved.
link_name: Indian authorities arrest first suspect in rape of nun

Calif. seeks to block initiative that calls for the execution of gay people
California, Washington bills would restrict police 'stingray' tracking
Colorado indicts 32 members of marijuana trafficking enterprise

status_message: The New York Times, citing an unnamed senior military official involved in the crash investigation said March 25 that one of the plane's pilots were locked out of the cockpit before the plane crashed. His attempts to open the door can be heard on the cockpit's voice recorder.
link_name: Report: One pilot locked out of cockpit before Germanwings crash

status_message: Senior military officials told the AP March 25 that the U.S. is conducting airstrikes against IS militants in Tikrit to help Iraqi forces retake the city. Other reports had previously indicated orders had been given to begin airstrikes.
link_name: US conducts airstrikes against IS militants in Tikrit

status_message: At an Army press conference officials said former prisoner of war U.S. Sgt Bowe Bergdahl is formally charged with desertion and "misbehavior before the enemy," a charge that could see him face life in prison if convicted.
link_name: Lawyer: Bowe Bergdahl charged with desertion

status_message: Saudi Arabia has deployed a significant task force to its extensive border with Yemen, including an increased tank presence. The Saudis said the move was purely defensive, but it has raised concerns that Yemen will become a power struggle between Sunni Saudi Arabia, and Shiite Iran, which has been accused of backing the Houthi uprising.
link_name: Saudi Arabia readies force on Yemen border, says no plan for intervention

status_message: Bergdahl's attorney, Eugene Fidell, told the Washington Post March 25 that his client will be charged with desertion. The move comes ahead of a press conference at 3:30 pm ET where Army officials said they will discuss Bergdhal's case.
link_name: Lawyer: Bowe Bergdahl charged with desertion

status_message: Boeing has been granted a patent for a "force field" with the design name of Method and system for shockwave attenuation via electromagnetic arc. The field, in theory, would activate a protective plasma shield using lasers, electricity and microwaves, after sensing a nearby explosion.
link_name: Boeing granted 'force field' patent

link_name: Facebook opens Messenger to third-party apps
