link_name: A page we can call home‚Ä¶

status_message: Monash's Center for Additive Manufacturing placed its 3D-printed jet engine on public display for the first time at the International Air Show in Avalon, Australia on Feb. 26.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: A law banning public protests outside courts, parliament and the prime minister's offices was overwhelmingly supported on its first reading by the interim parliament on Feb. 26. It is currently illegal under martial law for more than five people to gather in public.
link_name: Thai interim parliament approves draft law restricting protests

status_message: Marijuana use, possession up to two ounces and growing up to six plants for people over 21 was legalized in Washington, DC. It does not apply to federal lands. Smoking is allowed only in private property. Renters are still subject to rental agreements. Sale or trade is forbidden, but giving away up to an ounce is allowed.
link_name: Recreational marijuana legalized in Washington DC

status_message: The bill would undo requirements that force workers to join or pay dues to a union as a condition of employment. Supporters of the bill say it will make the state's businesses more competitive. The Wisconsin State Senate approved the bill 17-15 on Feb. 25, just five days after it was proposed. All Democrats and one Republican voted against it. The bill moved to the state Assembly, where Republicans also hold a majority. Union workers protested outside the state Capitol in Madison.
link_name: Wisconsin Senate approves anti-union law

status_message: China's Central Government Procurement Center (CGPC) removed products of U.S. tech companies from its list of approved equipment, an investigation by Reuters published Feb. 26 said. It affects Cisco, Apple, McAfee and Citrix. The list is non-binding for local governments, state-owned enterprises and the military.
link_name: Chinese government removes US tech firms from approved buyer list

status_message: The U.S. Treasury's Financial Crimes Enforcement Network and the California Department of Business Oversight launched probes into Citigroup and its Banamex USA unit, Citigroup reported Feb. 25.
link_name: More US agencies looking into possible money laundering at Citigroup

status_message: Ocean Maritime Management renamed and transferred ownership of 13 of its 14 cargo ships to "evade assets freezes by member states," a report by a panel of experts that will be reviewed by the UN Security Council Feb. 26 says. The cargo ships moved freely despite UN sanctions, the report says.
link_name: UN: North Korean shipping company evading sanctions
'Mystery' bright spots seen as spacecraft approaches Ceres
Morgan Stanley to pay $2.6 billion to settle Justice Dept. charges over mortgages
Lizard Squad hacks Lenovo website over 'Superfish' controversy
Stockton, second largest US city to declare insolvency, exits bankruptcy
Supreme Court reverses conviction of fisherman charged under white-collar crime law
Report: YouTube generated $4 billion in revenue in 2014
Robots allow doctors to conduct remote house calls
Former Mississippi prison head pleads guilty in corruption case
Patient sues Olympus over contaminated scopes linked to UCLA superbug outbreak
Facebook paid researchers $1.3 million in 2014 for discovering security flaws
New 'Forever' stamp will honor Maya Angelou
Google renews enterprise push with Android for Work

status_message: Swiss-based drone maker Flyability is developing a crash-proof, bouncing drone with potential use in disaster relief. In a Feb. 10 video, the company demonstrated uses ranging from searching for victims of disasters to surveilling difficult-to-access buildings.
link_name: Swiss-made 'crash-proof' drone to help victims in disaster areas

status_message: Officials at Russia's Oil and Gas Research Institute Feb. 24 said at least 7 new holes have appeared in northern Russia and there could be "20 to 30 craters more." Vasily Bogoyavlensky, deputy director of the institute, called for urgent research in to the origins of the holes "to prevent possible disasters."
link_name: More mysterious craters appear in Siberia

status_message: The AP reported that local residents witnessed approximately 2,000 books transported out of Mosul library in pickup trucks, after which the books were reportedly burned. The library was first destroyed during the 2003 invasion of Iraq, but rebuilt using local efforts.
link_name: Thousands of historic books reportedly seized, destroyed by IS in Mosul

status_message: Federal prosecutors filed charges against three Brooklyn men, including two Uzbek citizens and a Kazakh national, on Feb. 25. The youngest man, 19-year-old Akhror Saidakhmetov, is alleged to have posted threats against FBI agents and police officers in an Uzbek-language forum.
link_name: Three Brooklyn men detained on charges of supporting IS

status_message: A study conducted by the French national HIV research agency shows Truvada taken before and after sex by gay men can help reduce the risk of HIV. The study, which was stopped ahead of schedule in Nov. 2014 due to promising results, was the subject of a discussion at the Retrovirus Conference in Seattle Feb. 24.
link_name: Study: HIV-prevention pill taken before and after sex can prevent infection

status_message: Pebble has now raised more than $8.9 million in its second-ever Kickstarter campaign. The company launched the crowdfunding campaign on Feb. 24 alongside the announcement that it will release a color smartwatch called Pebble Time in May. Pebble raised its target amount of $500,000 in just 17 minutes.
link_name: Pebble returns to Kickstarter for color smartwatch

status_message: A study of 640 children published in The New England Journal of Medicine Feb. 23 showed that compared to those who were not exposed to peanuts, children who were fed peanut products during infancy are significantly less likely to develop a peanut allergy.
link_name: Study suggests early exposure to peanuts may prevent peanut allergies

status_message: Daniel A. Rosen, the director of counterterrorism programs and policy at U.S. Department of State, was arrested by D.C. police after an alleged online conversation with an officer from the child protection unit of Fairfax County PD. Rosen will face charges in Fairfax County, Virginia.
link_name: State Dept. official charged with soliciting minor for sex

status_message:
A jury awarded Samantha Elauf, who was rejected from a job as a store "model" at a Tulsa, OK, Abercrombie & Fitch $20,000 in a suit filed by the federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) on her behalf. The 10th Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver ruled against the award, saying Elauf should have challenged the company's policy on head coverings.

The Supreme Court will hear the case today.
link_name: Supreme Court to hear Abercrombie & Fitch hijab case

status_message: A federal jury in Texas Feb. 24 ordered Apple to pay $532.9 million in damages for infringing three patents owned by Smartflash, a Texas company that was seeking $852 million and a percentage of sales from Apple's devices. Apple immediately said it would appeal the verdict, saying the Smartflash patents were invalid.
link_name: Apple must pay $532.9 million following Smartflash patent trial

status_message: Ex-president Saleh amassed a fortune worth $32 billion to $60 billion while he was in power, a UN report submitted Feb. 20 found. He transferred most of the assets to at least 20 countries often using fake names and front companies. Yemen's annual GDP is about $35 billion. The country suffers from mass poverty.
link_name: Ex-Yemeni president hid a fortune of tens of billions, sanctioned by UN

status_message: A new Charlie Hebdo issue, its first in six weeks, hit newsstands Feb. 24. The issue features a cover showing far-right leader Marine Le Pen, a TV news crew, a bishop and a Muslim extremist in pursuit of a dog carrying a copy of the magazine. Subscriptions to the magazine have increased 2,500%.
link_name: Charlie Hebdo publication returns, subscribers increase 2,500% since attack

status_message: Mayor Bill de Blasio, late Feb. 24, changed New York City's rules on the ultra-Orthodox blood-sucking practice, dropping the requirement for a parental consent form. Former Mayor Michael Bloomberg's introduction of the consent form requirement angered ultra-Orthodox communities.
link_name: NYC mayor changes rules on ultra-Orthodox circumcision ritual

status_message: Torture or ill-treatment of detainees in Afghanistan is "regular and prevalent," a UN report released Feb. 25 said. It found more than a third of 790 people interviewed Jan. 2013 to Dec. 2014 reported serious mistreatment. The number of people who said they were tortured was lower than in the UN's 2013 report.
link_name: Torture of detainees in Afghanistan remains rampant, UN says

status_message: In a free vote Feb. 3, British MPs voted 382-128 to legalize a technique to allow babies created from two different mothers. The House of Lords approved the bill by a majority of 232 votes on Feb. 24.
link_name: Britain becomes the first country to allow babies from DNA of three parents

status_message: Russia will continue to be a partner in the ISS program until 2024, Roscosmos' science and technology council said Feb. 24. Russia plans to detach its ISS modules and reconstruct them into a Russian space station. Russia also said it will send manned and robotic missions to the Moon in the coming decades.
link_name: Russia to detach ISS modules after 2024, build own space station

status_message: The IOM announced Feb. 24 that it would facilitate resettlement of migrants from Nauru to Cambodia. The IOM has already negotiated issues such as family resettlement, health, education, and free movement within Cambodia. It may negotiate on Cambodian citizenship for migrants.
link_name: IOM to assist resettlement of detained migrants who headed to Australia

status_message: The company issued a response on Feb. 25 to The Intercept report. Gemalto said it determined its office networks had been hacked, but that it "could not have resulted in a massive theft of SIM encryption keys."
link_name: SIM card manufacturer Gemalto disputes hacking report

status_message: Netflix will premiere a "Pee-wee's Big Holiday" produced by Judd Apatow and Paul Reubens (Pee-Wee Herman) and directed by John Lee. The movie will be made in 2015. It is about "a fateful meeting with a mysterious stranger [who] inspires Pee-wee Herman to take his first-ever holiday."
link_name: Netflix to distribute new Pee-wee Herman movie

status_message: Police arrested the driver of the abandoned pickup truck, Jose Alejandro Sanchez-Rameriz, 54, on suspicion of felony hit-and-run. The truck likely had been driving down the tracks and not across them, Sumwalt said. Sanchez-Rameriz told police the truck got stuck on the tracks.
link_name: Pickup truck driver arrested for LA Metrolink crash

status_message: BNP leader and ex-Prime Minister Khaelda Zia failed to appear in the anti-corruption court in Dhaka for the fourth time on Feb. 25. Judge Abu Ahmed Jamadder, who is hearing the two graft cases against her, issued an arrest warrant.
link_name: Bangladesh court orders arrest of opposition leader

status_message: On Feb. 24, the FBI and the State Department issued a "Wanted" poster and offered a $3 million reward for information leading to Evgeniy Bogachev's arrest and/or conviction. The amount is the highest bounty offered by U.S. authorities for a suspected cyber crime.
link_name: FBI offers record $3 million reward for Russian hacker

status_message: The Inglewood City Council voted 5-0 on Feb. 24 to approve a $2 billion stadium proposal. The council vote sidesteps a public vote and an environmental review of issues including air pollution, noise and traffic, the AP reported. It essentially jump-starts construction, which could begin by the end of 2015.
link_name: Inglewood City Council approves plan for NFL stadium

status_message: The White House on Feb. 24 nominated Katherine S. Dhanani to be the first U.S. ambassador to Somalia since 1991. If confirmed, Dhanani would oversee the U.S. mission currently located in Nairobi, Kenya.
link_name: White House nominates first ambassador to Somalia in 24 years

status_message: A jury convicted Eddie Ray Routh of murdering Chris Kyle, subject of the film "American Sniper," and another man Feb. 24.
link_name: Eddie Ray Routh convicted of murder in 'American Sniper' trial
Supreme Court seems to side with 401(k) investors
European Parliament takes step to reform carbon emissions trade by 2018
Leader of German anti-Islamic group reinstated after Hitler mustache scandal
Kingpin of Amazon's biggest deforestation ring detained
Georgia set to execute first female prisoner since 1945
Wisconsin lawmakers seek to pass new anti-union law

status_message: The challenge to overturn California's plastic bag ban has qualified for the Nov. 2016 ballot, California state officials said Feb. 24. The move halts implementation of the California law until after voters decide on its fate.
link_name: Challenge to California's ban on plastic bags qualifies for 2016 ballot
UK intelligence committee head resigns amid cash-for-access scandal
Reddit bans posting of nude photos without subject's consent
Rep. Schock may have violated billing rules for flights and Katy Perry concert

status_message: President Obama vetoed the Keystone XL pipeline bill Feb. 24, the same day that Congress officially sent the bill to the White House for a signature. The Senate will vote March 3 to try to override the veto-- though it lacks the votes to do so. To override the veto, the Senate would need 67 votes.
link_name: Obama vetoes bill to approve Keystone XL pipeline
Toronto 'mystery tunnel' puzzles investigators
Study finds molecular link between obesity and Type 2 diabetes

status_message: U.S. Department of Justice announced Feb. 24 that the independent federal investigation into the 2012 shooting death of Trayvon Martin "has been closed" after finding insufficient evidence to pursue federal criminal charges against George Zimmerman. The Justice Department said in July 2013 that it would review the case
link_name: Feds close investigation into death of Trayvon Martin

status_message: After a Feb. 23 meeting in Geneva, U.S. and Iranian negotiators may be on the brink of achieving a deal to limit the Iranian nuclear program for at least 10 years. The deal proposes to ease nuclear restrictions on Iran in the final years of that period. Observers say this is a nod to Iranian hardliners, as well as U.S. constituents.
link_name: U.S. and Iran negotiators weigh 'historic' nuclear deal to limit program for 10 years
Apple adds racially diverse emoji in latest OS X beta

status_message: Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-KY) says he will offer two bills in an effort to end the stalemate. One bill would fund DHS and the other would try to undo President Obama's executive order on immigration. While the move was welcomed by House Speaker Boehner, it is unclear if the bills will pass the House.
link_name: McConnell offers plan to end stalemate on DHS funding bill

status_message: A South African spy wrote to headquarters June 2012 that a CIA agent was "desperate to make inroads into Hamas in Gaza," according to leaked cables published by Al Jazeera and the Guardian Feb. 23. The U.S. government has a ban on contacting the group because of its terrorist designation.
link_name: CIA tried backchannel contact to Hamas despite ban, leaked cables show

status_message: NJ Superior Court judge Mary C. Jacobson ruled on Feb. 23 that Gov. Chris Christie (R-NJ) violated state law when he failed to pay the full amount into the state's public pension system last year. The judge ordered Christie to find a way to pay the $1.57 billion he owed.
link_name: NJ Judge rules Gov. Chris Christie violated state law in pension payments case

status_message: Pebble Feb. 24 launched a second Kickstarter alongside the announcement that it will release a color smartwatch called the Pebble Time in May. The company asked backers for $500,000, an amount that was raised in 17 minutes. More than $2 million was raised by 11am ET.
link_name: Pebble returns to Kickstarter for color smartwatch

status_message: A French national working for an international organization was kidnapped by gunmen who also forced her translator and bodyguard into a car, according to a French foreign ministry statement. The foreign ministry said it had been in touch with the woman's family and was doing everything in its power to locate her.
link_name: French national kidnapped in Sana'a, foreign ministry says

status_message: The group of Eurozone finance ministers (Eurogroup) has accepted the Greek request for a bailout extension, according to a Greek finance ministry official cited by Reuters on Feb. 24. As part of the four-month extension, the Greek government was required to submit a reform program.
link_name: Eurozone ministers approve Greek bailout extension, reports say

status_message: An emergency bushfire alert warned people to leave the areas of Casuarina and Bertram in Kwinana. Blazes raging across 198 acres closed the Kwinana Freeway. The unpredictable and out-of-control bush fires are considered a threat to life and property.
link_name: Bushfires besieging Western Australia expected to spread

status_message: Two bids were submitted on Feb. 24 to the South Korean military to build a homegrown fighter jet. The project has a budget of $8.3 billion to develop and build 120 jets over the next decade. The jet will be similar in specifications to the F-16.
link_name: Pair of bids submitted to create South Korean fighter jet

status_message: Israeli troops shot dead a 20-year-old Palestinian in the Deheishe refugee camp in Bethlehem in the occupied West Bank on Feb. 24, the Israeli military and a hospital official said. Palestinians threw stones at soldiers who entered the camp before the soldiers opened fire, residents and the Israeli military said.
link_name: Israeli troops kill Palestinian in Bethlehem refugee camp

status_message: An Indonesian court on Feb. 24 denied to stay the executions of Australians Andrew Chan and Myuran Sukumaran. They were sentenced to death as leaders of the so-called "Bali Nine." The men and seven others were arrested in 2005 trying to smuggle heroin from Indonesia to Australia. President Joko Widodo has denied clemency.
link_name: Indonesian court denies clemency appeal for Australians convicted of drug smuggling

status_message: On Feb. 23, jurors viewed the first of the three taped confessions by Hernandez, recorded in 2012, as well as a second taping recorded 12 hours later. Hernandez's lawyer Harvey Fishbein rebutted the videos, saying Hernandez "can't tell the difference between reality and fantasy."
link_name: Jurors see second Etan Patz murder confession video

status_message: The results from 6,663 rape kits in Houston previously untested due to a backlog matched 850 DNA profiles in an FBI database, Houston officials said Feb. 23. Some of the kits date as far back as 1987. Charges have been filed against 29 suspects of sexual assaults, six of whom have been convicted.
link_name: Houston police find hundreds of DNA matches in rape kit backlog

status_message: Arkansas Gov. Asa Hutchinson allowed SB 202, which prohibits local governments from enacting expanded anti-discrimination laws, to go into law without his signature Feb. 23.
link_name: Arkansas bars local governments from expanding anti-discrimination laws

status_message: An analysis of Los Angeles crime data by the LA Times found that since Nov. 2014 narcotics arrests dropped 30% in LA and 48% in areas patrolled by the county Sheriff's Department. Property crimes, including burglary and auto theft, were up 10% in sheriff's territory and up 7% in LA.
link_name: Los Angeles narcotics arrests, prison population down after Prop. 47
FIFA task force says 2022 World Cup can only happen in November and December
Report: Violence by guards against inmates persists at Rikers Island
Apple closes at record high, reaches $774.7 billion in value
Ethiopia sets world record for most HIV testing in a day
Report finds Facebook in violation of EU privacy laws
Texas prison riot forces now-'uninhabitable' facility to shut down
NJ senators ask attorney general to launch Sandy insurance fraud probe
Google buys Softcard mobile payment technology, IP
Marine who went missing in Iraq in 2004 found guilty of desertion
YouTube releases app designed specifically for children

status_message: Four days after being sworn in, new Defense Secretary Ashton Carter said Feb. 22 said gender identity should not preclude a transgendered person's right to serve in the military, only their "suitability for service." Carter also said he is "open-minded" about a review of the military ban against transgendered people.
link_name: Defense Secretary Ashton Carter "open-minded" about review of military transgender ban

status_message: Existing home sales in January fell 4.9% to a seasonally adjusted rate of 4.82 million units, below economists' expectations of 4.95 million units. The National Association of Realtors released an analysis on Feb. 23 showing that the rise in house prices above the pace of inflation and low housing supply discouraged American home buyers.
link_name: US existing home sales fell to lowest level in 9 months in January

status_message: Despite The Intercept's report, Dutch firm Gemalto claimed Feb. 23 that its products, including SIM cards and banking cards, are safe and that it doesn't expect "to endure a significant financial prejudice." The company plans to announce further details of its internal investigation on Feb. 25.
link_name: Hacked SIM card manufacturer claims products are secure

status_message: Utah's House Feb. 19 voted 72-1 in favor of a bill to allow patients with terminal illnesses to elect to forgo requirements that drugs be subject to final approval by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA). The bill will now move forward to the state Senate for consideration.
link_name: Utah House passes bill allowing terminally ill patients to use experimental drugs

status_message: Joseph Scott Pemberton appeared in court Feb. 23 under heavy guard at a pre-trial hearing for the murder of Laude. Pemberton did not speak when asked to enter his plea. The judge entered a not guilty plea for him. His trial is expected to start in March.
link_name: US Marine declines to enter plea in murder of transgender woman

status_message: A judge sentenced Alaa Abdel Fattah and Mohamed Abdul Rahman to 5 years in prison and fined them 100,000 Egyptian pounds ($13,000) in a retrial for breaking an anti-protest law. Another 23 activists received 3 years. "Down, down with military rule!" was shouted in the courtroom after the verdict was read.
link_name: Egyptian court sentences prominent activists to five years for protesting

status_message: The Ukrainian military will not immediately remove heavy weapons from the east, Ukrainian military spokesperson Anatoly Stelmakh said early Feb. 23. The two sides agreed a day earlier that they would do so within a few days.
link_name: Ukraine halts plans to remove heavy weapons in the east as conflict continues

status_message: Thai student-activists who staged a satirical play called "The Wolf Bride" to mark the anniversary of a student-led uprising in 1973 were imprisoned for two-and-a-half years on Feb. 23. Patiwat Saraiyaem, 23, and Porntip Mankong, 26, pleaded guilty to lese majeste and confessed to defaming the monarchy.
link_name: Thai students imprisoned for play deemed critical of the monarchy

status_message: Canada's Valeant said Feb. 22 that it will buy North Carolina-based Salix for $10.4 billion, or $158 per share. Salix closed at $157.50 per share Feb. 20. Valeant will pay off $4.1 billion of Salix's debt. Salix makes drugs for gastrointestinal diseases.
link_name: Drug company Valeant buys Salix for $10.1 billion

status_message: At least 50,000 homes and businesses on Queensland's Central Coast remained without power, water, and sewage on Feb. 23. Three days earlier, Cyclone Marcia destroyed hundreds of homes on the Queensland and Northern Territory coasts before rains caused severe floods.
link_name: Areas hardest hit by Australian cyclones remain isolated with essential services down

status_message: Foreign runners will not be allowed into North Korea to compete in the April marathon, said Koryo Tours and Young Pioneer Tours, which arrange tours of North Korea from China, on Feb. 23. North Korea has closed its border to all tourists since Oct. 2014 over Ebola fears.
link_name: North Korea bans foreign runners at marathon over Ebola fears

status_message: China summoned India's ambassador to China Feb. 21 to protest Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi's visit to Arunachal Pradesh in northeast India near the disputed Chinese border. Modi was in the area to mark an anniversary and to see the launch of a train line and other business.
link_name: China summons Indian ambassador over Modi's border visit

status_message: At least 70 bodies were recovered after a ferry with up to 140 people onboard capsized after being hit by a cargo vessel. Around 70 people have been rescued. The search at the site of the accident was called off Feb. 23 after the ferry was lifted to the surface and towed ashore.
link_name: Bangladesh ferry capsizes in deadly crash with cargo vessel

status_message: An 18-year-old Palestinian man stabbed a Jewish ultra-Orthodox man in Tzahal Square in central Jerusalem on Feb. 22. According to reports, the attacker was subdued by Nir Barkat, the mayor of Jerusalem, and his security detail.
link_name: Jerusalem mayor tackles Palestinian who stabbed Orthodox man in city square

status_message: "Fifty Shades of Gray" earned $23.2 million Feb. 20-22 to remain the No. 1 film at the box office for the second straight weekend.
link_name: 'Fifty Shades of Grey' dominates weekend box office again

status_message: On Feb. 22, Homeland Security Secretary Jeh Johnson addressed a propaganda video released on Feb. 21 by the Somalia-based terror group Al-Shabaab.
link_name: Mall of America shoppers cautioned by DHS head after terror threat
Razzie Awards names 'Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas' worst movie of 2014
Procter & Gamble to sell 100 brands by mid-2016

status_message: While a tentative contract still needs approval from port operators and a vote by union members, work resumed on Feb. 21 at ports across the West Coast. The disruption has caused a backlog of billions of dollars worth of cargo that needs processing.
link_name: Work resumes at West Coast ports after tentative deal reached
Gloves from Muhammad Ali-Sonny Liston 'phantom punch' fight fetch $956,000
Study: Half of Americans may be exposed to cancer-causing carcinogen in soda

status_message: My Micro NY has begun constructing prefabricated micro-apartments at the Brooklyn Navy Yard. The modular units will be turned into a 55-unit micro-apartment complex at 335 East 27th Street, which will begin leasing in the summer of 2015.
link_name: 'Micro unit' apartments under construction in NYC

status_message: Oral arguments begin Feb. 23 in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.
link_name: Big tobacco fights court-mandated ads admitting they deceived the public

status_message: The UN's children's agency UNICEF reported Feb. 21 that 89 boys, some as young as 13, had been abducted in northern South Sudan.
link_name: UN says 89 boys abducted in South Sudan

status_message: According to a confidential IAEA report issued Feb. 19 and obtained by Reuters, Iran has ceased testing new IR-5 centrifuges to refine uranium as part of an agreement with the agency.
link_name: Iran has stopped testing disputed uranium gas centrifuges, IAEA says

status_message: U.S. astronauts Barry "Butch" Wilmore and Terry Virts conducted a spacewalk on Feb. 21, a day after concerns over equipment in some spacesuits forced NASA to briefly postpone the mission.
link_name: Spacewalk outside space station begins after delay for suit problem

status_message: Announced on Feb. 20, TwitchCon will be the company's first community convention. Twitch said the convention will take place Sept. 25.
link_name: Twitch to hold San Francisco convention in September
Mayweather-Pacquiao boxing match set for May 2

status_message: The Dept. of Transportation's National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) said Feb. 20 that it is fining Japan's Takata $14,000 per day until the airbag maker complies with the agency's two "Special Orders" issued in late 2014.
link_name: Airbag maker fined $14,000 a day by US agency
West Indies, New Zealand win Cricket World Cup matches
NASCAR suspends Kurt Busch indefinitely for domestic abuse charges

status_message: Former Yemeni President Abd-Rabbu Mansour Hadi left his residence in Sana'a Feb. 21 and flew to his home in Aden, according to multiple reports. It is unclear whether he was intentionally released or if he escaped from house arrest.
link_name: Former Yemen president leaves house arrest
Dominique Strauss-Kahn trial concludes, verdict expected in June
Kevin Rose's North Technologies shuts down Tiiny app
US government warns Lenovo customers about Superfish
New York City judge evicts rent-stabilized Airbnb host
Arrest made in connection to January Colorado Springs bombing
Greece to receive four-month extension on European loans
MLB announces changes aimed at speeding up games
FDA grants permission for 23andMe's Bloom syndrome test
'Slender Man' teen stabbing described in interrogation video
Ex-Virginia first lady Maureen McDonnell sentenced to a year for corruption

status_message:
Foreign holdings of US debt reach record $6.15 trillion in December:

China and Japan are the two largest holders of U.S. debt, followed by Belgium. China reduced its holdings by 0.5% to $1.24 trillion in Dec. 2014, while Japan reduced U.S. Treasury debt by 0.9% to $1.23 trillion. Belgium held only $335.4 billion in U.S. debt in Dec. 2014.
link_name: Foreign holdings of US debt reach record $6.15 trillion in December

status_message: YouTube plans to debut an app designed for kids, which will initially only be available for Android, on Feb. 23. The app will host original episodes of children's shows like "Sesame Street" and "Thomas the Tank Engine," and will have a unique user interface with large icons and minimal scrolling.
link_name: YouTube to debut app designed for children

status_message: Gazprom said on Feb. 19 that it will provide gas deliveries directly to rebels in the region at the "current sale-and-purchase contract between Gazprom and Ukraine's Naftogaz." A Russian news agency later reported Naftogaz resumed deliveries to the region after a brief interruption.
link_name: Gazprom supplying gas to eastern Ukraine rebels, CEO says

status_message: Arkansas legislature passed the "Intrastate Commerce Improvement Act" Feb. 13, to prohibit all cities and counties in the state from passing non-discrimination ordinances that protect classes of people not already covered by state law. The law does not mention the LGBT community specifically.
link_name: Arkansas set to pass non-discrimination bill with no LGBT protections

status_message: A court sentenced Russian opposition figure Alexei Navalny to 15 days in jail for breaking a law that restricts demonstrations. He was barred from attending a rally on Russia's struggling economy planned for March 1. He handed out leaflets for the event and used Twitter to encourage people to attend.
link_name: Russian court jails opposition figure Navalny for 15 days

status_message: Seventeen teams were involved in deals just before the 3pm EST trade deadline Feb. 19. Point guard Brandon Knight was traded to the Phoenix Suns. Another point guard, Goran Dragic, went from the Suns to the Miami Heat. Goran's brother Zoran Dragic was traded to the Miami Heat.
link_name: Dozens of players moved at the NBA trade deadline

status_message: In 2014, President Xi Jinping became the first Chinese leader to visit Sri Lanka in 28 years. Sirisena's predecessor Mahinda Rajapaksa struck a $1.5 billion deal giving China the right to develop a port and facilities. Sri Lanka is reconsidering the port deal with China, Reuters reported on Feb. 20.
link_name: Sri Lanka reviews port deal with China amid tensions with India

status_message: A surrogacy law passed Feb. 20 carries a prison sentence of up to 10 years and a $6,200 fine, as well as lesser penalties for surrogacy agencies that break the rules. Thailand's surrogacy industry has gone largely unregulated, leading to widespread accusations of abuse and "fertility tourism."
link_name: Thailand surrogacy law to stop foreigners from using Thai mothers

status_message: Cyclone Lam deteriorated in Northern Territory into a tropical low storm by late Feb. 20. Heavy rain continued to cause local flooding, the Australian Bureau of Meteorology said. Cyclone Marcia's destruction prompted the Insurance Council of Australia to declare some areas catastrophe zones on Feb. 20. Authorities warned of severe flooding if the cyclone, which was downgraded to a category 2 storm, joined up with a storm cell over Brisbane, the Gold and Sunshine Coasts.
link_name: Cyclones lash northern Australia before being downgraded inland

status_message: Myanmar asked China to help it prevent rebel attacks from Chinese territory, Myanmar presidential official Hmuu Zaw said Feb. 19. He called on China to detain Kokang leader Pen Jiasheng and his associates "if they happened to be [in] China."
link_name: Myanmar asks China for military assistance against rebels

status_message: The San Diego Chargers and Oakland Raiders told The LA Times Feb 19 they're proposing a shared, privately financed $1.7 billion stadium in Carson. The teams said the proposal is a contingency plan if publicly subsidized stadium deals in their respective cities don't occur in 2015.
link_name: San Diego Chargers and Oakland Raiders propose shared NFL stadium
Air France-KLM reducing investments by $680 million
Revenge porn site operator Hunter Moore to plead guilty
French gov't survives no-confidence vote after bypassing lawmakers on economic reforms

status_message: The U.S. National Security Agency (NSA) and the UK's Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ) stole the encryption keys used by the world's largest SIM card manufacturer, making it significantly easier to eavesdrop on mobile phone conversations worldwide. The Intercept, based on documents provided by Edward Snowden, first reported the news on Feb. 19.
link_name: Report: NSA, GCHQ hacked into SIM card manufacturer
3,500 Koreans awaiting family reunions died in 2014
UK regulator to investigate investment and corporate banking
Microsoft begins accepting bitcoin for digital content
Coalition against Islamic State meets in Saudi Arabia
Poroshenko calls for int'l peacekeeping mission in Eastern Ukraine

status_message: In a blog post on the company's website, Walmart CEO Doug McMillon announced a plan to raise nearly 500,000 U.S. employees' wages to at least $9. In addition, citing strong quarterly figures, Walmart said it would introduce a "bold new initiative on pay and training" to apply to future employees.
link_name: Walmart to implement company-wide minimum wage of $9/hour
Crowdsourced ideas coming in for new 'MacGyver' series with female lead
UK defense secretary warns of Russian threats to Baltic states
White House names first 'chief data scientist'
Warmer oceans blamed for surge of sea lions on California's shores
Native American activist plans lawsuit over Facebook real name policy

status_message: Google's Inbox email app now supports the Firefox and Safari web browsers, Android tablets, and Apple's iPad. The app, which debuted in October 2014, initially only supported Chrome, Android smartphones, and the iPhone.
link_name: Google adds Safari, tablet support for Inbox email app
Superbug outbreak at UCLA leaves 2 dead, up to 179 exposed
Lenovo publishes instructions on how to remove Superfish adware

status_message: Cyclones Marcia and Lam are expected to make landfall early Feb. 20. Destructive winds of up to 183 miles per hour and torrential rainfall of more than 11 inches are expected to hit the Australian states of Queensland and the Northern Territory, Australia's Bureau of Meteorology said Feb. 19.
link_name: Australia's Top End region braces for Cyclones Marcia and Lam

status_message: A judge investigating how computer files were deleted at the headquarters of Spain's ruling People's Party has misplaced lawsuit documents, Madrid's regional court said Feb. 18. Madrid's High Court asked for the case, which includes accusations of illegal party financing, to be reconstructed.
link_name: Spanish judge investigating government corruption misplaces lawsuit documents

status_message: Greece submitted a formal request Feb. 19 for a six-month extension of loans, Dutch Finance Minister Jeroen Dijsselbloem, who chairs the Eurogroup of euro zone finance ministers, said on Twitter without elaborating. The Greek government released documents a day earlier with its positions on economic reforms.
link_name: Greece submits six-month loan extension request from euro zone

status_message: Thailand's military-appointed attorney general filed three charges with the Supreme Court on Feb. 19, including an anti-corruption charge and two counts of negligence. The court will decide on March 19 whether to proceed against Yingluck, who faces a maximum of 10 years jail.
link_name: Ousted Thai premier charged with corruption and negligence for rice subsidy scheme

status_message: A study released in February found female inmates are "denied basic reproductive health items." Pregnant women "face poor conditions" and have insufficient food, it found. The Correctional Association of New York, an advocacy group that monitors prisons in New York state, conducted the study.
link_name: New York inmates shackled during pregnancy despite state ban, report says
Researchers develop experimental shot that could work as HIV vaccine alternative
This winter is one of the warmest on record for most of the US
Samsung acquires LoopPay mobile payment provider

status_message: The UK passed an amendment to the Criminal Justice and Courts Bill that quadruples the amount of time that online trolls could face in jail, raising the maximum sentence to two years. The amendment applies only to England and Wales.
link_name: UK online trolls to face up to two years in prison

status_message: Italian police raided the homes of 21 women connected to Berlusconi Feb. 17 in search of cash after prosecutors alleged that he paid them off to lie about details of his sex parties in court. The payments, made through Berlusconi's personal accountant, amounted to over $2,500 a month or more.
link_name: Berlusconi accused of tampering with witness testimony, paying 21 women to lie

status_message: Bush laid out his vision for foreign policy during a speech at the Chicago Council on Global Affairs on Feb. 18. Bush criticized Obama's approach to foreign policy saying it is "inconsistent and indecisive," and that Obama has replaced diplomacy with, "hashtag campaigns." He said Obama's approach "no longer inspire[s] fear in our enemies."
link_name: Jeb Bush lays out foreign policy vision in Chicago speech

status_message: Uber Feb. 18 said that it had raised an additional $1 billion as part of its Series E round of funding. That brings the total amount raised in the round to $2.8 billion after the company in December 2014 raised $1.8 billion. The company is now valued at $40 billion.
link_name: Uber raises another $1 billion in funding

status_message: The next round of negotiations to restore full diplomatic ties with Cuba are scheduled to take place Feb. 27 in Washington, the State Department said. Negotiations are being led by Assistant Secretary of State Roberta Jacobson and Josefina Vidal, the Cuban Foreign Ministry's top official for U.S. affairs.
link_name: New round of US-Cuba negotiations scheduled for next week

status_message: National Association of Manufacturers CEO Jay Timmons said during a Feb. 18 interview on CNBC that a total shutdown of the ports could cost $2 billion per day. Timmons said manufacturers are cutting or eliminating hours, and that orders have been lost.
link_name: Total shutdown of West Coast ports could cost $2 billion per day

status_message:
BuzzFeed, the Guardian, and NPR were among several media companies that filed a legal brief Feb. 17 in support of Twitter's lawsuit against the U.S. government over surveillance investigation gag orders.  

The media companies argued that denying Twitter's ability to release detailed information about national security-related requests for user information violates its right to free speech.
link_name: The Guardian, NPR back Twitter in surveillance lawsuit

status_message: According to reports on Feb. 18, President Barack Obama will name Joseph P. Clancy as head of the Secret Service. Clancy, former head of Obama's security detail, has served as interim acting director since Julia Pierson resigned amid scandal in October 2014.
link_name: Joseph Clancy said to have been named acting director of the Secret Service

status_message: Japan Post on Feb. 17 offered buy Australian logistics company Toll Holdings. The merged company will be the world's fifth-largest logistics and freight group in terms of revenue after FedEx Corp., Japan Post said. The deal needs approval by Australia's Foreign Investment Review Board.
link_name: Japan Post bids $5.1 billion for Australian logistics company

status_message: The Swiss attorney general led a raid of the offices of HSBC's Geneva subsidiary, HSBC Private Bank. Prosecutors also announced the launch of a criminal probe "for suspected aggravated money laundering." The investigation was into the bank and could extend to individuals, Geneva's prosecutor said.
link_name: Swiss prosecutors open HSBC criminal probe and raid its offices

status_message: On Feb. 18, Pres. Widodo named interim police chief Badrodin Haiti to take the position full time. The candidate needs parliamentary approval. He replaced three-star general, Budi Gunawan even though a court cleared Gunawan on Feb. 15 of abuse of power.
link_name: Indonesian president nominates new police chief after bribery allegations stir outcry

status_message: Haiti canceled the third and final day of Carnival due to the deadly accident, Prime Minister Evans Paul said Feb. 17. The country is holding three days of mourning and will give the victims a state funeral.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The number of asylum seekers arriving to Italy in February exceeded the January total of 3,528 who arrived in January, Italy's Ministry of Interior said Feb. 17. The International Organization for Migration (IOM) warns the 2015 human smuggling season started early "with potentially lethal consequences."
link_name: More than 7,000 asylum seekers have fled across the Mediterranean in 2015

status_message: On Feb. 17, the Limestone County court set a bench trial for April 29 for Eric Parker, who pleaded not guilty to third degree assault. Alabama Governor Robert Bentley ordered a parallel police investigation into the case. Parker's actions did not meet the "high standards" of the department, Madison's police chief said.
link_name: Alabama policeman pleads not guilty to assault that partially paralyzed Indian man

status_message: AIDS Healthcare Foundation President Michael Weinstein filed a ballot initiative proposal with the state of California on Feb. 17 that would ask voters to decide whether pornography actors should be required wear condoms in California-filmed movies.
link_name: Advocates want California voters to decide if pornography actors must wear condoms
Mars One announces 100 finalists for human colony plan

status_message: The White House said in a video Feb. 17 that 11.4 million people have signed up for private health coverage. The figure beats the administration's target of 9 million signups for 2015.
link_name: White House says 11.4 million people have enrolled for Obamacare
Zillow completes $2.5 billion acquisition of Trulia
Carnegie Mellon mistakenly tells 800 applicants they were admitted
Sony opens pre-orders for SmartEyeglass
US approves sale of military drones to allies
TweetDeck updated to allow sharing accounts without sharing passwords

status_message: A Moscow court on Feb. 17 lifted opposition figure Alexi Navalny's house arrest while upholding his suspended 3.5-year sentence.
link_name: Russian court ends opposition critic Alexei Navalny's house arrest
Myanmar declares state of emergency in restive border region
Bypassing legislature, French gov't passes economic reforms by decree
Cleveland sees cash boost from the return of LeBron James
AT&T using targeted ads to subsidize gigabit broadband
Family of unarmed Mexican national files claim after police shooting
France is tracking hundreds of suspected sleeper agents

status_message: On Feb. 17, Anthony "Tony" Bosch was sentenced to four years in prison for charges of steroid distribution, the maximum federal sentence. Bosch pleaded guilty in Oct. 2014, and his sentence may be reduced if he agrees to help with an ongoing investigation.
link_name: Tony Bosch, center of an MLB doping scandal, sentenced to 4 years

status_message: At least two plumes in the spring of 2012 on Mars reached 200 kilometers (124.3 miles) in altitude over a large area, a study published Feb. 16 in Nature said. Other plumes have been spotted on the Red Planet before, but never at this altitude, scientists said. The plumes also lasted for weeks.
link_name: High-altitude plumes spotted on Mars in 2012 remain unexplained

status_message: Prosecutors appealed Navalny's sentence on a theft conviction, asking for an increase to 10 years, Russian news agency RIA reported Feb. 17. The announcement came two days after police detained Navalny and fellow opposition campaigner Nikolay Lyashkin for distributing leaflets for a protest planned for March 1.
link_name: Russian prosecutors want 10-year jail term for Putin critic

status_message: Transocean CEO Steven Newman will step down as chief executive and relinquish his seat on the oil drilling company's board, the company said Feb. 16. Transocean Chairman Ian Strachan will become interim CEO. Newman's departure was seen as a surprise by the industry.
link_name: Transocean CEO resigns as oil revenues fall

status_message: New home prices fell 5.1% year-on-year in January, the largest decline on record, China's National Bureau of Statistics said Feb. 16. Sixty-four of the 70 major cities that are tracked saw month-to-month declines from Dec. 2014 to Jan. 2015, with 69 cities seeing year-on-year declines.
link_name: New home prices in China suffer largest year-on-year drop on record

status_message: Egypt signed a deal with France on Feb. 16 worth 5.2 billion euros ($5.9B) to purchase 24 Rafale jets (pictured), a naval frigate, and air-to-air missiles. The deal diversifies Egypt's military, which primarily relies on U.S. equipment. It was the first successful deal to sell Rafale jets abroad.
link_name: Egypt signs $5.9 billion arms deal with France

status_message: U.S. District Judge Andrew Hanen ordered a temporary halt to the president's executive action on Feb. 16. The ruling stems from a Dec. 2014 lawsuit by 26 states that argues the president overstepped his authority by issuing the executive action.
link_name: Texas federal judge issues temporary halt to Obama immigration action

status_message: Walmart filed a complaint in federal court against the state of Texas, challenging a state law that blocks most publicly traded companies from selling alcoholic products other than beer and wine.
link_name: Walmart sues Texas for permission to sell hard liquor
Emergencies declared in five southern states ahead of storm
'Perfect' emerald-cut diamond could fetch up to $25 million at auction
Chargers tell San Diego they are 'keeping a close eye' on LA stadium
Facebook pressured by Native American users to revise real name policy

status_message: The IMF's Catastrophe Containment and Relief (CCR) Trust aims to provide debt relief to countries in West Africa struggling to fight Ebola outbreaks. Liberia, Sierra Leone, and Guinea will be the first nations to receive a total of $100 million dollar in grants from CCR.
link_name: IMF builds fund to support disaster relief in low-income African countries

status_message: Swiss stocks have rebounded slightly and volatility has been staved off after a January decision to lift a cap on the country's exchange rate. The Swiss Market Index rose by 9.5% on Feb. 16 from a one-year low of 7,899 on Jan. 16.
link_name: Switzerland rebounds from economic hit after franc's revaluation

status_message: Lance Armstrong was found guilty of "perjury, fraud and conspiracy" and was ordered to pay $10 million dollars in damages to Dallas-based SCA Promotions on Feb. 16.
link_name: Lance Armstrong found guilty of fraud, ordered to pay $10M

status_message: Two former prostitutes, who had provided testimony in the criminal case, dropped their civil case against Strauss-Kahn on Feb. 16. Their attorney said the move was made because it would be difficult to prove that Strauss-Kahn knew the women were prostitutes.
link_name: Ex-prostitutes drop civil case against DSK, criminal trial continues

status_message: VA Sec. Robert McDonald said during an NBC Meet the Press interview Feb. 15 that 900 people have been fired in connection with the scandals since he took over the agency and that the VA is making "fundamental changes... in terms of leadership." The VA said in Nov. 2014 that 5,600 people had been disciplined.
link_name: Veterans Affairs chief: 900 people have been fired over vet scandal

status_message: "Saturday Night Live" celebrated its 40th anniversary on Feb. 15 with a primetime Sunday special, which average an impressive 23.1 million viewers.
link_name: 'SNL' 40th anniversary show breaks NBC ratings record

status_message: DPP leader Tsai Ing-wen on Feb. 15 formally registered to participate in the March primary. She is not only expected to run unopposed in her party, but is considered the favorite to win the presidency in 2016. Her party routed the ruling KMT party of President Ma Ying-jeou in local elections in Nov. 2014.
link_name: Taiwan opposition leader registers for 2016 presidential election

status_message: Ferry captain Lai Sai-ming was sentenced to eight years in prison on Feb. 16. He was found guilty Feb. 14 of 39 counts of manslaughter, or one count for each of the deceased. The captain of the Lamma IV was acquitted of manslaughter, but was convicted of endangering the safety of others. He was sentenced to nine months in prison Feb. 16.
link_name: Captains in deadly 2012 Hong Kong ferry crash sentenced to prison

status_message: India on Feb. 15 defeated rival Pakistan by 76 runs in Adelaide, Australia in group play in the World Cup. India defeated Pakistan in 2011 in the World Cup semifinal on its way to winning the championship that year.
link_name: India, Ireland win early Cricket World Cup matches

status_message: Despite poor reviews, "Fifty Shades of Grey" earned $81.67 million at the North American box office in its opening weekend of Feb. 13-15. The revenue is a Valentine's Day weekend record. Once ticket sales are counted for Feb. 16, it will have a 4-day President's Day weekend record as well.
link_name: "Fifty Shades of Grey" ropes in $81.67 million over Valentine's Day weekend

status_message: Preliminary data showed Japan's gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 0.6% in Q4 2014, bringing the country out of recession, the government said Feb. 16. GDP also grew 2.2% year-on-year in the Oct.-Dec. 2014 quarter, but the growth was lower than the 3.7% predicted by analysts.
link_name: Japan exits recession with first quarter of growth since early 2014

status_message: An Italian and Maltese rescue operation Feb. 15 pulled more than 2,100 migrants from 12 boats from Libya and brought them to Italy, Italian emergency services said. Four armed men in a speed boat intercepted the Italian coast guard and took one of the empty migrant boats, Italy's transport ministry said.
link_name: Rescue operation pulls more than 2,100 migrants from boats on the Mediterranean

status_message: Kolinda Graber-Kitarovic, 46, was sworn in Feb. 15 in Zagreb. She began her five-year term by promising to work "to make Croatia a wealthy nation." She campaigned to decentralize the government by giving more power to regional authorities.
link_name: Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovic sworn in as first female president in Croatia

status_message: Approximately 20,000 anti-austerity protesters gathered in Athens on Feb. 15, the day before newly-elected Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras was to meet with eurozone finance ministers in an attempt to renegotiate the country's 240 billion euro bailout.
link_name: Tens of thousands rally in Greece to protest bailout

status_message: A video that appeared Feb. 15 on the Twitter feed of a website that supports the Islamic State purportedly shows the execution of 21 Egyptian Coptic Christians kidnapped in Libya in January.
link_name: New Islamic State video purportedly shows execution of 21 Christian Egyptians

status_message: The FAA on Feb. 15 released proposals for regulating commercial drone use in U.S. skies.
link_name: FAA announces proposed federal regulations for drone use
UK leaders announce joint commitment on climate change

status_message: A new snowstorm is hitting the Northeast over the Feb. 14-15 weekend. Many areas of Massachusetts had more than a foot of new snow by 11am on Feb. 15, and some areas of the state had two feet of new accumulation. Most of New England is forecasted to see several more inches of snow through Feb. 16.
link_name: US Northeast hit with new snowstorm

status_message: The Polar Star was towing the Antarctic Chieftain, an Australian-flagged fishing boat, to open waters on Feb. 15. The Chieftain's propellers were too damaged to function in the ice, according to New Zealand's search and rescue organization. The ship's hull was undamaged and no oil spilled.
link_name: US icebreaker tows Australian fishing boat trapped in Antarctica

status_message: The U.N. Committee on Enforced Disappearances (UNCED) said Feb. 13 that Mexico needs to investigate tens-of-thousands of "enforced disappearances" -- people who have been kidnapped by, or whose abductions are permitted by authorities. UNCED is calling on Mexico to pass a law making enforced disappearance a crime.
link_name: UN calls on Mexico to investigate tens-of-thousands of 'disappearances'
Ukraine ceasefire goes into effect
Two charged in foiled Nova Scotia Valentine's Day mall shooting plot

status_message: The Postal Service is soliciting bids from automakers to design and manufacture the next generation of delivery trucks, which would replace the aging fleet of iconic, boxy Grumman "Long Life Vehicles" it currently uses.
link_name: USPS seeks to replace aging fleet of delivery trucks
South Sudan's cabinet seeks to postpone elections until 2017
Shots fired, one person killed, at Copenhagen free speech event

status_message: Alibaba confirmed Feb. 13 that the SEC had asked it for more information regarding a recent report by Chinese regulators claiming that many of the goods sold on the company's consumer website Taobao were counterfeit. Alibaba said it would cooperate with the SEC, but stressed that it was not a formal investigation.
link_name: SEC probes Alibaba regarding counterfeit goods
Sandy Hook Advisory Commission report calls for comprehensive reform

status_message: Deezer has now begun the global rollout of its Deezer Elite high-resolution streaming audio service.
link_name: Deezer rolling out high-end streaming music service worldwide
FDA approves new GMO apples
Bankrupt SkyMall attracts bidder with plan to save struggling in-flight catalog
Utah House votes to reintroduce firing squads for capital punishment
Nike drops FuelBand wristband requirement for mobile app
Google revises bug-reporting following Microsoft complaint
Flu season is ebbing, CDC says
Dow ends week above 18,000, S&P 500 sets new record

status_message: SIGAR released a report Feb. 12 on $20M incinerators that were never used. U.S. troops burned trash including hazardous materials in open-air pits even after the Pentagon made policies against them in 2009. SIGAR has hired people to write about "lessons learned" in Afghanistan, agency head John Sopko said.
link_name: US watchdog urges 'lessons learned' from Afghanistan war

status_message: Eric Parker, one of the two police officers who injured Patel, was arrested Feb. 12 on charges of assault and will be fired, Madison Police Chief Larry Muncey said. Muncey also apologized to Patel's family. The FBI is investigating the case. The probe's details will be reported to the U.S. Justice Department.

status_message: At least 10 people were killed and dozens were injured in a series of blasts and gunfire at a Shiite mosque near Peshawar, officials said. A provincial minister confirmed that a suicide bomber carried out at least one blast.

status_message: At least eight troops and three civilians were killed in fighting in eastern Ukraine within the previous 24 hours, the Ukrainian government said Feb. 13. Another 34 Ukrainian troops were injured. The heaviest fighting was near Debaltseve between Donetsk and Luhansk.
link_name: Ukrainian soldiers, civilians killed as ceasefire approaches

status_message: Burmese state media said that 47 troops were killed and over 70 others injured in clashes with Kokang rebels in the preceding few days. No casualty figures were given for civilians or rebels. It is unclear who is in control of the provincial capital of Laukkai. Several civilians fled, including some to China.

status_message: China's Cyberspace Affairs Administration (CAA) is focusing on "fraud" and "prostitution" on dating websites in China, the CAA said Feb. 12. The sites "must enforce online real-name registration" and accounts that do not comply "must be closed," according to state media.

The ban only applies to photos or videos that are shared, online or offline, with the explicit intent to harm the other person. The UK justice secretary noted that it was "almost beyond belief" that people would share such material with the intent to cause harm.

status_message:
Alabama police officer accused of partially paralyzing Indian grandfather:

When Sureshbhai Patel was approached by Madison, Ala. police responding to a call Feb. 6 about a suspicious person looking into garages, he repeatedly said, "no English" and "India," and pulled away when officer attempted to pat him down. Officers say they were attempting to frisk for a weapon when Patel put his hand in his pocket and was then forced to the ground.

status_message: Wearable computing company Fitbit is now recommending that users occasionally "take a break" from wearing its devices to avoid rashes and other forms of skin irritation. Fitbit claims that only a "very limited percentage" of users have complained about skin irritation, and that this can be caused by wearing the devices too tightly.
link_name: Fitbit recommends wearers 'take a break' to avoid rashes

status_message: Myanmar President Thein Sein on Feb. 11 approved a law that would allow a referendum to make amendments to the country's constitution, a lawmaker told Reuters. The changes in the constitution, if made, could allow opposition leader and Nobel Laureate Aung San Suu Kyi to run for president in the elections in 2015.
link_name: Myanmar approves law to allow referendum on constitution

status_message: Expedia said Feb. 11 that it had agreed to acquire rival travel service Orbitz in an all-cash deal valued at $1.6 billion. Both companies' boards of directors have already approved the deal, though it still requires regulatory approval.
link_name: Expedia buys Orbitz for $1.6 billion

status_message: Job cuts in the energy sector have exceeded 100,000 globally recently, Bloomberg reported Feb. 12. About 40% of the 53,041 job cuts planned for early 2015 by U.S.-based firms were directly related to oil prices, according to a report by outplacement firm Challenger, Gray & Christmas.
link_name: Falling crude prices take toll on global oil jobs

status_message: Australia's unemployment rate rose to 6.4% in January, up from 6.1% in Dec. 2014. The rate is the highest in the country since August 2002. The total number of unemployed in Australia was 795,200, including people looking for full and part-time work.
link_name: Australia's unemployment rate reaches 12-year high

status_message: Pinterest is launching "App Pins" on Feb. 12. The card will work like other Pins but will let users download apps directly onto iOS devices. Pinterest says it will not make money on the downloads.

status_message: The U.S. Feb. 11 filed a complaint with the World Trade Organization (WTO) over what is says are unfair competition practices by China in seven industries, including agriculture, textiles and advanced materials.

status_message: District official Kusen Andalas said that a proposal for a virginity test for girls at the district's high school raised by a member of the district parliament the week before would not be implemented. Human Rights Watch, Islamic leaders and others denounced the proposal.

status_message: On Feb. 12, New Zealand asked the U.S. Coast Guard to send the Polar Star to help rescue the "Antarctic Chieftain," an Australian-flagged fishing boat trapped by ice.

The ACLU and professors at the UC Irvine School of Law filed a lawsuit Feb. 10 seeking information on "roving patrols" by the U.S. Border Patrol that extend nearly 100 miles into U.S. territory from the border. They previously submitted a a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request.

status_message: Sri Lanka's Northern Provincial Council on Feb. 10 passed a resolution accusing successive governments of committing genocide against Tamils. status_message: Apple will invest $848 million in First Solar's California solar farm and will get power under a 25-year purchase agreement, the companies said Feb. 10. The construction of the 2,900-acre "California Flats Solar Project" will begin mid-2015 and be completed by the end of 2016.
link_name: Apple to invest $848 million in California solar power plant

status_message: South Korean coast guard commander Kim Kyung-Il was found guilty Feb. 11 of professional negligence resulting in death over the ferry disaster. He was sentenced to four years in prison. Kim's coast guard boat was the first on the scene of the rescue, but contributed to what was widely regarded as a slow response.
link_name: Coast guard officer sentenced to 4 years for South Korea ferry disaster

status_message: Asiana Airlines will buy 25 A321neo planes from Airbus for 3.1 trillion won ($2.83 billion), the South Korean airline said in a regulatory filing Feb. 11. The 180-seater planes will be delivered in 2019 through 2025. Asiana operates 33 single-aisle A320 and A321 jets and will replace the A321s with A321neos.
link_name: South Korea's Asiana Airlines to buy Airbus jets for $2.8 billion

status_message: Walter Storey, 47, was executed by lethal injection after midnight Feb. 11 for the 1990 murder of a neighbor. The U.S. Supreme Court in a 5-4 vote denied his appeal to stay the execution on the grounds that Missouri does not make public where it gets the drugs for lethal injections.
link_name: Missouri inmate executed after Supreme Court denies appeal

status_message: The White House said late on Feb. 10 that President Obama will announce Feb. 11 that about 1,200 of the remaining 1,300 troops deployed to West Africa in 2014 to aid in the Ebola epidemic will leave the region by April 30. Around 1,500 troops have already departed.
link_name: Obama to recall troops sent to West Africa to aid in Ebola effort

status_message: Prosecutors say Navy officers helped Leonard "Fat Leonard" Francis, head of Glenn Defense Marine Asia, gain multimillion-dollar contracts, including giving him confidential ship routes. Francis bribed the officers with prostitutes, travel and gifts. He's also accused of overcharging the Navy $20 million.

status_message: Lawyers filed a petition Feb. 8 to ban the Israel Hayom newspaper during elections, saying it is "a propaganda platform... masquerading as a newspaper." Netanyahu blamed the Yediot Ahronot newspaper and the Ynet website on Feb. 9 for "smear attacks" against him and his wife. The outlets aim "to topple the Likud's leadership headed by me, and to close Israel Hayom," he said.

status_message: Leaked audio aired Feb. 7 purportedly of Egyptian President Abdel Fatah Al-Sisi and two top advisors described a request for Gulf donors to send billions directly to the Egyptian military. The men also joked about the wealth of Gulf leaders. The Egyptian prime minister on Feb. 9 called the recordings "lies."

status_message: The heads of Benghazi medical facilities told officials hospitals were stretched beyond their limits. Hospitals were facing shortages of staff and supplies, and equipment was falling into disrepair. At least two hospitals were forced to close, leaving only two functioning in the city.

status_message: The ruling BJP was headed for its worst defeat in regional elections since coming to power in May 2014. It was leading only in two assembly constituencies in Delhi out of 70 and won one by midday Feb. 10. The Aam Admi Party (AAP) was projected to form a government as it was leading in 41 constituencies and won 26.
link_name: Aam Admi Party to form government in Delhi, Modi's BJP concedes defeat

status_message: The Italian Coast Guard said Feb. 9 that 29 migrants captured at sea had died of hypothermia before it could get them to land for medical treatment. A total of 105 migrants were taken off the inflatable boat, which encountered rough seas en route from Libya.
link_name: Twenty-nine migrants die of hypothermia while trying to reach Italy

status_message: Malaysia's top court on Feb. 10 upheld the sodomy conviction of opposition leader Anwar Ibrahim and sentenced him to five years in prison. With this conviction Anwar has been disqualified from seeking office and cannot participate in elections due in 2018.
link_name: Malaysian court upholds opposition leader Anwar Ibrahim's sodomy conviction

status_message: Right-handed starting pitcher James Shields signed a signed a 4-year, $75 million contract with the San Diego Padres. The deal, which is pending a physical likely to take place on Feb. 10, is the latest in a number of acquisitions by the Padres in the offseason, including a trade for Matt Kemp.
link_name: Pitcher James Shields signs $75 million contract with Padres

status_message: Oregon Attorney General Ellen Rosenblum opened an investigation Feb. 6 into reports that Gov. John Kitzhaber's fiancee, Cylvia Hayes, used her role in his office for personal gain. Rosenblum called the allegations "very serious - and troubling." Kitzhaber wrote to Rosenblum Feb. 9, asking for a "factual review."

status_message: Japan's cabinet changed the country's Development Cooperation Charter on Feb. 10. It allows the government to provide funds to foreign militaries for non-combat purposes, including disaster relief.

status_message: Operations returned to all 29 ports on Feb. 9. Contract negotiations will resume Feb. 11. status_message: UN-brokered talks on Yemen's political disputes resumed on Feb. 9, but ended quickly after two parties walked out.

status_message: A few hundred people marched near the border with mainland China to protest "parallel traders," or mainland Chinese that visit Hong Kong to buy goods for resale on the mainland. The protesters complain that traders overwhelm the streets. Police used pepper spray and arrested at least 12 people at a mall.
link_name: Police use pepper spray at Hong Kong protest against mainland China shoppers

status_message: China's exports and imports both fell in January, the government said Feb. 8. Imports had their largest decline since May 2009 in January, falling 19.9% year-on-year, much more than analysts expected. Exports fell by 3.3% year-on-year in January, after rising 9.7% year-on-year in Dec. 2014.
link_name: China's imports fall by largest margin since 2009

status_message: Seven people were arrested in connection with a brutal gang rape and murder of a mentally challenged woman, police said. The women went missing on Feb. 1. Her body was found on Feb. 4 with several injuries and some parts missing.

status_message: "Boyhood" won the 2015 BAFTA for best film on Feb. 8. The film also took home BAFTA's for Patricia Arquette for supporting actress and Richard Linklater for directing.
link_name: "Boyhood" wins best film at BAFTA

status_message: Won Sei-hoon was found guilty by an appellate court Feb. 9 in relation to an online smear campaign against opposition candidates during presidential election in Dec. 2012. He was sentenced to three years in prison. He was South Korea's top spy until March 2013 and was indicted in June 2013.
link_name: South Korea's ex-spy chief found guilty of ignoring election smear campaign

status_message: Liu Han, the former head of a major Chinese conglomerate, was executed Feb. 9. Liu's brother Lui Wei and three others were also executed for leading a crime organization that killed and intimidated Liu's rivals. Liu was sentenced to death in May 2014. He has been linked to Zhou Yongkang's son.
link_name: Chinese billionaire, 4 others, executed for 'mafia-style' gang

status_message: Feb. 8 brought the start of another snowstorm in New England. The slow-moving storm closed Boston schools on Feb. 9 and 10. All non-emergency Massachusetts state employees have Feb. 9 off. More than 1,300 flights were canceled for Feb. 9.

status_message: Meizu and Alibaba said Feb. 9 that Alibaba has invested $590 million for an undisclosed state in Meizu, which makes relatively inexpensive smartphones similar to the much larger Xiaomi.
link_name: Alibaba invests $590 million in Chinese smartphone maker Meizu

status_message: Beck won Album of the Year and Best Rock Album for "Morning Phase." Sam Smith won Song of the Year, Best New Artist and Best Pop Vocal Album.
link_name: Sam Smith, Beck take top Grammy honors

status_message: The low-tech police practice of observing snowless rooftops, caused by the equipment and heat needed to grow marijuana indoors, seems to be widespread. The strategy produced two raids and arrests in early February.
link_name: Dutch police look to rooftops to bust illegal marijuana growers

status_message: The Ivory Coast beat Ghana on penalties 9-8 after their game ended in a 0-0 draw to win the Africa Cup of Nations title on Feb. 8. Goalkeeper Boubacar Barry scored the decisive goal for the Ivorians, who won their first title since 1992.
link_name: Ivory Coast wins first Africa Cup of Nations title in 23 years

status_message: Egyptian authorities have decided to start the retrial for two jailed Al Jazeera journalists, according to attorneys representing Baher Mohamed and Mohamed Fahmy. The men will return to court beginning on Feb. 12. Australian Al Jazeera journalist Peter Greste was released Feb. 1 and deported.
link_name: Egypt sets Feb. 12 retrial date for jailed Al Jazeera journalists

status_message: Germany has seen more than 375 cases of measles since Oct. 2014, according to the Robert Koch Institute. Two-thirds of those occurred in January, with most cases concentrated around Berlin and its surrounding state.
link_name: Germany records 254 cases of measles in January outbreak

status_message: Turkey's spy chief Hakan Fidan resigned to run for parliament in June, two senior officials said Feb. 7. Erdogan would gain a strong ally in parliament if Fidan were elected.

status_message: SpaceX will make a second attempt at landing a rocket on an ocean barge at 6:10 pm Eastern on Feb. 8. The rocket will launch a weather satellite into orbit before the attempted landing on an autonomous barge named "Just Read the Instructions," 370 miles from the coast of Florida.
link_name: SpaceX to attempt second landing of a rocket on ocean barge

status_message: Jordan said Feb. 8 it conducted 56 airstrikes in 3 days of sorties in Iraq and Syria. The strikes were part of Jordan's "relentless" and "earthshaking" response to the brutal killing of a Jordanian pilot at the hands of the Islamic State.

status_message: Prime Minister Abbott on Feb. 8 called for a party "spill vote" on his leadership to occur on Feb. 9, a day earlier than previously scheduled. The earlier vote was to "end the uncertainty," he said. Removing Abbott would require approval of more than 50% of the 102 party members voting.
link_name: Tony Abbott pushes up party vote on his leadership

status_message: The African Union agreed Feb. 7 to send 8,700 troops from Nigeria, Chad, Cameroon, Niger and Benin to fight Boko Haram. The decision was an increase from the 7,500 troops approved a week earlier. The forces will include soldiers, policemen and civilians. Neither a budget nor a deployment timetable was given.

status_message: The commission said on Feb. 7 that they were studying possible sanctions for bishops suspected of covering up or failing to prevent sex abuse. "There have to be consequences," said Cardinal Sean O'Malley of Boston. The gathering marked the first full meeting of the commission since it was formed.
link_name: Vatican sex abuse commission considering sanctions over coverups

status_message: The UN Security Council discussed a draft resolution on Feb. 6 that would ban the sale of antiquities from Syria, similar to a move passed by the Council a decade ago to curb looting in Iraq. The resolution will ask all 193 UN member states to take action, requiring them to report back in 90 days with steps taken.

status_message: Approximately 100,000 Seattle Seahawks t-shirts, hats and hoodies, all emblazoned with "Super Bowl Champions" and "Back 2 Back," will not go on sale to the public but instead will be sent to countries most in need of clothing.

status_message: Brian Williams told his staff Feb. 7 that he had "decided to take myself off of my daily broadcast for the next several days." Lester Holt will anchor the show in his absence.

status_message:
129 workers rescued at garment factory in Mexico where they were abused:

Authorities, working off an anonymous tip, raided the factory Feb. 4 and arrested four South Korean nationals who were managers and owners of the factory. The garment factory is run by a South Korean firm called Yes International.
link_name: 129 workers rescued at garment factory in Mexico where they were abused

status_message:
Canada's Supreme Court strikes down ban against doctor-assisted suicide:

In a landmark unanimous decision, Canada's Supreme Court ruled that the provision against aiding and abetting someone to commit suicide deprives people suffering from grievous and irremediable medical conditions the right to life, liberty and security of the person.
link_name: Canada's Supreme Court strikes down ban against doctor-assisted suicide

status_message:
6 of 88 detainees released after 2009 're-engaged', down from 101:

The director of the National Counterterrorism Center told a U.S. Senate panel on Feb. 5 that the re-engagement rate of the 88 detainees released from Guantanamo between Jan. 2009 and Sept. 2014 was 6.8%, or 6, down from 33.3% prior to 2009. The Obama administration has tried to make the case that recidivism rates have declined while he has been in office.
link_name: 6 of 88 Guantanamo detainees released after 2009 're-engaged', down from 101

status_message:
Senators call for investigation into Verizon supercookie tracking technology:

At issue is Verizon's use of a mobile phone tracking technology commonly called a supercookie. The supercookie uses a unique identifier of each mobile phone to track customers' browsing habits. The goal of the technology is to be able to serve better targeted ads based on users' browsing habits and interests.
link_name: Senators call for investigation into Verizon supercookie tracking technology

status_message:
Gauguin painting sells for record sum of $300 million

An oil painting by famed French Post-Impressionist artist Paul Gaugin has been sold by the Rudolf Staechelin Family Trust, a Swiss private collection, and purchased by Qatar Museums Authority, according to the New York Times.
link_name: Gauguin painting sells for record sum of $300 million

status_message: Chancellor Angela Merkel of Germany and France's President Francois Hollande announced a surprise visit to Moscow, Feb. 6, to speak directly with Russian President Vladimir Putin on the now year-long conflict in Ukraine. The pair met with Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko Feb. 5.
link_name: Merkel and Hollande visit Putin to discuss Ukraine

status_message:
UK court imprisons man for 12 years for fighting with extremists in Syria:

A UK court on Feb. 6 gave Imran Khawaja, 27, a 12-year sentence on charges related to fighting with extremists in Syria. Khawaja was arrested in June 2014 after returning to the UK and faking his own death to go undetected. He has been featured in recruitment videos. He will serve a minimum of eight years.
link_name: UK court imprisons man for 12 years for fighting with extremists in Syria

status_message:
California regulations allow oil waste into protected water aquifers:

State regulators have allowed oil companies to inject waste fluids into federally-protected aquifers with more than 2,500 permits, an AP analysis published Feb. 5 found. Many of the permits date back decades, but 46% were in the last four years under Gov. Jerry Brown. Most came after the 1974 Safe Drinking Water Act.
link_name: California regulations allow oil waste into protected water aquifers

status_message: A U.S. District court ruled Feb. 4 that former Lady Gaga producer Rob Fusari must pay $7.3 million to Wendy Starland, the woman who helped 'discover' the singer-songwriter. Starland was awarded half the profits from the singer's career in a 2014 court ruling.
link_name: Producer owes $7.3 million to woman who discovered Lady Gaga

status_message: Uber said on Feb. 5 that it will introduce an in-app panic button for app users in India that would allow riders to alert the local police and a feature to share their trip details and real-time location with family and friends. Uber said the features will be available on its app from Feb. 11.
link_name: Uber to introduce in-app panic buttons in India

status_message:
UK tribunal rules some intelligence sharing with US was unlawful:

The UK Investigatory Powers Tribunal (IPT) ruled Feb. 6 that some intelligence-sharing between UK and U.S. spy agencies was unlawful. The IPT found GCHQ was not transparent through Dec. 2014, but has since been compliant. It was the first ruling against a spy agency since the IPT was created in 2000, the BBC said.
link_name: UK tribunal rules some intelligence sharing with US was unlawful

status_message: The U.S. added 257,000 jobs in January, the Labor Dept. reported Feb. 6. Economists had expected the country to add 230,000. The overall unemployment rose slightly to 5.7% from 5.6%. December was revised up to 329,000 from 252,000 jobs added.
link_name: US adds 257,000 jobs in January, but unemployment rises to 5.7%
