status_message: Thai authorities raided a Buddhist temple known as the Tiger Temple, seizing more than 100 tigers and dozens of protected wild birds, officials said. Authorities were investigating possible links to wildlife trafficking. The animals and birds are being kept in the temple until investigations are complete.
link_name: Authorities raid Thailand Tiger Temple on suspected wildlife trafficking

status_message: Crude oil prices remained volatile on Feb. 6. Brent was trading up 2.2% at $57.80 and U.S. crude was up 2.54% at $51.76 at 3:25pm Singapore time. Brent and U.S. crude rose over 4% on Feb. 5 on clashes at a Libyan oil field and a move by China's central bank to ease cash reserve requirements for banks.
link_name: Crude oil prices rise in volatile trading

status_message: East Timor Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao, 68, submitted his resignation to President Taur Matan Ruak. The president has not yet announced whether or not he will accept the resignation, which is part of an effort to "restructure" the government. The two men will meet later to decide Gusmao's fate.
link_name: East Timor prime minister resigns

status_message: The level of neonicotinoid insecticides used for agriculture impairs bumblebees' brain cells, according to a study published Jan. 29. Researchers say the study doesn't prove neonicotinoids are solely responsible for the global decline in insect pollinators, but that a clear relationship has been established.
link_name: Bumblebee brains damaged by neonicotinoid pesticides, researchers show

status_message: University of South Florida researchers submitted a report to the Florida Cabinet on Feb. 3 about their work. A total of 51 individuals have been found in 55 graves. The updated information includes two more identifications, bringing the total number of remains identified through DNA to five.
link_name: Report details deaths and abuse uncovered at former Florida reform school

status_message: Starting in March, pension checks will shrink by 6.7% for retired city workers in Detroit. In addition, retirees and current employees must repay some $212 million in excess interest accrued through a municipal savings plan.
link_name: Detroit pensioners forced to pay back excess interest
Investigators find no problems with signals, barrier in fatal New York train accident
15,000 pre-Columbian relics found along Nicaragua canal route

status_message:
Obama wants $133 million to fight heroin and prescription drug overdose:

President Obama is requesting $133 million in new funding from Congress to fight overdoses from prescription painkillers and heroin. The bulk of the funding, about $60 million, will go to states to help fighting the epidemic. The rest of the funding will be split between federal agencies.
link_name: Obama wants $133 million to fight heroin and prescription drug overdose

status_message: RadioShack filed for bankruptcy on Feb. 5, after 94 years in business. The company said it would sell off as many as 2,400 of its 4,000 stores to hedge fund Standard General, the company's largest investor. Sprint will move into 1,750 of the acquired stores, according to the Wall Street Journal.
link_name: RadioShack files for bankruptcy

status_message:
Call of Duty series surpasses $11 billion in sales:

Activision said Feb. 5 the "Call of Duty" series has generated more than $11 billion in sales since the first game was released in 2003. Activision pegged that number at $10 billion in November 2014. Activision said "Advanced Warfare" was the top-selling game worldwide in 2014 but did not say how many units it shipped.
link_name: Call of Duty series surpasses $11 billion in sales
Arizona takes up bill that would allow direct Tesla sales
Two killed in shooting at the University of South Carolina
Defense in Hernandez trial accuses police of shoddy treatment of crime scene

status_message:
Sony Pictures co-chairman Amy Pascal to step down:

Pascal was heavily criticized in December 2014 after emails leaked as part of the cyberattack appeared to show her joking that President Obama's favorite movies were "Django Unchained" and "12 Years A Slave." Pascal later apologized for the "cultural blindness" displayed in the emails.
link_name: Sony Pictures co-chairman Amy Pascal to step down

status_message:
Lawyer refutes claims Harper Lee didn't approve release of new novel:

Friends and residents of Monroeville, Alabama, where Lee resides in an assisted living facility, told Alabama Local News Feb. 4 that they believe "Go Set a Watchman" is being published against the author's will. Sawyer noted that Lee's health has been in decline since a 2007 stroke that also left her largely deaf, saying, Lee's "mind is not in a condition to make these decisions."
link_name: Lawyer refutes claims Harper Lee didn't approve release of new novel
Swatch to release smartwatch within three months

status_message:
Greece leader says he opposes 'blackmail' as talks continue with ECB:

The European Central Bank (ECB) on Feb. 4 said it would not accept junk-rated Greek bonds as collateral against loans, starting Feb. 11. The move will force the Greek central bank to pump money into the country's banks. Greece said on Feb. 5 that the country's banks were adequately capitalized and fully protected.
link_name: Greece leader says he opposes 'blackmail' as talks continue with ECB

status_message:
Iraqi government lifting decade-old curfew in Baghdad:

Prime Minister Haider Al-Abadi ordered the end of a curfew in Baghdad on Feb. 5. It will go into effect Feb. 7. The decision was to "facilitate the movement of citizens" and return life to normal "despite the existence of a state of war," Al-Abadi's spokesman said. Baghdad had a vibrant nightlife before the 2003 U.S.-led invasion.
link_name: Iraqi government lifting decade-old curfew in Baghdad

status_message:
Germany proposes 'cooling off' period for politicians before entering private sector:

The German government on Feb. 4 began discussing a draft bill to restrict politicians from entering private-sector companies and lobby groups before the end of a one-year 'cooling off' period. In exceptional cases, the period could be extended to 18 months.
link_name: Germany proposes 'cooling off' period for politicians before entering private sector

status_message: Julia Garratt was released on bail on Feb. 3 after six months in detention, the Garratt family said Feb. 5. She has been ordered not to leave China for a year. "No evidence of any crime has been provided to the Garratts, family members, or their lawyers of any criminal conduct," the family said.
link_name: China releases Canadian woman on bail, husband still in custody

status_message: Delhi police on Feb. 5 detained several protesters, including nuns and priestsm during a march against attacks on churches in the Indian capital. Christian groups and activists had planned a silent march toward the Indian home minister's residence after unknown people vandalized a church in south Delhi on Feb. 2.
link_name: Police detain protestors marching against church attacks in India's capital

status_message: A class action suit was brought against the leadership of the Arizona Department of Child Safety and the Department of Health Services on Feb. 3 in a federal court. The lawsuit in the name of 10 children in the foster care system says the Arizona system "shocks the conscience."
link_name: Class action suit brought against Arizona children services for abuse accusations

status_message: At least 12 people were still missing Feb. 5, officials said. Rescuers pulled out 15 survivors from the wreckage, including a two-year-old boy. Thirty-one people were confirmed dead.
link_name: Dozens of divers searching for missing people from Taiwan plane crash
Netflix to launch in Japan this year
Health insurer Anthem says hackers stole 'tens of millions' of records
CEO says he's 'ashamed' of how Twitter handles online abuse
Pentagon nominee Ashton Carter says he will push for sending arms to Ukraine
Senate Republicans propose nixing filibuster for Supreme Court nominees
Under Armour to acquire MyFitnessPal for $475 million
Tablet shipments grow 4.4% in 2014 despite soft Q4
HHS says 7.5 million people have enrolled for Obamacare through federal marketplace
Ebola outbreak in West Africa sees first increase in cases in 2015
Boko Haram attack in Cameroon kills 76
Michigan will recognize about 300 same-sex marriages performed in 2014
Ontario court approves liquidation of Target Canada
Senate Democrats block bill to undo Obama's immigration order a second time

status_message:
US won't return Guantanamo Bay to Cuba, officials say:

Roberta Jacobson testified to the House Foreign Affairs Committee Feb. 4 that the United States is not considering returning the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay to Cuba, going against remarks made by President Raul Castro last week. Jacobson acknowledged that Cuba had raised the issue of Guantanamo, saying, "we are not interested in discussing that."
link_name: US won't return Guantanamo Bay to Cuba, officials say

status_message: Ross Ulbricht was convicted on all counts Feb 4 for his role in the creation and operation of the Silk Road. He faces a minimum of 30 years in prison.
link_name: Closing arguments heard in Silk Road trial

status_message:
Lawmakers want FDA to investigate adulterated herbal supplements:

In letters sent Feb. 2, New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman asked GNC, Target, Wal-Mart and Walgreens to remove store-brand herbal supplements from their shelves. Schneiderman alleges that supplements sold by the retailers either include ingredients not listed on product labels or don't have ingredients listed on the labels.
link_name: Lawmakers want FDA to investigate adulterated herbal supplements

status_message:
US to destroy largest remaining cache of chemical weapons:

In March, the Pueblo Chemical Depot in C.O. will begin neutralizing 2,800 tons of mustard agent in 780,000 shells. Along with Russia, Libya and Iraq, the U.S. is one of four countries that have admitted to having chemical weapons but missed the 2012 deadline to eradicate set at the 1997 Chemical Weapons Convention.
link_name: US to destroy largest remaining cache of chemical weapons

status_message:
FCC proposes regulating Internet like a public utility:

The FCC will propose regulating the Internet like a public utility under Title II of the Communications Act, Chairman Wheeler said Feb. 4. Title II regulation will enable the FCC to more strictly regulate Internet service providers, including wireless providers.
link_name: FCC proposes regulating Internet like a public utility

status_message:
Alibaba testing delivery by drones:

Alibaba's Taobao is running a three-day test of drone delivery of certain products from Feb. 4-6, the company said Feb. 4. The tests will be conducted in at least three cities and will be delivered to around 450 customers.
link_name: Alibaba testing delivery by drones

status_message:
9/11 '20th' hijacker claims Saudi link to Al-Qaeda:

Zacarias Moussaoui, the so-called "20th hijacker," testified that members of Saudi Arabia's royal family financed Al-Qaeda, Feb. 3 reports said. He testified in a case filed against Saudi Arabia by relatives of those killed in the Sept. 11, 2001 attacks. The Saudi embassy called him "deranged" in a Feb. 2 statement.
link_name: 9/11 '20th' hijacker claims Saudi link to Al-Qaeda

status_message:
Caddies sue PGA tour over bibs with logos:

More than 80 caddies are involved in the suit, which was filed Feb. 3. Bibs bear the logos of companies like Coca-Cola and Buick and all money from advertisements go directly to the PGA Tour. The lawsuit claims that the PGA retains "tens of millions of dollars in advertising revenue" for the bib advertisements annually.
link_name: Caddies sue PGA for compensation for promoting sponsors on tour bibs

status_message:
North Korea says it won't talk to "gangster" United States

 Since the gangster-like U.S. imperialists are blaring that they will 'bring down' [North Korea], oblivious of its poor plight facing adverse fate, the army and people of [North Korea]‚Ä¶ has neither need nor willingness to sit at [the] negotiating table.
- North Korea National Defense Commission

North Korean state media relayed a statement from the Defense Commission, which chaired by Kim Jong-un, on Feb. 4. The statement comes a month before annual U.S.-South Korea military drills which the North often says is a ploy to prepare for an invasion of the North.
link_name: North Korea says it won't talk to "gangster" United States

status_message:
Policeman guarding polio vaccination team shot dead in Pakistan:

A policeman guarding a polio vaccination team was shot dead by gunmen on motorcycle in western Pakistan, officials said. The assailants escaped unhurt. No group has taken responsibility for the attack. Officials said the vaccination drive remained unaffected after the incident.
link_name: Policeman guarding polio vaccination team shot dead in Pakistan

status_message: Greece has started talks with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to swap its outstanding debt for growth-linked bonds, Finance Minister Yanis Varoufakis said in an interview published Feb. 4. On Feb. 2, he told the Financial Times that Greece would no longer call for a write-off of its 315-billion-euro foreign debt.
link_name: Greece begins talks with IMF on debt

status_message: Alibaba's Taobao is running a three-day test of drone delivery of certain products from Feb. 4-6, the company said Feb. 4. The tests will be conducted in at least three cities and will be delivered to around 450 customers.
link_name: Alibaba testing delivery by drones

status_message: A soldier identified as Sergeant Yim, 23, was sentenced to death by a military tribunal on Feb. 3. Yim's lawyers will appeal and plan to argue that Yim was bullied by other soldiers. One of Yim's victims was a staff sergeant. He had to receive the death penalty under Korean law for killing a superior.
link_name: South Korea soldier who killed 5 fellow troops sentenced to death

status_message: Crude prices fell Feb. 4 on demand worries, after rising for four consecutive days. Brent was trading down 2.6% at $56.39 and U.S. crude was down 3.6% at $51.14 at 1120 GMT on Feb. 4. U.S. crude rose more than 7% on Feb. 3 to its highest price since Dec. 2014.
link_name: Oil prices snap four-day rise

status_message:
Small TransAsia plane crashes in river in Taiwan soon after takeoff:

A TransAsia ATR-72 plane crashed into the river after hitting a bridge soon after taking off from Taipei Songshan Airport, according to Taiwan city government spokesperson Sidney Lin.

http://cir.ca/news/transasia-plane-crash-february-2015

Photo via @Missxoxo168 on Twitter
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: A Metro-North Railroad train hit a Jeep Cherokee on the tracks in Valhalla, New York, and then burst into flames at around 6:30 pm. At least six people, including the driver of the vehicle, were killed, according to the New York Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
link_name: At least 6 dead in train, vehicle collision north of New York City

status_message: Authorities said on Feb. 3 that a 59-year-old man, who was arrested on suspicion of murder days earlier, will be released.
link_name: Man released in SF investigation of body parts in suitcase

status_message: Major League Baseball said in a memo to teams Feb. 3 that it has eliminated a requirement for Cuban players to obtain a U.S. government license before being allowed to sign contracts.
link_name: MLB to allow Cuban players to sign contracts without obtaining US government license
US imposes visa restrictions on Venezuelan officials
Closing arguments heard in Silk Road trial
Take-Two ships 45 million 'Grand Theft Auto V' units
Web inventor warns against 'positive data discrimination'
NASA funding would increase under Obama budget
Officials say California water usage fell 22% in December year-over-year, meeting targets

status_message:
Draft of arrest warrant for Argentine president found at dead prosecutors home:

Viviana Fein, the prosecutor investigating Nisman's death, confirmed that he had prepared a draft of the warrant requesting the president's arrest in June 2014. Fein originally denied the existence of any such warrant and later clarified her statement.
link_name: Judges turn away Alberto Nisman's case against Argentine president

status_message:
NTSB: Selfies likely caused Colorado plane crash:

The National Transportation Safety Board said Jan. 27 that a two-seat Cessna 150 plane that crashed in Colorado, killing two people in May 2014, was "likely" the result of the pilot and passengers taking selfies. A GoPro camera found in the wreckage recorded the pilot and other passengers taking selfies on their cell phones during a series of short flights before the crash.
link_name: NTSB: Selfies likely caused Colorado plane crash
Senate Democrats block bill to undo Obama's immigration order
2 French soldiers wounded in knife attack outside Jewish community center
Appeals court rejects request to delay start of same-sex marriages in Alabama
Senate approves bill to curb military suicides
Judges turn away Alberto Nisman's case against Argentine president

status_message: An unverified video released on Feb. 3 apparently shows Jordanian pilot Moaz Al-Kasasbeh being burned alive by IS militants after delivering a monologue.
link_name: Islamic State releases video appearing to show Jordanian pilot burned alive

status_message:
UK lawmakers approve bill to allow babies from DNA of three parents:

In a free vote Feb. 3, British MPs voted 382-128 to legalize a technique to allow babies created from two different mothers. The bill will require the approval of the House of Lords before becoming law.
link_name: UK lawmakers approve bill to allow babies from DNA of three parents

status_message:
Harper Lee to release a sequel to "To Kill A Mockingbird" this July:

Pulitzer Prize-winning Lee, 88, announced her plans to release "Go Set a Watchman" through Harper publishing house Feb. 2. The 304-page book is the author's first new work in 50 years, and second novel ever published. The publisher is planning an initial run of 2 million copies, calling the existence of the previously unknown work "an extraordinary gift."
link_name: Harper Lee to release a sequel to "To Kill A Mockingbird" this July

status_message: Prosecutors indicted Dutch journalist Frederike Geerdink for "terrorist propaganda" for social media posts about the banned Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK). Many local journalists, mostly Kurdish, have been accused of the same crime in the past. Geerdink has reported in Turkey since 2006 with a focus on Kurdish issues.
link_name: Turkey indicts Dutch journalist for social media posts about Kurds

status_message:
US Big Three automakers see double-digit sales growth in January:

Fiat Chrysler's sales grew 14% in January, just slightly better than the 13.8% predicted by analysts. Ford sales were up 15.6% after a supply-constrained December -- beating expectations of 12.8%. GM slightly missed expectations of 18.8% growth with an 18.3% boost in sales.
link_name: US Big Three automakers see double-digit sales growth in January

status_message: Standard & Poor's will pay nearly $1.4 billion in a settlement with the Dept. of Justice to end a civil suit and 19 other lawsuits filed by attorneys general in several states. In addition, the credit rater will pay $125 million to settle with the California Public Employees' Retirement System (Calpers).
link_name: S&P pays $1.38 billion in DOJ settlement over mortgage ratings

status_message: Uber Feb. 2 announced a partnership with Carnegie Mellon University to create the Uber Advanced Technologies Center in Pittsburgh. The research and development facility will focus on "key long-term technologies" including mapping, vehicle safety, and "autonomy technology."
link_name: Uber, Carnegie Mellon to research vehicle automation

status_message: Irish building materials supplier CRH on Feb. 2 agreed to buy some assets from Holcim and Lafarge for 6.5 billion euros ($7.37 billion). The assets mainly include operations in Europe, Canada, Brazil and the Philippines that generated an estimated revenue of 5.2 billion euros ($5.9 billion) in 2014.
link_name: Ireland's CRH agrees to buy assets from Holcim, Lafarge for $7.37 billion

status_message: Cuba published 10 photos of Fidel Castro talking with a university student Feb. 2. In first-person account published with the photos, the student-leader writes about how he and Castro discussed current events on Jan. 23. They were the first photos of Castro since Aug. 2014.
link_name: Cuba publishes first photos of Fidel Castro in several months

status_message: Mohamed Fahmy gave up his Egyptian citizenship Feb. 2 to pave the way for his release, his family said. Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister John Baird said Fahmy's release was "imminent." An Egyptian law allows the president to deport convicted foreigners. It would not affect Baher Mohamed, who only has Egyptian citizenship.
link_name: Al Jazeera journalist gives up Egyptian citizenship in bid for prison release
Study: Smoke from fires intensifies tornadoes
'Revenge porn' site operator guilty of extortion, identity theft

status_message: Chilean President Michelle Bachelet said she is going to send a bill to lawmakers calling to ease the nation's ban on abortions.
link_name: Chile's president wants to ease abortion restrictions
Judge rejects New York's claims that Wells Fargo violated mortgage settlement
Robin Williams' widow and children in legal dispute over his estate
WA state files $17 million lawsuit over 2013 bridge collapse
FCC to overrule state laws that ban cities from developing broadband networks
FCC to propose regulating Internet like a public utility
Benedict Cumberbatch calls on UK to pardon 49,000 men convicted of homosexuality
Costa Rica moves to free-floating currency
No correlation between anti-vaccine views and political party, study finds
Harry Reid returns to the Senate after eye surgery
Line messaging app introduces grocery deliveries in Southeast Asia

status_message: Iran successfully launched its Fajr (Dawn) satellite into orbit, state media reported. Fajr is the fourth satellite made in Iran sent into space since 2009 and the first since 2012. The satellite is the latest iteration of the Omid (Hope) satellite.
link_name: Iran launches its first satellite since 2012

status_message: Exxon Mobil Corp on Feb. 2 reported a 21% decline in profit for the fourth quarter, mainly on lower oil prices and planned maintenance at its refineries. The company reported a net income of $6.57 billion, or $1.56 per share, compared with $8.35 billion, or $1.91 a year ago.
link_name: Exxon Q4 profit declines 21% on lower oil prices, maintenance costs

status_message: A new program to help Croatia's poorest citizens tackle their debt and unfreeze blocked bank accounts went into effect on Feb. 2. The government is planning to spend up to $300 million on the program, titled "fresh start", that will cancel the debt of Croatians who make less than $138 a month and have debts up to $5,100.
link_name: Croatia cancels debt of its poorest citizens

status_message: Islamic State fighters fled the outskirts of the border town of Kobane a week after Kurdish fighters routed them, a UK-based monitoring group said Feb. 2. Kurdish YPG fighters also took another 13 villages since a day earlier. Fighting raged in the town for months with airstrikes targeting IS positions.
link_name: Islamic State fighters withdraw from Syrian border town Kobane

status_message: The UN hadn't delivered aid to the Yarmouk camp through the end of January because armed groups were blocking access to it. Kraehenbuehl did not specify in an interview with Reuters which groups were responsible. Up to 18,000 people are in the camp, which is short on food, water and medicine.
link_name: Thousands of Palestinian refugees in Damascus cut off from aid

status_message: The UK government came under fire in late January after a debate in the House of Commons revealed 90 Syrian refugees were resettled in 2014. The government pledged in Jan. 2014 to resettle 500, and later scaled down to "several hundred" Syrians over several years. More than 3.7 million are registered with the UN.
link_name: UK criticized for admitting small number of Syrian refugees

status_message: Macau in January saw gambling revenue fall by 17.4% year-over-year to $2.97 billion. It was the eight straight month of declines compared to the previous year. Overall in 2014, Macau gambling revenue fell 2.6% to $44 billion. In general, about two thirds of gambling revenue comes from mainland Chinese visitors.
link_name: Macau suffers eight straight months of declining gambling revenue

status_message: Strauss-Kahn, 65, is facing charges of "aggravated pimping as part of an organized gang," despite prosecutors asking for the case to be dropped in over a lack of evidence. He is on trial with 13 other defendants in an alleged prostitution ring.
link_name: Trial of former IMF chief Dominique Strauss-Kahn begins in France

status_message: Violence in Iraq killed 1,375 people, including 790 civilians, and wounded another 2,240 in January, the UN said Feb. 1. More than 600 civilians were killed monthly in all but two months since May 2013. The UN cannot verify all reports of deaths, so "figures reported have to be considered as the absolute minimum."
link_name: At least 1,375 Iraqis killed in January, majority were civilians

status_message: Keo Chandara, 63, a former inmate in Ta Chan prison told the UN-backed court Feb. 2 that he helped in digging up more than 12,000 skulls from mass graves in the prison after the Khmer Rouge regime fell in 1979. Chandara, a prosecution witness, said that prisoners, including women were tortured with metal pincers and acid.
link_name: Witness tells Cambodian court he unearthed over 12,000 skulls from Khmer Rouge prison

status_message: South Sudanese President Salva Kiir and rebel leader Riek Machar signed a ceasefire. It proposes that the two sides will come to a power-sharing agreement, including the formation of a government with Machar to return as vice president. They previously signed a ceasefire in Jan. 2014, but it was often violated.
link_name: South Sudan groups sign ceasefire to come closer to power-sharing deal

status_message:
Ukrainian military and rebels battle for transport hub:

The Ukrainian military and rebels were battling for the Kiev-held transport hub of Debaltseve following the collapse of Jan. 31 peace talks. At least 28 people including 17 civilians died in two days of fighting, government officials and separatist rebels told the AFP Feb. 2. Civilians were evacuating the town.
link_name: Ukrainian military and rebels battle for transport hub

status_message:
Bangladesh opposition leader sued over killings in anti-government protests:

A pro ruling party organization on Feb. 2 sued BNP leader Begum Khaleda Zia and three other party leaders for allegedly masterminding killings during the ongoing anti-government movement. A judge asked Dhaka police to investigate and submit a report on March 1. Khaleda is already facing charges in two arson attack cases.
link_name: Bangladesh opposition leader sued over killings in anti-government protests

status_message:
Chinese government says 89% of cities missed pollution targets in 2014:

China's Ministry of Environmental Protection said Feb. 1 that 66 of 74 cities failed to meet air pollution targets in 2014. Seven of the ten most polluted cities were in Hebei Province, which surrounds the Beijing municipality. The most polluted city in China was Baoding, also in Hebei.
link_name: Chinese government says 89% of cities missed pollution targets in 2014

status_message: Groundhog Punxsutawney Phil, saw his shadow after emerging from a burrow during the 129th celebration of Groundhog Day. According to tradition, if the groundhog sees his shadow, there will be 6 more weeks of winter.
link_name: Punxsutawney Phil sees shadow, 6 more weeks of winter

status_message: Israel in 2015 demolished 77 Palestinian homes and structures built without permits by Feb. 1, according to the UN. The demolitions resulted in 110 people, about half of which are children, losing their homes. In 2014, Israel demolished 590 Palestinian homes and structures, displacing 1,177 people.
link_name: Israel demolished 77 Palestinian homes and structures in 2015

status_message: South Sudanese President Salva Kiir and rebel leader Riek Machar signed a ceasefire on Feb. 2. It proposes that the two sides will come to a power-sharing agreement, including the formation of a government with Machar to return as vice president. They previously signed a ceasefire in Jan. 2014, but it was often violated.
link_name: South Sudan groups sign ceasefire to come closer to power-sharing deal

status_message: Five policemen were killed in an attack on a police checkpoint in Kandahar, Afghanistan, on Feb. 1, according to an official. The Taliban took responsibility for the attack. An investigation was ongoing over the incident.
link_name: Taliban attack on checkpoint kills five Afghan policemen

status_message: More than 2,000 flights have been canceled Feb. 2 including at airports in Chicago, New Jersey and Boston. Both Chicago and Detroit have canceled school Feb. 2. New York City issued a hazardous travel advisory, warning of ice and slippery roads. Amtrak plans to operate normally Feb. 2.
link_name: Another winter storm bears down on Midwest and Northeast

status_message: Workers belonging to the USW began striking at 9 oil refineries and chemical plants in the U.S. on Feb. 1. The strike came after the union and the plants failed to reach an agreement over pay, safety measures and staffing. Talks over a new 3-year agreement began Jan. 21.
link_name: US oil workers on strike at 9 refineries, chemical plants over contract issues

status_message: In one of the strangest endings to a Super Bowl ever, Seattle took the ball all the way to the one yard line with time winding down in the game, but an interception ended the drive, giving the Patriots the ball and seconds later, the Super Bowl win.
link_name: Patriots are Super Bowl XLIX champions, beat Seahawks 28-24

status_message: Forecasts call for total snow accumulation of 10-16 inches across the Midwest, including Detroit, Cleveland and Fort Wayne, Indiana. Chicago is experiencing more than 12 hours of hazardous blizzard conditions with wind gusts up to 45mph, causing more than 1,000 flights to be canceled.
link_name: Another winter storm bears down on Midwest and Northeast
Las Vegas authorities investigating political extortion scheme
Global unemployment to hit 212 million by 2019, UN labor agency says

status_message: Children of illegal immigrants, mainly from Haiti, in the Dominican Republic had until Feb. 1 to apply for a birth certificate so they can apply for citizenship in two years, but few have done so and risk becoming stateless.
link_name: Tens of thousands of undocumented people in Dominican Republic may become stateless

status_message: The Sandy Hook Advisory Commission is debating whether or not Nancy Lanza, the mother of the Newtown killer, should be named as a victim in their official report. Some believe she contributed to the massacre because her guns were used to carry it out, and because her son clearly needed mental health treatment.
link_name: Sandy Hook panel debates if Nancy Lanza was a victim

status_message: Gene therapy is intended to treat diseases caused by a single genetic mutation. Theoretically, by repairing or replacing the genetic code, the patient could be cured. Currently, most gene therapies focus on eye disorders, hemophilia, and immune deficiencies but UK drug maker AstraZeneca hopes to use gene therapy to fight cancer.
link_name: Drug makers are advancing gene therapy research

status_message: Australian Al Jazeera journalist Peter Greste was released Feb. 1 and is on a flight to Cyprus, according to Egypt's state news agency and police. No updates have been reported, however, on the two Al Jazeera journalists with him, Mohamed Fahmy and Baher Mohamed.
link_name: Al Jazeera journalist Peter Greste has been released from Egyptian custody

status_message:
Fire at important Moscow library a 'great loss to science'

The library was created in 1918. It holds 10 million documents, some of which date to the 16th century. It has one of the best collections of Slavic language works, but also important works from Europe and the U.S.
link_name: Fire at important Moscow library a 'great loss to science'

status_message: Protesters opposed to mainland China's rules on elections planned a rally in Hong Kong Feb. 1, in the first major protests in more than a month. As many as 50,000 people were expected, but only about 3,000 showed up by the late afternoon. Around 2,000 police officers were on the scene as well.
link_name: Hong Kong protesters return to the streets

status_message: Green Bay Packers QB Aaron Rodgers won the NFL MVP award Jan. 31 with 31 of the 50 first place votes. J.J. Watt (pictured) of the Houston Texans was second. He would have been the first defense player to win the award since Lawrence Taylor in 1986. Watt was the first ever unanimous Defensive Player of the Year.
link_name: Aaron Rodgers takes home second NFL MVP award

status_message: The NFL announced eight new inductees into the Pro Football Hall of Fame on Jan. 31, including deceased linebacker Junior Seau (pictured). In addition to Seau and Bettis, the 2015 class is: Tim Brown, Charles Haley, Bill Polian, Will Shields, Mick Tingelhoff and Ron Wolf.
link_name: 2015 Pro Football Hall of Fame class announced

status_message: On Jan. 31 the DRC military announced an offensive against FDLR rebels in the north of the country's North Kivu province. The military action is being conducted without the help of the UN force deployed to the country, known as MONUSCO. The DRC government had given the rebels a deadline of Jan. 2 to disarm.
link_name: Democratic Republic of Congo launches offensive against Rwandan rebels

status_message: Although Ko finished second in the Coates Golf Championship on Jan. 31 in Florida, the second place finish earned her enough points to take the top worldwide ranking in the LPGA tour. She eclipsed the record set by Tiger Woods, the youngest ever No. 1 in the men's tour, by nearly four years.
link_name: 17-year-old LPGA player becomes youngest world number one in golf history
US adults and scientists have conflicting views on science
Mexico to cut spending by $8.4 billion amid low oil prices
Tiger Woods slips out of top 50 in world rankings, first time since 2011
Zimbabwe's Robert Mugabe elected chairman of African Union

status_message: Ukrainian representatives and separatists met with Russian and European diplomats on Jan. 31 for peace talks in Minsk, Belarus, but were unable to reach an agreement. Both sides blamed the other for collapsed talks and for firing on civilian targets.
link_name: Ukraine peace talks end without agreement as fighting continues

status_message: A video was released Jan. 31 in which Japanese journalist Kenji Goto appears to be beheaded by the same IS militant featured in previous execution videos. No mention was made in the 1 minute, 7 second video about the fate of the Jordanian pilot also held by the group
link_name: Islamic State releases video showing apparent beheading of Japanese hostage
Hernandez jurors can watch Super Bowl, but must leave if former Patriot is mentioned
African Union agrees to send 7,500 troops to battle Boko Haram in Nigeria
Disney will debut its first Latina princess
Nintendo to share YouTube ad revenue with producers
More U.S. criminals were exonerated in 2014 than any other year

status_message: The Washington Post reported Jan. 30 that the assassination of Imad Mughniyeh by a car bomb was conducted by the Israeli and U.S. government jointly. The report confirmed U.S. involvement by five former U.S. intelligence officials. The U.S., like Israel, has never admitted to its role in his killing.
link_name: CIA, Mossad assassinated Hezbollah's Mughniyeh jointly, Washington Post reports

status_message: U.S. firms lost $179 million between Oct. 2013 and Dec. 2014 to crimes the IC3 is calling "business email compromise" scams. 1198 firms in the U.S. and 928 outside the county have been hit.
link_name: US firms lost $179 million to email hacking scams in 14 months

status_message: In an interview with CNN Jan. 30, outgoing Secretary of Defense Chuck Hagel acknowledged there were disagreements between he and the White House over the pace detainees should be transferred.
link_name: Hagel, White House disagreed on Gitmo transfers
New York legislators challenge NFL's state tax-exempt status
California reports 91 measles cases, 58 cases linked to Disneyland outbreak
Stocks slide to end week, Dow drops 250 points
Trial begins in Etan Patz case 35 years after NYC boy's murder
Judge questions constitutionality of US 'no fly' list
After 100-year absence, rare Sierra Nevada fox spotted at Yosemite
Record number of elderly people hospitalized this flu season
Dartmouth bans liquor in an effort to curb campus sexual assault
Eurozone unemployment falls to lowest level since 2012
Former president of Panama to face corruption probe
Obama seeks $215 million for data-driven, personalized medicine effort
Spain's economy grows 2% in the fourth quarter, on consumer spending

status_message:
Eleven people murdered each day in El Salvador in 2014:

Gangs in El Salvador are estimated to have 60,000 members out on the streets and another 10,000 in prison. The two most powerful groups, MS-13 and Barrio 18, began as eastern Los Angeles street gangs and have since become influential transnational organizations. The country's murder conviction rate is only 5%, according to Al Jazeera.
link_name: Eleven people murdered each day in El Salvador in 2014

status_message: In a conference call to supports, Jan. 30, Mitt Romney said he would not be running for president, despite his confidence that he could win the GOP nomination. His remarks were obtained by radio host Hugh Hewitt, and confirmed by the New York Times.
link_name: Romney tells supporters he will not run for president in 2016

status_message: Chinese state media outlet Xinhua on Jan. 30 quoted Chinese education minister Yuan Guiren, who said Chinese universities will "never let textbooks promoting western values appear in our [college] classes."
link_name: "Western values" won't be taught at colleges, Chinese education minister says

status_message: Andy Murray won his semifinal match against Tomas Berdych in four sets Jan. 29. Murray will play either Novak Djokovic or Stan Wawrinka in the final.
link_name: Andy Murray reaches men's finals at Aussie Open

status_message: The woman who said she was raped in a Delhi Uber car sued the company Jan. 29 in a U.S. federal court. The lawsuit, filed in San Francisco, accuses Uber of negligence and fraud, which resulted in a sexual assault that "humiliated, degraded, violated and robbed plaintiff of her dignity."
link_name: Delhi woman passenger who accused driver of rape sues Uber in US

status_message: The Indian government on Jan. 30 began selling 10% of Coal India, the largest coal producer in the world. The government, which holds 90% of the company, could get as much as $3.7 billion from the sale. Coal India's trade unions have announced protests throughout the country against the sale.
link_name: India launches sale of 10% of state coal mining company

status_message: Secret co-founder Chrys Bader to leave the company
link_name: Secret relaunches with focus on location, private messaging

status_message: A record 1.3 billion smartphones were shipped in 2014, a 27.6% increase from 2013, the IDC said Jan. 29. In the final three months of 2014, 375.2 million smartphone were shipped, an 11.9% increase from the third quarter. Growth in shipments year-over-year were slowing, however, the IDC noted.
link_name: Record 1.3 billion smartphones shipped in 2014

status_message: Texas officials administered a lethal injection to Robert Ladd, 57, for the 1996 murder of 38-year-old Vicki Ann Garner. Citing a 1970 psychological evaluation, Ladd's lawyers had argued that he has an IQ of 67 and was therefore not eligible for the death penalty. The U.S. Supreme Court rejected that argument, as well as another questioning the potency of Texas' supply of pentobarbital.
link_name: Texas executes man after Supreme Court rejected mental impairment claim
California meets judges' prison overcrowding target 1 year early
Agents search homes of former PG&E exec, utility official in judge-shopping probe

status_message: Shake Shack priced its shares at $21 each on Jan. 29, ahead of its initial public offering the following day. That price values the fast casual dining chain at about $745 million.
link_name: Burger chain Shake Shack sets shares at $21 ahead of IPO
Art in Parisian suburb depicting high heels on Muslim prayer rugs pulled over threats
Boy Scouts settle sex abuse lawsuit, keeping 'perversion files' sealed
Ebola virus is mutating, scientists warn
Google's fourth quarter revenue up 15%
Amazon beats profit estimates, misses on revenue goal
Senate passes bill to approve Keystone XL pipeline
Ford recalls Taurus, two other vehicles for defects
Obama to propose budget that increases spending by $74 billion above sequestration levels
Spain's Princess Cristina to sell $6.8m property to raise court bond
Nissan recalls 768,000 crossover vehicles and SUVs worldwide
Renzi nominates constitutional court judge for Italian presidency
Man who owned gun that killed Argentine prosecutor comes forward
FCC updates broadband definition to 25 Mbps

status_message: A feature-length film, by director Sean Baker, shot entirely on an iPhone 5s premiered on Jan. 23 at the 2015 Sundance Film festival. The film, Tangerine, tells the story of two trans sex workers in Hollywood, and has received largely positive critical response.
link_name: Sundance film shot entirely on iPhone 5s garners critical attention

status_message:
Castro demands Guantanamo Bay in return for US-Cuba reconciliation:

President Raul Castro said in a Jan. 28 speech that Cuba would insist the United States return the Guantanamo Bay naval base as a step toward normalizing US-Cuban relations. Castro made the remarks during a two-day summit of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States.
link_name: Castro demands Guantanamo Bay in return for US-Cuba reconciliation

status_message: Samsung on Jan. 29 posted its first annual loss in three years following a weak Q4 2014. The company's mobile unit, which includes its smartphone business, posted its fifth straight quarterly decline. While Samsung did earn $4.9 billion in profit (down 27% from a year earlier), smartphone rival Apple earned $18 billion in profit.
link_name: Samsung posts first annual loss in three years

status_message: China's Central Military Commission will expand its corruption probe into the country's military, the defense dept. said Jan. 29, according to Reuters. The probe will include the navy, air force, the People's Armed Police and the second artillery corps, which controls China's nuclear missiles.
link_name: China to expand corruption probe to its military

status_message:
New claims for jobless benefits hit 15-year low:

The number of people who filed new claims for jobless benefits in the week ending Jan. 24 decreased by 43,000 to 265,000 -- the lowest level since April, 2000, the Labor Dept. reported Jan. 29. The four-week moving average, considered a better measure of the labor market, decreased by 8,250 to 298,500.
link_name: New claims for jobless benefits hit 15-year low

status_message: Dozens of people were missing after an overloaded boat capsized near the Bangladeshi Island of Kutubdia in the Bay of Bengal, police said. The coast guard rescued at least 30 people and search operations to rescue others were ongoing. Police said all those in the boat were Bangladeshis and were heading to Malaysia illegally.
link_name: Dozens missing after Bangladesh boat capsizes in Bay of Bengal

status_message: Indonesia has denied clemency and is preparing to execute 11 people, nine of whom were convicted of drug offenses, the office of the country's attorney general said Jan. 28. Seven of those on death row are foreign nationals, including the two Australian citizen leaders of the so-called "Bali Nine."
link_name: Indonesia preparing to execute 11 people including 7 foreigners

status_message: A report released Jan. 28 said commercial satellite imagery showed indications of activity by North Korea at its Yongbyon reactor. However, the report also says that it is too soon to "reach a definitive conclusion."
link_name: Satellite imagery shows possible activity at North Korean nuclear reactor

status_message: French copilot Remi Emmanuel Plesel, 46, and not the captain, was at the helm of the plane when it went down Dec. 28, Indonesian officials said Jan. 29. The crew was considered properly trained and the aircraft was "airworthy," Siswosuwarno said.
link_name: AirAsia flight was flown by copilot when it crashed

status_message: Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi on Jan. 28 sacked the country's foreign secretary Sujatha Singh and replaced her with India's ambassador to the U.S., Subrahmanyam Jaishankar. U.S. President Barack Obama left India a day earlier. The government did not give any explanation for the move.
link_name: India removes foreign secretary, replaces with ambassador to US

status_message: A federal judge sentenced Pedro and Margarito Flores, 33-year-old twin brothers, to 14 years in prison for their role in smuggling 71 tons of cocaine and heroin into the U.S. for the Sinaloa and Beltran Leyva cartels in Mexico. The Flores brothers would have faced life sentences, but received reduced penalties because they worked as informants for the U.S. government since 2008.
link_name: US judge gives 14 years to drug-smuggling twin brothers

status_message: As many as 1,000 people were being monitored for measles in three Arizona counties, Humble said Jan. 28. The state has so far confirmed seven cases of the measles. Two recent cases have been linked to an Arizona family of four that contracted the virus after a trip to Disneyland.
link_name: Arizona has several confirmed cases of measles, others being monitored
Autopsy on ex-spy killed with rare isotope 'most dangerous' ever
McDonald's names new CEO amid sluggish sales
US attorney general nominee says she supports Obama's action on immigration
IBM confirms 'a few thousand' job cuts

status_message: Google on Jan. 28 claimed it fought all gag orders that prevented it from telling users their data was being sought by law enforcement agencies as part of an investigation into Wikileaks. Google said it "litigated up and down through the courts" in an effort to inform its users about the data requests.
link_name: Google claims it fought gag orders in Wikileaks probe
US home prices growing more slowly

status_message: The Federal Trade Commission said Jan. 28 that TracFone agreed to a $40 million fine to settle charges that it misled millions of customers into thinking they were getting unlimited, unthrottled data. The FTC said wireless carriers cannot advertise "unlimited" data while simultaneously slowing download speeds.
link_name: TracFone fined $40 million over data throttling

status_message:
Facebook beats Q4 2014 earnings expectations 

- Reports monthly active users of 1.39B

- $3.85 billion in revenue, analysts had expected $3.77 billion
link_name: Facebook beats Q4 2014 expectations

status_message: In a regulatory filing, Jan. 28, Shake Shack increased its offer price range from $14-16 per share, to $17-19 per share. If sold at the top end, Shack Shack would have a market cap of $675 million.
link_name: Burger chain Shake Shack adjusts IPO price range

status_message: The Fed kept its near-zero interest rate unchanged following its first policy meeting of the year. It also repeated that it will remain "patient" in raising rates, but dropped the phrase "considerable time" in reference to hiking the interest rate. The Fed did not release new economic forecast following the meeting.
link_name: Fed keeps near-zero interest rate unchanged

status_message: Universal Pictures announced Jan. 27 that Michael Fassbender will play Steve Jobs in the upcoming biopic about the Apple visionary, a film entitled "Steve Jobs." Academy Award winners Danny Boyle and Aaron Sorkin will serve as director and writer of the picture, respectively.
link_name: Michael Fassbender, Seth Rogen to star in Steve Jobs movie

status_message:
Portugal star Luis Figo to challenge FIFA presidency:

Figo, 42, announced his candidacy Jan. 28. Since retiring from playing in 2009, the former Barcelona and Real Madrid winger has been involved with the Portuguese national team and Italy's Inter. The deadline for candidates to declare is Jan. 29.
link_name: Portugal star Luis Figo to challenge FIFA presidency

status_message: Russia's government unveiled a $35 billion spending plan, including $23 million to bail out Russia's hardest-hit banks and firms, on Jan. 28. Finance minister Anton Siluanov has said the government would cut expenditures by 10% in 2015, without specifying which sectors would be affected.
link_name: Russia unveils $35 billion anti-crisis plan to bail out biggest banks

status_message: The social network Ello plans to release a native mobile app in May, the company told the New York Observer on Jan. 28. The company in recent weeks has added the ability to share media from sites like SoundCloud and YouTube.
link_name: Ello to release mobile app in May

status_message: 22-year-old British singer Sam Smith and Beyonce are both nominated for six Grammy Awards, including including album of the year. Other nominees for album of the year include Beck's "Morning Phase," Ed Sheeran's "X" and Pharrell Williams' "Girl."
link_name: Sam Smith, Beyonce lead nominations for 2015 Grammy Awards

status_message:
AT&T to develop original video series for Snapchat:

The 12-episode series is called "SnapperHero" and is expected to debut on Snapchat within the next few weeks. It will star YouTube celebrities like Anna Akana and Freddie Wong playing the role of super heroes. Snapchat itself is not involved with the production.
link_name: AT&T to develop original video series for Snapchat

status_message: Saudi Arabia beheaded four people since King Salman took the throne on Jan. 23. One person was executed Jan. 26 and three were executed Jan. 27, the same day that U.S. President Barack Obama met with Salman. There were 16 executions in Saudi Arabia in 2015 as of Jan. 28.
link_name: Four people beheaded since new Saudi king has taken the throne

status_message: Luke Martin Jr. of New Bern, NC died on Jan. 25 at the age of 97 in the home his father, Luke Martin Sr., built in the 1890s. The elder Martin was born into slavery in Plymouth, NC in 1836 before he escaped to join 1st North Carolina Colored Volunteers, later called the 35th U.S. Colored Troops.
link_name: Son of ex-slave who fought in Union Army dies at age 97

status_message:
Two Israeli soldiers killed, seven wounded in Hezbollah attack:

An anti-tank missile hit an Israeli military convoy in disputed territory along the border of Lebanon. The attack caused several casualties, Israel's military said. Israel fired several shells into Lebanon, according Lebanon's state news agency.
link_name: Hezbollah fires missile on Israeli military vehicle, Israel shells Lebanon

status_message: Kristen Wiig, Melissa McCarthy, Leslie Jones, and Kate McKinnon are set to star in the reboot directed by "Bridesmaids" director Paul Feig.
link_name: New 'Ghostbusters' movie to be released in summer 2016

status_message: Pfizer settled a class action lawsuit for its "off-label" marketing practices for $400 million, according to a Jan. 27 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The suit contends Pfizer promoted products for uses not approved by regulators. Pfizer denied wrongdoing. A judge must approve the settlement.
link_name: Pfizer to pay $400 million to settle off-label marketing lawsuit

status_message: The presiding judge on Jan. 28, Circuit Court Judge John C. Hayes III, is the nephew of the judge who originally convicted the men in 1961.
link_name: Court to toss convictions of 'Friendship Nine' civil rights era activists

status_message: The Federal Trade Commission approved the Safeway and Albertsons merger on Jan. 27. The companies will sell 168 stores in eight states to address FTC concerns about markets where the two chains compete head-to-head. Safeway will be delisted when the merger closes.
link_name: Feds clear $9.4 billion Albertsons, Safeway merger
Fidel Castro cautiously backs US-Cuba diplomatic efforts
Supreme Court won't halt execution of inmate who lawyers say is mentally disabled
NASA to use Russian Soyuz spacecraft even after US manned flights begin
At least 8 dead in attack on hotel in Tripoli, Libya
Judge refuses to dismiss charges against Perry on constitutional grounds

status_message: Apple CEO Tim Cook revealed on Jan. 27 that the Apple Watch will begin shipping in April. Cook revealed the April shipping date during the company's latest earnings call. Apple made $18 billion in profit in the quarter, a record for the company.
link_name: Apple Watch to ship in April
Mexican attorney general declares 43 missing students dead
FTC calls for better safeguards for connected devices

status_message:
Apple earnings beat expectations by a wide margin:

Quarterly profit in the last quarter was 18 billion, a record rise of 38%

Apple sold 74.4 million iPhones in the quarter, analysts expected 65 million sold
link_name: Apple earnings beat expectations, quarterly profit rises to record 38%
Yahoo posts mixed Q4 2014 results, will spin off Alibaba stake
Scientists make cancer breakthrough by 'reverse boiling' an egg
House mulling lawsuit against Obama over executive action on immigration
Mormon leaders call for LGBT protections in Utah
Report: Comcast ghostwrites local officials' letters of support for merger
US Trade Representative asks Congress for greater trade deal authority

status_message: A former Lt. Colonel in the U.S. army, Tony Schaffer, told the host of Fox News' The O'Reilly Factor on Jan. 26 that Sgt. Bowe Bergdahl will be tried for desertion. He cited senior defense officials who said Bergdahl had been given a charge sheet. If convicted, Bergdahl, who returned to regular duty in San Antonio, Texas, in July 2014, could face 5 years in jail.
link_name: Retired officer says Bowe Bergdahl to be charged with desertion, former officer says

status_message: An Egyptian appeals court on Jan. 27 confirmed the prison sentence for three prominent activists: Ahmed Maher, Mohammed Adel and Ahmed Douma. The decision left them with no legal options. The ruling came days after several people died in protests on the anniversary of the 2011 uprising.
link_name: Egyptian court confirms prison sentence for three prominent activists

status_message: French counterterrorism police raided Lunel, in southern France, on Jan. 27, arresting several people suspected of recruiting foreign fighters to travel to Syria and Iraq. French interior minister Bernard Cazeneuve confirmed the arrest of five suspects aged between 26 and 44. Over the past year, at least 10 residents of Lunel have travelled to Syria, he said.
link_name: French police arrest five in terror raid in southern France

status_message: The UK economy grew at 2.6% over the course of 2014, its fastest rate of growth since 2007, and up from 1.7% in 2013. There was some disappointment as the economy grew 0.5% in the final three months of the year, down from 0.7% in the three months prior. The slowdown was attributed to contractions in construction and energy.
link_name: UK economy grew at 2.6% in 2014, fastest rate in seven years

status_message: UNRWA said Jan. 27 it exhausted its resources and was suspending payments to families in Gaza for rebuilding homes. The agency said it received $135 million of the $720 million donor pledges for its cash assistance program to 96,000 refugee families.
link_name: UN cuts funds for rebuilding Gaza due to lack of donor payments

status_message: USAID on Jan. 26 said it suspended its contractor International Relief and Development (IRD) over "serious misconducts in performance, management and internal controls." Since 2007, IRD has received more than over $2.4 billion from the agency for development projects in Iraq and Afghanistan.
link_name: USAID suspends major contractor in Iraq and Afghanistan over misconduct

status_message: At least two gunmen stormed the upscale Corinthia Hotel and an explosion went off in its parking lot around the same time. Up to three guards were killed. The area was sealed off and the hotel evacuated. It was unclear if the gunmen were still holed up in the hotel or if they had hostages.
link_name: Gunmen storm upscale hotel in Tripoli, Libya

status_message: What was billed as a 'historic and destructive' storm by the National Weather Service turned out to be less than in most parts of New York. Long Island saw the worst, with snow totals of up to 14 to 18 inches. New England was hit harder, with wind gusts up to 62mph and Connecticut and Massachusetts seeing a foot or more of snow..
link_name: Northeast winter storm less severe than forecasted

status_message: Up to 20,730 foreign fighters have gone to Iraq and Syria, the London-based ICSR research group said late January. The number would exceed all conflicts since World War II. Lower estimates have put the number around 17,000. ICSR based its estimate on government figures, media reports and militant groups' statements.
link_name: Up to 20,730 foreign fighters in Iraq and Syria, research group says

status_message: At least two rockets fired from Syria into the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. No casualties were reported. The Israeli military fired artillery, saying it hit a source of the rockets, Israeli newspapers reported. The Israeli military evacuated the Mount Hermon ski resort and sirens rang in the area.
link_name: Israel fires artillery into Syria after rockets land in the Golan Heights

status_message: The government restored power across the country after the Jan. 25 outage, but electricity was cut for 12 hours in parts of Sindh, Punjab and Balochistan Jan. 26 after a fresh outage at a power plant in Sindh. Officials said 11 of the 17 units were shut due to fog and a gas leak from a pipeline.
link_name: Most of Pakistan goes dark after attacks on power lines

status_message: The Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA) is using cameras on highways to track millions of vehicles in the U.S., DEA documents obtained by the ACLU showed Jan. 26. Cameras are used to monitor vehicle movements, time, direction and location. Cameras also take pictures that identify drivers and passengers.
link_name: DEA tracking license plates across the country

status_message: Bryant tore his right shoulder rotator cuff during a game Jan. 21. Bryant and the Lakers decided on Jan. 26 that he will have surgery. "Kobe is probably not going to play" again this season, Lakers coach Byron Scott said. The torn rotator cuff is his third straight season-ending injury.
link_name: Kobe Bryant to have surgery, likely done for the season

status_message:
Third seeded Rafael Nadal lost his quarterfinal match Jan. 27 in straight sets to Tomas Berdych, who is seeded seventh. Nadal had previously won 18 of the 21 matches the two had played all-time.

On the women's side, second seed Maria Sharapova defeated seventh seed Eugenie Bouchard of Canada Jan. 27 in straight sets. Tenth seed Ekaterina Makarova (pictured) upset third seed Simona Halep earlier in the day, also in straight sets. Sharapova and Makarova, both from Russia, will meet in the semifinals.
link_name: Nadal knocked out of Aussie Open

status_message: After hours behind closed doors, Assembly Democrats announced late Jan. 26 that they will ask Silver to resign as speaker. Silver has not yet responded to the decision. If Silver resigns, Assembly Majority Leader Joe Morelle (D-Rochester) would automatically become speaker until a permanent choice is made.
link_name: NY Assembly Democrats ask arrested speaker Silver to resign
Indiana's governor to roll out state-run news organization
Seller of Dr. Oz-endorsed diet pills to pay $9 million over 'deceptive' ads
Senator Harry Reid recuperating after surgery on his right eye
Lance Armstrong blames cycling culture for doping, says he'd 'probably do it again'
Prosecutors attempt to link Ross Ulbricht email address to Silk Road
Sling TV earns positive reviews ahead of launch
S&P cuts Russia's credit rating to 'junk'
AT&T to buy Nextel Mexico for $1.875 billion
Microsoft meets earnings expectations in Q2 FY15

status_message: Jeffrey Sterling, 47, was found guilty Jan. 26, on nine counts of unauthorized disclosure of national defense information, and related charges. Prosecutors said Sterling's disclosures to New York Times reporter James Risen endangered lives and hurt U.S. efforts against Iran's nuclear program. Sterling will remain free on bond until sentencing in April.
link_name: Ex-CIA officer convicted of leaking classified info to reporter
HHS announces Medicare payment reforms to reward quality care
Arizona readies for Super Bowl, some public alcohol consumption allowed in Phoenix
Yale investigating second case of sexual assault in four days
Ex-Virginia Gov. McDonnell allowed to remain free pending corruption appeal
Founding member Tom DeLonge quits Blink-182
Oklahoma to ask Supreme Court to halt executions pending review
GM to compensate at least 50 death claims linked to faulty ignition switch
Oculus forms 'Story Studio' to explore use of VR for movies
Greek F-16 jet crashes in central Spain, 10 dead
Small drone lands on White House grounds
Boy Scouts' 'perversion files' to go public in civil trial

status_message: Bitcoin startup Coinbase on Jan. 26 launched the first regulated, U.S.-based bitcoin exchange. The exchange is insured and is fully regulated by about half of all states in the U.S. including California and New York. Coinbase said it took about five months to secure regulatory approval.
link_name: Coinbase opens the first US-based bitcoin exchange

status_message: An estimated 3.3 million people are displaced in Iraq. The humanitarian situation in Iraq had "deteriorated" since her last visit in Sept. 2012, said UNHCR special envoy Angelina Jolie
link_name: Iraqi refugees struggling to make ends meet

status_message: NATO ambassadors scheduled an emergency meeting with Ukraine on Jan. 26 to discuss the ongoing conflict in eastern Ukraine. The extraordinary ambassadorial meeting, scheduled on Ukraine's request, is the first since August 2014. EU foreign ministers will meet on Jan. 29 to discuss further sanctions against Russia.
link_name: NATO, Ukraine to hold special meeting in wake of renewed unrest

status_message: Kurdish fighters gained control of the majority of the border town of Kobane with fighting on its edges, according to a UK-based monitoring group and an official. [IS] is on the verge of defeat," Kurdish official Idriss Nassan said. Fighting has raged in the town for months with airstrikes targeting IS positions.
link_name: Kurds take over Syrian border town of Kobane from Islamic State

status_message: Syriza was projected on Jan. 26 to win 149 seats in the Greek parliament, two short of an absolute majority. Syriza and the right-wing Independent Greeks party agreed to form a coalition after an hour of talks. Both parties are opposed to the terms of the country's international bailout loans.
link_name: Greece's Syriza forming coalition government after winning elections

status_message: Almost 80% of Pakistan suffered one of its worst power blackouts after attacks blew up two power lines late Jan. 24. They affected the local power station and eventually the national grid. As of late Jan. 25, most of the Balochistan province remained without power, an official said.
link_name: Most of Pakistan goes dark after attacks on power lines

status_message: An appeals judge on Jan. 26 upheld convictions for 11 activists who were sentenced to one year in prison for protesting against a real estate project in Nov. 2014. He also reduced the sentences of eight women to 10 months. The sentence of Nget Khun, a 75-year-old activist, was reduced to six months.
link_name: Cambodian court upholds prison sentences for land rights activists

status_message: Cablevision is introducing a WiFi-based mobile service called Freewheel on Jan. 26. The service will cost $9.95 a month for Cablevision Optimum Online customers or $29.95 a month as a standalone service. The plan will offer unlimited calling, texting and data over WiFi.
link_name: Cablevision to offer WiFi mobile calling plan

status_message: Eddie Redmayne won the SAG for leading actor in a film for "The Theory of Everything." Julianne Moore won the best actress SAG for "Still Alice." Patricia Arquette won the SAG for best supporting actress in a film for "Boyhood" while J.K. Simmons won the best supporting actor SAG for "Whiplash."
link_name: "Birdman" takes top film prize at Screen Actors Guild Awards

status_message: Wikileaks sent a letter to Google on Jan. 26 asking details on what materials Google handed over to the the FBI after a warrant was issued in March 2012. Wikileaks also wants to know why Google did not inform Wikileaks employees of the request until Dec. 23, 2014.
link_name: Google released emails of three Wikileaks members to the FBI

status_message: Energy imports combined with a lower yen led to Japan posting a record trade deficit of $109 billion in 2014, the government said Jan. 26. The deficit was 11.4% larger than the 2013 deficit, which was the previous record. Imports in 2014 also reached a record high.
link_name: Japan had a record trade deficit in 2014

status_message: NJ Gov. Chris Christie filed paperwork with the Federal Election Commission Jan. 23 to form a political action committee (PAC), the Wall Street Journal reported Jan. 26. The PAC, called "Leadership Matters For America," will be led by Republican finance chief Ray Washburne and staffed by some of Christie's aides.
link_name: Chris Christie forms PAC for likely 2016 presidential run

status_message: Three boxes found Jan. 25 contained over 700 kilograms of ivory, which could fetch up to $1.5 million on the black market. Wildlife officials said the crates contained 76 tusks and an additional 61 pieces of ivory, as well as pangolin scales. The tusks appeared to have been recently cut from elephants.
link_name: Uganda officials seize $1.5 million worth of ivory

status_message: Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi and U.S. President Barack Obama said on Jan. 25 that two key issues have been resolved regarding a long-stalled civilian nuclear power agreement.
link_name: India and US reach deal on nuclear pact during Obama visit

status_message: More than 30 members of the government's Special Action Forces were killed in a fight with members of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) on Jan. 25, marking the largest single-day combat loss in several years.
link_name: Clash with Philippines rebel group leaves at least 30 police dead

status_message: The National Weather Service on Jan. 25 issued a Blizzard Watch for parts of the Northeast, warning of hazardous conditions Jan. 26-27.
link_name: 'Major winter storm' set to impact Northeast

status_message: President Obama announced on Jan. 25 that he will formally ask Congress to protect an additional 12.28 million acres of the Arctic Refuge, including 1.4 million acres of the Coastal Plain, as wilderness -- the highest level of protection available to public lands.
link_name: Obama asks Congress to protect 12 million acres of Arctic Refuge

status_message: Boko Haram militants launched an offensive Jan. 25 on the city of Maiduguri, where they met resistance from Nigerian government troops and vigilantes.
link_name: At least 100 Boko Haram fighters killed in attack on Nigerian city

status_message: Joseph Sledge walked out of a North Carolina prison a free man Jan. 23, thanks to exonerating DNA evidence and efforts by the Center on Actual Innocence and the North Carolina Innocence Inquiry Commission. Sledge served 36 years of a life sentence for a double murder in 1976.
link_name: North Carolina man freed after 36 years in prison

status_message: Ansar Al-Sharia said on Jan. 24 that its leader, Mohammed Al-Zahawi, had died. The group didn't provide details about how or when Zahawi was killed, but other militants claim he was mortally wounded in Oct. 2014 during clashes in Benghazi.
link_name: Libya's Ansar Al-Sharia confirms leader's death

status_message: SpaceX and the Air Force on Jan. 23 announced an "agreement on a path forward" regarding the dispute over military launch contracts. Former U.S Attorney General John Ashcroft mediated the settlement. The Air Force pledged to expand "the number of competitive opportunities for launch services."
link_name: SpaceX drops lawsuit against Air Force over military contract dispute

status_message: Fourteen people were arrested Jan. 24 and charged with exploitation of juveniles for the purpose of hazardous employment. A suspect is believed to have paid parents between 5,000-20,000 rupees ($80-325) before bringing their kids to Hyderabad to work.
link_name: More than 200 child laborers rescued in India

status_message: Anti-government protestors demonstrated in Caracas on Jan. 24 in an event dubbed the "March of the Empty Pots." Protestors are upset with the current economic situation and chronic supply shortages.
link_name: Anti-Maduro protestors march in Venezuela's capital

status_message: Jason Rezaian's brother, Ali, told the New York Times Jan. 23 that Jason is out of solitary confinement and is now in a cell with a cellmate. Rezaian had been placed in solitary confinement six months prior.
link_name: Jailed US journalist out of solitary confinement in Iran

status_message: Four suspects were arrested in the autonomous Spanish city of Ceuta on the Moroccan border on Jan 24. They are two sets of brothers originally from Morocco who hold Spanish citizenship. Police found combat gear and knives during a search following the arrests.
link_name: Spain arrests 4 suspected Islamist extremists in North Africa

status_message: Pauline Cafferkey, a healthcare worker who was the first person in the UK to be diagnosed with Ebola, was discharged from the hospital on Jan. 24 after making a full recovery. Cafferkey, who had been in critical condition after her diagnosis in late Dec. 2014, said she was "happy to be alive."
link_name: Scottish nurse discharged after recovering from Ebola

status_message: Cadbury chocolate, KitKat bars, Toffee Crisps, Yorkie bars and Maltesers made in the UK will not be brought to the U.S. by two major importers as a result of a settlement in January with Hershey.
link_name: Hershey lawsuit blocks import of many UK chocolates

status_message: A video released Jan. 24 appeared to show a picture of the decapitated body of Haruna Yukawa being held by Kenji Goto, who appeared to be alive. Japanese authorities said they were working to authenticate the video. If confirmed, Yukawa would be the first Japanese citizen executed by the extremists.
link_name: Alleged IS video appears to show 1 of 2 Japanese hostages dead
Gloves from Muhammad Ali-Sonny Liston 'phantom punch' fight to be auctioned
Report: Obama rules out third-party collection of phone metadata

status_message: President Obama will cut short his trip to India and travel to Riyadh to pay his respects to the family of the late king and visit with Saudi Arabia's new King Salman, the White House announced Jan. 24.
link_name: President Obama will visit Saudi Arabia to offer condolences, meet with new leadership

status_message: Thompson scored 37 points on 13 for 13 shooting, including making nine three-pointers (also a record) in the third quarter of a game against the Sacramento Kings. Thompson also made his two free throw attempts in the quarter. 32 of his points came in the last seven minutes of the 12 minute period.
link_name: Warriors' Thompson sets NBA scoring record for a quarter
Baseball legend Ernie Banks dies at 83

status_message: The rate that California parents refuse to vaccinate their kindergartners due to personal beliefs fell from 3.1% in 2013 to 2.5% in 2014, according to data from the California Department of Public Health. The LA Times reported Jan. 23 that it's the first time the number has dropped in a dozen years.
link_name: Fewer California parents refuse to vaccinate kindergarteners under new law
Denver woman sentenced to 4 years for trying to join Islamic State
IRS warns of scammers as tax season begins
US deploys troops to train Syrian rebels to fight Islamic State
California health officials report 68 measles cases, 48 tied to Disneyland
Federal judge strikes down same-sex marriage ban in Alabama
More insider trading guilty pleas thrown out after appeals court ruling
ACLU settles with town to stop its cops from ticketing headlight flashers
Winter's first big snow to hit Northeast US this weekend
Raleigh, NC, may be next Google Fiber city - reports
Supreme Court agrees to hear case challenging lethal injection protocol
McDonald's sales drop 7% in 'challenging' 2014
US union membership drops slightly to 11.1% in 2014
Box surges 65% in first day of trading
TSA agents discovered 2,212 guns at airport checkpoints in 2014
Pro-Russia rebels launch offensive in eastern Ukraine after rejecting peace deal

status_message: The U.S. Army has released a report into the motivations behind Fort Hood shooter Ivan Lopez's April 2014 rampage.
link_name: Ft. Hood shooter gave no hint of rampage before April 2014 shooting, report finds
Gov't scales back sharing of personal information from Healthcare.gov
Democrats pick dates for 2016 convention

status_message: French Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius said Jan. 23 that a 67-year-old woman who had been kidnapped Central African Republic's capital city of Bangui has been released. The humanitarian worker is reported to be in good health.
link_name: Kidnapped French aid worker released in Central African Republic
Sony asks permission to delay earnings following 'The Interview' hack

status_message: The parent company behind SkyMall filed for bankruptcy protection on Jan. 22, according to papers filed with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Phoenix. SkyMall had revenue of about $33.7 million in 2013 and $15.8 million for the nine months that ended September 28, 2014.
link_name: In-flight catalog SkyMall files for bankruptcy

status_message: "Gemini" was announced by Cameron and Tyler Winklevoss on Jan. 23. The exchange, which they plan to open within the next few months, is based in New York City and will be regulated by the state's financial regulators.
link_name: Winklevoss Twins create New York-based bitcoin exchange

status_message: Oil prices rose Jan. 23 on the news of the death of Saudi Arabia's King Abdullah. Brent rose as much as 2.6% to $49.79 per barrel and U.S. crude rose as much as 3.1% to 47.75. Beveridge, however, does not see any imminent change in policy. Saudi is the largest oil producer in the OPEC.
link_name: Oil prices rise on policy uncertainty after Saudi King's death

status_message: Uber restarted its operations in India's capital and applied for a radio taxi operator license by Jan. 23. The move could change its operations because radio taxi operators need a fleet of cars with the name of the company written on their vehicles.
link_name: Uber restarts service in India's capital, applies for taxi license

status_message: Clinical trials to test the effectiveness of two Ebola vaccines will begin in Liberia within two weeks, the U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services said Jan. 22. A total of 27,000 people will be involved. Health workers will be the first to participate. Another trial is planned for Sierra Leone.
link_name: Large scale human trials of Ebola vaccines to begin in Liberia

status_message: South Korean President Park Geun Hye on Jan. 23 nominated Lee Wan Koo as prime minister. Lee is the parliament floor leader of Park's Saenuri Party. Lee will replace Chung Hong-won if approved. Park is fighting to regain the public's confidence. Her most recent approval rating dropped to 30%.
link_name: South Korean president makes third prime minister nomination since ferry sinking

status_message: The CDC reported Jan. 22 that a third of women aged 15-55 enrolled in Medicaid and more than a quarter with private insurance had filled a prescription for an opioid painkiller each year between 2008-2012. Health officials are concerned women may be unknowingly exposing an unborn child to opioids.
link_name: CDC: High rates of painkiller prescriptions among women of childbearing age

status_message: Sierra Leone is lifting all Ebola quarantines in the country with the exception of people that have been in close contact with those infected, President Ernest Bai Koroma said in a televised speech Jan. 22. Earlier in the day, the country said it will reopen schools in March, after being closed for 8 months.
link_name: Sierra Leone lifts most Ebola quarantines

status_message: Hutchison Whampoa is in "exclusive talks" to purchase O2 UK for $13.9 billion in cash, Hutchison said in a Jan. 23 regulatory filing in Hong Kong. An additional $1.5 billion could go to Telefonica based on the merged company's performance in the UK.
link_name: Hutchison Whampoa in talks to buy UK carrier O2

status_message: U.S. District Judge Carl Barbier is presiding over the trial to appropriate blame, damages and penalties under the Clean Water Act for the largest offshore oil spill in U.S. history. BP previously paid about $28 billion to settle civil claims, cleanup efforts and spill response.
link_name: Expert blames BP spill for economic woes around Gulf of Mexico

status_message: Second-seed Roger Federer lost to unseeded Andreas Seppi of Italy on Jan. 23 in third round in four sets. It was the first time Federer lost to Seppi in 11 matches. Federer had made it to at least the fourth round of the Australian Open every year he played since 2002.
link_name: Roger Federer knocked out of Australian Open

status_message: Researchers at Texas Tech University have found antibiotics used in animal-based agriculture and antibiotic-resistant genes on dust blown from cattle feedlots. The study, published Jan. 22, found feedyards pose a "significant potential for widespread distribution" of antibiotic-resistance bacteria.
link_name: Study: antibiotics, antibiotic-resistant genes found in feedlot dust

status_message: A federal jury found Ashad Razzak guilty of four felonies on Jan. 22, stemming from a 2010 search of a hotel room. Richard Yick was found not guilty of civil rights charges. He was with Razzak but didn't take part in the search. The trial of a third officer who was present, Raul Elias, has been delayed.
link_name: SF police officer convicted in illegal hotel room search caught on video

status_message: Dreamworks Animation confirmed Jan. 22 it is laying off 500 employees, and reducing the number of movies it produces from three a year to two. The layoffs are 18% of its workforce. According to company CEO Jeffrey Katzenberg, the company became too ambitious and its performance has been inconsistent.
