link_name: DreamWorks Animation laying off employees, cutting movies
Starbucks earnings up 82% in holiday quarter
Box prices shares at $14, values company at $1.67 billion
Record number of rhinos killed in 2014 in South Africa
King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia dies at 91
Apple doubles Tim Cook's compensation
South Sudan factions sign peace deal to reunite divided political party
Scientists move 'Doomsday Clock' to 3 minutes to midnight
Argentine president says controversial prosecutor didn't commit suicide
New Orleans City Council passes smoking ban for bars, casinos
Study: Climber nationality influences odds of summiting, death
German investor confidence hits three-month peak in January

status_message:
Drug delivery drone crashes near US-Mexico border

The drone, found in a parking lot, was carrying several packets of methamphetamine weighing about 6.5 pounds. Authorities are investigating the drone's origins and who may have controlled it. According to authorities, this is not the first time they have seen a drone used for smuggling drugs.
link_name: Drug delivery drone crashes near US-Mexico border
Qatari man, once held as enemy combatant, is released from prison

status_message:
Barrett Brown sentenced to 5 years in obstruction case 

Brown had pleaded guilty in April to charges brought against him, including transmitting a threat in interstate commerce, accessory after the fact to unauthorized access to a protected computer, and interfering with the execution of a search warrant.
link_name: Barrett Brown sentenced to 5 years in obstruction case

status_message: A drone, found in a parking lot near the U.S. - Mexico border, was carrying several packets of methamphetamine weighing about 6.5 pounds. Authorities are investigating the drone's origins and who may have controlled it.
link_name: Drug delivery drone crashes near US-Mexico border
California law requires condoms to be made available to all state prisoners

status_message: The House approved a bill Jan. 22 to bar federal funding for "any abortion" in a 242-179 vote. The vote came after House leadership pulled a vote on a separate anti-abortion bill that would have banned abortions after 20 weeks of pregnancy.
link_name: House passes bill to ban federal funding for abortions

status_message: Yasmin Nakhuda, the former owner of Darwin the Japanese snow macaque that achieved viral fame as the "Ikea Monkey," acquired two new macaques in January from an Ottawa zoo, according to a Facebook page dedicated to Darwin.
link_name: Former 'Ikea Monkey' owner buys 2 new snow macaques
Kim Dotcom's Mega debuts encrypted chat app

status_message: A timer on The Pirate Bay is now counting down to Feb. 1. The site is being hosted from a server in Moldova in Eastern Europe. Trabia, the company that operates the data center where the server is located, said it supports "freedom of speech" but that it complies with all international laws regarding copyright.
link_name: The Pirate Bay shows timer counting down to Feb. 1
Coalition needs 'two years' to expel Islamic State from Iraq, says UK

status_message: Sec. of State John Kerry, Jan. 21, said an unnamed Mossad official told him that a bill before Congress that would automatically impose sanctions on Iran if nuclear talks failed would be "like throwing a grenade into the process." Mossad issued a statement Jan. 22, denying that it opposed sanctions on Iran.
link_name: In break with Netanyahu, Mossad warns against US Congress bill on Iran sanctions
Navy to allow enlisted female sailors to serve on submarines
Reports: Yemen's government offers resignation

status_message: Israeli bulldozers razed a Palestinian home in East Jerusalem on Jan. 21, the third such demolition in the city in two days.
link_name: Israel demolishes three Palestinian homes in Jerusalem in two days

status_message: In the last two decades, the Ebola virus has been responsible for declines in the populations of Africa's great apes, who share 98% of human DNA. Even singular outbreaks, while infrequent, have the capacity to affect several lifetimes of great ape populations.
link_name: Ebola has killed one-third of the world's great apes since the 1990s

status_message: The ECB governing council announced Jan. 22 it will buy 60 billion euros ($70 billion) in bonds each month from March 2015-Sept. 2016. ECB President Mario Draghi said the stimulus package aimed to maintain eurozone inflation at just under 2%. Draghi also confirmed the key interest rate would stay at 0.05%.
link_name: European Central Bank announces bond-buying stimulus program

status_message: The high court in India's capital on Jan. 20 asked the government to release about $270,000 of funds belonging to Greenpeace India sent from its Amsterdam headquarters.
link_name: Indian court orders government to release Greenpeace funds

status_message: NY Assembly speaker Sheldon Silver was arrested on federal corruption charges in lower Manhattan on Jan. 22, surrendering to FBI agents outside 26 Federal Plaza, The New York Times reported. Before being processed by federal agents, according to law enforcement officials, Silver said "I hope I'll be vindicated."
link_name: NY Assembly speaker Sheldon Silver arrested in corruption case

status_message: Industries Minister Amir Hossain Amu said over 7,000 opposition activists have been arrested since the protests started and offered cash rewards for any information on protest leaders.
link_name: Thousands arrested in Bangladesh for protests

status_message: A study published Jan. 20 in Nature says European researchers used x-rays for the first time to read sections of a still-rolled up scroll from Herculaneum. The technique uses 3D x-rays that deciphers the papyrus from the ink on it.
link_name: Researchers read Vesuvius scroll using x-ray technique

status_message: Venezuela's economy shrank by 2.8% in 2014 with inflation of 64%, President Maduro said Jan. 21 during his annual address. He mentioned falling oil prices and that the country's highly subsidized gas is a "distortion." His response to falling oil revenues: "God will provide."
link_name: Venezuelan president says economy shrank by 2.8% in 2014

status_message: NY Attorney General Eric Schneiderman proposed amended complaint against Barclays over the probe related to high speed trading on Jan. 21. Barclays rejected the charges and said it will defend the allegations. A hearing on the case is set for Feb. 11 in the New York State Supreme Court.
link_name: NY state prosecutor issues amended complaint against Barclays for high-speed trading

status_message: Indonesian President Joko Widodo on Jan. 22 denied clemency to Andrew Chan, one of the two Australian ring leaders of the so-called "Bali Nine" drug smugglers. They were arrested in 2005 trying to smuggle heroin from Indonesia to Australia.
link_name: Indonesian president denies clemency to Australian drug smuggler

status_message: The funerary mask of the famed boy-king Tutankhamun suffered damage by a hasty repair to cover up that its beard snapped off. Conservators at the Egyptian Museum in Cairo confirmed to the AP Jan. 21 that the mask's beard was glued back on with epoxy. The Antiquities Ministry and the museum administration were not immediately available for comment. The conservators spoke under the condition of anonymity.
link_name: King Tut's mask damaged by repairing it with epoxy

status_message: The Ukrainian military was holding onto buildings and territory at the Donetsk airport, Ukraine's defense ministry said. Ukrainian volunteer brigades, however, said they lost all control over the airport complex the previous evening. At least six Ukrainian soldiers died in fighting there Jan. 21.
link_name: Ukrainian military losing control of Donetsk airport

status_message: Nigeria and neighboring countries agreed to ask the UN Security Council for a resolution to authorize a military force to combat Boko Haram, Bazoum said Jan. 21. No date for submitting such a proposal was given. The Security Council condemned Boko Haram days earlier.
link_name: African Union to ask UN Security Council for resolution to fight Boko Haram
HHS says 7.1 million people have enrolled for Obamacare through federal marketplace
Kansas officials link fracking byproduct to earthquakes
Prince Andrew, Duke of York, asked to respond to underage sex allegations under oath

status_message: No civil rights charges for Darren Wilson, the former Ferguson police officer who killed Michael Brown. A Justice Dept. investigation remains open, however.
link_name: Justice Dept. to recommend no civil rights charges against officer in Ferguson shooting
EBay to lay off thousands ahead of PayPal spinoff
Senator Harry Reid to undergo surgery on his right eye

status_message: One year after he was sworn in to a second term amid scandal, NJ Governor Chris Christie's approval rating has hit a four-year low, according to a poll released Jan. 21. 46% of NJ citizens approve of the job he's doing while 48% disapprove.
link_name: Chris Christie's approval hits four-year low in wake of controversies, poll says

status_message: PEGIDA leader Lutz Bachmann has resigned after a picture posted on his Facebook profile showed him posing as Hitler. The profile has since been deleted. German prosecutors have also launched a criminal investigation against Bachmann for inciting racial hatred. Bachmann denies he is a racist.
link_name: German anti-Islamic group leader quits after picture surfaces of him posing as Hitler

status_message: Houthis and Yemeni President Hadi have reached an agreement to end the standoff in Sana'a, according to a report by the state news agency SABA citing a statement by President Hadi. The agreement calls on Houthis to leave the presidential palace, and for the government to increase Houthis representation in government.
link_name: Yemen reaches deal with Houthis to end standoff in Sana'a

status_message: An investigation on conditions at the the U.S. Meat Animal Research Center in Nebraska by the New York Times published Jan. 19 has found that experiments and surgery have caused "illness, pain and premature death" over many years. The taxpayer-funded center was founded by Congress in 1964.
link_name: Federally funded research center risks animal welfare in meat experiments

status_message: The personal data, including contact details and online passwords, of over 1 million customers of UK shoe retailer Office were revealed in a data breach in May 2014, according to the BBC. The data was being held in an unencrypted database at an unsecured location outside the current infrastructure of the company.
link_name: Data breach at UK shoe retailer Office exposes customer data

status_message: Hundreds of detainees have been on hunger strike at the Australian-managed camp since Jan. 13. Although guards broke through a blockade on Jan. 19 set up by the hunger strikers, the protests continued into their ninth day as of Jan. 21.
link_name: Hunger strike at Australian refugee camp in Papua New Guinea continues

status_message: A fuel shortage reached Karachi Jan. 19 after pumps went dry in Punjab, Islamabad, Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa and other cities a week earlier. Opposition parties on Jan. 20 demanded an investigation. The shortage comes as oil-importing countries have benefited from falling crude oil prices.
link_name: Pakistanis wait in long lines as fuel crisis affects essential services

status_message: A federal jury convicted former union head Joseph Dougherty, 73, of racketeering, conspiracy and extortion on Jan. 20. He faces up to 15 years in prison. He was taken into custody pending his sentencing in April.
link_name: Federal jury convicts union boss in 'shadow gangs' racketeering trial

status_message: U.S. Supreme Court Justices appeared divided during oral arguments Jan. 20 over a challenge to a Florida law that bans judicial candidates from directly soliciting campaign contributions. Some justices seemingly favor restrictions on finances to combat corruption, while others say the law inhibits free speech.
link_name: Supreme Court appears split in judicial campaign finance case

status_message: A knife attack injured at least ten people on a bus in Tel Aviv on Jan. 21, including the driver. Three people were in serious condition. The suspect, a 23-year-old Palestinian resident of the West Bank town of Tulkarm, was shot in the leg after leaving the bus by a prison guard in the area. The event was described as a "lone-wolf" attack.
link_name: Knife attack injures at least 10 people on Tel Aviv bus

status_message: Two of the rooftop businesses across the street from Wrigley Field filed a federal lawsuit against Cubs owner Tom Ricketts on Jan. 20. The rooftops agreed in 2004 to a 17% revenue sharing deal with the club as long as their view to the field wasn't obstructed. The suit seeks unspecified damages.
link_name: Rooftop businesses sue Cubs over Wrigley Field renovations

status_message: Beyond the potential benefit for those without bank accounts, Walmart SVP Daniel Eckert admitted that "it's always a good thing to have customers in our stores that have jingle in their purses."
link_name: Walmart to cash out tax refunds

status_message: A poll by WBUR in Boston published Jan. 20 said 75% of residents want a referendum on whether the city should vie to host the Olympics. About 51% in the poll support a bid. Boston Mayor Martin Walsh said later in the day that he would not stand in the way of a referendum, but does not support one.
link_name: Boston residents polled support referendum on hosting Olympics

status_message: The NFL is investigating whether footballs used in the Jan. 18 AFC Championship Game were deflated below NFL regulations. A deflated football is easier to grip. The NFL rulebook cites discipline "including but not limited to, a fine of $25,000" against the head coach or team personnel for altering game balls.
link_name: NFL continues investigation into possible deflated footballs

status_message: Five employees at Walt Disney Parks and Resorts in Southern California contracted measles, the organization's head doctor Pamela Hymel said Jan. 20. Three have recovered and two are still out sick, she said. Other employees who had contact with them are on sick leave as a precaution.
link_name: Disney theme parks employees contract measles
Report: Obamacare website sharing personal information
Greenpeace identifies 4 activists who damaged Nazca Lines site
Mayor of Paris to sue Fox News over claims of 'no-go zones' for non-Muslims
Justice Dept. reaches $134,000 settlement over fake Facebook page
Study suggests prescription pain pill abuse is on the decline
Google, Fidelity invest $1 billion in SpaceX
Advocacy group calls for end of bison culling program
IBM posts mixed Q4 2014 results
Netflix massively beats profit estimates in Q4 2014

status_message: Facebook on Jan. 20 said it would take steps to reduce the number of fake news stories and hoaxes that users see in their News Feed. These steps include adding a label to stories that users have reported as being false or misleading (pictured) and reducing the distribution of these stories altogether.
link_name: Facebook will rely on users to report fake News Feed stories
Switzerland braces for economic impact of franc's rise in value
Feds testing honey at border to detect and tax Chinese imports
Current Guantanamo Bay detainee releases memoir

status_message:
Five Chechens arrested in south of France on suspicion of terrorism:

Police found a cache of explosives in the raid, according to a local prosecutor. They were found in close proximity to a football stadium, but authorities have not determined if the stadium was the target.
link_name: Five Chechens arrested in south of France on suspicion of terrorism

status_message: The study, published by the Deloitte consulting firm on Jan. 20, claims that Facebook added 4.5 million jobs to the worldwide economy and added $227 billion in economic activity in 2014. The study examined businesses that maintain a presence on Facebook as well as growth in devices that are used to access Facebook.
link_name: Facebook claims $227 billion in added economic activity

status_message: Krakow prosecutors, Jan. 20, filed a request at a regional court for the extradition of director Roman Polanski to the U.S. If successful, Poland's justice minister would have final say on the extradition. Polanski is currently in Poland shooting a movie.
link_name: Polish prosecutors request extradition of Roman Polanski

status_message: Computer security firm SplashData on Jan. 20 revealed its list of the top 25 most commonly used passwords online. 123456 and password were the two most commonly used passwords for the past four years, with 123456 overtaking password for the first time in 2013.
link_name: 123456 remains most used password in 2014

status_message: U.S. military commander in Afghanistan John Campbell said in an interview published Jan. 19 in the Army Times that he was considering to recommend extending the U.S. mission in Afghanistan and keep more troops there.
link_name: US general considering extending mission in Afghanistan

status_message: Houthi fighters gained access to the presidential palace following clashes with the presidential guard on Jan. 20, Al Arabiya reported. Fighting was ongoing around the residence. The U.S. embassy also reported one of its vehicles was fired upon the previous evening at a checkpoint.
link_name: Houthi fighters enter Yemen's presidential palace, report says

status_message: A Jan. 20 HRW report outlines a proposed counterterrorism law that will likely be rubber stamped as is in March. The says report the legislation (in Chinese), which will create a new agency, gives the Chinese government broader license than it already has to stifle dissent.
link_name: HRW: Proposed counterterrorism law in China too broad

status_message: Seven people have died from swine flu at a government-run hospital in Hyderabad since Jan. 1, officials said Jan. 18. More than 15 people have died and over 150 cases have been reported as of Jan. 20 in the southern states of Andhra Pradesh and Telangana since an outbreak in Dec. 2014.
link_name: Swine flu outbreak kills more than 30 people in India

status_message: Prime Minister Hun Sen called in a televised speech Jan. 19 for trials of 19 opposition members, including seven members of parliament, to proceed. The speech came as a July 2014 political truce between the CNRP and Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party (CPP) may be unraveling.
link_name: Cambodian prime minister calls for opposition lawmakers to be jailed

status_message: The viruses carried by commercial honey bees can jump to wild bee populations, which pollinate an estimated 80% of flowering plants around the world, according to a study published Jan. 16 in the Journal of Applied Ecology.
link_name: Study: Commercial bee diseases threaten wild bees

status_message: China closed 133 WeChat accounts because they "disobeyed socialist core values" and "severely disturbed the online order," the country's Cyberspace Administration said in Chinese state media on Jan. 20. The accounts were "distorting Chinese history," according to the report.
link_name: China shuts down 133 WeChat accounts for "distorting Chinese history"

status_message: A male contract worker died Jan. 19 after falling 30 feet into an empty water storage tank, plant operator TEPCO said Jan. 20. The name of the man, who was in his 50's, has not been released. "[TEPCO] promise[s] to implement measures" to avoid another accident, Fukushima manager Akira Ono said.
link_name: Second worker in a year dies at shuttered Fukushima plant

status_message: In a video released Jan. 20, the Islamic State (IS) threatened to kill two Japanese hostages within 72 hours if the group does not receive $200 million as ransom. The video identified the male hostages as Kenji Goto Jogo and Haruna Yukana. Japan is working on authenticating the video.
link_name: Islamic State threatens to kill Japanese hostages in video
GOP presidential hopefuls must meet 'threshold' to participate in primary debates
Mexico to use drones to protect world's smallest porpoise species
Syrian diplomatic efforts change tack amid ongoing violence, rise of extremists
Report: DreamWorks Animation plans layoffs
Pope Francis says Catholics don't have to breed 'like rabbits'
Astronomers say two more planets may exist in our solar system
French aid worker reported kidnapped in Central African Republic
Courts to hear challenge to Northern Ireland's abortion ban
UK ends fraud probe into HP-Autonomy deal
German authorities ban anti-Islamic rally, citing terror threat

status_message: The key reservoir in Brazil's most populous city, Sao Paulo, is at just 6% capacity halfway through the country's rainy season, the water utility provider said Jan. 19.
link_name: Brazil's largest city could face worst drought in 80 years
Report: AOL planning restructure, layoffs
World's richest 1% to own more than the rest combined by 2016, Oxfam says

status_message: Facebook is now testing a feature among a small number of users that automatically transcribes voices messages sent using Messenger into text. Facebook will gauge reaction to the feature before deciding whether or not to widely deploy it.
link_name: Facebook releases dedicated Groups app
Journalists' emails collected by UK surveillance agency

status_message: Nearly 600,000 people could join the workforce in Spain in 2015, Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy said in a Jan. 18 interview with Spanish news agency Efe. He also stuck with a previous expectation of 2% GDP growth, which is better than predictions by analysts, but matches the Bank of Spain.
link_name: Spanish prime minister expecting economic recovery in 2015

status_message:
Iraq oil exports in December reached highest levels in decades:

Iraqi oil output reached 4 million barrels per day (bpd) of oil in December 2014, "a historical figure, and the first time Iraq has achieved this," Abdel Mehdi said Jan. 18.
link_name: Iraq oil exports in December reached highest levels in decades

status_message:
EU calls for alliance with Muslim countries following Paris attacks:

EU leaders met Jan. 13 to discuss the best ways to counter terrorism "not only in Europe but in other parts of the world," according to Mogherini. The immediate focus for the 28-nation EU is preventing "foreign fighters" from returning home from countries like Syria and Iraq more radicalized.
link_name: EU calls for alliance with Muslim countries following Paris attacks

status_message: The Bangladesh government ordered telecom operators to block messaging services WhatApp, mypeople and Line, local reports said. The services were blocked Jan. 19, the Dhaka Tribune reported. The government on Jan. 17 ordered Viber and Tango blocked, citing security reasons, the telecommunication regulator said.
link_name: Bangladesh blocks messaging apps after weeks of protests

status_message: Fifth-seeded Ana Ivanovic of Serbia was upset in the first round of the Australian Open Jan. 19 by Czech qualifier Lucie Hradecka 1-6, 6-3, 6-2.
link_name: Ana Ivanovic ousted in first round of Australian Open

status_message: Four men from Brazil, Nigeria, Malawi and the Netherlands each and two women from Vietnam and Indonesia were executed Jan. 17, officials said. All were shot to death. Indonesian President Joko Widodo rejected appeals from Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff and the Dutch government to pardon their countrymen.
link_name: Indonesia executes 6 people including 5 foreigners for drug trafficking

status_message: Pope Francis' Sunday mass in Manila on Jan. 18 attracted a record six million people, Philippine authorities said. The previous record at a Catholic mass of four million people was set in Manila by the late Pope John Paul II in 1995 during the last papal visit to the island nation.
link_name: Largest Catholic mass ever held in Manila by Pope Francis

status_message: Ukraine's military said Jan. 18 it "almost completely clear[ed] the territory of the airport" from separatists. Rebels said Jan. 19 they remained in control of the airport since taking it Jan. 15. The Ukrainian military did not confirm a retreat.
link_name: Ukraine separatists claim control of Donetsk airport after government assault

status_message: American skier Lindsey Vonn won her 62nd career World Cup event Jan. 18 in Cortina D'Ampezzo, Itay. The win ties Vonn, 30, with Annemarie Moser-Proell, who raced in the 1970's.
link_name: Lindsey Vonn ties skiing victories record

status_message: Former Tigers pitcher Max Scherzer has agreed to a 7-year deal with the Washington Nationals, according to CBS Sports and MLB.com on Jan. 18. Neither Scherzer nor the Nationals have confirmed the deal. No reports included its financials.
link_name: Starting pitcher Scherzer reportedly signs 7-year deal with Nationals

status_message: "American Sniper" on Jan. 16-18 had the largest January opening weekend in history, earning $90.2 million at the North American box office. The film is expected to make $105 million including Martin Luther King Day, more than double the previous MLK weekend haul of "Ride Along" ($48.6M) in 2014.
link_name: "American Sniper" shoots to record January opening

status_message: Icy roads led to hundreds of accidents throughout the Northeast on Jan. 18. At least four people died in crashes in Pennsylvania. One person in Maryland and one person in Connecticut also died in crashes. Dozens of other people were injured throughout the region.
link_name: Icy roads on the US East Coast cause deadly car crashes

status_message: Gunfire broke out near the presidential palace between Yemeni troops and Houthis fighters, according to multiple reports. Roads and schools in the area shut. Explosions and gunfire could be heard throughout the capital. State TV was not reporting on the events due to power cuts.
link_name: Gun battles erupt near Yemeni presidential palace

status_message: Malian Health Minister Ousmane Kone on Jan. 18 declared the country Ebola-free after 42 days with no new cases. Mali had six deaths from eight confirmed cases of Ebola in 2014.
link_name: Health minister declares Mali free of Ebola

status_message: Obama's plan, unveiled by the White House on Jan. 17, would generate $320 billion in additional tax revenue by closing loopholes while increasing taxes on the wealthy and financial institutions.
link_name: Obama to reveal tax cuts for middle class in State of the Union

status_message: Boko Haram militants kidnapped at least 60 people during attacks on two villages in northern Cameroon on Jan. 18. Most of those abducted were reported to be women and children. Several people were also killed, officials said. The kidnapping is the largest committed in Cameroon by the extremists.
link_name: Boko Haram kidnaps at least 60 during raid in Cameroon

status_message: An Israeli helicopter fired two missiles at a target in Syria close to the border with Israel, according to Lebanese media reports on Jan. 18. Reports suggest a senior Hezbollah commander may have been the target.
link_name: Reports say Israeli helicopter launched strike inside Syria near Golan Heights

status_message: According to federal law enforcement officials, the vice president and his wife were not at home when several shots were fired by a passing vehicle on Jan. 17. Secret Service and local police did not catch the suspects as they sped away.
link_name: Gunshots fired outside Biden's Delaware residence

status_message: University of California president Janet Napolitano announced a decision to implement an incentive-pay policy in January. Athletic directors and coaches with winning records will be eligible for bonuses only if their teams maintain a minimum 2.0 GPA with a full-time course load. They can also receive new bonuses for athletes' academic success.
link_name: University of California links coach bonuses to grades

status_message: A study released mid-January by the Southern Education Foundation (SEF) showed 51% of children in U.S. public schools qualified for free or reduced-price lunches in 2013. In 2000, 38% qualified. The National School Lunch Program includes families that earn up to $43,568, for a family of four.
link_name: Majority of US public school students are from low income families

status_message: Human Rights Watch and a coalition of more than a dozen other advocacy groups called on Bahrain's allies in Europe to push for the charges against Nabeel Rajab to be dropped ahead of an expected court ruling on Jan. 20. Rajab faces up to six years in prison if convicted.
link_name: Human rights groups call on Bahrain to drop charges against activist

status_message: Sen. Patrick Leahy (D-VT) is leading the first congressional delegation to Cuba on a Jan. 17-19 trip. He's joined by five other democratic members of congress, including Sen. Richard Durbin (IL) and Rep. Chris Van Hollen (MD). They will meet with Cuban government officials and other nations' ambassadors to Cuba.
link_name: Members of Congress visit Cuba for first time since new policy announced
Romney giving presidential run 'serious consideration'

status_message: Charlie Hebdo's latest cover, which portrays the likeness of the Prophet Muhammed, has angered many Muslims.
link_name: Violent protests over 'Charlie Hebdo' in Middle East, Asia, Africa

status_message: The Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection Jan. 16. Archbishop John Nienstedt claimed the archdiocese cannot withstand the financial demands of an onslaught of lawsuits: 20 suits have been filed while another 100 are pending against the church.
link_name: Sex abuse lawsuits force St. Paul-Minneapolis archdiocese into bankruptcy

status_message: An art exhibit claiming to explore the societal implications of robots breaking the law and the ethical implications of Deep Web marketplaces was seized by police after its three-month run. Police will likely tell the artists how they are going to proceed with their investigation the week of Jan. 19, a spokesman for the artists said Jan. 16.
link_name: Police seize bot that bought drugs on the Deep Web

status_message: Belgium mobilized 300 troops in its major cities, Jan. 17, to guard potential targets for a terrorist attack. Among the buildings being guarded were Jewish schools, synagogues, government buildings and embassies.
link_name: Soldiers stand guard on Belgian streets

status_message: Yemeni officials said Jan. 17 that President Abd-Rabbo Mansour Hadi's chief of staff, Ahmed Awad bin Mubarak, and two of his guards were kidnapped in Sana'a during the day by armed men. No one has publicly claimed responsibility for the abduction and police said there has been no ransom demand.
link_name: Yemeni president's chief of staff abducted

status_message: State and local police can no longer use federal law to take ownership of seized private property, a controversial practice known as asset forfeiture, under a new directive announced by Attorney General Eric Holder Jan. 16.
link_name: US Attorney General limits asset seizure by local, state police
Monsanto gains approval to use herbicide-resistant soybean and cotton seeds
Floods in southeast Africa kill at least 214, displace thousands
AT&T closes $2.5 billion deal for Mexican carrier Iusacell
Chinese media report 'unprecedented' drug crackdown
Fox News restored to Dish Network
Justice Dept. reveals DEA database of American telephone records

status_message: After a long trend of narrow rulings on same-sex marriage, the Supreme Court has finally agreed to decide whether all 50 states must allow gay and lesbian couples to marry.
link_name: Supreme Court to decide whether all 50 states must allow gay and lesbian couples to marry.
Goldman Sachs earnings beat estimates, but disappoint market
New York state allocates $500 million for broadband expansion
Muhammad Ali released from hospital following urinary tract infection
NOAA and NASA researchers say 2014 was the warmest year on record
Five charged after Belgian counter-terror raid
Xbox One outsells PS4 in December in US
Head of Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services steps down

status_message: The Paris prosecutors' office said Jan. 16 that a dozen people had been arrested the night before in connection with the Paris attacks, saying they may have provided "logistical support." It was not immediately clear which attack the suspects are believed to be part of.
link_name: Twelve arrested in France in connection with Paris attacks

status_message: Berlin police on Jan. 16 arrested two Turkish citizens in their 40s who are suspected of "providing financial and logistical support" to the Islamic State (IS). The men were taken into custody after 250 police carried out raids on 11 residences.
link_name: Germany arrests two people suspected of recruiting for Islamic State

status_message: Vanessa Marzullo, 21, and Greta Ramelli, 20, were freed Jan. 15 after five months in captivity. They were kidnapped in Aleppo, Syria.
link_name: Kidnapped Italian aid workers freed in Syria

status_message: Agnes Chow, Oscar Lai, Derek Lam and Joshua Wong were arrested Jan. 16 after turning themselves in to Hong Kong police. All but Wong were released a few hours later. It wasn't immediately clear why Wong was still in police custody.
link_name: Hong Kong student protest leaders arrested
UK Mars rover lost for a dozen years found on Red Planet

status_message: The U.S. will deploy 400 troops to train some Syrian rebels to fight against the Islamic State (IS), Pentagon officials said Jan. 15. Further details on the deployment have not been made public.
link_name: US sending 400 troops to train Syrian rebels to fight Islamic State

status_message: Around 5,000 protesters marched in Lima, one of the 11 cities Peru that held demonstrations. The Jan. 15 rallies were the fourth set of demonstrations against the so-called Pulpin Law.
link_name: Protests escalate over youth labor law in Peru

status_message: The New Horizons probe began collecting data from about 134 million miles from Pluto on Jan. 15. NASA will use images of Pluto from the probe to guide the ship toward the dwarf planet. The first such picture will be taken Jan. 25, at which time the planet will still appear quite small.
link_name: NASA probe begins six-month final approach to Pluto
Lack of data on police use of force is 'unacceptable,' Holder says
Judge caps BP's 2010 Gulf oil spill fine at $13.7 billion
Tech companies propose $415 million settlement in poaching lawsuit
Flu vaccine only 23% effective this season, CDC says
Florida set to execute man with controversial drug combination
Navy captain pleads guilty to bribery charges
Right-wing 'bullet caucus' on the rise in Brazil

status_message:
Silk Road Trial: Ross Ulbricht's defense claims Mt. Gox leader was Dread Pirate Roberts:

On Jan. 15, the third day of the trial, Ross Ulbricht's defense team claimed that Mark Karpeles, the former CEO of bitcoin exchange Mt. Gox, was the actual Dread Pirate Roberts.
link_name: Silk Road Trial: Ross Ulbricht's defense claims Mt. Gox leader was Dread Pirate Roberts
More measles cases tied to Disney outbreak
Elon Musk to build Hyperloop test track

status_message:
Obama to be interviewed by YouTube vloggers after State of the Union:

The White House said Jan. 22 that Obama will be interviewed by YouTubers Bethany Mota, Hank Green and Glozell Green after the State of the Union. The move is seen as part of an effort to reach out to young people. The White House also posted a short promotional video for the interviews.
link_name: Obama to be interviewed by YouTube vloggers after State of the Union

status_message:
Google Glass will leave Google X, the company's experimental R&D division, according to multiple reports by BBC, Fortune and WSJ. 

As part of the shakeup, Nest's Tony Fadell will oversee the stand-alone Glass unit. The reports also noted that Google plans to release a new version of Glass this year.
link_name: Google Glass to leave Google X, will be overseen by Nest's Tony Fadell - reports
Ukraine moves to replace soldiers on front line against separatists

status_message: "We will not allow ourselves to be divided by those who, in the face of Islamist terror, place Muslims in Germany under general suspicion. There must be no ostracism of Muslims, no sweeping suspicions. As chancellor, I will come to the defense of Muslims in this country against that." - Angela Merkel, German chancellor
link_name: Merkel issues open call in German parliament against "ostracism of Muslims"
Maker Studios partners with Vimeo for exclusive videos
Spain reports 1.1% drop in prices in December

status_message:
Catalonian sets up snap elections to test support of independence:

Late Jan. 14 Catalonia President Artur Mas called for snap regional elections in Sept. 27 to test support for Catalonian independence. The election will happen one year after Mas signed a decree calling for a referendum.
link_name: Catalonian sets up snap elections to test support of independence

status_message:
Euro reaches new nine-year low as Greece falls short of budget targets:

The euro fell 1% against the dollar to $1.1773, its lowest since Dec. 2005, before closing at $1.1789 on Jan. 14. Greek inflation, which reached -2.6% in December 2014, is an ongoing cause for concern for the European Central Bank (ECB), which will likely announce an expansion of its policy of quantitative easing at a meeting on Jan. 22.
link_name: Euro reaches new nine-year low as Greece falls short of budget targets

status_message:
Syrian government and rebels begin truce in Homs:

Rebel fighters and the Syrian military began a ten-day ceasefire in the rebel-held area of Al-Waar in northwest Homs, activists told the AP. Fighters agreed to the truce to spare the area from further military action and destruction. The government has blockaded Al-Waar for about 20 months.
link_name: Syrian government and rebels begin truce in Homs

status_message:
Sea level rise since 1990 may have accelerated faster than previously thought:

A study published in Nature on Jan. 14 found that scientists had overestimated sea level rise from 1901-1990. The findings suggested that sea level rise since 1990 had accelerated 25% faster than previously thought. The study authors said projections of sea level rise would likely be affected.
link_name: Sea level rise since 1990 may have accelerated faster than previously thought

status_message:
Bank of America Q4 profit down on drop in fixed income trading revenue:

Bank of America reported on Jan. 15 its fourth quarter net income fell to $3.1 billion, or $0.25/share from $3.4 billion, or $0.29/share, a year ago. Total revenue fell to 18.7 billion, from $21.7 billion in the last quarter of 2013.
link_name: Bank of America Q4 profit down on drop in fixed income trading revenue

status_message:
New US rules for Cuba go into effect Friday:

The White House released a fact sheet Dec. 17, 2014 titled, "Charting a New Course on Cuba." It outlines steps by the Obama administration to improve relations with Cuba. Headline measures include establishing full diplomatic relations and an embassy in Havana, and lifting several travel restrictions.
link_name: New US rules for Cuba go into effect Friday

status_message:
U.S. foreclosures neared 17-month high in December:

RealtyTrac reported 148,023 homes were scheduled for foreclosure in the fourth quarter of 2014, an increase of 4% from the third and up 7% from the fourth quarter in 2013. In December, the rate of new foreclosures increased 14% from the previous year, nearing a 17-month high of 59,358.
link_name: U.S. foreclosures neared 17-month high in December

status_message: Pope Francis arrived in the Philippines Jan. 15 in the first papal visit to the island nation in 20 years. As many as eight million people are expected to attend a Sunday mass in Manila on Jan. 18. That could make it the largest papal mass ever.
link_name: Pope Francis arrives in the Philippines

status_message: The Russian government may have to reduce its budget by as much as 10% (excluding defense) because of low oil prices, Russian Finance Minister Anton Siluanov said Jan. 14. The government could receive $45 billion less in 2015 if oil prices continue to hover around $50 a barrel, he said.
link_name: Russia may slash budget due to low oil prices, finance minister says

status_message: A federal judge in New York on Jan. 14 dismissed the lawsuit against Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi. U.S. District Judge Analisa Torres upheld the U.S. government's argument that Modi was entitled to immunity from civil lawsuits filed in the U.S. as a sitting head of government.
link_name: US court dismisses civil lawsuit against Indian Prime Minister Modi

status_message: Xiaomi on Jan. 15 announced a new flagship phone, the Xiaomi Note. The 5.7-inch phone has two slots for 4G SIM cards, runs a Snapdragon 801 2.5GHz processor and has 3GB of RAM. It will go on sale in China Jan. 27 for 2299RMB ($371).
link_name: Xiaomi reveals new flagship phone

status_message: At least three state governors in Venezuela banned lines outside stores by Jan. 13, saying the crowds are becoming dangerous. Some Venezuelans are making a living by waiting in line for other people who are too busy during the day.
link_name: Venezuelan governors ban lines outside of stores at night

status_message: Iranian Foreign Minister Javad Zarif met U.S. Sec. of State John Kerry in Geneva three times on Jan. 14 for intensive talks on Iran's nuclear program. U.S. and Iranian negotiators were following up with technical talks. Zarif was also scheduled to meet his German and EU counterparts ahead of wider talks Jan. 18.
link_name: Iranian foreign minister meeting counterparts ahead of wider nuclear talks

status_message: Beijing's air pollution went "beyond index" on Jan. 15, meaning it exceeded the scale's highest reading of 500, according to the U.S. Embassy in Beijing. Both the PM2.5 and larger PM10 levels in the city were extremely high by midday. Pollution has exceeded the index several times, most recently in October 2014.
link_name: Beijing's air pollution goes "beyond index" again

status_message: Josh McNary, 26, was charged with rape, battery and criminal confinement on Jan. 14. He was taken into custody later in the day. Court documents accuse McNary of sexually assaulting a 29-year-old woman in his apartment on Dec. 1, 2014.
link_name: Backup linebacker for NFL's Colts charged with rape
49ers promote defensive line coach to head coach
Woman pushing for criminal charges against Bill Cosby

status_message: Chiquita said Jan. 14 that it will shutter its North Carolina headquarters following the buyout from the two Brazilian firms, which was completed in early January. Operations at headquarters are expected to wind down over the next year and a half. Some 300 workers are employed at the office.
link_name: North Carolina Chiquita headquarters to shutter following takeover deal

status_message: Hundreds of migrant workers have continued to die during the construction of Qatar's World Cup soccer venues ahead of the 2022 event.
link_name: Qatar World Cup stadium construction continues to be deadly for migrant workers

status_message: The French government said Jan. 14 it is reducing its troops in Central African Republic from 2,000 to 800. The 1,200 French troops are expected to be out of the country by autumn. The move comes after the UN provided peacekeeping troops to CAR.
link_name: France pulls 1,200 troops from Central African Republic

status_message: The RNC said in a statement issued late Jan. 14 that it will host its convention July 18-21, 2016.
link_name: Republicans pick dates for 2016 party convention
Obama to push for paid time off for more US workers
JPMorgan legal costs push Q4 profit down 7%
Justice Dept. issues new guidelines for news media leak investigations
Internet.org project releases free app in Colombia

status_message:
FBI arrests Ohio man for alleged plot on US Capitol:

Christopher Lee Cornell, also known as Raheel Mahrus Ubaydah, was arrested Jan. 14, for an alleged plot to bomb and shoot lawmakers at the U.S. Capitol.
link_name: FBI arrests Ohio man for alleged plot on US Capitol

status_message: The Secret Service will dismiss four of its most senior officials and a fifth will be retiring
link_name: Secret Service review calls for taller White House fence, more agents

status_message:
HHS says nearly 6.8 million people enrolled for Obamacare:

Health and Human Services reported Jan. 14 that nearly 6.8 million people have signed up for insurance plans in the 36 states where the federal government operates the healthcare marketplace through Jan. 9. HHS expects a final rush of people to sign up before the Feb. 15 deadline to avoid a penalty.
link_name: HHS says nearly 6.8 million people enrolled for Obamacare

status_message:
US journalist indicted, referred to Tehran court:

Iran's judicial authorities have indicted Jason Rezaian and referred his case to the Tehran Revolutionary Court, according to reports from Iranian news agencies, Jan. 14. The charges against Rezaian are not public.
link_name: US journalist indicted, referred to Tehran court

status_message: Blackberry stock jumped over 20% on Jan. 14 following a report that Samsung approached the company about a potential takeover.
link_name: BlackBerry stock soars on report of Samsung interest in takeover

status_message:
Google to test modular Project Ara smartphones in Puerto Rico:

Google will release the first of its Project Ara modular smartphones in Puerto Rico later this year, the company confirmed at a Jan. 14 developer conference. Google is working with local wireless carriers Claro and Open Mobile as part of the release.
link_name: Google to test modular Project Ara smartphones in Puerto Rico

status_message:
Number of new confirmed Ebola cases fall to lowest in months:

The World Health Organization said Jan. 14 that new confirmed cases in the three countries hardest hit by the outbreak fell to lowest in months. Sierra Leone and Guinea reported the lowest number of new confirmed cases since August 2014. In Liberia, new cases fell to the lowest since June 2014.
link_name: Number of new confirmed Ebola cases fall to lowest in months

status_message: The value of a single bitcoin fell below $200 on Jan. 14, one day after falling below $250 for the first time since October 2013. By midday on Jan. 14, bitcoin was hovering around $186. Bitcoin's value steadily declined throughout 2014 after reaching a high of around $650 in June of that year.
link_name: Bitcoin now trading below $200

status_message:
House votes to block funding of Obama programs to delay deportations:

The House voted to block President Obama's 2012 action delaying the deportation of young immigrants in a 218-209 vote Jan. 14. Democrats were joined by 26 Republicans in opposing the bill. The bill is an amendment to a Dept. of Homeland Security funding bill. The House also voted 237-190 to block funding for Obama's November executive action.
link_name: House votes to block funding of Obama programs to delay deportations

status_message:
South Sudan conflict could cost neighboring countries billions, report says:

The economies of Ethiopia, Kenya, Sudan, Uganda and Tanzania could lose an estimated $53 billion combined if conflict in South Sudan continues for five years, a report by London-based consultancy Frontier Economics said Jan. 14. Foreign peacekeeping and humanitarian missions could cost $30 billion, it said.
link_name: South Sudan conflict could cost neighboring countries billions, report says

status_message:
'Transformers' leads 2014 Razzie nominations, recognizing the year's worst movies:

"Transformers: Age of Extinction" starring Mark Wahlberg earned seven nominations this year, including worst picture and worst sequel. Other worst picture nominees include Kirk Cameron's "Saving Christmas," "Left Behind," "The Legend of Hercules," and "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles."
link_name: 'Transformers' leads 2014 Razzie nominations

status_message:
Tech companies reach larger settlement in poaching lawsuit:

Adobe, Apple, Google, and Intel have reached a larger settlement with employees in the class action lawsuit, the details of which are expected to be released later on Jan. 14. The New York Times reported that the new settlement amount could be as high as $415 million, up from $324.5 million offered in 2014.
link_name: Tech companies reach larger settlement in poaching lawsuit

status_message:
European scientists conduct simulation to prepare for meteor impact:

In Nov. 2014, the ESA held a 2-day simulation of a meteor strike, the agency said in December. The simulation looked at a meteor of between 12-38 meters in diameter. The scientists looked at what they would be able to do to inform the public at intervals of up to a month in advance.
link_name: European scientists conduct simulation to prepare for hypothetical meteor impact with Earth

status_message: A number of GOP House lawmakers, as well as at least one Democrat, are drafting a bill to bypass court rulings in Michigan, Minnesota, Wisconsin and Wyoming that overturned the delisting of gray wolves as endangered in those states. The bill is led by Rep. Reid Ribble (R-Wisc.).
link_name: US House members drafting bill to delist gray wolves as endangered

status_message: One of Singapore's Navy ships found the plane's fuselage, Singaporean Defense Minister Ng Eng Hen confirmed Jan. 14. Search officials believe many of the bodies of the missing victims may be trapped in the fuselage.
link_name: Fuselage of submerged AirAsia plane found

status_message: The World Bank on Jan. 13 cut its global economic growth outlook for 2015 and 2016 to 3% and 3.3%, respectively, due to slow financial recovery in the eurozone and Japan. In June 2014, the bank forecast growth of 3.4% for 2015 and 3.5% in 2016.
link_name: World Bank cuts global economic growth outlook

status_message: Tesla will need to sell about half a million cars to be profitable by general U.S. accounting standards by 2020, Musk said Jan. 13. Shares in the company dropped 6.7% to $190.80 in after-hours trading on the news.
link_name: Tesla won't be profitable until at least 2020, says CEO Musk

status_message: South Korea's parliament has passed a bill to compensate people affected by the sinking of the ferry. The payments will be funded by state money and private donations, and will include scholarships for students who survived the disaster. Fishermen who suffered losses from taking part in the search will also be eligible for money.
link_name: South Korea passes compensation plan for people affected by ferry sinking

status_message: A federal judge in Sacramento is reviewing a case that could downgrade marijuana from Schedule 1, the most dangerous class which includes heroin and LSD. The case questions the constitutionality of the drug's classification under the 1970 Controlled Substances Act.
link_name: Federal court considers reclassifying marijuana as less dangerous substance
Bartender indicted for threatening to kill House Speaker John Boehner
China shutters 50 websites and social media accounts

status_message: A Russian admiral said Jan. 13 that the country's entire Northern Fleet, which totals around 3,000 ground troops, will be moved to a base near the border with Finland. The Northern Fleet also includes 39 ships and 45 submarines.
link_name: Russia expanding military base near Finnish border
US reports $2 billion surplus in December
NYC agrees to end Rikers solitary confinement for inmates 21 and under
Strong bond sales indicate confidence in Portuguese economy

status_message: Ross Ulbricht admitted on Jan. 13 to creating the Silk Road website on the first day of his trial, but claimed he handed over control of it to someone who went by the handle Dread Pirate Roberts. Ulbricht's defense team said running the website was "too stressful" for him and that he was merely the "fall guy" for Dread Pirate Roberts.
link_name: Ross Ulbricht admits to creating Silk Road, claims he isn't Dread Pirate Roberts

status_message: Instacart confirmed on Jan. 13 that it had raised $220 million in a funding round that was led by Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers, a venture capital firm that previously backed companies like Google, Twitter, and Uber. Several publications reported the company is now valued at $2 billion.
link_name: Grocery delivery startup Instacart raises $220 million
New Jersey Muslims take NYPD to court over surveillance
GoPro declines to four-month low as Apple gets camera patent
Soybeans drop 36 cents following USDA supply report
US designates Pakistani Taliban leader a 'global terrorist'

status_message: Progressive groups in New Hampshire will hold their first meeting of an effort dubbed "Run, Warren, Run" on Jan. 17. The gathering aims to compel the Massachusetts senator to run in the 2016 race for president.
link_name: New Hampshire progressives will meet to 'draft' Warren for 2016 run
Shelling in Donetsk, Ukraine, leaves 10 dead in passenger bus
PC version of Grand Theft Auto V delayed until March
Bitcoin falls below $250 for first time since 2013
Ebola infection rates fall in Liberia and Sierra Leone

status_message: New episodes of the cult hit "Community" will debut on Yahoo on March 17, the cast revealed at a Jan. 13 Television Critics Association event. Two episodes will be available on March 17, with one episode released per week thereafter. There will be 13 episodes in all.
link_name: Community debuts on Yahoo on March 17

status_message:
Martin Luther King Jr.'s children return to court over late leader's Nobel prize and Bible: 

Bernice King contends her brothers, Dexter King and Martin Luther King III, want to sell their father's relics, something she opposes. The three return to court on Jan. 13 to face Fulton County Superior Court Judge Robert McBurney, who is to decide which side will ultimately control the items.
link_name: Martin Luther King Jr.'s children return to court over late leader's Nobel prize and Bible

status_message:
UK prime minister suggests banning encrypted messaging apps:

UK Prime Minister David Cameron, who faces an election in May, said in a Jan. 12 speech that if his government is re-elected it would propose legislation that would ban encrypted communication tools. The suggestion was immediately criticized by computer security experts.
link_name: UK prime minister suggests banning encrypted messaging apps

status_message:
Indonesia president's pick for police chief named corruption suspect:

On Jan. 13, Indonesia's anti-graft agency named three-star general and police chief nominee Budi Gunawan as a bribery suspect. On Jan. 10, President Widodo named Gunawan as his sole candidate to head the police force, which is considered to be one of the most corrupt institutions in the country.
link_name: Indonesia president's pick for police chief named corruption suspect

status_message:
Thai government steps up actions against human trafficking:

The Thai government said Jan. 12 that it convicted more than 100 people for human trafficking in 2014. It also introduced new regulations in its fishing sector to crack down on illegal and unregistered fishing activities, including abuse of foreign workers and deployment of satellite devices in fishing boats.
link_name: Thai government steps up actions against human trafficking

status_message:
Italian president stepping down for health reasons:

Italian President Giorgio Napolitano is stepping down to allow parliament to name a new head of state, Prime Minister Matteo Renzi said Jan. 13. Napolitano, 89, was widely expected to do so after citing age-related health problems in Dec. 2014. The process to replace him is expected to begin by the end of January.
link_name: Italian president stepping down for health reasons

status_message:
Venezuela sets limits at state-run supermarkets to cut lines and protests:

Police began to enforce a presidential directive on Jan. 12 to limit shopping at government-owned food stores to two days a week. Long lines at the stores in the previous week had sparked unrest. Police detained at least a dozen people. Shoppers have their IDs checked at stores under the new rules.
link_name: Venezuela sets limits at state-run supermarkets to cut lines and protests

status_message:
Senior commander in Kony's LRA will face trial at ICC:

Dominic Ongwen, a senior commander in the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA), will face trial at the International Criminal Court (ICC) at The Hague, a Ugandan military spokesman told Reuters on Jan. 13. Ongwen is wanted by the ICC for war crimes charges including crimes against humanity.
link_name: Senior commander in Kony's LRA will face trial at ICC

status_message:
Pakistan's provincial government to allow staff to carry guns to school:

Educational institutions have been asked to hire people from retired armed forces, as the government cannot provide police protection to all. Installation of security cameras and barbed wire fences have also been made mandatory in schools.
link_name: Pakistan's provincial government to allow staff to carry guns to school

status_message:
Woody Allen to write and direct TV series for Amazon:

Amazon confirmed Jan. 13 that Woody Allen will write and direct an original television series for the company's Instant Video streaming service. The untitled project will consist of 30-minute episodes. Additional details, including the cast, will be released later.
link_name: Woody Allen to write and direct TV series for Amazon

status_message:
Facebook to deliver AMBER Alerts to find missing children:

Facebook on Jan. 13 announced a partnership with the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children to display AMBER Alerts in users' feeds. The alerts display photos and other information about the missing child, including the name and description (where available) of the the child's abductor.
link_name: Facebook to deliver AMBER Alerts to find missing children

status_message: At least 54 attacks and threats at Muslim sites and mosques occurred in France since the Charlie Hebdo attack
link_name: Funerals held for France attack victims

status_message: At least 14 people died and more than 100 were hospitalized after consuming spurious liquor in northern India, officials said. Police found large containers of chemicals when they raided the shop that sold the homemade liquor in small packets. The shop owner was arrested.
link_name: Bootlegged liquor in India kills 14 people and hospitalizes more than 100

status_message: UVA reinstated Phi Kappa Psi on Jan. 12 after police found no "substantive basis to confirm that the allegations raised in the article occurred" at the fraternity. However, the investigation into the allegations is continuing, Charlottesville Police Captain Gary Pleasants said.
link_name: UVA fraternity in Rolling Stone article reinstated

status_message: Dublin-based Shire PLC said Jan. 11 it would buy U.S.-based NPS Pharmaceuticals for $5.2 billion in an all cash deal to boost its presence in the area of treating rare diseases. The announcement comes after Shire's plans to sell itself to Illinois-based AbbVie Inc for $52 billion collapsed in Oct. 2014.
link_name: Shire to buy NPS Pharma for $5.2 billion in all cash deal

status_message: An average of six people die of alcohol poisoning a day, according to a Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) study in early January. Most of the people who die are men aged 35-64 years old. Alaska had the highest death rate. Alcoholism was a factor in 30% of the poisonings caused by binge drinking.
link_name: CDC: Alcohol poisoning causes six US deaths a day

status_message:
Ohio State wins college football championship:

The Ohio State (OSU) Buckeyes won the 2015 College Football Playoff championship game 42-20 on Jan. 12 in Arlington, TX, over the Oregon Ducks. The win was OSU's eight national title and first since 2002. Coach Urban Meyer won his third national title after winning a the head coach of Florida.
link_name: Ohio State wins college football championship

status_message: Two officers who shot a homeless man in Albuquerque were each charged with a single count of murder on Jan. 12. District Attorney Kari Brandenburg said she will not use a grand jury. Instead, a judge will decide at an open hearing whether there is enough evidence to proceed with the charges. No date has been set for the hearing.
link_name: 2 Albuquerque officers charged with murder in death of homeless man

status_message: A senior adviser to California Attorney Gen. Kamala Harris (D) said Jan. 12 that Harris will announce her intention to run for the seat being vacated by Sen. Barbara Boxer. The move makes Harris the first person to announce intentions to run for the seat.
link_name: California Attorney General Kamala Harris to announce 2016 run for Senate
One person dead, dozens sent to hospital after DC subway fills with smoke
Federal court clears way for new lethal injection protocol in Oklahoma

status_message: The bill to approve the Keystone XL pipeline cleared its first procedural hurdle on the floor of the Senate on Jan. 12. In a 63-32 vote, Senators moved to advance the bill. The measure is expected to get a final vote during the last week of January.
link_name: Keystone XL pipeline clears procedural hurdle in Senate
Justice Dept. will not compel Times reporter to testify in CIA leak trial
Following attacks in France, right-wing rallies swell in Germany
PC shipments decline 2.1% in 2014
Schumer urges FDA to address poor conditions at food warehouses

status_message: A federal judge struck down South Dakota's ban on same-sex marriage Jan. 12, saying the ban violates the 14th Amendment. However, the decision was stayed because the case "presents substantial and novel legal questions, and because there is a substantial public interest in uniformity and stability of the law."
link_name: Federal judge strikes down South Dakota same-sex marriage ban
Nielsen claims tweets can predict success of new TV shows
Designer John Galliano debuts first couture show after 4-year hiatus

status_message: 2012 vice presidential candidate Paul Ryan says he won't be on the top half of any ticket in 2016.
link_name: Paul Ryan says he will not run for president in 2016

status_message:
Paul Ryan says he will not run for president in 2016:

"After giving it a lot of thought, I've decided not to run for president. Our work at the House Ways and Means Committee over the next few years will be crucial to moving America forward, and my job as Chairman deserves undivided attention."
- Rep. Paul Ryan (R-WI)
link_name: Paul Ryan says he will not run for president in 2016
Microsoft criticizes Google for disclosing Windows security hole
Supreme Court declines to hear case over blood tests for DUIs
Rex Ryan named Buffalo Bills' new head coach
Russian intelligence sought to recruit Edward Snowden, source says

status_message: Speaking at the Federal Trade Commission, President Obama on Jan. 12 proposed a law that would require companies to alert their customers within 30 days of a cyberattack that their data may have been stolen. There is currently no federal law requiring companies to issue such alerts.
link_name: President Obama proposes new cybersecurity measures

status_message:
US Central Command Twitter account hacked:

The Twitter account for U.S. Central Command was seemingly hacked on Jan. 12 by an Islamic State-affiliated group calling itself the "CyberCaliphate." The hackers used the account to post numerous documents containing contact information for U.S. military personnel and their families.
link_name: US Central Command Twitter account hacked
Experts including Elon Musk warn against 'pitfalls' of artificial intelligence

status_message:
Israeli deputy interior minister resigns amid corruption probe:

Kirshenbaum on Jan. 12 became the fourth senior Yisrael Beiteinu politician to step down ahead of elections. Police have frozen her bank accounts. Police made several other arrests as part of the corruption probe on the same day she made the announcement.
link_name: Israeli deputy interior minister resigns amid corruption probe

status_message:
Spotify reaches 15 million paying subscribers:

Spotify said Jan. 12 that it now has a total of 60 million users worldwide, with 15 million of those being paying subscribers. The company in November 2014 said it had 50 million users, 12.5 million of which were paying subscribers.
link_name: Spotify reaches 15 million paying subscribers

status_message:
"Taken 3" opens with $40.4 million at box office:

"Taken 3" starring Liam Neeson earned $40.4 million at the North American box office in its opening weekend of Jan. 9-11, despite poor reviews. In its first weekend of wide release, "Selma" took second place with $11.2 million.
link_name: "Taken 3" opens with $40.4 million at box office

status_message: Cuba released all 53 detainees in deal with US, officials say
link_name: Cuba released all 53 detainees in deal with US, officials say

status_message: French Defense Minister Jean-Yves Le Drian (right) said Jan. 12 that 10,000 troops would be deployed nationwide starting Jan. 13. An additional mix of 5,000 troops and police will guard the country's 700 Jewish schools, he said following an emergency cabinet meeting.
link_name: Police and troops to be deployed in France, including at hundreds of Jewish schools

status_message: Emotions ran high as students returned to the Peshawar school Jan. 12 for a new term after the Dec. 16 massacre. Pakistani Army Chief Gen. Raheel Sharif greeted students and met parents. Some schools in Peshawar are getting security measures like extra walls.
link_name: Pakistani children return to classes after Peshawar school attack

status_message: Modi said at a global investor summit in Gujarat on Jan. 11 that his government would provide stable taxes and a favorable policy environment for foreign investors in India. He started the summit when he headed Gujarat in 2003. The summit has seen billion-dollar commitments, but few investments actually happened.
link_name: Indian Prime Minister Modi appeals to global investors with policy promises

status_message: "Taken 3" starring Liam Neeson earned $40.4 million at the North American box office in its opening weekend of Jan. 9-11, despite poor reviews. In its first weekend of wide release, "Selma" took second place with $11.2 million.
link_name: "Taken 3" opens with $40.4 million at box office

status_message: Assailants threw Molotov cocktails at the entrances of the home (pictured) and office of Jimmy Lai, publisher of the newspaper Apple Daily overnight Jan. 11/12. No one was injured.
link_name: Molotov cocktails thrown at house and office of prominent Hong Kong businessman

status_message: According to the state electoral commission, with almost all of the votes counted, Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovic garnered 50.4% of the vote. Her opponent, Ivo Josipovic, earned 49.6%.
link_name: Croatia elects first female president by narrow margin

status_message: The White House will host an anti-extremism summit Feb. 18. Representatives will work on programs that engage communities, religious leaders, the private sector and the tech community.
link_name: White House to host anti-extremism summit in February

status_message: A mass rally began at the Place de la Republique just after 3pm local time, led by France's president and prime minister, as well as other leaders and dignitaries from around the world. The country's interior ministry said the rally was "unprecedented" and the largest in French history.
link_name: Dozens of world leaders join large Unity March in Paris

status_message: Libya's rival governments agreed to talks "next week" in Geneva to try to end a political stalemate and armed conflict, the UN said Jan. 10.
link_name: Rival Libyan governments agree to UN-brokered talks

status_message: Malian President Ibrahim Boubacar Keita on Jan. 10 appointed seven new members of the cabinet, including the key posts overseeing the military and economy. He did not change the important positions at the foreign affairs and mines ministries. Fresh peace talks with separatists were scheduled for later in the month in Algeria.
link_name: Mali's president picks government before peace talks

status_message: Twenty demonstrators from anti-torture groups Code Pink and Witness Against Torture protested on Cheney's property on Jan. 10, the eve of the 13th anniversary of the opening of Guantanamo Bay prison to call for its closure.
link_name: Two anti-torture protesters arrested outside Dick Cheney's home

status_message: Divers located the plane's data recorders on Jan. 11, but were unable to immediately retrieve the "black box" because it was located under wreckage from the plane. Crews will attempt to move the debris on Jan. 12.
link_name: Divers locate AirAsia flight data recorders

status_message: Nintendo will no longer distribute its games or consoles in Brazil, the company announced Jan. 9. Imported games and gaming systems are more expensive in Brazil. For example, Nintendo's Super Smash Bros. retails for $74 in Brazil and only $60 in the United States ‚Äî a 20% difference.
link_name: Nintendo to stop selling in Brazil because of high tariffs

status_message: Twenty-six children have died due to complications for this year's flu, the CDC reported Jan. 9. According CDC Director Tom Frieden, this flu season is "shaping up to be a severe one." He said it is "too soon" to tell whether the flu season has reached a peak.
link_name: CDC says this flu season will be 'severe'

status_message: Supporters of legal medical marijuana in Florida said Jan. 9 they are seeking a new ballot measure for 2016 to allow medical cannabis. Supporters say they hope their ballot measure puts pressure on state lawmakers to introduce legislation for legalized marijuana.
link_name: Supporters of legal medical marijuana in Florida seek 2016 ballot measure

status_message: A suicide bombing Jan. 10 at a cafe killed at least seven people and injured more than 30 others. The Al-Qaeda-linked Nusra Front, based in Syria claimed, responsibility. The bombing took place in a predominantly Alawite neighborhood in the northern city of Tripoli. Lebanon's army said military police would investigate.
link_name: Suicide bombing kills at least 7 in northern Lebanon

status_message: Australian police arrested two men Jan. 10 during an anti-terror raid in Sydney, accusing them of possessing and acquiring illegal ammunition. The raid followed a "long-running" investigation into people who have helped fighters in Syria and Iraq. According to authorities, the raid wasn't the "result of any specific terrorism threat."
link_name: Australian authorities arrest two men in anti-terror raid

status_message: Researchers found that lifespan and female fertility decreased in children born during solar maximum -- when the sun reaches peak solar activity and has the most sunspots in its 11-year natural solar cycle.
link_name: Study shows high solar activity may shorten human lifespans

status_message: More than 700,000 people took to the streets on Jan. 10 in cities across France, including some 30,000 in the western city of Nantes (pictured). Marchers there walked behind a banner reading: "Live together, free, equal and in solidarity." The demonstrations came a day before a mass march in Paris.
link_name: Hundreds of thousands rally across France after violent attacks

status_message: Scientists programmed "Cepheus" with the rules of heads-up limit Texas hold'em for two players. Using 4,000 CPUs, it played trillions of hands against itself over two months, learning from mistakes to create an essentially perfect strategy to win money in the long-term. Findings were published Jan. 9 in the journal Science.
link_name: Computer algorithm can beat humans at poker

status_message: George Zimmerman was arrested and later booked late on Jan. 9. Zimmerman's lawyer said his client was arrested for throwing a wine bottle at his girlfriend earlier in the week. He was released on $5,000 bond and ordered to surrender all firearms.
link_name: George Zimmerman arrested on aggravated assault charge

status_message: Netflix is now estimated to have 30 million VPN users worldwide, according to the latest statistics from research firm GlobalWebIndex. At least 20 million of these users are estimate to be in China alone.
link_name: Netflix estimated to have 30 million VPN users worldwide

status_message: After several days of delays, SpaceX successfully launched its Falcon 9 rocket and the unmanned Dragon cargo capsule on its way to resupply the ISS. SpaceX had intended for Falcon 9 to land softly on a sea platform after its initial launch, but instead the rocket came down hard.
link_name: SpaceX launch a success, experimental landing fails

status_message: Searchers used underwater balloons to raise the tail section to the surface Jan. 10. The tail was then hoisted using a crane onto a ship. It is unclear whether the plane's flight recorders may still be inside the tail.
link_name: Tail of AirAsia plane removed from ocean
Chicago-area man indicted for trying to join Islamic State
FBI and Justice Dept. recommend felony charges against retired Gen. Petraeus
Russia lists transgender people as unfit to drive
Justice Department intervenes in trademark dispute over Redskins name
Coca-Cola plans to cut up to 1,800 jobs
Comcast denies offering perks to high-profile customers
Starbucks COO takes 'coffee break'
More than half of adults over age 65 use Facebook, survey finds
Silk Road trial set to begin on Tuesday
Calif. governor unveils $164.7 billion budget
Obama pitches free community college
Researchers crowdsource effort to find Genghis Khan's tomb from space
Radical UK imam sentenced to life in prison in New York
Ringleader in Florida A&M marching band hazing death sentenced to 6 years in prison

status_message:
House passes bill to approve Keystone XL pipeline:

The House passed the bill to approve the pipeline in a 266-153 vote on Jan. 9, with 28 Democrats joining Republicans. The bill now moves to the Senate. Only one Republican, Rep. Justin Amash (R-MI), did not vote for the bill. Amash voted present.
link_name: House passes bill to approve Keystone XL pipeline

status_message:
Japan approves additional $26 billion for budget to fund stimulus:

Abe's cabinet approved a 3.118-trillion yen ($26 billion) supplementary budget to fund stimulus on Jan. 9 for the current fiscal year. The supplementary budget will be financed through unspent money from previous budgets and extra tax revenues.
link_name: Japan approves additional $26 billion for budget to fund stimulus

status_message:
Mali names new prime minister amid talks with rebel groups:

On Jan. 8, in the third change of government since the August 2013 election of President Ibrahim Boubacar Keita, Keita replaced outgoing prime minister Moussa Mara with 73-year-old veteran prime minister Modibo Keita (pictured). In 2014, Keita (no relation) served as government negotiator in talks with rebel groups, paving the way for a roadmap agreement.
link_name: Mali names new prime minister amid talks with rebel groups

status_message:
Winds over 100mph disrupt travel and power in Scotland:

Up to 85,000 properties in Scotland were left without power while ScotRail suspended its services as gusts over 100mph hit the country. Many ScotRail lines resumed service early Jan. 9, though railway delays and cancellations are expected throughout the weekend.
link_name: Winds over 100mph disrupt travel and power in Scotland

status_message:
Six killed ahead of peace talks in eastern Ukraine:

Two civilians and four soldiers were killed in mortar and rocket attacks by Ukrainian forces on the disputed airport and downtown area of Donetsk, local authorities said Jan. 9. Seven people, including four soldiers, were injured. Three soldiers were also killed in the region Jan. 6, a Ukrainian army spokesman said.
link_name: Six killed ahead of peace talks in eastern Ukraine

status_message:
Indonesia cracks whip on low-cost airlines with new fare hike:

Indonesia's transport ministry has come out with new domestic airfare revisions to ensure that low-cost carriers have enough money to focus on safety features, an official said Dec. 7. The decision comes in the wake of the recent crash of AirAsia flight QZ8501.
link_name: Indonesia cracks whip on low-cost airlines with new fare hike

status_message:
U.S. soldiers return to bases to train Iraqi soldiers:

U.S. soldiers return to bases to train Iraqi soldiers:

The U.S. military opened Camp Taji to reporters in early January. U.S. soldiers are training Iraqi soldiers at Taji and Al-Asad Air Base in Anbar Province, the previous homes of tens of thousands of U.S. soldiers. They aim to train 5,000 Iraqis in 6-8 weeks at Taji under a $1.2 billion U.S. train-and-equip program.
link_name: U.S. soldiers return to bases to train Iraqi soldiers

status_message:
Cuba releases 36 detainees as part of deal with US:

36 detainees, including 29 members of the opposition Patriotic Union of Cuba (UNPACU), were released Jan. 7 and 8, bringing the total number of released detainees to 39, the group said in a Jan. 9 statement. The detainees were released on the condition they regularly report to authorities. The names of the detainees were not provided.
link_name: Cuba releases 36 detainees as part of deal with US

status_message:
Paris police kill hostage-taker in kosher grocery siege:

Police moved in on the kosher grocery in a Paris suburb, with gunfire and explosions reported. The suspect was reported dead, and several hostages were reported free. The hostage-taker, Amedy Coulibaly, has ties to Cherif Kouachi, a suspect in the shootings at Charlie Hebdo.
link_name: Hostages taken in Paris kosher supermarket

status_message:
French police kill Charlie Hebdo suspects in raid:

Police killed the Kouachi brothers, the two at-large suspects in the Charlie Hebdo shootings, in a raid on a print shop in Dammartin-en-Goele, about 25 miles northeast of Paris. Gunfire and explosions could be heard from television footage. The pair had a hostage who is reported to be safe.
link_name: French police conducting operation to capture magazine attack suspects

status_message:
Box seeks $1.55 billion valuation in updated IPO filing:

Box expects to price shares in its upcoming IPO at $11 to $13 per share, which would give the company a valuation of as much as $1.55 billion. The company expects to raise $162.5 million in the IPO, according to documents filed with the SEC on Jan. 9.
link_name: Box seeks $1.55 billion valuation in updated IPO filing

status_message:
French police launch assault on location where Charlie Hebdo shooters have hostage:

Police are carrying out an operation in Dammartin-en-Goele, about 25 miles northeast of Paris, to try to detain the two suspects in the Charlie Hebdo shooting. Gunfire and explosions could be heard from television footage. The suspects are believed to be in a print shop and have a hostage.
link_name: French police conducting operation to capture magazine attack suspects

status_message:
Measles cases linked to Disney theme parks in California continues to rise:

Dept. of Public Health in Ca. said Jan. 7 nine patients with confirmed cases of the measles visited Disneyland or Disney California Adventure between Dec. 15 and Dec. 20, 2014. It was confirmed Jan. 9 that three more unvaccinated children likely contracted measles at Disney parks during that time.
link_name: Measles cases linked to Disney theme parks in California continues to rise

status_message:
