UN sending team to Darfur after reports of civilians displaced in fighting:

The UN is deploying a team to Darfur following reports that increased conflict had displaced civilians, the UN said Jan. 8. The UN accused the Sudanese government of escalating operations against armed opposition groups.
link_name: UN sending team to Darfur after reports of civilians displaced in fighting

status_message:
Hostages taken in Paris kosher supermarket:

Police have the kosher supermarket surrounded and are in communication with the hostage taker. As a precaution police have shut down Paris' major ring road, and ordered that Jewish businesses in the Marais district shut down.
link_name: Hostages taken in Paris kosher supermarket

status_message:
Boko Haram gunmen kill dozens in fresh attacks on northeastern Nigeria town:

Boko Haram gunmen killed dozens of people and torched houses in fresh attacks Jan. 6-7 on the northeastern Nigerian town of Baga, officials and eyewitnesses said. This was the second attack after capturing the town over the Jan. 4 weekend. Witnesses said most of the villages and towns in the region were "burnt to the ground"
link_name: Boko Haram gunmen kill dozens in fresh attacks on northeastern Nigeria town

status_message:
Saudi Arabian blogger flogged in public for webforum on religion:

Saudi Arabian editor Raif Badawi is believed to have received 50 lashes in public on Jan. 9 on charges that he insulted Islam. He is expected to received another 50 lashes every week until his sentence is carried out.
link_name: Saudi Arabian blogger flogged in public for webforum on religion

status_message:
US unemployment falls to 5.6% with 252K jobs added in December:

The U.S. added 252,000 jobs in December, the Labor Dept. reported Jan. 9. Economists had expected the country to add 240,000 new jobs, below figures of 321,000 in November. The overall unemployment rate declined to 5.6%.

The US private sector has now added net-positive jobs for 58 straight months, the longest streak since at least 1939
link_name: US unemployment falls to 5.6% with 252K jobs added in December

status_message:
Johnson & Johnson begins human trial of its Ebola vaccine:

Johnson & Johnson (J&J) said Jan. 6 it began testing its Ebola vaccine in humans. J&J will produce more than 400,000 doses of vaccines by April and two million doses in 2015. In Oct. 2014, J&J said it invested $200 million into its joint vaccine program with Danish company Bavarian Nordic.
link_name: Johnson & Johnson begins human trial of its Ebola vaccine

status_message: Yingluck appeared in front of Thailand's assembly Jan. 9 and denied the impeachment charges against her.
link_name: Thailand's Yingluck denies charges in impeachment hearing

status_message: The U.S. military will withdraw from 15 bases in Europe, the Pentagon said Jan. 8. The largest withdrawal will be from RAF Mildenhall in the UK, where 3,200 U.S. personnel will be relocated. The Pentagon says the closures will save $500 million annually.
link_name: Circa News | News, Re-imagined

status_message: WHO data published Jan. 8 showed 20,972 reported cases and 8,259 deaths from Ebola. The vast majority were in the three countries hit hardest by the outbreak: Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone. Ebola's spread might have "leveled off" in Sierra Leone, however, despite 248 new cases, WHO said Jan 7.
link_name: Ebola might have "leveled off" in Sierra Leone despite new cases

status_message: Modi on Jan. 8 appealed to people of Indian origin living abroad to return to the country. He said the government needed their contribution to steer development. Modi has eased visa rules, which includes lifetime visas for Indians overseas, which he promised in his U.S. visit.
link_name: Prime Minister Modi asks Indians abroad to return to steer development

status_message: Police are carrying out an operation in Dammartin-en-Goele about 20-25 miles northeast of Paris to try to detain the two suspects. The town has been cordoned off and residents were instructed to stay at home. The suspects are believed to be in a print shop and have hostages.
link_name: French police conducting operation to capture magazine attack suspects

status_message: Astronomers using Cassini and Earth-based telescopes determined Saturn's exact location in space during its orbit to within two miles, NASA said Jan. 8. The measurement is "50 times more precise" than earlier measurements. It took years of study.
link_name: NASA's determination of Saturn's location now '50 times' more accurate

status_message:
Indonesia detects "pings" in continued search for AirAsia black boxes:

Santoso Sayogo of Indonesia's National Transportation Safety Committee said Jan. 9 that searchers have detected "pings" that may be from AirAsia's flight recorders. Another official said "the location of the ping is reported to be near where the tail was found." Divers are being dispatched.
link_name: Indonesia detects "pings" in continued search for AirAsia black boxes

status_message: Jaycee Chan was convicted Jan. 9 for "allowing others to take drugs in a property, workplace or hotel." He received a six month prison sentence and a small fine. The maximum penalty for the crime in China is three years.
link_name: Jackie Chan's son sentenced to 6 months in Chinese prison over drug charge
New York City to ban plastic foam containers beginning in July
Type 1 diabetes cuts 11-13 years off life, study finds

status_message:
Obama says he wants to offer free community college in the US:

President Obama said in the statement posted on Vine that he wants offer free community college for the first two years "for anyone willing to work for it." Details have not been released. The statement comes ahead of a visit to Tennessee on Jan. 9 where Obama will talk about higher education.
link_name: Obama says he wants to offer free community college in the US

status_message:
Boston picked as US candidate to bid for 2024 Summer Olympics:

Boston beat Los Angeles, San Francisco and Washington, DC. Boston organizers will now spend the next two years working to get support from the International Olympic Committee, which will pick the host city in 2017.
link_name: Boston picked as US candidate to bid for 2024 Summer Olympics
Lenovo to bring Motorola brand back to China
Google's US search market share drops to lowest levels since 2008
Research links Ohio earthquakes to hydraulic fracking near fault lines
HPV testing could replace Pap for cervical cancer screening
FCC considers raising broadband threshold to at least 25 Mbps
Honda fined $70 million by feds for underreporting deaths
Google asked to remove 345 million piracy links in 2014
Bill to approve Keystone XL clears first Senate hurdle
Monsanto earnings down 34%, falling corn demand to blame
App Store revenue jumps 50% in 2014
California Sen. Barbara Boxer will not seek reelection in 2016

status_message:
Federal judge overturns California's ban on foie gras:

U.S. District Judge Stephen V. Wilson issued a ruling Jan. 7 overturning the state ban on foie gras because the law interferes with an existing federal law that regulates poultry. The lawsuit was brought by producers in New York and Canada, and restaurant groups.
link_name: Federal judge overturns California's ban on foie gras

status_message:
Line debuts Uber-like taxi service in Tokyo:

Line Taxi will initially only be available in the Tokyo metropolitan area, though Line plans to expand the service into other parts of Japan. The taxis are provided by Nihon Kotsu, a large Japanese taxi company that has more than 3,000 taxis in Tokyo alone. Line will handle the payment processing.
link_name: Line debuts Uber-like taxi service in Tokyo

status_message:
Black holes could merge, create cosmic collision:

As published in the journal Nature on Jan. 7, scientists report an unusual repeating light signal from a distant quasar, most likely the result of two supermassive black holes in the final phases of a merger, something that has been predicted, but never observed before.
link_name: Black holes could merge, create cosmic collision

status_message:
Activist investors plead with Yahoo not to seek large acquisitions:

Starboard on Jan. 8 sent a letter to Yahoo CEO Marissa Mayer and the company's board advising them not to pursue any large-scale acquisitions and to instead focus on merging with AOL. Recent media reports suggest that Yahoo had considered buying CNN and Scripps, which owns cable channels Food Network and HGTV.
link_name: Activist investors plead with Yahoo not to seek large acquisitions

status_message:
Food stamp enrollment could drop by 1 million in 2016:

A report by the progressive Center for Budget and Policy Priorities released Jan. 5 found that enrollment for benefits under the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) could fall by 1 million in 2016. Falling unemployment rates and the return to a controversial 1996 welfare provision are cited as reasons for the forecast.
link_name: Food stamp enrollment could drop by 1 million in 2016

status_message:
Beijing begins crackdown on Uber, related taxi apps:

Transportation regulators in Beijing will now fine unlicensed taxi drivers for services like Uber and Tencent-backed DiDi up to 20,000 yuan ($3,200) for engaging in "illegal commercial operations." Several other Chinese cities, including Shanghai and Nanjing, had already banned these services.
link_name: Beijing begins crackdown on Uber, related taxi apps

status_message:
Syrian refugees freeze to death in Lebanon:

At least four Syrian refugees including two children in Lebanon died by Jan. 7 due to a storm across the country. Winds reached 56mph. Refugees are facing their fourth winter with little protection from the bitter cold other than makeshift tents. About 1.1 million refugees are registered in Lebanon.
link_name: Syrian refugees freeze to death in Lebanon

status_message:
Al-Qaeda destroys tomb of 13th century Muslim scholar in Syria:

The Al-Qaeda-linked Nusra Front destroyed the mausoleum of the revered 13th century Islamic scholar Imam Nawawi. Hardline groups like Nusra and the Islamic State consider shrines as idolatry and have destroyed them. In Dec. 2014, the UN said 290 historic sites had been damaged or destroyed.
link_name: Al-Qaeda destroys tomb of 13th century Muslim scholar in Syria

status_message:
9 cases of measles linked to Disney theme parks in California:

On Jan. 7, the Department of Public Health in California announced that nine patients with confirmed cases of the measles visited Disneyland or Disney California Adventure between Dec. 15 and Dec. 20, 2014. Three more California residents suspected of having the illness are under investigation.
link_name: 9 cases of measles linked to Disney theme parks in California

status_message:
Tesco to close 43 stores, unveils cost cutting measures:

Tesco said Jan. 8 it would close 43 of its underperforming stores in the UK, cut overhead costs by around 30 percent and sell off some assets. The grocer also said it would cut its capital expenditure to GBP 1 billion ($1.5 billion) for 2015/16 from GBP 2.1 billion expected in 2014/15.
link_name: Tesco to close 43 stores, unveils cost cutting measures

status_message:
Sony delays PS4 launch in China:

Sony on Jan. 8 said it was delaying the launch of the PS4 in China due to "various factors." The console was originally scheduled to launch on Jan. 11. China in early 2014 lifted a law, first passed in 2000, that banned the sale of foreign video game consoles. Sony has called China a market with "great potential."
link_name: Sony delays PS4 launch in China

status_message:
Kepler spots two exoplanets in habitable zones:

NASA said Jan. 6 that 8 new exoplanets spotted by Kepler have been confirmed. Two of the exoplanets are roughly the size of Earth, are likely rocky, and are believed to be in the habitable zones of their stars. At least one of the other relatively small new exoplanets is also inside its star's habitable zone as well.
link_name: Kepler spots two exoplanets in habitable zones

status_message: Some 680 people had been extradited to China from abroad in 2014 on charges of economic crimes, including corruption, China's Ministry of Public Security said Jan. 8. The ministry said 390 people had turned themselves in. Some economic crimes in China carry the death penalty.
link_name: Circa News | News, Re-imagined

status_message: The FAA issued two drone exemptions on Jan. 6 for a real estate broker and a company that wants to use drones for aerial photography for agricultural use. That brings the total to 13 approvals of the use of drones for 12 entities nationwide.
link_name: FAA has given 13 approvals for the commercial use of drones

status_message: President Mahinda Rajapaksa is facing Maithripala Sirisena, who was Rajapaksa's health minister until he unexpectedly broke away from Rajapaksa to run. Political observers believe the election will be closely contested.
link_name: Sri Lankans go to the polls to elect president

status_message: Workers at Coal India Ltd. called off their five-day strike Jan. 7, averting a power crisis in India. The decision came after a meeting between workers' unions and India's coal and power minister. The government promised to form a committee to address workers' concerns, union representatives said.
link_name: India's coal workers call off strike, power crisis averted
Splinter rebel group continues to fight Philippine troops
Obama to launch 3-day tour ahead of State of the Union to tout agenda
French police identify gunmen behind magazine massacre
New York City to reverse public school cell phone ban

status_message:
Fed says interest rates unlikely to rise for at least 2 months:

In minutes released Jan. 7, Federal Reserve officials signaled that it was not yet ready to increase interest rates. Fed Chair Janet Yellen later clarified that the committee would likely wait at least two more months before hiking rates.
link_name: Fed says interest rates unlikely to rise for at least 2 months

status_message:
Boulder, Co. becomes the latest city to challenge Airbnb rentals:

In January, Boulder, Colorado became the latest city to challenge Airbnb by issuing cease-and-desist notices to 20 property owners accused of renting out space in their homes through the service. The city also targeted those using Vacation Rentals by Owner for the same purpose.
link_name: Boulder, Co. becomes the latest city to challenge Airbnb rentals

status_message:
FCC confirms Feb. 26 net neutrality vote:

The FCC will vote on net neutrality regulations at its Feb. 26 meeting, Chairman Tom Wheeler confirmed Jan. 7. The Washington Post first reported on Jan. 2 that the FCC would likely vote on the regulations before the end of February.
link_name: FCC confirms Feb. 26 net neutrality vote

status_message:
Iran blocks communication apps LINE, WhatsApp, Tango:

According to Iran's official IRNA news agency, on Jan. 7 the judiciary ordered three personal communication applications--LINE, WhatsApp and Tango--to be blocked in the country within hours upon announcement. President Hassan Rouhani's administration has long opposed the decision.
link_name: Iran blocks communication apps LINE, WhatsApp, Tango

status_message:
Monster sues Beats over fraud, pirated technology:

Monster, which filed the lawsuit against Beats, Dr. Dre, Iovine, and HTC, claims that Beats unfairly defrauded it out of an ownership stake after agreeing to the HTC deal. Monster also claimed Beats stole its engineering technology after not extending their partnership in 2012.
link_name: Monster sues Beats over fraud, pirated technology

status_message:
AT&T to let subscribers roll over unused data:

AT&T on Jan. 25 will begin allowing select customers to roll over their unused data to the next month. AT&T claims the move, announced Jan. 7, is a way of "saying thanks" to the 50 million customers who will benefit from the plan.
link_name: AT&T to let subscribers roll over unused data

status_message:
Large Hadron Collider set to double former energy level in March, CERN says:

The atom smasher will return for its second three-year run in March 2015, as reported by the BBC. In February 2013, CERN started powering down the LHC for an overhaul scheduled to take two years. It officially went offline two days later.
link_name: Large Hadron Collider set to double former energy level in March, CERN says

status_message:
Time Warner Cable adds $2.75 monthly sports fee:

The fee, which goes into effect this month, marks the first time that Time Warner Cable has added a monthly sports fee to its customers' bills. The sports fee also comes as the company has increased cable modem rental fees from $5.99 per month to $8 per month.
link_name: Time Warner Cable adds $2.75 monthly sports fee

status_message:
Binge drinking kills six a day in US, most are middle-aged men:

According to a CDC report released Jan. 6, the toll from fatal intoxication passes 2,220 on an average year. Seventy-five percent of binge drinking deaths occur among adults between the ages of 35 and 64, and more than 75 percent of those who die are men. Seventy percent are white people.
link_name: Binge drinking kills six a day in US, most are middle-aged men

status_message:
Intel allocates $300 million to improve workforce diversity:

Intel announced the $300 million pledge at a Jan. 6 press conference in Las Vegas. The company will use the money to "reach full representation at all levels" by 2020. The company also plans to use some of the money to help improve workforce diversity across the entire technology sector.
link_name: Intel allocates $300 million to improve workforce diversity

status_message:
Bill Gates helps fund machine that turns human waste into water:

The machine works by heating feces to 1,832 degrees F to draw off water, which is then further treated to ensure drinkability. The dried-out feces can then be burned to produce enough heat to generate electricity needed to extract the water, and extra electricity can be sold to outside users.
link_name: Bill Gates helps fund machine that turns human waste into water

status_message:
US trade deficit fell $3.2 billion to $39 billion in November:

The U.S. trade deficit shrank 7.6% in November to a seasonally adjusted $39 billion, the U.S. Commerce Dept. said on Jan. 7. The ongoing global economic downturn and the bolstered U.S. dollar meant imports into the U.S. were down 2.1% in November to $240.97 billion, while exports decreased 1.0% to $196.4 billion.
link_name: US trade deficit fell $3.2 billion to $39 billion in November

status_message:
Canada, Australia in talks with Egypt to free Al Jazeera journalists:

Australia was holding daily talks with the Egyptian government "at the highest level" to free Peter Greste, Australian Foreign Minister Julie Bishop said Jan. 7. Canada was also in talks to free to free Mohamed Fahmy, Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister John Baird said a day earlier.
link_name: Canada, Australia in talks with Egypt to free Al Jazeera journalists

status_message:
Canada, Australia in talks with Egypt to free Al Jazeera journalists:

Egyptian Baher Mohamed, Canadian-Egyptian Mohamed Fahmy and Australian Peter Greste were each sentenced in June 2014 to seven years in prison. They were accused of aiding terrorists, fabricating video footage, and threatening Egypt's national security.
link_name: Canada, Australia in talks with Egypt to free Al Jazeera journalists

status_message: A tribunal for the New York City Taxi and Limousine Commission suspended five of Uber's six dispatch bases in the city on Jan. 6 after Uber refused to turn over trip data. Uber says it can continue to operate with just one dispatch base. It was also fined $200 for each base, the ruling said.
link_name: Taxi tribunal suspends most Uber dispatch bases in NYC

status_message: NASA on Jan. 5 released a high resolution image of the famous "Pillars of Creation" that Hubble first captured in 1995. NASA also released a panorama image by Hubble of the nearby Andromeda Galaxy. The panorama is made up of "7,398 exposures taken over 411 individual pointings" and is the largest Hubble image ever assembled.
link_name: NASA releases high-res Hubble images ahead of telescope's 25th anniversary

status_message: JPMorgan Chase on Jan. 5 agreed to settle its portion of an antitrust lawsuit for manipulating forex rates. It will pay $100 million as a part of the settlement, Reuters reported. Several investors, including hedge funds, pension funds and the city of Philadelphia filed the 2013 lawsuit.
link_name: JPMorgan to pay $100 million in antitrust lawsuit on foreign exchange manipulation

status_message: The Obama administration worked aggressively in the last two months of 2014 to transfer detainees from the Guantanamo Bay prison, the NYT reported Jan. 5. On Dec. 30, 2014, the U.S. sent five cleared detainees to Kazakhstan. In total, 28 detainees were transferred to other countries in 2014.
link_name: Additional detainees transferred from Guantanamo Bay at the end of 2014

status_message: Three gunmen killed 12 people and critically injured at least five at the offices of Charlie Hebdo. The dead include ten staff members and two police officers. The perpetrators fled in a getaway car, which they are believed to have abandoned after stealing another.
link_name: Gunmen launch deadly attack on French satirical magazine

status_message: U.S. Navy Commander Jose Luis Sanchez, 42, pleaded guilty Jan. 6 in San Diego to bribery and conspiracy to commit bribery. Sanchez was accused of accepting travel, prostitutes and $30,000-$120,000 in bribes for sensitive Navy information. He faces up to 20 years in prison when he is sentenced March 27.
link_name: U.S. Navy commander pleads guilty to bribery

status_message: Construction on California's high-speed rail project began Jan. 6 with a groundbreaking ceremony in Fresno. Gov. Jerry Brown presided over the ceremony, and acknowledged opponents of the project by saying "everything big runs into opposition." Some people protested outside the ceremony.
link_name: California begins building bullet train line

status_message: WhatsApp has more than 700 million monthly active users, CEO Jan Koum said Jan. 6. The company previously said in August 2014 that it had 600 million monthly average users. Users are sending 30 billion messages a day.
link_name: WhatsApp users sending 30 billion messages a day

status_message: Nigerian villagers and fisherman agreed Jan. 5 to a $83.5 million settlement from Shell. Individuals will receive $53.1 million of the total, with the remaining $30.4 million going to the community. The community will use the funds for infrastructure, Kogbara told the AP.
link_name: Shell to pay $83.5 million settlement for Nigeria oil spills

status_message: Curators at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston opened the Massachusetts State House time capsule for the first time on Jan. 6. Inside were 24 coins, five newspapers, a silver plaque engraved by Paul Revere, a "title page," a medal of George Washington, and an impression of the state seal on paper.
link_name: Second Boston time capsule opened

status_message: A government report on the protests released Jan. 6 reiterated the Leung and other leaders' support for the Beijing-dictated election law for chief executive for 2017. The city will start a second round of consultations about the 2017 election on Jan. 7.
link_name: Hong Kong government reiterates support for Beijing election rules

status_message: Two men were arrested Jan. 6 in connection with the shooting of two officers. Jason Polanco, 23, was charged with attempted murder and robbery. Joshua Kemp, 28, was charged with robbery. Police say that Polanco fired a .44 Magnum handgun at the officers. Kemp was arrested after checking himself into a hospital with a gunshot wound.
link_name: Two suspects arrested in shooting of NYPD officers

status_message: A car bomb went off in front of a police academy, killing at least 30 people and wounding dozens, police said. The victims included students at the academy and people waiting in line to enroll with the police. No one immediately claimed responsibility for the attack.
link_name: Bombing hits outside of police academy in Yemen's capital

status_message: A section of the tail of the plane has been located in the Java Sea, said Indonesia's search and rescue chief on Jan. 7. No further details have been given at this time.
link_name: Section of tail of AirAsia plane found
FBI investigating explosion outside Colorado Springs NAACP office
Economic struggles face those living under Islamic State rule
Army looking for 'active shooter' near military hospital in El Paso, Texas
Neil Young debuts hi-res music download store
23andMe strikes Parkinson's disease research deal with Genentech

status_message:
Dow continues slide, down 130 points:

The Dow slid a further 130 points Jan. 6, the day after taking a 331 point dive, closing at 17,372. Investors are concerned about continually falling oil prices, along with a lack of confidence in U.S. economic growth.
link_name: Falling oil prices give Wall Street jitters
Eurozone economy growing at 0.1%
Comcast to offer gigabit Internet in 2015

status_message:
Son of NY hedge fund founder charged in father's shooting death:

70-year-old Thomas Gilbert Sr., founder of Wainscott Capital Partners Fund, was found shot once in the head inside his Manhattan apartment on Jan. 3. His son, Thomas Gilbert, Jr. was taken into custody the following day and charged with homicide and possession of a criminal weapon on Jan. 6.
link_name: Son of NY hedge fund founder charged in father's shooting death
Baseball Hall of Fame elects 4 new members
CNBC drops Nielsen ratings for daytime programming

status_message:
Ex-Virginia Gov. McDonnell sentenced to 2 years in prison for public corruption:

The trial lasted five weeks, during which jurors heard from 67 witnesses. Businessman Jonnie R. Williams, who is at the center of the controversy, spent 15 hours on the witness stand. Witnesses gave unflattering testimony about the lavish lifestyle of the couple and about Maureen's angry temperament.
link_name: Ex-Virginia Gov. McDonnell sentenced to 2 years in prison for public corruption
New cartel emerges in Mexico state
John Boehner reelected to 3rd term as House Speaker

status_message:
Sony positions latest Walkman for audiophiles:

The mobile device runs Android and is expected to cost $1,200 when it's released this spring.
link_name: Sony positions latest Walkman for audiophiles

status_message:
Top Brazil cop dismissed for urging violence on World Cup protesters:

Col. Fabio Souza, who led riot police in a clash in Rio last summer that resulted in 40 injured protestors, was dismissed on Jan. 5, 2014. Souza allegedly urging violence against protesters and making references to Nazism in a WhatsApp chat with other officers sent between Dec. 2013 and Jan. 2014.
link_name: Top Brazil cop dismissed for urging violence on World Cup protesters

status_message:
UHD Alliance formed to boost 4K TV adoption:

The group includes a large number of manufacturers, content creators, and distributors that are working together to promote Ultra HD, the next television resolution standard after 1080p. Among the chief goals of the group is to increase the amount of Ultra HD content available to consumers.
link_name: UHD Alliance formed to boost 4K TV adoption

status_message:
US warns of a potential threat to U.S. banks and hotels in Indonesia:

"The U.S. Embassy has been made aware of a potential threat against U.S.-associated hotels and banks in Surabaya, Indonesia. The U.S. Embassy recommends heightened vigilance and awareness of one's surroundings when visiting such facilities." - U.S. Embassy in Jakarta
link_name: US warns of a potential threat to U.S. banks and hotels in Indonesia

status_message:
Female suicide bomber targets Istanbul police station:

Istanbul's governor confirmed the attack on a police station in the city's Sultanahmet district, a popular tourist area. Governor Vasif Sahin said the female bomber spoke English while attempting to enter the building.
link_name: Female suicide bomber targets Istanbul police station

status_message:
Former CBS correspondent Sharyl Attkisson sues Justice Dept. for illegal surveillance:

Attkisson, formerly of CBS News, is seeking $35 million in damages. She alleges that three separate computer forensic exams prove that hackers monitored her work between 2011 and 2013. She also claims intruders installed software to steal data and obtain passwords on her home and work computers.
link_name: Former CBS correspondent Sharyl Attkisson sues Justice Dept. for illegal surveillance

status_message:
Myanmar government sets five-week deadline for ceasefire with ethnic groups:

Myanmar President Thein Sein met with leaders of ethnic rebel groups, several of which have been fighting the Myanmar government since its establishment in 1948, on Jan. 5. Sein said he would grant greater powers, up to creating a federal union, to ethnic groups in exchange for a nationwide ceasefire.
link_name: Myanmar government sets five-week deadline for ceasefire with ethnic groups

status_message:
Former federal cybersecurity director gets 25 years for child pornography:

According to the Dept. of Justice, Timothy DeFoggi had since March 2012 traded, viewed, and discussed child pornography online using Tor, a software tool that lets users browse the web anonymously. DeFoggi expressed a desire to violently rape and murder children on a Tor website, which was shut down by the FBI on December 2012.
link_name: Former federal cybersecurity director gets 25 years for child pornography

status_message:
PS4 sales top 18.5 million units worldwide:

A total of 18.5 million PS4 consoles have been sold to consumers worldwide since its November 2013 debut, Sony said Jan. 5, with 4.1 million units being sold during the past holiday season. The company last said in November 2014 that it had sold 13.5 million units, up from 10 million in the summer.
link_name: Sony details PlayStation game streaming service pricing

status_message:
China detains activist who helped dissident Chen Guangcheng escape house arrest:

Activist Guo Yushan, founder of a think-tank researching civil society and regulatory reform, was detained in Beijing, China on January 6. Guo was ostensibly arrested for "illegal business activity," but is also known as an activist who helped Chen Guangcheng (pictured) escape house arrest in 2012.
link_name: China detains activist who helped dissident Chen Guangcheng escape house arrest

status_message:
Sen. Feinstein plans to introduce legislation to ban torture:

Outgoing Senate Intelligence Committee Chair Dianne Feinstein (D-CA) on Jan. 5 published a letter to President Obama with proposals that the U.S. "never again engages" in torture. Feinstein, who led Senate efforts to investigate torture, said she will introduce legislation to "close all torture loopholes."
link_name: Sen. Feinstein plans to introduce legislation to ban torture

status_message: The Jan. 6 launch was aborted late in the countdown due to "actuator drift," NASA said. The issue would have affected the "thrust factor control system," which would trigger an automatic launch abort. The launch will be reattempted Jan. 9 at 5:09am EST.
link_name: SpaceX supply mission to International Space Station delayed

status_message: Therese Serignese and Linda Traitz on Jan. 5 joined the defamation lawsuit against Cosby initiated by Tamara Green. Serignese claims Cosby raped her in 1976. Traitz says she was groped by Cosby in 1970.
link_name: Two women join defamation suit against Bill Cosby

status_message: South Korea said Jan. 6 that North Korea likely now has as much as 88 pounds of weapons-grade plutonium at its disposal. The biannual military report also says that the North's intercontinental ballistic missile program has "very much addressed the issues of accuracy and reliability."
link_name: South Korea: North Korea closer to mounting nuclear warhead on rocket

status_message: Power generation in India could be hit as workers at Coal India Limited began a five-day strike Jan. 6. The strike is against Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi's plan to expand private companies in the coal sector. Coal India increased its shipments to power plants ahead of the strike.
link_name: India could face power shortage with coal workers on strike

status_message: Uber on Jan. 6 withdrew its plea from the Delhi High Court against a ban on its services. The company complained, however, that it was the only one complying with the ban, pointing to Ola Cabs, another banned service. The court directed the government to take action against those violating the ban.
link_name: Uber withdraws plea against its ban in Delhi

status_message: President Beji Caid Essebsi nominated Habib Essid as prime minister on Jan. 5. Essid held various positions in the interior ministry under Zine El Abidine Ben Ali's regime. He served as interior minister and as a security adviser in the Islamist-led government after 2011. He is a U.S.-educated agricultural economist.
link_name: Ex-regime politician tapped as Tunisian prime minister

status_message: A Larimore Public School District bus failed to stop at a stop sign in front of train tracks. It was hit by an oncoming freight train, police said. The 62-year-old bus driver and a 17-year-old female student were thrown from the bus and died. The incident occurred during clear weather.
link_name: North Dakota school bus hit by freight train, at least 2 killed

status_message:
Guatemalan dictator's genocide retrial suspended after brief hearing

The retrial began on Jan. 5, but was quickly suspended after defense lawyers successfully argued that one of the court's judges could not be impartial in the case.
link_name: Guatemalan dictator's genocide retrial suspended after brief hearing

status_message: In a preliminary hearing on Jan. 5, a judge officially ordered Eric Frein to stand trial for charges of murder and terrorism. Frein is accused of shooting two Pennsylvania troopers, killing one of them, in an ambush attack. He was arrested on Oct. 30, 2014.
link_name: Alleged state trooper killer to stand trial in Pennsylvania

status_message:
Falling oil prices give Wall Street jitters

The Dow plunged 331 points on Jan. 5 to close at 17,501.65, its worst day in three months. Similarly affected was the S&P 500 which lost 1.83% of its value, and the Nasdaq which was down 1.57%. U.S. crude slumping to below $50 per barrel was cited as a cause of market jitters.
link_name: Falling oil prices give Wall Street jitters
Gogo creates fake SSL certificates to throttle in-flight Internet

status_message:
CDC says US flu activity expanding, 21 children dead

The U.S. flu season is continuing to expand, with 43 states reporting "high or widespread" influenza activity, the CDC reported on Jan. 5. Most infections have resulted from the circulation of "drifted" H3N2 viruses, which have changed slightly over time and aren't as susceptible to vaccines.
link_name: CDC says US flu activity expanding, 21 children dead

status_message:
Iran's president suggests nationwide vote on thorny issues:

In a Jan. 4 speech, Iranian President Hassan Rouhani said he would consider putting controversial issues to a direct, nationwide referendum rather let such issues be decided by Parliament. Iran's 1979 constitution allows for such referendums, but none has ever been held.
link_name: Iran's president suggests nationwide vote on thorny issues

status_message:
New York Times reporter refuses court questions on CIA sources

At a pretrial hearing Jan. 5, James Risen refused to answer questions which could directly or indirectly identify his source at the CIA. The hearing was set to determine what information Risen would reveal if called as a prosecution witness in the trial of former CIA officer Jeffrey Sterling.
link_name: Circa News | News, Re-imagined

status_message:
Morgan Stanley says employee stole client account data

Morgan Stanley said on Jan. 5 that it was advising about 900 clients that an employee had stolen private data. The employee has been fired and Morgan Stanley said law enforcement and regulatory authorities have been alerted. Stolen data did not include account passwords or Social Security numbers.
link_name: Morgan Stanley says employee stole client account data

status_message:
Son of NY hedge fund founder expected to be charged in father's shooting death

70-year-old Thomas Gilbert Sr., founder of Wainscott Capital Partners Fund, was found shot once in the head inside his Manhattan apartment on Jan. 3. His son, Thomas Gilbert, Jr. was taken into custody the following day.
link_name: Son of NY hedge fund founder expected to be charged in father's shooting death

status_message:
Sony details PlayStation game streaming service pricing:

Sony on Jan. 13 will launch a monthly subscription option for PlayStation Now, the company's service that lets users stream games over the Internet. The company revealed Jan. 5 that one month of unlimited access will cost $19.99, with a three-month package available for $44.99.
link_name: Sony details PlayStation game streaming service pricing

status_message:
Miami-Dade court ruling allows same-sex marriages to begin in Florida:

Judge Sarah Zabel lifted a stay on her ruling that Florida's same-sex marriage ban violates equal protections under the U.S. Constitution and allowed for same-sex couples to apply for marriage licenses at 12 p.m. on Jan. 5, when her two-page order reached the Miami-Dade clerk of courts office.
link_name: Miami-Dade court ruling allows same-sex marriages to begin in Florida

status_message:
Mike Huckabee quits Fox News to consider 2016 presidential run:

Current Fox News host and former Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee said his Jan. 3 show would be his last on the network as he ponders a presidential run. "The honorable thing to do at this point is to end my tenure here at Fox," he said. Huckabee, 59, said he won't make a decision about running until late spring.
link_name: Mike Huckabee quits Fox News to consider 2016 presidential run

status_message:
Dish Network reveals online TV service called Sling TV:

Dish Network on Jan. 5 officially revealed Sling TV, an online TV service that will let users watch live channels like ESPN, Food Network, and TNT over the Internet. The service, which does not yet have a release date, will cost $20 per month.
link_name: Dish Network reveals online TV service called Sling TV
Russian oil output hit post-Soviet high in 2014

status_message:
Prince Andrew, Duke of York, deny ties to underage sex ring:

In papers filed Dec. 30, a woman identified as "Jane Doe #3" claims to have been "converted into a sex slave" from 1999-2002 by billionaire Jeffery Epstein, a friend of Prince Andrew's until 2011. Epstein plead guilty to charges of solicitation of a minor for prostitution in 2008.
link_name: Prince Andrew, Duke of York, deny ties to underage sex ring

status_message:
Third-parties make up 40% of total Amazon shipments:

Amazon said Jan. 5 that third-party sellers shipped more than 2 billion items worldwide in 2014, doubling its 2013 total. Amazon also said that third-party sellers made up 40% of the site's total shipments. That suggests at least 5 billion items in total were shipped in the year.
link_name: Third-parties make up 40% of total Amazon shipments

status_message:
Trial of Boston bombing suspect Dzhokhar Tsarnaev begins:

Tsarnaev appeared in court for the start of trial proceedings. Judge George O'Toole Jr. said opening statements will begin Jan. 26, and the trial will last three to four months. Judge O'Toole will select 12 jurors and 6 alternates from the 1,200 summoned to jury duty.
link_name: Trial of Boston bombing suspect Dzhokhar Tsarnaev begins

status_message:
First transgender mayor elected in India:

Madhu Kinnar, 35, won a mayoral election, becoming the first transgender person to become mayor in India. She won by 4,537 votes over her rival from Prime Minister Narendra Modi's party. Kinnar is a member of the Dalit caste previously known as "untouchables." She earned a living by singing and dancing on trains.
link_name: First transgender mayor elected in India

status_message:
UN-brokered dialogue in Libya hit with repeated delays:

U.N.-brokered peace talks scheduled for Jan. 5 were postponed without setting a new date. The talks were previously planned for Dec. 9, but were delayed as conflict escalated and two rival governments would not agree to meet. U.N. Special Envoy to Libya Bernadino Leon has been trying to broker a ceasefire for months.
link_name: UN-brokered dialogue in Libya hit with repeated delays

status_message:
FBI employees with ties abroad report security bias:

Those in the Post-Adjudication Risk Management plan, or PARM, face frequent security interviews, polygraph tests, scrutiny of personal travel, and reviews of communications and files downloaded. Among the affected are Muslim and Asian personnel hired to fill intelligence and counterterrorism roles.
link_name: FBI employees with ties abroad report security bias

status_message:
Spain's unemployment rate falls for 5th straight month:

In an announcement before a popular Christmas-related holiday, Three Kings' Day, on Jan. 6, Spain's Labor Ministry said the country's unemployment rate fell for five consecutive months in December 2014, posting the sharpest annual drop since 1998. The number of jobless claims declined 64,405 to 4.45 million between Nov.-Dec.
link_name: Spain's unemployment rate falls for 5th straight month

status_message:
Tomb of previously unknown ancient queen found in Egypt:

Archaeologists discovered the tomb of Queen Khentakawess, the Egyptian Ministry of Antiquities said. She was the wife of Pharaoh Neferefra, who ruled in the middle of the Fifth Dynasty (2450-2325BC). The name of Khentakawess, who was previously unknown, was inscribed on the inner walls of the tomb.
link_name: Tomb of previously unknown ancient queen found in Egypt

status_message:
St. Louis Rams owner plans Los Angeles stadium:

For two decades, efforts have been made to bring the NFL franchise back to the nation's second-largest media market. Kroenke's move marks the first time an existing team owner has controlled a local site large enough for a stadium and parking. The Rams have been in St. Louis since 1995.
link_name: St. Louis Rams owner plans Los Angeles stadium

status_message: Temperatures could drop as low as 35 degrees below normal in parts of the northern U.S. by Jan. 6 and will "drive all the way down south," National Weather Service meteorologist Paul Kocin said. Wind chills may drop temperatures as low as 45 degrees Fahrenheit below zero in parts of Minnesota.
link_name: Northern US under warnings for freezing temperatures

status_message: Pope Francis announced 20 new members of the College of Cardinals during a mass at St. Peter's Square on Jan. 4. Five are over 80 years old and cannot vote. The 15 voting cardinals came from 14 different countries. He bypassed many dioceses, mostly European, that traditionally fill seats in the college.
link_name: Pope appoints 20 cardinals from 18 nations

status_message: Jean-Luc Godard's "Goodbye to Language" was named best picture by the National Society of Film Critics on Jan. 3. The 3D movie, which also was a winner of the 2014 Cannes Film Festival jury prize, involves a couple that are having an affair and a stray dog.
link_name: "Goodbye to Language" chosen as best film by National Society of Film Critics

status_message: Turkey approved the building of a new church for the first time since it became a secular republic in 1923, officials said Jan. 2. The church for the small Assyrian community will be in the Yesilkoy district in Istanbul. The Muslim majority country has around 100,000 Christians.
link_name: Turkey approves building of first new church since 1923

status_message: The AA pilots union agreed Jan. 4 to vote on a five-year contract that includes a 3% increase in each of the next four years, in addition to an immediate 23% salary increase (retroactive to Dec. 2, 2014). The pilots are expected to vote in January.
link_name: American Airlines pilots agree to vote on contract offer

status_message: Xiaomi sold 61.12 million smartphones in 2014, which represented 227% growth from 2013, the company said Jan. 4. Those sales contributed to a pre-tax revenue of 74.3 billion RMB ($11.94 billion) for the year, or 135% growth from 2013.
link_name: Xiaomi phone sales tripled in 2014

status_message:
Navy successfully tests prototype laser weapon in the Persian Gulf

The Office of Naval Research announced in Dec. 204 that it had tested a laser weapon system for the first time aboard the USS Ponce in the Persian Gulf. Testing took place from Sept. 2014 to Nov. 2014. The system "operated seamlessly with existing ship defense systems," the Navy said.
link_name: Navy succesfully tests prototype laser weapon in the Persian Gulf

status_message:
Sierra Leone district locked down for 2 more weeks to contain Ebola

WHO data published Jan. 2 showed 20,381 reported cases and 7,989 deaths, with the vast majority in the three countries hit hardest by the Ebola outbreak: Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone. While Liberia has the highest death toll in the region, Sierra Leone has the most cases.
link_name: Sierra Leone district locked down for 2 more weeks to contain Ebola

status_message:
Four killed in bomb blast south of Yemen's capital

At least four people died and 25 were wounded in a Jan. 4 bombing in the city of Dhamar, 60 miles south of Sana'a. A group of Shiite Houthi militiamen were meeting in the house that was bombed. The state news agency Saba reported that "terrorists elements" were likely responsible for the blast.
link_name: Four killed in bomb blast south of Yemen's capital

status_message:
India criticized for blocking access to popular websites to fight extremism

The government has restored access to some websites after more than 30 were blocked in an effort to target extremist information posted anonymously online.
link_name: India criticized for blocking access to popular websites to fight extremism

status_message:
Transport ship runs aground off English coast

Officials are assessing how to salvage the Hoegh Osaka after it ran aground off of southern England on Jan. 4. The 590ft vessel is listing at 45 degrees, but is not taking on any water.
link_name: Transport ship runs aground off English coast

status_message:
Two Republicans launch bids to challenge Boehner for House Speaker

Reps. Louie Gohmert (R-TX) and Ted Yoho (R-FL) said over the Jan. 3-4 weekend they will each challenge John Boehner for House Speaker. According to Yoho, electing a new Speaker "is not a personal vote against Representative Boehner," but rather "against the status quo."
link_name: Two Republicans launch bids to challenge Boehner for House Speaker

status_message:
Sluggish manufacturing growth capped a tough year for the eurozone

The Manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) ended the year at 50.6, less than the expected 50.8 for the eurozone, according to a Jan. 2 Markit report.
link_name: Sluggish manufacturing growth capped a tough year for the eurozone

status_message:
Rikers inmate who hanged himself was supposed to be on suicide watch

Fabian Cruz hanged himself to death in his jail cell Jan. 1, a day after a jail psychiatrist said Cruz should be placed on suicide watch for constant monitoring. An unnamed guard had allowed Cruz to return to his cell, in violation of jail policy. Cruz was awaiting sentencing for a felony sex crime.
link_name: Rikers inmate who hanged himself was supposed to be on suicide watch

status_message:
Belgium in January to euthanize man convicted of rape and murder

A Belgian justice ministry spokesperson confirmed to a local news outlet that 51-year-old Frank Van Den Bleeken will be euthanized on Jan. 11, saying "the time has come."
link_name: Belgium in January to euthanize man convicted of rape and murder

status_message:
Funeral for second slain NYPD officer held in New York

The funeral for Wenjian Liu was held Jan. 4 in Brooklyn and attracted thousands of mourners. "Our obligation is to try to do good to honor this man," FBI Director James Comey said. Many officers in attendance again turned their backs when Mayor Bill de Blasio spoke despite a plea days earlier by the NYPD's commissioner.
link_name: Funeral for second slain NYPD officer held in New York

status_message:
Obama to launch 3-day tour ahead of State of the Union to tout agenda

President Obama will go on a three-day tour ahead of the annual address to preview his agenda. The plan is a break from his usual approach of going on tour after the speech. The president will talk about higher education, housing and jobs on stops in Tennessee, Arizona and Michigan. Obama's tour begins Jan. 7.
link_name: Obama to launch 3-day tour ahead of State of the Union to tout agenda

status_message:
Report: Engine icing likely led to AirAsia crash

Indonesia's meteorological research agency said that ice-related engine failure likely led to the AirAsia crash, but they drew no final conclusions about the cause.
link_name: Report: Engine icing likely led to AirAsia crash

status_message:
Stuart Scott, ESPN anchor, dead at 49

Stuart Scott passed away the morning of Jan. 4, ESPN said, following recurring bouts of cancer. He was 49.
link_name: Stuart Scott, ESPN anchor, dead at 49

status_message:
Edward Brooke, first African-American popularly elected to US Senate, dies at 95

Former Sen. Edward Brooke died on Jan. 3 at the age of 95 from natural causes at his home in Florida, a former aide said and the Massachusetts Republican Party confirmed. Brooke, a Republican, served in the Senate from 1967-1979.
link_name: Edward Brooke, first African-American popularly elected to US Senate, dies at 95

status_message:
Israel freezes Palestinian funds over ICC bid

On Jan. 3, multiple reports cited unnamed Israeli officials confirming that some $127 million in funds that are typically transferred each month from Israel to the Palestinians had been halted in response to the ICC bid. The funds come from taxes and other duties collected on goods that move through Israel.
link_name: Israel freezes Palestinian funds over ICC bid

status_message:
Nighttime breathing issues may cause obesity in kids

In the first study to observe both sleep duration and breathing problems as separate risk factors for obesity, researchers found that snoring and sleep apnea are linked to weight gain in children.
link_name: Nighttime breathing issues may cause obesity in kids

status_message:
Lebanon plans first visa requirements for Syrians as refugees flood country

Lebanon on New Year's Eve announced unprecedented restrictions on Syrians entering the country, for the first time requiring Syrian nationals to have a visa. The measure is set to take effect on Jan. 5. Syrians can apply for six types of visas: tourist, business, student, transit, short stay and medical.
link_name: Lebanon plans first visa requirements for Syrians as refugees flood country

status_message:
AirAsia search locates 4 large pieces of debris as bad weather hampers recovery

Search officials said Jan. 3 that sonar had located four large metal objects, including one measuring 59 feet long and 18 feet wide, believed to be debris from Flight QZ8501. The pieces were found after an oil slick was spotted in the search area, but divers were unable to get visual proof or recover additional bodies due to bad weather
link_name: AirAsia search locates 4 large pieces of debris as bad weather hampers recovery

status_message:
First person in the UK to be diagnosed with Ebola is now in critical condition :

Pauline Cafferkey, a healthcare worker who was the first person in the UK to be diagnosed with Ebola, is now in critical condition, the London hospital that's treating her said Jan. 3. A hospital spokesperson was "sorry to announce" that her condition has gradually deteriorated in the past two days.
link_name: Italian Ebola patient released from hospital

status_message:
Abu Anas Al-Libi, alleged plotter of U.S. embassy attacks, dies in New York:

Al-Libi died in New York while awaiting trial for allegedly plotting the 1998 bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. U.S. Attorney Preet Bharara said in a court filing that Al-Libi was taken from the Metropolitan Correctional Center to a New York hospital on Wednesday "due to sudden complications arising out of his long-standing medical problems."
link_name: Abu Anas Al-Libi, alleged plotter of U.S. embassy attacks, dies in New York

status_message:
Chrome textbook price comparison extension draws legal complaint:

Occupy The Bookstore's developers said in a Reddit AMA Jan. 2 that Follett, a college textbook company, threatened them with legal action if they did not remove the extension. The extension was first released in April 2014 and has been downloaded 15,000 times, up from 2,000 times before news of the legal threat became public.
link_name: Chrome textbook price comparison extension draws legal complaint

status_message:
No new charges for attempted Reagan assassin in James Brady death

The Justice Dept. said Jan. 2 that no new charges will be filed after James Brady died in Aug. 2014. The medical examiner in Washington, DC, ruled in August that Brady's death was a homicide resulting from the injuries he suffered in the shooting 33 years ago.
link_name: No new charges for attempted Reagan assassin in James Brady death

status_message:
US warns arrest of Bahraini opposition leader will 'inflame tensions'

Sheikh Ali Salman, head of Bahrain's main opposition party, was arrested Dec. 28. In a Jan. 1 statement, the U.S. State Dept. warned the detention "will only inflame tensions" in the country. Authorities said he was being questioned for publicly saying the opposition had received offers to arm itself, which it refused.
link_name: US warns arrest of Bahraini opposition leader will 'inflame tensions'

status_message:
Study finds electric eels remotely control prey

A study observed eels' hunting strategy and suggests that eel high-voltage volleys are selected to most efficiently induce involuntary muscle contraction in nearby animals.
link_name: Study finds electric eels remotely control prey

status_message:
Human rights monitor says 76,000 died in Syria's civil war in 2014

The UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (SOHR) said Jan. 1 that an estimated 76,021 people died in 2014 in Syria due to the civil war. The figure is the deadliest in the four years of war and includes 17,790 civilians, of which 3,501 were children.
link_name: Human rights monitor says 76,000 died in Syria's civil war in 2014

status_message:
New York police officer detained for allegedly attacking transit worker

NYPD officer Mirjan Lolja, 37, turned himself in on Jan. 2 in connection with an attack Dec. 23 at 2:30am on a female transit worker, who claims she was pushed to the ground and choked. Lolja, who was off-duty, said the two struggled after she tried to take his phone.
link_name: New York police officer detained for allegedly attacking transit worker

status_message:
Prosecutors seek death penalty for LAX shooter:

Federal prosecutors said in court filings Jan. 2 that they will seek the death penalty for Paul Anthony Ciancia. According to the filing, Ciancia's premeditated crime caused people "to fear for their lives and experience extreme emotional distress."
link_name: Prosecutors seek death penalty for LAX shooter

status_message:
Dish Network begins beta testing online TV service

Dish Network is now inviting customers of its DishWorld online TV service to beta test the "next generation" of the service, several customers wrote on Reddit Jan. 2. This new service will carry channels like ESPN, Food Network, and TNT. The first generation of DishWorld mainly carries international channels.
link_name: Dish Network begins beta testing online TV service

status_message:
FCC to vote on net neutrality rules in February: 

The FCC plans to finalize and vote on net neutrality regulations by the end of February, it confirmed to the Washington Post on Jan. 2. The agency currently has a meeting scheduled for Feb. 26 where a vote would likely be held if the rules are finalized in time, the Post reported.
link_name: FCC to vote on net neutrality rules in February

status_message:
Twitter rolling out 'while you were away' recap feature:

Twitter has begun to roll out a recap feature it first described in November 2014 that attempts to show users important tweets they may have missed while away from the service. Twitter determines which tweets to highlight based on metrics like the number of times it was retweeted and favorited.
link_name: Twitter rolling out 'while you were away' recap feature

status_message:
French economist Thomas Piketty refuses country's highest honor, criticizes priorities

"It isn't up to the government to decide who's honorable, they would do better to concentrate on reviving growth," Piketty said when he refused the accolade on Jan. 1.
link_name: Economist Thomas Piketty refuses France's highest honor, criticizes priorities

status_message:
US population hits 320.09 million:

The U.S. population is up 0.73% from the year before. The population is also up 3.67% from when the last census was taken in April 2010.
link_name: US population hits 320.09 million

status_message:
New iCloud password-cracking tool released online

A new tool that lets users attempt to crack iCloud passwords was released online on Jan. 1. The tool, called iDict, exploits a vulnerability in iCloud to repeatedly guess a user's password. Such attacks, called brute force attacks, are usually prevented by limits placed on the number attempted password guesses.
link_name: New iCloud password-cracking tool released online

status_message:
US adds new sanctions against North Korea over Sony hack: 

President Obama approved new sanctions against 10 senior North Korean officials and three companies on Jan. 2. The administration said it is part of its "proportional response" to the Sony hack.
link_name: US adds new sanctions against North Korea over Sony hack

status_message:
CIA report takes responsibility for most UFO sightings in the 1950s and 1960s

The CIA report, titled "The CIA and the U-2 Program, 1954-197," says high altitude tests in the early evenings led to pilots reporting UFO sightings. The CIA said the report was its top read story of 2014.
link_name: CIA report takes responsibility for most UFO sightings in the 1950s and 1960s

status_message:
Studies suggest ketamine may effectively treat depression:

Yale, Mount Sinai and the National Institute of Mental Health, among others, have researched ketamine as a depression aid and all suggest using the drug as treatment. According to some studies, depression treated with the drug known as 'Special K' melts away in a few hours.
link_name: Studies suggest ketamine may effectively treat depression

status_message: Fox News viewership is down 12% from a year ago after going dark on Dish Network
link_name: Fox channels go dark on Dish Network amid contract dispute

status_message:
US manufacturing slows to six-month low: 

The Institute for Supply Management (ISM) reported Jan. 2 that its manufacturing index fell to 55.5 in December from 58.6 in November. That was also below economists' expectations of 57.6, according to Reuters. Similar numbers from financial data firm Markit also indicated a decline in manufacturing.
link_name: US manufacturing slows to six-month low

status_message: Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid was hospitalized overnight after breaking several ribs and bones in accident involving exercise equipment, according to the senator's office.
link_name: Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid hospitalized overnight with broken bones

status_message:
Italian Ebola patient released from hospital: 

Fabrizio Pulvirenti, an Italian doctor who contracted Ebola while treating patients in Sierra Leone, was released on Jan. 2 from a hospital in Rome. Pulvirenti, 50, had Italy's only known case of the disease and was in the hospital for more than a month. He is considering returning to Sierra Leone to further treat Ebola patients.
link_name: Italian Ebola patient released from hospital

status_message:
At least 26 killed by army rocket during wedding in Afghanistan:

At least 26 people were killed and dozens were injured when a rocket fired by Afghan soldiers hit a house during a wedding, officials said. There was a fight between Afghanistan's army and Taliban militants in the area during the time of the incident.
link_name: At least 26 killed by army rocket during wedding in Afghanistan

status_message:
Italian coast guard takes control of abandoned migrant ship:

The Italian coast guard said Jan. 2 it took control of an abandoned merchant ship carrying at least 400 migrants and was heading to the port of Crotone. Someone on board of Ezadeen, the Sierra Leone-registered ship, used the maritime radio to make a distress call, seeking help. The coast guard was trying to board the ship from Jan. 1.
link_name: Italian coast guard takes control of abandoned migrant ship

status_message:
Oregon to meet Ohio State in college football National Championship

The college football National Championship game will feature Oregon and Ohio State, and kicks off at 8:30 ET. The matchup was set after a pair of games on New Year's Day between the top four teams in the country.
link_name: Oregon to meet Ohio State in college football National Championship

status_message: GM issued fresh recalls over faulty ignition switches Jan. 1 that cover 83,572 SUVs and trucks sold between 2007 and 2014 in the U.S., and about 9,000 vehicles in Mexico and Canada.
link_name: GM recalls more than 92,000 trucks and SUVs for faulty ignition switch

status_message: Mario Cuomo, former New York governor and one-time presidential contender, died Jan. 1 at the age of 82. Gov. Andrew Cuomo, his son, was sworn-in to a second term earlier the same day.
link_name: Mario Cuomo, three-time New York governor, dies at 82

status_message:
Ebola deaths top 7,900 in West Africa

WHO data published late Dec. 31 showed 20,206 reported cases and 7,905 deaths, with the vast majority in the three countries hit hardest by the Ebola outbreak: Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone.
link_name: Ebola deaths top 7,900 in West Africa

status_message:
Barack and Michelle Obama's first date gets Hollywood treatment

Filming for "Southside With You" is set to begin in July, 2015 on location in Chicago. No release date has been announced.
link_name: Barack and Michelle Obama's first date gets Hollywood treatment

status_message:
Pew survey: Email is most used workplace technology

The survey notes that email, the Internet and landline telephones are the three most important tools for adult workers. Reliance on email continues among U.S. office workers despite threats posed by phishing and malware, and competition from social media and startups.
link_name: Pew survey: Email is most used workplace technology

status_message:
U.S. Supreme Court to put filings online, will still prohibit video

In his year-end report on the judiciary, Chief Justice John Roberts wrote on Dec. 31 that the U.S. Supreme Court will posts briefs and appeal petitions online by 2016, at the earliest. Decisions have been posted on its website since 2000.
link_name: US Supreme Court to put filings online, will still prohibit video

status_message:
Egyptian court orders retrial for Al Jazeera journalists

After an appeal, Egypt's top court ordered a retrial on Jan. 1 for three Al Jazeera journalists. Defense lawyers said the prosecution acknowledged problems with the verdict. The new trial will begin within a month, but the men will remain in custody.
link_name: Egyptian court orders retrial for Al Jazeera journalists

status_message:
Divers continue to recover bodies from AirAsia crash

Search crews on Jan. 1 recovered two more bodies from the area where flight QZ8501 came down, bringing the total recovered to nine.
link_name: Divers continue to recover bodies from AirAsia crash

status_message:
North Korea's Kim says he's open to summit with South Korea

"Depending on the mood and circumstances, there is no reason not to hold the highest-level summit," North Korean leader Kim Jong-un said in a New Year's message.
link_name: North Korea's Kim says he's open to summit with South Korea

status_message:
Lithuania, last of the three Baltic states, joins euro

Lithuania became the 19 country to formally adopt the euro on Jan. 1. Prime Minister Algirdas Butkevicius said the euro would "become a guarantor of both economic and political security."
link_name: Lithuania, last of the three Baltic states, joins euro
